<HEADLINE>Explosions on Richter scale Blasts at Beaufort's war dump</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749698</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE have been nine unexplained explosions, some as strong as a small
earthquake, around the controversial munitions dump at Beaufort's Dyke off the
Scottish coast.
The blasts were recorded by scientists in Edinburgh.
A local Labour MP said it ``raises terrifying questions'' and warned of
``potential catastrophe''.
The Second World War munitions dump is thought to contain more than a million
tons of bombs, shells, and gas canisters, and the explosions took place south
of a new pipeline being built by British Gas between Scotland and Northern
Ireland.
The head of the team of scientists, Dr Chris Browitt, said the dumped munitions
could have caused the underwater blasts.
The earthquake experts are now involved in talks with the Scottish Office about
establishing a system for monitoring underwater activity in the area.
Scientists at the British Geological Survey centre in Edinburgh said they hoped
this could help them discover the cause of the explosions recorded in the past
year around the 263-fathom trench, six miles off the Galloway coast.
Some of the underwater blasts could have reached up to 2.5 on the Richter
Scale, the equivalent of a small earthquake, scientists said.
The BGS is understood to be bidding for Scottish Office cash which would be
used to fund comprehensive research into the cause of the explosions.
The latest development follows a long standing row over the Second World War
dump. The laying of the gas pipeline near the site has attracted fierce
criticism. Opponents of the project claim the excavation of the seabed
disturbed the dump, sending 4000 flares and incendiary devices to the surface
and on to Scottish and Irish beaches.
In October, dangerous canisters were washed up on the south-west coast burning
a four-year-old boy who picked them up.
Last month, the Scottish Office agreed to commission an emergency survey of the
dump ``to allay public fears''.
Dr Browitt, director of BGS Scotland, said although it was possible the
munitions could have caused the blasts, there were several other possible
explanations, such as Royal Navy manoeuvres, civil engineering work, or
wreck-clearing operations.
He said: ``We should be looking at this in greater detail and we are currently
talking to the Scottish Office about proposals to this effect.''
The BGS has four monitoring stations in the Irish Sea. Dr Browitt said
Admiralty charts were altered in 1968 to provide a warning of the possible
dangers after two ships were rocked by explosions near the trench.
He explained that there were several hundred underwater explosions recorded
around the British coast throughout the year: at least 100 of those would be in
Scottish waters, with some in the Beaufort's Dyke area.
However, he said further investigations could detect many more explosions.
Mr George Foulkes, the Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley MP, has campaigned
against the laying of the pipeline by British Gas. He said fisherman had also
reported explosions over the last 40 years.
He added: ``Reports of up to 10 explosions in the last year raises terrifying
questions. If a pipeline is laid in an area where there have been explosions it
could have a catastrophic effect. This underlines the importance of carrying
out a detailed survey.''
He said ``an explosion in that area would be absolutely disastrous. We must
have an immediate investigation into the intensity and every aspect of these
explosions.
``And what with the chemicals and nerve gas supposed also to be in the area,
any dislodgement could mean the possibility of alien matter getting into the
fish and the food chain. It is an absolute disaster of unbelievable proportions
waiting to happen.''
He said Scottish Office Ministers had promised to look at the possibility of
conducting an enhanced survey. He welcomed the news that BGS might be involved
in research work. Mr Foulkes added: ``There should be a moratorium on
commercial activity until we get a full explanation as to the cause of the
explosions.''
A Scottish Office spokesman confirmed that talks were taking place.
The official survey report from the Marine Laboratory in Aberdeen is due to be
published on January 8. Gas is due to start flowing through the pipeline by
October next year.
</TEXT>
