<HEADLINE>Late booking rush starts for festive holidays in the sun</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749699</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE are in a rush to get away to the sun over Christmas and New Year,
according to travel agents.
Last-minute bookings for the festive period have been taken, mainly for the
Canary Islands.
Portugal is also a favourite, according to tourist group Frutin Travel, whose
holidays are on offer at #130 for seven nights in Portugal with return flights
included.
A spokesman for the company said that apartment holidays at #350 including
flights, on a week-long basis, were being taken at late notice.
He added: ``We have also noted that the Canaries is a popular choice for the
New Year, because of its climate.''
A.T Mays said that it too was experiencing heavy bookings over the New Year
period, with the Canaries, Cyprus, Florida, and winter sports resorts in Europe
the main choices.
Thomson said it would be taking about 100,000 people away, many going to far
away spots such as Barbados and the Indian Ocean.
British Midland airline, which has recently opened new routes in Europe,
confirmed that it was taking additional bookings.
Going Places estimates that more than 500,000 Britons will be heading abroad
over the festive period.
British Airways is expected to take 250,000 people overseas. While operating no
domestic flights on Christmas Day, it will operate 24 long-haul flights from
Heathrow, along with 11 short-haul flights. Included in its menu are 1300
turkeys.
Glasgow and Edinburgh airports said yesterday that while demand was high, no
additional flights were scheduled because bookings in general had been made
earlier this year.
A spokeswoman at Glasgow airport said: ``We are busy, and Tenerife is proving
very popular this year because of its climate.''
Direct Holidays, which recently opened a new office in Edinburgh, said it was
enjoying heavy bookings, particularly to the Canaries.
It was quoting self-catering prices for a week, including return flights, at
#239, #319 for a fortnight, and #369 on a half-board basis in a four-star hotel.
</TEXT>
