<HEADLINE>Union welcomes bullying inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749700</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE council workers' union, Unison, yesterday welcomed an internal inquiry into
allegations of bullying and harassment within Scotland's second biggest
district council.
Preliminary findings are expected to be presented to the chief executive of
Edinburgh District Council, Mr William Blyth, next month.
Senior Unison official John Ross said the large-scale allegations of bullying,
harassment, and victimisation had come from nine members of staff and four
former workers within the temporary accommodation section of the authority's
housing department.
``The situation was first raised with us a year ago and we asked for an inquiry
at that time. It appears to have been a situation which has arisen over a
number of years, but it is only now that the staff have said enough is
enough,'' he said.
Mr Ross said he could not comment on whether the complaints targeted certain
individuals within the department, but welcomed the appointment of the
council's director of planning, Mr Graham Duncan, as head of the investigation.
Edinburgh District Council yesterday confirmed it had launched an investigation
into the allegations.
Mr Blyth said: ``I have called for an investigation into allegations made by
Unison on behalf of employees and ex-employees in the temporary accommodation
section of the housing department. The council will not be saying anything
futher until the investigation is complete.''
</TEXT>
