<HEADLINE>A short walk away from Glasgow's bustling hub, Christmas cheer is in short supply Dining on crumbs of comfort</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749701</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE festive lights end at Argyle Street, but spotlit by the unaccustomed angle
of the winter sun, the Saltmarket glitters. Children coax a tune from an old
toy piano. Parents pick over the second hand clothes, plates, and pictures that
once were someone's pride and joy, and bug-eyed soft toys that fell off a
lorry. ``My God, it's freezin,'' screech the traders, cheerful because the
buying frenzy has seeped down to Paddy's Market at last.
Purple decorations dangle in a window in the High Court building. Next door in
Hope House, equally garish tinsel spirals round the pillars of the Oasis day
room. The only other colour among the grubby walls and stacking chairs of the
Salvation Army hostel is in the language of the group clustered round the pool
table.
``They do their best to make it cheerful,'' says John, in quiet gratitude. If
you met him spinning out his Invalidity Benefit in the cafes or pubs around the
Clyde, you'd take him for a generation older than his 49 years. He's been in
the hostel for three weeks since he came out of hospital, after a stroke, but
this is his second time round this particular route. He split up with his wife
two years ago as a result of both his and her problem with alcohol. She's now a
member of Alcoholics Anonymous, but he's never been one for meetings.
He visits fairly regularly, taking his washing in a plastic bag, but he's not
sure whether he's up to a family Christmas. With six children, it used to be a
great occasion when they were small. ``I was working so it wisnae a problem to
buy presents, but I feel sorry for young folk with two or three kids now with
all this unemployment.
``To tell the truth, I've no been feeling too good,'' he says. It seems he will
be just as likely to stay in Clyde Street to share the Hope House turkey.
About half the 120 residents will be there for Christmas dinner, unable or
unwilling to go to relatives. Nora Morrison will be among them as she has been
for the last dozen years. At 81 she has no family now except for a few cousins
- ``And what would would cousins ever do for you?''
She'll be singing the old carols on Christmas morning in Hope House, the
Salvation Army hostel in Glasgow. She was a fine singer in her youth on Lewis
and the service every morning is one her the chief joys of her life. A large
capable woman, whose appearance belies her age, she's one of the few elderly
people to live in the hostel as more people are channelled to independent
living. It is partly because she's used to institutional living in hotels and
hospitals, but more because she is frightened to live on her own in a big city,
that she has made a hostel for the homeless her home.
``I had a flat, but Glasgow people can be awful clannish. They wouldn't knock
on the door, just push a card underneath at Christmas. I'll never forget
that,'' she says, unable still to fathom a way of life which does not include
visiting and helping your neighbours.
With the guileless art of the Celtic storyteller, she recalls leaving home at
17 to follow the herring as the country girls did, though the town girls from
Stornoway wouldn't consider it. Her job was to pack as quick as lightning,
despite frozen fingers, the fish her friends had gutted in Shetland, Mallaig,
North Shields, Hull, Lowestoft, or Yarmouth. An only child, Nora was born two
weeks after her father was killed in the First World War and was very close to
her mother, returning home at every opportunity.
During the Second World War she worked in the munitions factory at Bishopton
and in an aircraft factory in Birmingham. She was married briefly, but with no
possibility of a house of their own, there was conflict between whose parents
they would live with and she returned to her mother. Nora describes her as a
very godly person. ``The woman next door to us was married to a fisherman and
when there were no fish, they didn't have much money. Many's the time I've seen
my mother go to the van and buy a bag of groceries for her. She had a heart of
gold.''
After her mother's death, Nora found domestic work in a hotel then in hospitals
in the South of England, returning to Scotland for her retirement. ``I accepted
a flat in Castlemilk, but it was next to the lift in a multi-storey block and I
was so worried about someone breaking down the door that I was sitting up until
five in the morning. I have my room here where I can go to have a rest or write
a letter. I come down to watch the television, but it can get very noisy if
there are a lot of young people and I had money taken out of my handbag once
when I dozed off. There are some terrible people about. You could not make
friends with them. But it is very well run and Major Ward and his wife won't
take any nonsense. As well as paying for my bed, I pay #14 a week for my meals
in advance so I know I'll always get my food and then I save up to buy soap and
stockings and the things you need.
``We have a fine Christmas. It's not something we bothered with at home; that
was more New Year.'' Nora was heading south to find work when the former
barracks opened its doors to the homeless 30 years ago. Legislation and housing
benefit has changed much since then, but not the need of those who knock on the
door and ask for shelter.
</TEXT>
