<HEADLINE>Dart world ponders pit stop</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749702</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TV EXECUTIVES have developed a hi-tech strategy to increase even further - as
if that were possible - the excitement of darts.
For it is now possible for viewer to watch the game from an armpit level.
Sky Sports is pioneering the ``chest cam'' during the forthcoming televised WDC
World Darts Championship staged in Purfleet, Essex.
Tiny but still visible cameras will be attached to the clothing of players such
as Jocky Wilson and Eric Bristow.
The World Darts Council, a breakaway from the British Darts Organisation and
now holding its third world championship on Sky, is known for its showmanship.
Commentator Sid Waddell insisted the new camera angle would shed light on
serious aspects of dart play. He said this is a good idea because it shows how
much control the players have over the arc of flight.
The commentator did not think the cameras would impede the players. ``Some of
'em wear about three pounds in gold jewellery. If you hid a camera in that lot,
you would never notice it.''
</TEXT>
