<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Diana keeps royal party waiting</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749703</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS of the royal family were gathering for Christmas at Sandringham last
night, still waiting to hear whether the Princess of Wales will consent to a
``quickie'' divorce.
The princess is taking time to consider her response to the Queen's call for an
early divorce to end the 14-year marriage.
She turned down an invitation to spend Christmas at Sandringham and will be
away from Prince William, 13, and Prince Harry, 11, who will be at the Norfolk
estate with their father.
There is a belief she will agree to an early divorce, but could wait until the
new year before announcing her decision.
Instead of being with her children on Christmas Eve and Christmas Day, as
originally planned, she is expected to fly abroad for a holiday, possibly
skiing in the US, at Vail, Colorado.
She could also spend some time, probably in London, visiting the homeless and
other disadvantaged people as part of her ``queen of hearts'' charity work.
Whatever her decision on divorce, she will wish to obtain a deal which
guarantees her status, her position within the royal family and a high-profile
role as a goodwill ambassador before she gives her consent, according to one
newspaper report.
She is said to be appalled by the leaking of the Queen's call for a swift end
to her 14-year marriage.
She blames the disclosure on her husband's camp, according to the Daily Mail
report which claims she has asked her friends: ``How could they do this at
Christmas?''
In her Panorama interview, the princess said she was against a divorce, but
wanted to hear her husband's views.
Now, following the Queen's call, which has the backing of
the Prime Minister and Archbishop of Canterbury, Charles has let his wife know
he believes it is for the best.
Charles has acted to end speculation about his future and remove possible
objections to his becoming king by making it known he would not remarry after a
divorce.
The response puts to an end mounting speculation that the heir to the throne
might marry divorcee Camilla Parker Bowles.
Meanwhile, senior royals at Sandringham with the Queen and Duke of Edinburgh
were expected to include the Queen Mother, convalescing after her recent hip
replacement operation, Princess Margaret, her daughter Lady Sarah Chatto and
artist husband Daniel, and Margaret's son Viscount Linley and his wife
Viscountess Serena.
The Princess Royal is expected with her husband Commander Timothy Laurence and
children Peter Phillips, 18, and Zara Phillips, 14.
The Duke of York will stay with the rest of the family at Sandringham House
while his estranged wife, the duchess, will be at Wood Farm, nearby on the
estate, with daughters Princess Beatrice, seven, and Princess Eugenie, five.
The young princesses usually open their presents with their cousins at the
``Big House'', in Hanoverian tradition, on Christmas Eve.
In the past, the Queen has called in at Wood Farm for tea with the duchess.
Prince Edward is also expected at Sandringham but it is thought unlikely he
will be joined by girlfriend Sophie Rhys-Jones until after Christmas.
Speculation continues to mount that Edward and Sophie will announce their
engagement early in the new year.
</TEXT>
