<HEADLINE>Explorer sets third Polar record</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749704</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Oslo, Friday
FIFTY researchers formed a circle around the South Pole and cheered Norwegian
adventurer Borge Ousland as he dragged his sled the last yards of his third
polar skiing record.
The 45-day, 838 miles trek made Ousland the first person to ski alone and
unaided to both Poles.
Last year, he set the solo record for the North Pole, and in 1990 he and
another Norwegian were the first team make that trek with no help. Ousland has
also skied across Greenland.
``He got a fantastic reception at the South Pole,'' Ousland's spokesman, Hans
Christian Erlandsen, said after speaking to the skier by short-wave radio.
A doctor at the Scott-Amundsen Base examined Ousland and pronounced him fit,
except for some minor frost bite.
Ousland's trip, however, was only half over. He plans to ski all the way across
the frozen continent, becoming the only person to do that also.
Ousland and British adventurer Roger Mear, 45, both set off from Berkner Island
in the Weddell Sea in early November on separate efforts to become the first to
make the solo crossing. Mear gave up and was rescued on December 17.
On his return, Mear blamed the wrong type of snow.
His high-tech sled sank into snowdrifts and caused so much delay he radioed for
help after 41 days on the ice cap.
The 45-year-old Derbyshire explorer admitted the sled, which carried his
supplies for the 100-day walk across the sub-continent, had not been tested in
Antarctic conditions.
His defeat ended a race reminiscent of the first Norwegian-British showdown at
the South Pole in 1911, when Norwegian Roald Amundsen beat Briton Captain
Robert Scott in a race to conquer Antarctica. Scott and four team-mates died on
their way back.
Ousland will probably rest for a couple of days, before starting the 50-day
trek to the American McMurdo base on the other side of Antarctica.
``I don't think he'll say no to a good Christmas dinner at the Pole if he's
invited to the base,'' Erlandsen said.-AP.
</TEXT>
