<HEADLINE>Foreign Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749705</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Afghans deny
bombing link
PESHAWAR: The Afghan government denied yesterday that it had any responsibility
for a car bomb that killed 36 people and wounded more than 100 in the
northwestern Pakistani city of Peshawar. Official Kabul radio said some
Pakistani officials had blamed the Afghan government for Thursday's blast in a
busy shopping street.
Islamabad and Kabul have been on frosty terms since the Pakistani embassy in
the Afghan capital was sacked in September by protesters accusing Pakistan of
supporting the rebel Taleban militia. Islamabad denies the charge.
Fight for life
ATHENS; Doctors fighting to save ailing Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou
said yesterday he was fending off a new secondary infection but was still in
critical condition. ``In the last six hours the infection seems to be
controlled by antibiotics. His breathing is supported periodically by a
respirator. His heart has not been affected,'' the latest medical bulletin
said.
Kabul attacks
ISLAMABAD: The opposition Islamic Taleban militia fired 23 rockets at Kabul
overnight and yesterday, killing five people and wounding 22,
government-controlled Kabul radio reported. The radio, monitored in Islamabad,
said at least 12 rockets landed in Kabul on Thursday night, killing five people
and wounding 18, and a salvo of 11 rockets yesterday wounded four people.
Several shops and houses were destroyed.
Banda claim
BLANTYRE: A judge said yesterday there was no evidence showing that former
Malawian president Kamuzu Banda ordered the killing of four politicians in
1983. ``Although Banda had unlimited authority and power, there is no evidence
adduced in court to suggest that he ordered the killing,'' Judge Mackson
Mkandawire told the court and jurors during a summary of the case.
US quake
SAN FRANCISCO: A 4.9 magnitude earthquake rattled the Tahoe Valley area along
the northern California-Nevada border early yesterday, but officials said the
tremor caused no damages or injuries. The tremor struck at about 1 am and was
felt from Sacramento, California, to Yosemite National Park. It was centred
about 25 miles southwest of Yerington, Nevada, and about seen miles north
northwest of Markleeville, California, in the Tahoe Valley area along the
California-Nevada border.
Burundi fears
GENEVA: Gunmen are killing at will in Burundi, dragging the country into a
``genocidal trend'', a United Nations human rights investigator said yesterday.
Paulo Sergio Pinheiro, a Brazilian law professor who serves as special
investigator, warned that the Burundi ethnic crisis might explode and lead to a
mass exodus of Rwandan refugees.
</TEXT>
