<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man freed ahead of fire inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749706</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN charged with two murders after a fire at a hotel in Aviemore has been
released from prison, and the case against him has been continued.
In the meantime it was announced yesterday a fatal accident inquiry into the
New Year's Day blaze at the Four Seasons Hotel will go ahead on April 16 at
Inverness Sheriff Court.
After investigations police arrested 21-year-old Alan Moffat, of Drumpellier
Street, Blackhill, Glasgow, in late August and charged him with the murder of
fire victims Graham Strachan, 64, a Scott Lithgow director from Strathblane,
Stirlingshire, and Leeds woman Patricia Shaw, 55.
Mr Moffat was remanded to the Inverness's Porterfield Prison to await trial.
However, since the Crown Office was allowed to keep him in custody for no more
than 110 days before bringing the case to court, prosecuters ordered his
release on November 8.
With Mr Moffat at liberty, the Crown has a year from his original court
appearance to bring the case to trial rather than 110 days.
The four star Stakis-owned hotel was reopened at the beginning of August.
Mr Peter Watson, of Glasgow solicitors Levy and MacRae, who is representing the
families of the two victims, said: ``We are very pleased that a fatal accident
inquiry is finally being held. It has been a very difficult time for the
families.
``We will be expecting to hear a full explanation of the circumstances
surrounding the fire.''
</TEXT>
