<HEADLINE>Belfast killings raise fears that terrorist squads remain active Anger at refusal to free IRA men</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749707</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENSION increased between Sinn Fein and the Irish Government last night after
the Cabinet decided not to free nine IRA prisoners in time for Christmas.
The decision was made in the light of killings in Belfast this week linked to
the IRA, and a report that police had uncovered a plot by active service units
to stage a series of raids on cash shipments in-transit.
Information about the IRA plot from security chiefs moved the Cabinet to halt
the scheduled early release of the nine men.
Their release would have been part of Dublin's continuing bid to progress the
Northern Ireland peace process. Instead, they were only given parole for the
Christmas holiday, to return to jail by the New Year.
Among the nine is Thomas McMahon, who was jailed for life for the murder of
Earl Mountbatten on a fishing trip off County Sligo 16 years ago. Already
frequently released on parole, he has been on a pre-release training scheme for
almost a year.
If the IRA men had been freed permanently, they would have brought to 45 the
number of terrorist prisoners released by Dublin since the start of the
Northern Ireland ceasefire last year.
Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's senior strategist said, the move was a slap in
the face for his party.
Party leaders are expected to seek an early meeting with Irish Premier John
Bruton to discuss the decision. However, in the absence of further IRA-linked
incidents, more releases should be approved by Dublin early in the new year.
Maire Geoghegan-Quinn, former Irish justice minister said for the Irish Fianna
Fail opposition party that no government would take a decision to cancel
releases lightly.
``Looked at in the overall situation, there is no doubt widespread concern that
the recent spate of killings in Northern Ireland may have some connection with
the IRA.
``The decision has to be based on very careful consideration of sensitive
security information.''
Meanwhile, loyalist and republican prisoners left Northern Ireland's top
security Maze prison yesterday to spend Christmas with their families.
They have been given the usual seven days parole but there were complaints from
loyalists that with the ceasefire continuing they were not being allowed to
stay out for New Year.
Loyalists were let out first, followed by republicans.
Some 450 inmates applied for parole and around 390 were given it, said the
Prison Service - 25 more than last year.
Increases in remission for paramilitary prisoners introduced last month - up
from one third to 50% - meant that an extra 80 men had completed enough of
their sentence to qualify for parole.
The Northern Ireland Office said 86 prisoners were given final release last
month following the remission changes.
Against expectations, no IRA men transferred permanently from England to
Northern Ireland jails since the ceasefire to serve out their sentences for
mainland bombings and shootings were released.
The Prison Service said none of them qualified for parole.
Prisoners have to have served at least 11 years of their sentence, or in the
case of lifers, to have been given a provisional release date or had a
recommendation made to the Secretary of State for a release date by the life
sentence review board.
The decision has to be based on very careful consideration of sensitive
security information
Maire Geoghegan-Quinn,
former justice minister
</TEXT>
