<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents' day at Murrayfield</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749708</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was a royal fan club at Murrayfield yesterday as Peter Phillips, the
Queen's grandson, made sporting history when he played for the Scottish schools
rugby side.
The Princess Royal watched her son, with her husband Commander Timothy
Laurence, and Peter's sister, Zara. The boy's father, Captain Mark Phillips,
also attended the match, against a French schools side.
Peter, 18, is the first royal to play for his country at international level,
but the Scottish team, alas, lost 18-12 at a wet and windy Murrayfield. The
Princess Royal, who is president of the Scottish Rugby Union, declined to watch
the match from the royal box, choosing instead to join other parents in the
crowd of around 300.
The French side dominated the game from the beginning, scoring three tries,
while the Scots managed to score only through penalties.
After the match, Mr Tom Robertson, president of the Scottish schools rugby
team, said that the entire team, including Peter, had played well.
``They gave everything they had and Peter played his part to the full. He did
everything we expected him to do,'' he said.
He said it was now a matter for the selectors to decide if he will play in the
next international, against Wales on January 5.
After the match, Captain Phillips left with the rest of the royal party.
</TEXT>
