<HEADLINE>News Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749709</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Back door only
at City Halls
ACCESS to Glasgow City Halls will be through the back door only for the next
four years. The halls in Candleriggs are currently under renovation and signs
outside the main entrance redirect visitors to the back until June 1999.
A Glasgow District Council spokesman said: ``It's not like we are trying to
rebuild the pyramids or anything, but the work will take four years.''
Coining it
OLD coins left outside Strathcarron Hospice near Denny in Stirlingshire have
raised #40 for its funds. The coins were found in an old ice-cream carton with
the words ``For Strathcarron Hospice'' written on it.
Drugs warning
TWO young women who took amphetamine at a nightclub were admonished yesterday
at Stirling Sheriff Court. Mhairi Fleming of Broompark View, East Calder, and
Janey Agnew, of Trapain Crescent, Bathgate, both 20, had sentence deferred for
six months to be of good behaviour.
Post record
THE Post Office will have delivered almost 1.9 billion cards and letters by
Christmas Eve. Chief executive John Roberts said this had been its busiest year
and an extra 70 million items had been handled.
Radar glitch
THE Government has admitted that a new Royal Navy coastal radar has been
affecting the hearing aids of pensioners in Plymouth. A team of experts
examined the complaint regarding the installation at HMS Gunnery School after
pensioners reported hearing regular bleeps in their hearing aids.
Welcome signs
THE Scottish Tourist Board chairman, Mr Ian Grant, yesterday welcomed relaxing
the rules on signposting tourist attractions. Under the new Scottish Office
guidelines signs can be used for commercial enterprises and policy will be
decided locally.
Missing plea
POLICE in Edinburgh have asked for help in tracing a 13-year-old girl who has
been missing since November 25. Debbie Reid, who is also known as Cheyne, was
last seen when she set off from Ratho for a shopping trip in the capital. She
is about 5ft tall, of heavy build, with dark brown hair and eyes, and was
wearing a navy Reebok sweatshirt, checked blouse, and beige jeans.
Climber injured
STUDENT Martin Williams, 21, of Castleview Drive, Bridge of Allan, was
recovering in Belford Hospital, Fort William, with injured arms last night,
after falling 20ft in Corie Ne Ciste, on Ben Nevis, when one of his crampons
broke. He was taken by a Sea King helicopter from RAF Lossiemouth after his two
companions alerted rescue services.
</TEXT>
