<TEXT>
Councillors reject
city mosque plan
A PROPOSAL to build a new mosque in Aberdeen on a five-acre site, at the corner
of King Street and the beach esplanade, has been rejected by city councillors.
The present mosque in the Spital is said to be too small, but the arts and
recreation committee decided yesterday the King Street site was inappropriate
and referred the decision to the property committee.
Heated attack
EAST ANGUS MP Andrew Welsh yesterday in Arbroath attacked the Government for
cutting #31m from its home insulation grants scheme ,from #100m to #69m, next
year. The SNP housing spokesman said the cut would increase health risks for
those in poorly insulated houses, could mean 200,000 fewer houses being
insulated, the loss of 1000 jobs, and a #12m fall in sales to insulation
suppliers.
Victim named
POLICE have named the victim of a road accident on the A93 Blairgowrie to
Braemar road as Mr William Paisley, 33, of Broughty Ferry, Dundee. He was
travelling south when his red Honda Prelude left the road south of Bridge of
Cally during heavy snow.
Police move
GRAMPIAN joint police board is considering the #20m Woodhill House, the home of
outgoing Grampian Regional Council, as its new headquarters, it was disclosed
yesterday.
</TEXT>
