<HEADLINE>The #185m number comes up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749711</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS came early to the holiday island of Majorca yesterday when the #185m
top prize from Spain's biggest lottery ``El Gordo'' (The Fat One) - billed as
the world's richest - showered on the capital, Palma.
Wine flowed and people danced and sang in the streets as it was revealed that
the jackpot was shared between holders of 117 tickets bearing the number 45495.
Each ticket is worth #1.5 million, and the winning tickets were sold entirely
in the working class Coll d'Enravassa neighbourhood of Palma.
Within minutes of the winning number being drawn at lottery headquarters in
Madrid traffic police were rushing to Antonio Duran's lottery shop in the area
to try to sort out a massive jam.
Mr Duran said: ``Everyone seems to have won something, the tickets were that
spread out.
``I didn't keep a ticket for myself, but someone gave me two small shares as a
present.'' He won #8000.
``We'll be treating everyone to champagne,'' said a chef at a hotel whose staff
bought one of the winnning tickets.
``It's the first time it's happened to me,'' said a middle-aged woman. ``And
it's more than welcome; my husband is unemployed and my house is old.''
Each lottery ticket costs #160 and they are normally bought by friends,
families or workmates who club together to take shares. It was not known
exactly how many people held this year's winning tickets.
El Gordo is a national obsession in Spain and the country comes to a standstill
each December 22 as people watch a nationwide live television broadcast to see
if they have struck lucky.
In keeping with tradition, 28 boys and girls from Madrid's San Ildefonso school
took turns drawing the winning numbers.
The 1995 lottery was expected to pay out a total of almost #1000m in prizes. El
Gordo is ranked as the world's richest lottery although others often award
larger top prizes.
Statistics show Spaniards are the world's biggest gamblers after Filipinos.
</TEXT>
