<HEADLINE>Fishermen's leader says new quotas may lead to cheating</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749712</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE European fish deal met a cool welcome yesterday from Scotland's fishermen
who say it is a poor agreement, though it could have been
worse.
Some predicted last night that in spite of the concessions won some fishermen
would be forced to land illegally caught fish - black fish - to survive.
They added that jobs on land and at sea could be lost as a result of the cuts
involved in the agreement reached after 14 hours of talks.
Scottish Fisheries Minister Raymond Robertson welcomed the deal as the best
which could have been secured. He said: ``Overall this deal has to be seen as
a
balanced one and the best which could have been negotiated for our fishermen.
``Tony Baldry, the UK Fisheries Minster, and I were determined to strike the
right balance between responsible fish management to ensure a healthy future
for the industry and avoiding too much disruption in the short term.
``We achieved important increases in the stocks of interest to the Scottish
fleet - an extra 16,700 tonnes of herring and an extra 4700 tonnes of whiting.
``Overall, therefore, we have achieved a level of quotas for the Scottish
whitefish fleet at around the same level as this year both in the North Sea
and
in the West of Scotland.''
Mr Robertson added: ``The quotas for mackerel and North Sea herring are much
lower than for 1995. That reduction follows a number of years of intensive and
profitable fishing and we have to respect the warning from the scientists
about
the worrying state of these two stocks.''
However, his optimism for the future was not shared by the fishing community
even though the delegation was able to add more than 50,000 tonnes of fish
worth about #30m to the UK quota.
The industry pointed out that the success was simply in reducing the cuts they
face.
The processing industry demanded that catches be fixed years in advance,
rather
than days, to provide stability and to allow them to plan ahead like other
businesses.
The agreement was condemned by Mr Tom Hay, chairman of the Fishermen's
Association, the new organisation formed by disenchanted fishermen because of
the refusal of the Scottish White Fish Producers' Association to back moves
for
Britain to withdraw from the Common Fisheries Policy.
Mr Hay said that even before the cuts Scottish fishermen were unable to live
within the law and even more would now be forced to become law breakers by
landing black fish.
``These throttling regulations emanating from Brussels will mean more
fishermen
cheating and falsifying any document they can to retain their viability,'' he
said. ``This is a terrible situation.''
He added that conservation measures would only be respected by Scottish
fishermen if they were to reap the benefits in the future.
Mr Hay said he believed there had never been any over-fishing by British
vessels and that they had been granted derisory proportions from the 80% of
stocks within ``our waters''.
It was vessels from Spain and Portugal which were plundering the stocks and
the
solution to the problems could be achieved overnight by taking back into
British control an exclusive fishing zone.
The chief executive of Aberdeen Fish Merchants and Curers Association, Mr
Robert Milne, also predicted problems but said they were totally opposed to
CFP
withdrawal although the whole quota system had to be changed.
``I feel under the circumstances the Ministers have done as well as they
possibly could but really the quota levels are still such that industry ashore
and afloat cannot survive on that.
``I am very critical of the mechanism where we are told on December 22 what the
availability of raw materials will be for the
next year. No industry can operate like that.
``We have got to get a system in place where we know, possibly years in
advance, what the availability is going to be. We have
got to get multi-annual Total Allowable Catches.
Mr Milne said: ``The uncertainty is costing us a lot of money and is making us
less efficient than we would want to be.''
He added: ``I do think the time has come when our negotiations must take much
less notice of the scientific evidence. Marine
science is a very inaccurate science and more recognition must be taken of what
the fishermen are saying. They are out there all
the time and know what the stocks are like.''
Mr Bob Allan, chief executive of the Scottish Fishermen's Federation, agreed
that the Ministers had got as much out of it as
they could but from a very poor starting point.
He condemned the way Norway had been able to dictate terms in its negotiations
with the Commission and had asked the Ministers
to try to reopen the Norway negotiations, something they were not prepared to
attempt.
He said it was not a good deal for pelagic fishermen but the white fish
situation was not as bad as it might have been and the
Ministers deserved credit for that.
One of the things they had argued long and hard for was an increase in west
coast prawns from January 1, not like this year when
a review gave them an increase too late to be effective. He said they had been
unsuccessful but were assured the same review
mechanisms were in place and would be acted upon far earlier.
The main changes for British fishermen in key North Sea, western waters and
English channel fishing grounds nexy year compared
with UK catch quotas for this year are: herring - total quota for 1996 101,270
tonnes (117,840 in 1995); North Sea cod - 54,860
tonnes (50,960); haddock - 86,620 tonnes (85,215); whiting - 41,840 tonnes
(40,220); hake - 5460 tonnes (5900); North Sea plaice
- 22,290 tonnes (30,440); mackerel - 144,940 tonnes (217,350); North Sea sole -
990 tonnes (1285)
</TEXT>
