<HEADLINE>Russian communists stay ahead in poll count</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749714</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Friday
THE communists were firmly in the lead in Russia's parliamentary election, five
days after the vote, and final figures should be announced on Monday, the
Central Electoral Commission said today.
In voting on a party basis, which allocates half the 450 seats in the State
Duma lower house of parliament, the Communist Party remained first on 21.81% of
the votes cast after counting from 196 of the 225 electoral districts.
This, together with a strong showing in single-mandate constituency voting
which decides the other 225 seats, means the Communist Party led by Gennady
Zyuganov will occupy about one third of the seats in the new Duma.
The results, announced late today, fluctuated only slightly on the figures
published earlier in the day, when a commission official said about 56 million
votes had been counted from the December 17 election in the world's biggest
country.
The position of the top four parties set to clear the five percent barrier to
win places through party lists remained unchanged.
The communists were followed by the ultra-nationalists of Vladimir Zhirinovsky
on 11.29%. Third was Our Home is Russia of Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin,
on 9.74%.
The fourth group set to clear the five percent barrier needed to take up seats
in the Duma was the liberal Yabloko movement of economist Grigory Yavlinsky,
with 7.03%.
All other 39 parties were below the threshold and were not expected to clear it
when the commission announces the final count.
The count in the 225 first-past-the-post individual constituencies was
unofficially finished yesterday.
The communists won 58 of these constituency places. The Agrarian Party, a
likely ally for the communists, had 20 places, while Yabloko had 14 and
Chernomyrdin's bloc 10.
Altogether, 77 constituency seats have been won by independents who have yet to
declare their loyalties. Some may support the communists, although in the last
Duma most were pro-government.
Apart from the combined total of about 150 seats which the communists are
expected to have, around 30 other seats are expected to go to other leftist
parties.
Meanwhile, Russian troops laid siege to Chechnya's second town today after an
eighth day of fighting with separatist rebels who are holding strategic
buildings and pinning down isolated Russian units.
Lieutenant-General Stanislav Kavun, deputy commander of Russian interior troops
in Chechnya, said 36 of his men had been killed in the region since an upsurge
in fighting last week at the start of Russian parliamentary and local
elections. -Reuter.
</TEXT>
