<HEADLINE>Serbs set to flee with their dead New fears as Muslims prepare to take control of Sarajevo</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From KURT SCHORK Sarajevo, Friday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749715</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME Sarajevo Serbs dug up their dead today ready to flee the Bosnian capital
before Serb areas revert to Muslim-led government control under a peace plan
backed by a Nato-led, 60,000-strong world army.
``My heart has a terrible pain because we Serbs have been sold by the
politicians,'' lamented 32-year-old Jadranko as he and other relatives exhumed
the bodies of a father and son killed in the worst European conflict for 50
years.
With the peace signed and Nato gradually taking control over the peacekeeping
mission, the Bosnian government said today it was ending the formal state of
war which has existed since June 1992 on territory it controls. For the time
being a lesser state of alert would remain in force, the Bosnian state news
agency said. The decision, which was widely expected, comes a week after
Bosnia's self-styled Serb Republic announced it was ending its state of war.
A statement issued by Bosnia's presidency offered security guarantees to Serbs
living in suburbs around Sarajevo and called on them not to flee ahead of the
transfer of their areas to government control.
But despite this and assurances from Nato and the international sponsors of
last week's Paris peace agreements, many Serbs fear they will become victims
when the entire, Serb-besieged city comes under Muslim control.
``After (the peace agreeement) this is Moslem (Bosnian government) territory.
They will destroy our tombstones. We have here many Muslim tombstones. They are
not destroyed. But when the Muslims come, they will destroy ours,'' Jadranko
said.
As Nato troops fanned out across the country, the UN Security Council voted to
create a 1700-strong police force to control, recruit and organise local police
to allay such fears.
The force, to cost $90m in the first six months alone, is expected to be
deployed mainly in Serb suburbs of Sarajevo when they revert to government
control.
Leaders in these suburbs are preventing a Serb exodus in a final bid to reverse
parts of the Paris peace deal, UN aid officials said.
Thousands who want to leave their homes immediately are being stopped and
turned back at checkpoints or denied the paperwork they need as their leaders
campaign to make peace negotiators change their minds.
The UN-sponsored police force will come under the wing of Carl Bildt, the
European envoy in charge of civilian operations, who met Bosnian Serb leaders
in Pale today.
``It has been war, it is now peace, it is going to be very difficult to treat
the enemies of yesterday as partners of tomorrow,'' Bildt told reporters after
the meeting.
``Reconciliation is an extremely difficult thing to do. It is very easy to
start war, but it is very hard to have a genuine peace,'' he said after meeting
Velibor Ostojic, deputy ``prime minister'' of the Bosnian Serb government.
Nato officers reported that about 20,000 troops, a third of the Implementation
Force (IFOR), the largest in alliance history, had now deployed across the
wintry Bosnian landscape.
On the third day of its operation in Bosnia, Nato reported encountering no
resistance as the first units of the force penetrated further into the divided
country.
``There has been no significant delay of freedom of movement,''
Lieutenant-Colonel Mark Rayner, spokesman for the alliance's ACE Rapid Reaction
Corps, told reporters.
He said British forces had now reached the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Banja
Luka and secured other positions in areas previously barred to all foreign
troops.
A French general said his Nato troops would move within days to re-establish
freedom of movement around Bosnia's second major danger-point after Sarajevo,
the divided city of Mostar.
Brigadier-General Francois Gaubert said at a shell-battered airport in Ortijes,
a village just outside Mostar, he was determined to open up roads in the highly
sensitive area.
``Freedom of movement must be guaranteed throughout Bosnia, by day and by
night, and that is what we plan to do.''
Meanwhile, the Security Council today demanded that Croatia lift immediately a
December 27 deadline for Croatian Serbs, who fled Zagreb's army, to reclaim
their property.
In a statement read at a formal meeting, the council said that Croatia had
ignored earlier requests to lift any time limits on the return of refugees.
``The requirement that owners must reclaim their property by December 27
constitutes a virtually insurmountable obstacle for most Serb refugees,'' the
statement said.
``The Security Council strongly demands that the government of the Republic of
Croatia lift immediately any time-limits placed on the return of refugees to
reclaim property.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
