<HEADLINE>Hopes fade of more survivors in plane crash</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From GILLES CASTONGUAY Nogales, Colombia, Friday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749716</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESCUE workers all but gave up hope today of finding more survivors from the
wreckage of an American Airlines jet that smashed into an Andean mountain in
southwest Colombia with 164 people aboard.
Four people are known to have survived the crash of the Boeing 757 on Wednesday
night, four minutes before it was to land at Cali. At least 48 US citizens were
believed to be on board.
Other reports said six people were initially plucked alive from the wreckage,
nearly 12,000ft up on jungle-covered San Jose mountain, in Valle del Cauca
province.
But Cali University Hospital spokesman Humberto Rupiales said there were only
four survivors, and all were expected to fully recover.
``We don't expect to find more survivors,'' said Major Carlos Granados,
co-ordinator of the army rescue operation.
The plane's flight recorder was recovered early today and could provide
information why the aircraft apparently strayed up to 13 miles off course while
approaching Cali in clear weather. The ``black box'' is to be flown to the
United States for investigation.
Rupiales identified the survivors as Gonzalo Dussan, 37; his six-year-old
daughter, Michelle; Mercedes Ramirez, 21, and Mauricio Reyes, 19.
He said they were seated in the central part of the aircraft and were found
trapped amid twisted metal that may have shielded them from fatal injuries.
In Washington, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at least 48 US
citizens were believed to be on flight 965, which originated in Miami. ``This
is not a firm figure. It is possible that this figure could increase,'' Burns
said. Two of the four survivors are ``American citizens,'' he added.
Helicopters airlifted bodies in black plastic bags down to the town of Buga,
where rescue efforts are being co-ordinated and the bodies were being laid out
side-by-side for identification. Rescue efforts are expected to take about
three days, and Burns said about 20 US officials are involved in the effort and
the crash investigation.
The crash was the worst in Colombia's history. It was also the most deadly
involving a US carrier since the 1988 bombing of PanAm flight 103 over
Lockerbie that killed 270 people. It occurred within hours of the December 21,
1988, anniversary of the Lockerbie crash.
At the crash site reached after a three-hour walk through rugged and steep
terrain, relatives of passengers looked for their loved ones.
Dussan, a New Jersey man who was travelling with his wife and two children,
told reporters that he was unaware of any problems with the plane before he was
knocked unconscious when it hit the mountain. The fate of his wife and his son
was unknown.
Radio reports said the pilot reported nothing unusual seconds before the crash.
The airliner was carrying 156 passengers and a crew of eight. It went down in
an area dominated by leftist guerrillas, who have targeted radio beacons for
sabotage attacks in the past.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Double tragedy orphans boy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749717</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE parents of a nine-year-old boy have died within a few days of each other.
Ben Bradshaw - an only child - came home from school to find his mother dead
just two days after his father's funeral.
The results of a post-mortem examination to discover the cause of Annette
Bradshaw's death have yet to be released, a police spokesman said.
Her husband, builder Bill Bradshaw, died at the age of 45 last week from bowel
cancer.
Ben found his mother's body at the family home on the Peachcroft estate,
Abingdon, Oxfordshire, last Friday. He immediately dialled 999 and asked for an
ambulance and police.
Ben's headteacher, Mr John Fisher, said: ``This is a very tragic story and has
been a shock to us all. It has stunned the whole school. I sent a letter to
parents of all children at the school expressing our deep sympathy.
``Ben is an ordinary little lad and it is doubly tragic that it has happened at
this time of year.''
An inquest is expected to be held into the death of 44-year-old Mrs Bradshaw.
Ben is being looked after by relatives in Preston, Lancashire.
Mr David Hastings, a friend of the Bradshaw family who works as a computer
expert at Oxford University, said: ``Annette's death is a loss and it is hard
to react other than to be very shocked and sad.
``Ben took up most of her time, he is a lovely boy. He is very lively,
energetic and always very polite. This is such a tragic way for him to spend
Christmas.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Victims of gas rig explosion named</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749718</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Victims of gas rig explosion named
THE three men killed in an explosion on a gas rig at a Tyneside yard were named
yesterday.
Mr Steve Welford, 38, Mr Shaun McAlindon, 41, and Mr Ian Hamilton, 32, died in
the blast which happened when high-pressure gas escaped from a compression unit
100ft off the ground.
Mr Welford died instantly and Mr McAlindon and Mr Hamilton soon after in
hospital.
The men were working at Amec's Howdon yard on the River Tyne.
Mr Welford, of Whitley Bay, North Tyneside, Mr McAlindon, Jarrow, and Mr
Hamilton, of Hebburn, both South Tyneside, took the full blast as nitrogen
erupted from a pipe through which it was being passed to test the system.
The pipe fitters were also hit by pieces of metal as the structure gave way in
what a fire brigade spokesman said was like ``a balloon bursting under very
high pressure''.
Four other workers, Mr Philip Jeffries, 32, Mr James Marshall, 46, Mr Thomas
Lowe, 58, and Mr Eric Moir, 35, were released from hospital after treatment for
minor injuries and shock.
Apart from Mr Moir whose home is in Tornashban Gardens, Dyce, Aberdeen, the men
were all from the North-east of England.
The rig was undergoing final commissioning work before being towed across the
North Sea to start production on a new gas field off the coast of Denmark.
For Mr Hamilton, a father of two, it was his first shift of a 12-day temporary
contract to work on the rig.
His father-in-law, Mr Michael Watts, said: ``He was a fine upstanding young lad
- a smashing son-in-law and a splendid father.''
A spokesman at the home of Mr McAlindon, a father of teenage children, said his
wife Heather was too upset to talk.
Divisional officer Dave Simpson, of Tyne and Wear fire brigade, said: ``It was
a quite horrific incident. The men who died had no chance at all. They were
right on top of the pipe when it exploded.''
Health and Safety Executive officials are carrying out a full investigation.
A spokesman emphasised there was no evidence that safety regulations had been
breached.
Mr Dennis Scott, Amec's director of operations, said: ``There is nothing out of
the ordinary about the operation but obviously something did go wrong.
``There could be a number of reasons why it happened and I really would not
like to speculate until the investigation is completed.''
Amec was recently awarded the Sword of Honour by the British Safety Council for
its good safety record.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police plea for dignified vigil</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749719</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Police urged demonstrators to be ``peaceful and dignified'' at a vigil today to
be held in memory of Wayne Douglas. The 25-year-old's death in police custody
last week caused rioting in Brixton, south London, which resulted in #1m damage.
Police say two post-mortem examinations have ``vindicated'' the official
version of events that Mr Douglas's death was caused by a heart condition.
Campaigners claim, however, that he died while being restrained with excessive
force after being arrested for aggravated burglary.
</TEXT>
