<HEADLINE>Builders knife Wallace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749720</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PRIVATE housing development near a memorial which marks the spot where
William Wallace was betrayed and captured in 1305 is unlikely to be afforded
any connection with the Scottish patriot.
Glasgow District Council had refused a request to have streets named after
Wallace on the 520-house Briarcroft development built by Wimpey Homes at
Robroyston, in north-east Glasgow. The reason given was that several city
thoroughfares bore his name. Bartholomew's Glasgow Streetfinder lists 11 such
streets.
Yesterday the council appeared to relent. A spokesman said: ``If names
associated with the story of William Wallace can be incorporated into further
phases of this project we may consider them if we think they are appropriate.''
Mr William Douglas, secretary of the Society of William Wallace, welcomed the
change of heart, and said that the society would campaign to have the estate
named after Wallace.
However a spokeswoman for Wimpey Homes said: ``It is too late. The brochures
and signage.......have already been produced.''
A 20ft stone cross with a sculpted claymore and inscribed plaques, yards from
the estate, marks the site of the house where Wallace was seized by agents of
King Edward.I.
Supporters of Wallace will now have to take on Wimpey if their hero, recently
played by Mel Gibson in the film Braveheart, is to gain commemoration on the
estate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Angus is missed by EU jobs funding</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749721</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office has failed to win vital European funds for the Brechin area
which has been hit by the US Navy's gradual closure of its listening post at
Edzell, costing 400 jobs.
The European Union announced that #84m will be spent in Britain in areas hit by
the run-down in the defence industries.
Nearly #10m is coming to Scotland, which would generally be regarded as good
news. However, the delight was marred for Industry Ministry George Kynoch as he
was unable to secure any of the money for Edzell, which is in his own
constituency. Mr Kynoch has been criticised for lack of action by opponents.
Instead the money, which is in a spending programme called Konver, is being
used in Glasgow, Fife, Edinburgh, Cunninghame, and Argyll and Bute, where it
has to be matched by local authority money.
``The Government will continue to argue strongly for the area's inclusion and
will take the opportunity early in the new year to seek Edzell's inclusion
during discussions on proposals for extending the initiatives,'' said Mr Kynoch
yesterday.
Welcoming the money, Councillor Iain Macdonald of Strathclyde, chair of the
local authority based Arms Conversion Project, said there was still
insufficient help from the Government for local authorities, and he called for
a proper Defence Diversification Agency being established to bring together
defence companies, trade unions, local authorities, and Government departments
to tackle the problems of areas affected by defence closures.
The EU also announced #5.5m for Scotland to help alternative economic activity
in areas hit by textile closures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Arafat's wife joins Arab takeover Palestinians in Bethlehem celebrations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOMINIC EVANS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749722</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bethlem, West Bank, Friday
PLO leader Yasser Arafat's wife Suha arrived with her baby in Bethlehem today
as Palestinians celebrated their first day of rule over the traditional
birthplace of Jesus.
Hundreds of Palestinians cheered as the Christian-born Suha, carrying her
four-month-old daughter Zahwa, lit up a tall Christmas tree near the Church of
the Nativity.
``I am very happy to be here,'' she said, surrounded by Palestinian flags and
portraits of her Muslim husband, who was expected to make a triumphal entry
from Gaza tomorrow morning and attend Midnight Mass on Sunday.
Bethlehem yesterday became the fifth of six West Bank towns to be handed by
Israel to the Palestine Liberation Organisation by year's end under their
September deal expanding self-rule from Jericho and the Gaza Strip.
Earlier today, French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette was the first foreign
visitor to be received by Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij since the handover of the
town after 28 years of Israeli occupation.
``I am very glad to be in Bethlehem on the first day after the withdrawal. I
think it is a very good event for us to participate in the joy of the
Palestinian people. I feel very proud to be here,'' de Charette told reporters.
Mayor Freij presided over a ceremony today in which the Palestinian flag was
raised over former Israeli military headquarters to the skirl of bagpipes.
Freij denied reports on Israel Radio that citizens of the Jewish state would
not be welcome this Christmas in his town.
``We will not stop anyone coming to Bethlehem for shopping or sightseeing but
they must come without guns,'' he told Reuters.
But Israeli Tourism Minister Uzi Baram told Israel Radio: ``There is an
agreement between the (Palestinian self-rule) Authority and our groups that
Israelis will not go to Bethlehem to see the Christmas celebrations.''
The Israeli army said it was for now barring Israelis, but not foreign
tourists, from the town. Israelis were allowed only to visit Rachel's tomb on
Bethlehem's outskirts, it said.
Israeli soldiers yesterday waved to cheering Palestinians on leaving the
military headquarters. Church bells pealed, fireworks lit up the sky and
Palestinians fired off pistols when Israelis left Manger Square. Thousands sang
and danced.
The town of 45,000 is about 40% Christian and 60% Muslim. It is expected to be
flooded with 50,000 tourists on Christmas Eve.
Meanwhile, Arafat has appointed senior PLO figure, Mahmoud Abbas, to head a new
10-member commission supervising the first Palestinian elections next month,
officials said today.
The commission replaces an interim body which was headed by Saeb Erekat, a
member of the Palestinian Authority, who is also a candidate for the January 20
poll.
It is the first prominent post Abbas, better known as Abu Mazen, has taken
connected to the Palestinian self-rule deal with Israel he helped to negotiate
in Oslo in 1993.
Abbas was a key mover behind the breakthrough agreement but subsequently
withdrew from active public life and was reported to be unhappy at the way the
peace deal was being implemented.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
