<DOCNO>GH951223-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How to avoid catastrophe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749724</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is disappointing to see The Herald's economic forecasting reduced to the
level of the English press - whether or not there is confidence in the High
Street, whether or not there is a feel-good factor (For whom the tills tell,
December 20).
In any other field of knowledge such vague guesswork would be denounced as
meaningless mumbo-jumbo. There is a crying failure to link up these economic
vaticinations with other relevant areas of the economy.
As, for instance, that there are now some 20 million unemployed in Europe; and
that there is now, because of computerisation and automation, growth without
reduction of unemployment.
I even have it on good authority that the CBI thinks there will have to be a
40% reduction of costs throughout British industry.
The simple fact is that people do not have enough money in their pockets to
buy, despite the hype we shall read about Christmas sales breaking all records.
This is so because of competition, and hence downsizing, laying off hands, etc,
to keep the bottom line in the black.
The result is that fewer and fewer people are producing more and more goods,
working 60-hour weeks. So there is less and less money about to buy what this
hugely increased productivity produces.
It is not the consumers who hold the key to the economy. It is the Government
with its obsessive free-market dogma which is driving Britain towards economic
crisis.
What Britain needs is production for human welfare, not production for profit.
Otherwise we are heading straight for economic and social catastrophe.
Andrew Lockhart Walker,
7 Lovers' Loan, Dollar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bangour's future</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749725</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the 1980s the mention of the name ``Bangour General Hospital'' always
brought the response, ``Oh, yes, the burns unit''.
In fact, the fabulous testament to its history, The Bangour Story, written in
1991, shows within its covers that many and various firsts were pioneered there.
I'm sure that my late grandfather, who worked as a nurse there and never moved
more than half a mile from its 960 acres until he died in one of its wards in
1984, would have hoped that it could be preserved in some way with a lasting
memorial.
He certainly would have been very sad if he had thought that, when St John's
Hospital, Livingston, celebrates its twenty-fifth anniversary in the year 2015,
the buildings that made up its predecessor should be found in a similar
condition to those of Killearn Hospital (December 11).
Fiona McClay,
32 Lubnaig Gardens,
Bearsden.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Helpful Barras</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749726</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW is being promoted as a European and international city. Our museums and
galleries are free, well-attended, and win awards.
I show many overseas visitors around the city - the Tenement House, the
Burrell, Kelvingrove Art Gallery, and the Museum of Religion.
My last visitors, from New Zealand, were amazed and irritated to discover that
although they were able to buy postcards and greetings cards, they were unable
to buy the necessary stamps with which to post them.
Only 19p and 25p stamps were available but not the requisite 35p and 41p
stamps, or even the stamps to make up the postage for standard international
mail.
This was especially bizarre at Kelvingrove which even provides a letter-box.
The only helpful place was the square-yard section of the Barras Market where a
stallholder gave my friends stamps from his wallet.
The Barras gets none of the support the others do.
Simon Clegg,
36 South Woodside Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strong beacon</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749727</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I've a good mind to shout ``Christmas Tree!'' or sing ``Away in a Manger'' at
John Macleod just to spoil his Christmas.
I do, indeed, but I'm not allowed to. You see, as a Catholic who tries, often
unsuccessfully, to put into practice the rules of living laid upon me by my
pastors, my church, and my Maker, I must love John Macleod . . . and Ian
Paisley . . . and, man for man, the entire Rangers football team.
I don't have to like them but I must love them.
I know not of one thinking practising Catholic who has nowt but the greatest
admiration for the present Lord Chancellor. The quiet dignity, the steadfast
holding to principles (not notoriously Catholic principles), the sheer
integrity of the man, all shine out like a strong beacon in the filthy morass
of what we call Government.
To bring in ``assorted Roman Catholic bigots in high places already baying for
his blood,'' as being part-players in the recent Free Church family quarrel is,
in all seriousness, a matter for the psychiatrists (December 12).
Ian Fraser,
16 Whirlow Road,
Garrowhill, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
