<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cautious Blair   No intention of overturning changes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749729</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR BLAIR continues to ensure that Labour retains the image of moderation which
he has already imprinted on it. Just how important that is to its success may
only be guessed at but few would doubt that it is important to the lead Labour
at present enjoys in the opinion polls. The British political culture places no
premium on extremes - indeed, it is more likely to impose a penalty on any
party which allows itself to move too far from the middle ground where the
competition for votes is always most intense. Mr Blair has insisted that he has
no intention of overturning all the changes brought in by the Tories these past
16 years.
Several arguments suggest that he is right to be cautious. First, many of the
Thatcher changes, especially in industrial relations, were popular. At the
time, and even more with hindsight, it seems clear that the changes wanted by
Mrs Castle (``In Place of Strife'') during the Wilson administration would have
been enough to have satisfied public opinion about trade union rights and
responsibilities. The unions scuppered all of these, but the Thatcher proposals
which replaced them were more severe. Mr Blair must also have considered the
argument that any commitment to return to the old dispensation would simply arm
the Tories with tried-and-tested weaponry. Where the Tories did go too far - as
with union rights and representation at the communications centre at Cheltenham
- they are themselves beginning to retreat, a process Mr Blair will probably
both strengthen and speed. It is doubtful, however, if he will re-establish
unfettered rights to strike, the main right Mrs Thatcher withdrew.
Complete reversals of policy have been rare in post-1945 British politics. A
big exception concerned the steel industry which came and went from state
ownership more than once; but a general respect for each party's legislation
seems to have prevailed, mainly because the parties have not been as
ideologically motivated as their rhetoric would suggest. Each of the parties is
an informal coalition of groups and interests with a degree of overlap,
something which allows opinion to move to and fro far more easily than would be
the case were their separation more marked and permanent. In fact their own
centres of gravity move, something which has allowed Mr Blair to move Labour in
a direction and to an extent which makes it electable tomorrow where it was not
yesterday, so to speak.
Partisans do not always see this: they tend to imagine that votes are lost
because what a party offers is not extreme or ideological enough. In fact, it
is obvious that such opinion is immobile; whereas political change is brought
about by opinion which is fluid. Mr Blair is appealing to that sort of opinion
and he has to remain moderate to do so. He is far from being the first Labour
leader to know that: Neil Kinnock and John Smith both established similar
positions, to Labour's advantage, since its recovery in public esteem began
under them. Mr Blair is unusual only in that he has so far managed to marshal a
degree of support which escaped them. If he can maintain that into a General
Election campaign, Labour will be home and dry. Given the extent of the gap
between state revenues and public spending only a very bold critic would reject
Mr Blair's caution at this juncture. Its rejection would definitely involve an
open commitment to much higher direct personal taxation. Does anyone believe
that would be popular?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Spanish army officer killed by car bomb</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749730</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Leon, Spain, Friday
AN army officer and one other person died in a car bomb explosion in the
northern Spanish city of Leon today, police and local officials said.
Police confirmed that an artillery commander was killed when an explosive
device attached to a saloon car blew up soon after midday.
There was no immediate indication as to who was responsible, but the technique
was similar to that often employed by ETA (Basque Homeland and Freedom)
guerrillas.
Initial reports said the bomb had been attached to a car driven by the
commander in the centre of Leon, a major city in the region of Castilla-Leon.
ETA is last believed to have struck on December 11 when a car bomb went off in
a busy Madrid district last Monday, killing six navy employees and injuring a
dozen people.
No-one claimed responsibility for that attack but officials blamed ETA, which
has killed around 800 people in a 26-year-old struggle for Basque independence.
The officer was named as Major Luciano Cortizo who had been shopping in the
city. His 18-year-old daughter in the passenger seat was gravely injured in the
explosion and three passers-by were also taken to hospital.
In the past 11 days, ETA has killed eight people and injured 30 in three bomb
attacks.
Spain's chief of police said that there was no limit to the separatists'
campaign of ``terror for the sake of terror''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Retailer calls in BSE link scientist</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749731</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NATIONAL supermarket chain has called upon a scientist who believes there is
a link between mad cow disease and the fatal human brain condition CJDhas been
asked to pass details of his work.
The Asda chain wants to find out more about the method Dr Harash Narang is
developing in a bid to test cattle for the presence of bovine spongiform
encephalopathy before they are slaughtered.
Newcastle upon Tyne-based Dr Narang also claims the method can be used for
testing for Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease in living people. CJD is recognised as
the human equivalent of BSE.
The former Public Health Laboratory Service research scientist has long been at
the centre of controversy over his belief that BSE and CJD are linked, and
Asda's national quality control department, based in Leeds, contacted him about
his test.
The approach coincides with growing public concern which has seen sales of beef
dropping by more than 15% over the past month nationwide.
Dr Narang, who has also sent details of his test to Agriculture Minister
Douglas Hogg, said: ``I am very pleased someone seems to be taking notice.
``Asda only found out about my test after reading about it in an article.
`` This was only a short while after being told by the Ministry that there was
no way of testing live cattle.''
Mike Barber, Asda's meat production manager in charge of meat quality, said he
had not yet been able to study the details sent by Dr Narang.
``The position is we try to keep on top of developments in the industry but we
have total confidence in our meat goods.
``We only use reputable suppliers and we employ the most stringent
procedures,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How to avoid catastrophe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749732</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IAN Bell cheers the fact that there are now more people earning their bread
from art-related activities than there are now primary teachers, shipyard or
even whisky workers (December 20). Why the cheers?
Rather than cheer I despair because jobs for arty subsidy junkies can never
create the wealth required even for an independent Scotland never mind a
prosperous UK plc. Is there not a correlation between the number employed in
arts and the declining position of UK plc in the economic league?
Is not part of the problem that the media appears to be obsessed with the arts
(and The Herald is no exception) at the expense of the wealth-creating trades
and professions?
My solution is that for starters any teacher who discourages his or her star
pupil to take up technical subjects should be immediately dismissed.
Secondly, the media coverage now committed to the arts should be replaced with
technical subjects. In other words what UK PLC desperately need is to encourage
a generation of wealth creators.
I sincerely believe that what this country needs are more wealth creators. Of
course the Oxbridge arts faculties have produced some fantastic comedians, and
made UK broadcasting media one of the best.
But will it pay for my pension?
Knut Jespersen,
23 Ainslie Road, Girvan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#7000 hangover for Chris Evans</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749733</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HUNGOVER disc jockey Chris Evans was fined a day's pay yesterday for failing to
turn up for his BBC Radio 1 breakfast show on Thursday.
The #1m-a-year presenter, whose company, Ginger Productions, makes the
programme for the BBC, was believed to have been fined about #7000 by Radio 1
controller Matthew Bannister.
Evans, 29, spent almost half-an-hour in the controller's office where he was
warned about fulfilling his contract.
A BBC spokeswoman said: ``Chris has been severely told off and his wages
docked, which for him is quite substantial.''
Yesterday Evans returned to the airwaves in wise-cracking style and joked about
missing the programme.
``It's so good to be back, I feel like I've had a holiday in Bermuda - although
it was more expensive than a week in Bermuda, obviously,'' he told listeners.
Evans left Broadcasting House at 10am in his new Bentley. He refused to speak
about the incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lord Advocate to seek definitive legislation on doctors wishing to withdraw treatment Coma case goes to three judges</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749734</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S first ``right to die'' case is to be heard by three senior judges
because of the importance of the public policy issues involved.
The Lord Advocate also made it clear yesterday that he is pressing Government
colleagues to consider legislation to remove the legal uncertainty faced by
doctors who wish to withdraw treatment from patients in a persistent vegetative
state.
Lord Mackay of Drumadoon said it would be ``quite intolerable'' for doctors in
Scotland to feel at a disadvantage compared with their English colleagues who
have the legal protection of a House of Lords ruling.
He also explained why he had not issued a statement to the effect that doctors
treating 52-year-old Mrs Janet Johnstone, who has been in a deep coma at Law
Hospital, Carluke, for nearly four years, would escape prosecution if they
withdrew her artificial feeding.
The doctors and Mrs Johnstone's family agree that she should be allowed to die,
but because of risk of prosecution for murder or culpable homicide, Law
Hospital NHS Trust has asked for the protection of a Court of Session order
before taking any steps to withdraw treatment.
Lord Mackay argued yesterday that this was a case which the court should report
to three judges because it involved complex and important issues arising from a
very difficult human situation.
He agreed that there was ``considerable uncertainty'' about the legal issues
involved, except for one - there could be absolutely no doubt that, in its
present terms, the order sought by the NHS trust was incompetent.
``The position I adopt is to ensure that the court only grants a competent
order upon a proper examination of the legal issues involved,'' he said.
``It would do no service to those who have to practise in this field, nor would
it be of service to relatives or patients who are caught up in this situation,
for the court to pronounce a remedy out of a feeling of sympathy rather than a
proper legal examination of the issues.''
He pointed out that the Scottish Law Commission had recently produced a report
on the issue with a strong recommendation that legislation was needed.
That was now receiving the attention of the Government and the Lord Advocate
said he would be making it abundantly clear to his ministerial colleagues that
the problem should be addressed as a matter of urgency.
``It would be quite intolerable that the medical profession in Scotland should
feel at a disadvantage as opposed to their counterparts in England.''
In England, the House of Lords laid down in the Tony Bland case that there was
no absolute duty on doctors to continue treating a patient no matter what the
circumstances.
Lord Mackay said the suggestion had been made that doctors had not received
guidance from him. The complaint was that he had not formed a view as to the
lawfulness or otherwise of the course of conduct the doctors wished to follow
in Mrs Johnstone's case.
``In my submission it is not for the Lord Advocate of the day to provide
members of the public with legal advice or guidance as to whether their past
course of conduct has been lawful, or proposed course of conduct would be
lawful.
``The Lord Advocate cannot express a view that, if certain conduct takes place,
those who carry it out would be guilty of a crime because that is not for the
Lord Advocate to decide. That is for the High Court or the sheriff court to
decide after proper criminal proceedings.''
The Lord Advoate said the hospital in this case had relied heavily on the Bland
case, but there was a quite fundamental distinction between Bland's case and
this one.
The Bland question had been decided by the House of Lords judges expressly
addressing the issue of criminal responsibility and it appeared that civil
courts in England would adjudicate on issues of criminal responsibility.
That was not the case in Scotland, but it was clear that in this case the Court
of Session was being asked to involve itself in a question of criminal
responsibility. This was an area into which, until now, the Court of Session
had steadfastly refused to go.
His suspicion was that the main purpose of the present action was to get as
much protection as possible from criminal proceedings.
However, he expressed sympathy with the medical profession and relatives caught
up in a situation where there were differences between Scotland and England for
reasons which they might not readily understand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council withdraws licence for festive raves on police advice</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749735</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUNCIL took emergency measures yesterday to cancel Christmas and New Year
raves at one of Scotland's top rave venues, the Fubar Club in Stirling.
At an emergency meeting, Stirling District Council's civic licensing committee,
acting on police advice, suspended the club's public entertainment licence for
raves over the period.
There had earlier been a series of dawn raids on homes in Central Scotland.
It is understood that four people were arrested in connection with alleged drug
dealing at the Fubar. The four, who have not been identified, are expected to
appear in court on Tuesday.
The arrests are the result of a long-running police operation.
About 800 tickets for the Christmas Day rave have already been sold, and
Stirling's civic licensing chairman, Mr Geoff Hill, urged people to stay at
home.
Licensing committee members, meeting behind closed doors, voted to suspended
the Fubar licence for up to six weeks on the grounds of public safety. They
received a verbal report from the police divisional commander for Stirling,
Superintendent Joe Holden.
The committee will hold a full hearing in the new year at a date to the fixed.
The Fubar nightclub had intended to hold raves on Christmas Day, Boxing Day,
and Hogmanay.
A spokesman for Castle Leisure Ltd, which runs the nightclub, said directors
and other executives were attending Christmas functions and were unavailable
for comment.
The club was first granted a conditional six-month licence to hold raves in
November 1992, despite protests from local mothers. The women and members of a
self-styled Drugs Action Group said allowing raves would create a magnet for
drug dealing.
The licence was renewed for three years in April 1993, amid protests from local
residents about noise from the club. It is due to expire on April 23.
In December 1993, the civic licensing committee decided to suspend the club's
licence for one month because of a breach of conditions. It was said that
tickets for events had been advertised for sale on the door, when the licence
only allowed admission by pre-sold tickets.
The suspension of the Fubar's public entertainment licence does not affect the
club's discos or House Music evenings, which operate under a separate liquor
licence from Stirling licensing board.
A report will be sent to the board by the civic licensing committee explaining
the committee's decision.
</TEXT>
