<DOCNO>GH951223-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Breakthrough in diabetes could lead to end of insulin injections</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749736</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OVER one million British diabetics may be able to throw away their syringes and
simply pop a pill in the future thanks to a revolutionary medical breakthrough
by Scottish scientists.
The prospect of a new drug to treat the condition, which can cause blindness,
heart disease, and kidney failure, has attracted great interest from drug
companies anxious to conclude deals with the Scottish team.
More than three quarters of diabetics do not lack insulin within their bodies,
but suffer from a defective ``signalling system'' which prevents insulin from
stimulating muscle and fat cells in the proper way.
Now scientists have isolated an enzyme which plays a vital part in the
signalling process and allows the insulin to transform glucose into a form
which can be stored in the body.
The team, based at the University of Dundee, is led by Professor Philip Cohen,
one of the world's top 100 scientists, and has made one of the biggest
breakthroughs in 70 years of research into the disorder.
Yesterday he said: ``This is a very important breakthrough. We are doing the
research side of things. It is now up to the pharmaceutical companies to
develop a drug which can activate the enzyme.
``But with modern techniques for drug development it may not be long until we
see this new treatment for diabetes.''
The research has already attracted interest from several pharmaceutical
companies and researchers are confident that their findings mark the beginning
of the end for daily injections of insulin.
Professor Cohen said: ``Research into the insulin signalling system first began
in 1973, but it is only after advances in our understanding of the function of
enzymes, during research into heart disease and cancer, that we were able to
understand the importance of enzymes in diabetes.
``The more we unpick the chain of events involved in the signalling mechanism,
the easier it should be to develop drugs to treat diabetes.''
He said that the enzyme, named c-Akt, leaves only one or two of the secrets of
insulin left uncovered.
Researchers Dario Alesi and Darren Cross discovered that c-Akt can ultimately
protect against high levels of glucose in the blood, and had their findings
published in Nature scientific magazine.
The British Diabetic Association, which currently funds 66 research projects
and has allocated more than #4m for research into diabetes in 1996, has
welcomed the breakthrough.
Director of research Dr Moira Murphy said: ``Results such as these are an
important step forward in tackling diabetes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dutch soccer star faces road death prosecution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749737</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Amsterdam, Friday
DUTCH teenage striker Patrick Kluivert is to be prosecuted for causing death by
dangerous driving for his part in a fatal accident last September, the news
agency ANP reported today.
The 19-year-old Ajax Amsterdam player, who scored both goals against Ireland
last week to earn the Netherlands a berth in the 1996 European championship
finals, has already admitted to speeding.
Kluivert was unhurt when the BMW sports car he was driving ploughed into the
side of another vehicle on September 9, killing its driver and seriously
injuring a passenger.
He faces up to one year in jail, a fine of 10,000 guilders and a five-year
driving ban if found guilty of causing death by dangerous driving.
Laboratory tests on behalf of the Amsterdam public prosecutor estimate Kluivert
was travelling at around 104 kmph - double the speed limit - but his lawyer
says the car was going much slower. The case will open some time in the first
three months of next year, ANP added.
It was a second blow for Ajax after the club learned earlier that international
winger Marc Overmars would be out for the rest of the season with a serious
knee injury and would also miss the European finals in England.
q A man who threatened to kill tennis star Boris Becker and his family in a
bizarre extortion case was convicted by a Munich court today and given a
suspended two-year sentence.
Michael Jung, 29, was also ordered to immediately start psychiatric treatment.
Prosecutors had requested a four-year sentence but presiding judge Norbert
Schmitt accepted the defendant's statement that he never intended to carry out
his threats.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
