<DOCNO>GH951223-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Face on rock divides town</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749739</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN image of Jesus found on a rock has brought neither peace nor goodwill to the
people of the Australian wheat-belt town of Beverley this Christmas.
A deep rift has emerged between believers and doubters since local businessman
Julian Webb said he saw the image of Christ's face mystically appear on a slab
of granite at his farm six weeks ago, 87 miles east of Perth.
Attitudes among the 1400 townsfolk vary. Some think they have beheld a miracle,
others think it is a hoax and a tourist trap. There is a growing and uneasy
feeling that the rest of Australia is laughing at them.
Rumours abound that a wealthy American is preparing to buy the newfound relic,
together with up to half the town; that the face fulfills an aboriginal elder's
15-year-old prediction; and that it is somehow linked to other phenomena such
as crop circles and mysterious lights that appear over the town.
The divide between the sceptics and the faithful has soured relations in a way
no worldly controversy has in the past.
``It's because of the religion thing that gets people's backs right up,`` said
Ray Dickie, the doubting publican of the suitably secular Freemasons Hotel.
``If it was a nugget of gold someone found you could say `That's a fake' or
`It's got to be a plant' and you'd be entitled to your own opinion,'' he added.
``But with religion, some people give you a real serve.''
Dickie lamented that of the thousand-plus pilgrims and tourists who visited the
rock last weekend, when it was displayed at the Beverley town hall, none showed
an interest in drinking.
Local professional psychic Roma Paton has examined the energy fields of the
``miracle'' rock and doubts it is a hoax.
``Its energy field is very different from granite. I sensed no density from the
rock or the quarry around it,'' she said.
``If it is a hoax, then that doesn't explain the strange light my husband and I
saw over Beverley the night it was found (November 9) or the crop rings which
appeared three weeks earlier.''
She had also heard an aboriginal elder predicted 15 years ago that the face of
Jesus would appear in Beverley.
The rock will be displayed over Christmas, guarded by friends and relatives, at
the quarry site where it was found on Webb's property.
``I was fully expecting the backlash from the sceptics but the faith of so many
well-wishers has been enough to keep me going,'' Webb said.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP in Govan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749740</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAMERON Simpson reports that the SNP are rumoured to have tapped Dilip Deb to
stand for them. The SNP in Govan certainly did not. I speak as one of the
delegates for Govan South Branch to Govan Constituency Association.
Our branch put forward Nicola Sturgeon in September, and the other branch in
the constituency (Govan Riverside) put forward Patsy Thomson and Shona Robison.
The selection meeting for the constituency was on November 6, and the vote was
decisively for Nicola Sturgeon; our choice was ratified by our national
executive on November 11 - long before Labour's present shenanigans. It is
precisely because she is a candidate of such high calibre that Labour are
worried, and quite rightly so.
Andrew C Wilson,
3 Glencairn Drive,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
