<HEADLINE>HCI hindsight and foresight</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749741</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS amused by your leaderon Health Care International in which you say, ``It
was abundantly clear that HCI was a disaster in the making,'' and, ``lest we
forget, was an enterprise conceived and hatched for no better reason than
warped ideology'' (December 22).
Lest we also forget, in a previous leader (September 12, 1991) you said that
``the Clydebank initiative deserves a welcome'', and that my prediction of
failure for Health Care International came ``close to prejudice''.
Nor do I remember at that time any predictions of failure from the Scottish
National Party or the Liberal Democrats. Hindsight is a splendid facility given
to us all. Foresight is even better.
Sam Galbraith, MP,
House of Commons.
</TEXT>
