<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Planning row over Lord Chancellor's ancestral home</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749742</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE English owner of Lord Chancellor Lord Mackay of Clashfern's ancestral but
and ben in the Highlands faces being taken to court for allowing it to fall
into disrepair.
Lord Mackay takes his title from the former shepherd's cottage, Clashfearn,
situated on a rocky hillside near Scourie in Sutherland.
His late father lived there and generations of the family before him. Mr Mackay
later moved to Edinburgh to work on the railways. His son was born in the city
where he was to become a mathematics lecturer before going into law.
A cousin, Mrs Johan Munro, 86, who lives near the cottage, said yesterday: ``He
was up here with his wife visiting us in hospital about a year ago and he was
sad to see the state the cottage has fallen into. He obviously has a
sentimental attachment to it.''
Mrs Munro, her son, and council planners have been fighting for years for
chartered surveyor and estate agent Gerald Garratt of Derby to do something
about the cottage he bought as a holiday home about 15 years ago.
The cottage, with two rooms donwstairs and two attic bedrooms with skylights
upstairs, had part of the roof raised by Mr Garratt and a dormer window put in.
But the work was not completed and Mr Garratt has not been seen there for about
three years.
Mrs Munro said: ``The house is in an awful looking state. The slates have been
stripped off and the rain must be pouring in. I don't know what the man was
thinking about leaving it like this.
``The sad thing is since Lord Mackay took Clashfearn as his name a lot of
people are interested in seeing the place. It would be nice if it was in a
better condition.''
Sutherland planning officer David Polson described the stone-built cottage as
now looking ``rather odd'' with a third of the roof higher than the rest.
He said: ``Mr Garratt has repeatedly ignored requests from us to do something
about it. So he is now being served with a Waste Land notice ordering him to
put the cottage back the way it was before he started his part-completed
alterations.''
If this was disregarded, a report could be sent to the procurator-fiscal in
Dornoch and prosecution could follow.
Mr Polson added: ``It's not because it's Lord Mackay's former family home we
are taking this action. But his relatives have complained and the place is an
eyesore the way it is.''
Mr Garratt, at his business in Queen Street, Derby, said: ``I don't want to say
anything at the moment. I haven't been served with the notice yet. I've had
problems but not to do with the cottage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospital bids under scrutiny</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749743</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SEVEN private organisations have expressed interest in providing hospital
services in Stonehaven, as has the Grampian Healthcare NHS Trust.
Grampian Health Board will now consider the eight submissions and selected
organisations will be invited to meet informally with the board early next
month.
After more detailed consideration, the board will agree a short-list of
organisations who will be given a copy of the service specification to submit
tenders before April 16. Those on the short-list will be named at the end of
next month.
The Government caused controversy earlier this year when it rejected Grampian
Health Board's proposal that Woodcot Hospital in Stonehaven be disposed of and
a new hospital built on the site of Arduthie Hospital.
The Scottish Office NHS Management Executive told the board to invite open
competition. While some welcome the move as an opportunity for Stonehaven to
gain a hospital service tailored to the needs of the community, others see it
as a step towards privatisation of the National Health Service.
Grampian Healthcare are heading a consortium which includes Community Health
Services who run a number of private nursing homes, Miller Construction of
Scotland, and the British Linen Bank who will finance the project. Their
proposal involves a new hospital and a 30-bed nursing home on the Arduthie
Hospital site.
Details of the specification for the tender will be made public next month and
the document is currently in the final stages of preparation. It is based on
the needs identified by local GPs and the views of the people of Kincardine.
Mr Derek Ogston, Professor of Medicine at Aberdeen University and vice chairman
of Grampian Health Board, said yesterday: ``This is another major step forward
in the development of new hospital services in Stonehaven - provision which
would not have been possible if we were not going through this process.
``We have been very encouraged by the level of interest shown in this
innovative project.
``It is a good demonstration of the potential benefits that can be gained when
the public and private sectors work together and we look forward to further
discussions with interested organisations over the next few weeks.
``From a preliminary consideration of the submissions we are confident we will
be able to purchase excellent services to meet local needs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jimmy Stewart back in hospital for observation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749744</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Los Angeles, Friday
ACTOR Jimmy Stewart was admitted to a second hospital today after bumping his
head in a fall at his home.
Stewart, 87, injured himself yesterday when he fell down and hit his head
against a chair.
His publicist, John Strauss, said the actor, who starred in such memorable
films as Frank Capra's It's a Wonderful Life, Mr Smith Goes to Washington,
Harvey'' and Anatomy of a Murder, was admitted to St. John's hospital in Santa
Monica for observation. He is expected to remain there for the next 24 to 48
hours.
Stewart had been taken to Century City Hospital by paramedics late yesterday
after he slipped and fell at his Beverly Hills home. He was treated at the
emergency room and released shortly after midnight.
According to local television reports, eyewitnesses who were singing Christmas
Carols outside Stewart's Beverly Hills home said the popular screen actor was
taken out of his home on a stretcher with bandages on his head.
Although probably best known for his leading role in the annual holiday classic
It's a Wonderful Life, Stewart has starred in a wide range of films, including
thrillers such as Rear Window and Vertigo, comedies and even musicals, playing
the band leader in The Glenn Miller Story.
He was nominated for an Academy Award five times, winning once in 1940 for his
role opposite Katharine Hepburn in The Philadelphia Story in 1940.
q Evangelist Billy Graham was released from a New York hospital today following
treatment for broken ribs suffered in a fall, his main office said.
Graham fell in his room at a Manhattan hotel on December 12, suffering four
broken ribs and a bruised right shoulder.
The 77-year-old preacher has Parkinson's disease but doctors said they did not
believe that was what caused his fall.-AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Technology and jobs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749745</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I FIND it very depressing that in all the political debates on a variety of
subjects not one politician or political party has raised the major question
facing the social fabric, both now and in the future, namely the relationship
between people and modern technology.
The recent postal strike brought this question to a head as a problem which
exists in every factory, office, and shop.
Just how are we going to plan so that people will not feel fearful when
technology provides alternatives to personal labour? It is high time this
question is faced as doing nothing could be the cause of much social strife.
John D Breingan,
24 Rankin Drive, Largs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Escaped killer jailed again</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749746</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARMED police surrounded a flat where an escaped killer was hiding, a court
heard yesterday.
They were acting on a tip-off that David Cochrane, 43, who had been on the run
for two-and-a-half weeks, had a weapon.
However, Cochrane gave himself up and walked into the arms of the police, the
Glasgow Sheriff Court was told.
A search of his wife's flat revealed he had never been armed.
Yesterday Cochrane, who was convicted of murder in 1979, was jailed for a
further 15 months.
He admitted escaping from his escorts during a compassionate visit from Perth
Prison to his mother's home at Green Street, Calton, Glasgow, on November 7.
It was Cochrane's second escape from jail since beginning a life sentence.
Last March, after other prisoners had cut a hole in the perimeter fence at
Dungavel, Cochrane took his chance and walked through it.
He was detained soon after and sentenced to 60 days imprisonment.
Yesterday Mr John Macaulay, defending, said that Cochrane was suffering
emotional distress on two fronts: his mother's illness and the fact that he had
not seen his nine-year-old daughter for five months. Mr Kenneth Donnelly,
prosecuting, revealed that after an apparent argument with his wife Janice,
during a visit to his mother's home, prison officers agreed to let them speak
together just outside the living room door.
As they cuddled Mrs Cochrane, who married him in jail in 1988, suddenly opened
the front door then she snibbed it after he  had bolted
Cochrane and two other men were jailed for the murder with an iron bar of
Gallowgate butcher Thomas Woods and the attempted murder of his friend,
Constable Brian Coppins, during a robbery in the butcher's shop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Time to kiss and tell</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749747</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Making up with       Cannon and Ball was never going                 to be easy
but     Anvar Khan managed to keep them from getting too lippy as they helped
her to consumer test the latest lipsticks
BOBBY Ball is aghast. ``Do you honestly think, that my wife would believe this,
if I walk in, with a bag of lipsticks. `Where did you get these?' Oh, well I
did this interview in Glasgow......'' I am trying to offer both Tommy Cannon
and Bobby Ball a small token of appreciation for the time spent kissing me in
their dressing cubicle in the King's Theatre, Glasgow.
Bobby is chain-smoking. They have just finished the matinee performance of
Robin Hood and the Babes in the Wood. Cotton wool, pens, foundation, and a
bumper size bottle of Happy Shopper Table Salt at the special price of 44p, sit
on their 100-watt mirrored dressers. Glad to see they're still counting the
pennies at this advanced stage in their career.
There was a purpose to being here, being gently slagged by the amiable and
ebullient Cannon and Ball. For my mission was to see just how much staying
power long-lasting lipsticks really have, and how better to road-test them,
than under the mistletoe with a couple of stars, notorious for their decorum,
their sense of humour, and their durability.
The interview was not easy. I am gullible and the smaller, curlier half, is a
mischievous wee imp. Outrageous lies included working as Santa Claus in the
mornings at Marks &amp; Spencer. Cannon and Ball are men. Please take their
comments with a pinch of the Happy Shopper. They know what they like and what
they don't like, because, when it comes to how women look, male opinion is
almost always based on prejudice.
n.Shiseido SP5 Red and Famous, #16
``Don't press your lips together for a few minutes after putting this on,''
warned the sales assistant. ``You have to let this lipstick dry.'' Yes, one has
to stand in front of the mirror with one's jaw hanging open like a moo. Letting
your lipstick set is quite a concept. You're applying paint, a thin, plasticky
film of average colour. But it provides invisible kisses. I had to rub
violently at my lips with a tissue to get it off, because I neglected to buy
the special Shiseido Absolute Lipstick Remover at #8.95.
Cannon: My wife wears red lipstick, but I wouldn't buy this, not when I can't
even pronounce the name.
Ball: It sounds like a Chinese takeaway.
Cannon: It looks like a small biro. You want it to last a lifetime at #16.
Ball: If this was in my wife's bag I'd think it was a suppository.
n.Boots No7 Lasting Colour Lipstick in Matt Desire, #3.95
Matt lipsticks are, by their very purpose, dry. I applied this product on to
beeswaxed lips and had to blot several times with a tissue for me to trust it
enough to take. Although I was wearing lip pencil, after the first few hours of
the working day, coffee, a roll and a lot of talking, it tended to clump at the
corner of my big mouth. There is, in this tube, #4's worth of transferable
goop. Avoid his crisp white collar.
Ball: Why don't they make a lipstick which comes off your jacket?
Cannon: This doesn't look like desire to me. Why don't they invent a flavoured
lipstick, like a pint of McEwan's lager?
n.Max Factor Lasting Lip Colour in Teasing Pink, #3.49
A creamy substance which will only imprint a shell of a kiss on the cheek.
However, after delivering the first half dozen smackers, it tends to congregate
in the lines of your lips. Sticky. The outer, moisturising layer landslides
after a drink, to reveal pink stained lips. A quick slick of lip gloss to
lubricate, however, and you can carry on pecking.
Cannon: This is the strangest interview we've ever done. I think we'll have to
be careful in future when we're stopping here in Glasgow, after talking about
lipsticks.
Ball: It looks like a mouth freshener.
Cannon: It actually looks like one of my kid's finger crayons. You put your
finger in here......
n.Rimmel Lasting Finish Lipstick in Birthday Suit, #1.99
Gives even colour on the mouth but comes off on a glass of wine (not that I was
drinking on the job, not that Cannon and Ball drove me to it, no way). This is
not an adhesive. One kiss leaves a shimmering butterfly. But it's cheap, and if
you buy a pale colour such as this, where's the problem if it gets on someone's
shirt? Aren't they lucky to get a kiss from you anyway?
Cannon: Is that supposed to be the colour of skin? It's a very cheap, plasticky
case. I'd give it as a present to someone I didn't like. A naff effort.
Ball: We use Clarins, y'know.
Cannon: I'm getting bored. What do I know about lipstick anyway?
Ball: But seriously though, have you see the women who put that lip liner
around their mouths. They look as if they've got a bad heart.
n.Beauty Without Cruelty in Peony Passion, #2.65
Without the use of petrochemicals, with a sole reliance on natural, traditional
ingredients, this lipstick does pretty well. Even without pretensions to being
extra lasting, it remains on the lips for just as long as the Rimmel product.
It has a mild glossing effect, which frankly, makes lips more luscious. Warm,
soft and smoochy.
Ball: That's your colour, Tommy, you suit it!
Cannon: At #2 odd, can it be any good? I suppose they charge more if they test
a product on animals.
Ball: I like this blue case.
Cannon: I suppose women feel better with lipstick on. When a woman's made up,
she looks great, but I don't think a fella should see her doing it.
n.Cutex Lasting Colour Lipstick in Northern Lights, #3.49
An interesting interpretation of the colour of the Northern Lights. An
opalescent mauve. It will stay on your lips for up to five hours, but expect a
frost of purple after biting on the snowy plains of any white bread sandwich.
You must blot either before eating and drinking, or after, in order for the
colour to stick. You can kiss away the party hours, however, with this one, if
you're delicate. Just don't press too hard or you'll leave the dreaded tattoo.
Cannon: I hate lots of lipstick on a woman. You go on a date and you kiss her,
and then you walk about for hours with lipstick on yer face. I don't like
sliding about on them, women's lips, like being on a ski slope.
Ball: Can we go home now?
All lipsticks featured are available from Debenhams, Frasers, Boots, and good
independent chemists.
n Cannon and Ball are starring in Robin Hood and the Babes in the Wood at the
King's Theatre, Glasgow, until February 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Next step for Loch Lomond</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749748</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JAMES Freeman's report, Laying down law of the Loch, will provide heartwarming
news for all those who have campaigned for years for the introduction of
by-laws to control speed limits on Loch Lomond (December 19).
As your report notes, the by-laws are a significant step forward, but are not
the final answer. The introduction of a National Park, with an all-purpose
authority with planning powers - and adequate financial resources - is
essential to the long-term sustainable use of the Loch Lomond and Trossachs
area.
Michael Forsyth's support for the by-laws is a welcome recognition of the
nature and scale of the developmental pressures affecting this
internationally-renowned area, but his comment that the by-law measures are a
perfect example of local solutions to local problems is correct only in part.
Local solutions are essential if a national park mechanism is to work
successfully, and be seen as a democratically-based designation which has the
support of local people.
However, the problems of Loch Lomond are not only local, they are of European
and international significance. At a recent seminar Professor Adrian Phillips,
chairman of the World Conservation Union Commission on National Parks and
Protected Areas, set out the criteria by which Loch Lomond and the Trossachs
could receive international recognition.
He concluded on a personal note by saying: ``If it were decided to create a
National Park for Loch Lomond and the Trossachs, it would be a welcome partner
to the European and global network of protected areas.''
Malcolm Payne,
Scottish Council for National Parks,
West View,
East End,
Pitcairngreen,
Perth.
</TEXT>
