<HEADLINE>Another round - and no half measures this time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack Mclean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749750</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Our antiquated licensing laws were given a much-needed boost, thanks to one
eminent doctor. But, says Jack McLean, it's high time the job was completed
Temperance ladies were, in fact, supplying taverns with a livelihood in the
illicit trafficking in alcohol
A WEE while back I was on Radio Scotland talking about the public house
licensing laws, absurd as they are, and the young researcher couldn't quite
grasp what I was saying. It was about licensing laws and the Clayson Committee
Report.
Dr Christopher Clayson was a chest doctor, indeed a former president of the
Royal College of Physicians, and a very unlikely champion of topers like
myself. He is now damned near a hundred, and though no teetotaller, is not a
heavy tippler.
Yet it was Lord Clayson who changed the world of licensing; for Dr Clayson
produced a report which said that there could be such a thing as civilised
drinking in Scotland. He started his report in 1971 and eventually finished in
1976. It took more than four years to implement even a part of it. Indeed, much
of Clayson's proposals remain on hold.
The licensing laws in Scotland, and especially in the west industrial belt,
were much informed by temperance societies' zeal. The British Women's
Temperance Association, which adopted a white ribbon as its symbol and was
known ever after as White Ribboneers, once held sell-out meetings all over
Britain, and perhaps their most glorious hour was in 1895 when 80,000 women
turned out at the Albert Hall in London. These silly ladies should have known
better. They were, in fact, through the agency of their long-suffering
husbands, supplying the many owners of taverns, many of them in fact women,
with a very lively, well, livelihood in the illicit trafficking in alcohol.
Sabbath drinking is to this day forbidden in many parts of the Western Isles,
as a result of which the continued presence of the ``bothans'' - basically
shebeens - sees to it that Sabbatarian drunkenness is still prevalent in the
Western Isles. Do not listen to the Wee Free clergy or the community leaders in
Barra or Lewis. I could get a drink there on a Sunday quicker than I could in
Glasgow, believe me. Certainly in the early eighties even we had hotels only,
places in which you could only order alcohol if you were a bona fide traveller.
You had to sign a book with your name and address. Thus there were such
signatures as ``R Hood, Sherwood Forest'', and ``M Mouse, Hollywood''.
And how about Glasgow? I can assure you that here if I want a spot of the amber
after closing time it would not give me a moment's thought. The habit of most
publicans and bar staff of having a quiet wee relaxing half hour or so after a
long and busy day is well known, as is the wee invitation to a few selected and
favoured customers to join them. The after-hours, the overtime, the lock-in,
call it what you will, is still, technically, against the law.
Indeed the law often seems ludicrously zealous in the exercise of it when it
comes to licensing. As radio presenter Tom Morton put it not so long ago in the
programme for which I was a most distinguished contributor: ``If it was the
drinking that was the problem why don't the police turn up at your own door
when you are starting on your carry-out, demanding your presence outside and
locking you up.'' How can you be permitted the strong liquor on your own but
not in good company?
Around the turn of the century came many a piece of legislation; 1915 saw more
of it when Lloyd George curtailed any drinking in the afternoon (he thought it
would boost industrial production). By the time I became a drinker Scotland had
two things: the most draconian hours for the sale of liquor on licensed
premises in the Western world, and the worst alcohol problem as well. Scotland
continues to suffer from the highest rates of alcohol-related deaths in Europe
(oddly Ireland has one of the lowest because of the large numbers of
non-alcohol swallowers in that country), and Clayson's proposals were an
attempt to stem the awesome tide of alcohol-induced problems. By and large they
have worked.
Yet large parts of Scotland continue to be horribly uncivilised. Clayson wanted
family pubs, places where, as one would find anywhere in Europe, children could
go to any cafe or restaurant and their parents would have a strega or a cognac
or a glass of wine with a meal; places in which children took alcohol for
granted and their parents took theirs sensibly. Clayson's proposals were
dreadfully sensible.
Clayson proffered a new era. He wanted places in which alcohol could be offered
but there ``would be no public bar or table service, simply cafes where parents
could take their children''. It was all part of the idea of introducing
children to alcohol under parental control in a public place. The conditions
recommended for the recognition of such suitable pubs were not even debated.
``The Secretary of State for Scotland (the then somewhat Calvinistic Willie
Ross) said of children in the public bar that this would not be in line with
current Scottish practices. Well, of course we knew that. But we were planning
for 25 years or more ahead''.
It is now more than 25 years ahead. Drunkenness has subsided amazingly, (don't
listen to alarming reports of alcohol-induced acts of violence: there is
considerably less drunkenness, just a lot more violence, and no matter what a
variety of lobbies say the truth is that drugs are to blame for far more crime
than a night in the pub). The tendency towards all-out prohibition is still
strong in Scotland, and certainly in Glasgow and the west. Clayson wanted a
clearer view of alcohol use, and most certainly a clearer one of unacceptable
abuse. Irish children find little difficulty with the proximity of a nearby
pub, Europeans see no problem. The days are perhaps over in Scotland, or in
most of her cities, when licensed permises were glazed over with curtains and
dark windows, and a glamourous prurience.
Dr Clayson set off to destroy the business of licensing laws which established
the Scottish practice of heavy drinking, the carry-outs after 10pm (in my young
days it was 9.30pm closing and the tables were groaning with last-minute rounds
of beer and spirits bought), the culture of drinking till you dropped.
But Clayson, and after all he is a Scot, with the baggage of temperance and
moderation and excess upon him, got it wrong.
A few years ago he said he was mystified as to why licensing authorities had
allowed these hours to extend in the first place. He said: ``My committee's
original proposal was for the hours to run from 11am to 11pm and exceptions
were to be rigidly controlled.''
Clayson said, back in the early 1970s, that we have traditionally examined our
drinking and licensing laws every 10 years or so. We are now a quarter of a
century on from Clayson. Clayson made life a lot more civilised. (Not least for
publicans and bar staff who at last had shorter, and not longer hours, for the
split shift of an afternoon was grim.) But the time has surely come, after the
best and most continental summer Scotland has seen in more than 50 years, to
think again.
It is not really for you or me or anybody else, and most certainly not some
half-jaked politician, to decide when you eat or drink or sell food or alcohol
on the basis of what you or myself or it thinks is acceptable. Frankly a lot of
people, especially our amazed European visitors, find the blanket closure of
this city less worthy than any puritanical nonsense thought up by churches,
magistrates, and a police force quite so incapable of looking after citizens
that their first response is to send perfectly decent people to their beds
early, while incapable of policing the handful of people determined upon
delinquency, whatever age they may be.
Clayson and his report helped Glasgow to shift into the later part of this
century. New ways of approach are needed now. And why is the United Kindom not
looking abroad, in any way at all?
</TEXT>
