<HEADLINE>The way our fond memories can brighten the present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stewart Lamont</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749751</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMEN Corner was once the name of a pop group but I believe that its origins lie
in the Deep South of America, in black churches. It is a function akin to that
of a precentor in presbyterian churches which do not rely upon an organ to lead
singing.
However, those who occupy Amen Corner lead response to the sermon by
interjecting shouts of ``Amen'' or ``Hallelujah'' or other words of assent at
appropriate moments during the sermon, rather in the way that MPs shout ``hear,
hear'' during Front Bench speeches in the House of Commons. It has the effect
of whipping up an atmosphere of support for the speaker, and has been adopted
by many white churches who follow the charismatic tradition.
In these churches they tend to say things like ``Praise the Lord!'' as well as
the more routine Hallelujahs or Amens. Perhaps I have just not been saying the
right things in my sermons but apart from the rustling of sweetie papers in the
choir seats, I have yet to be interrupted by a chorus from Amen Corner. Until
this week, that is.
It wasn't quite an outbreak of mass hysteria. You can't count eight old ladies
taking communion in a back room at an old folks' home as a mass - even if one
of them turned out to be an RC.
Four sat quietly, two were stolen away by Morpheus during the communion service
but had the decency not to snore. The other two joined in the service as a
chorus, reciting the scripture reading along with me and the words of the
communion service.
I should mention that their participation was not of the off-putting ``echo''
style, in which they simply repeated what I was saying and finished a fraction
behind me. They actually knew the words and said them at the same time. Since
we are not strong on responses in my part of the Reformed tradition, I must
confess to wondering where they acquired the habit.
Rather than putting me off, it contributed a strong sense of communion to the
occasion.
Elderly people who are less aware of day-to-day events, often have clear recall
in respect of long-term memory, and this was obviously the case with my old
ladies in the nursing home. They reminded me of an important truth that we
often neglect - that we all have within us mental resources from the past which
can be invoked to brighten our reality in the present.
Too often we think of memory or the past as something which has gone for ever,
never to be recalled. Certainly we all know people who live too much in the
past, but what I am talking about is the capability to invoke memory to assist
us in the present.
In one way, Christmas provides a strong example of this. We enjoy it now, in
the present but most of us are susceptible to the memory of our Christmases in
the past. Watching children open their presents, or singing Away in a Manger,
or walking timidly up to Santa. There is magic and there is romance in the
present moment which has the stardust of memory sprinkled upon it.
As stated elsewhere on this page, one of the strengths of Christmas is that it
provides a common culture for a society which has fragmented into groups with
vastly different interests. This process is paralleled in science which has
succumbed to the disease of reductionism, resulting in scientists being unable
to explain their subject with others because the language, jargon, and
specialities have so little in common.
It affects not only science but the social sciences. Personally I find some of
the documents which emanate from social work departments to be as
incomprehensible as they must find some of the theology texts which are
produced by my colleagues in divinity faculties. Yet we are supposed to be
addressing different aspects of the human condition.
Even worse is the reductionist approach to compassion. Bureaucratised into
statutory care, privatised into businesses, or politicised into partisan
interests, there are glaring divides within the human agencies which look
askance at one another.
The NHS/social work leviathan is castigated or canonised depending on your
point of view. Private care agencies are treated with suspicion or seen as the
solution of all ills, according to prejudice. Charities float in and out of
this landscape trying to run with both fox and hounds - and who can blame them?
But some charities or church committees or political groups want to claim that
one particular way of dealing with human issues is morally superior. I get
pretty exasperated with any group which tells me that they have a monopoly on
compassion and lectures me for daring to question their solution with awkward
facts.
There is no more a ``right'' solution to poverty or homelessness than there is
one to asylum seekers or hunger in the developing world. But surely there is a
basis for a practical solution in a combination of compassion and common sense.
Is that, after all, another way of defining justice? When I read things that
annoy me in the newspapers, I usually find that either common sense or
compassion is lacking. (Whether it is princesses who want compassion but resist
common sense being applied to their situation; or surgeons who are put on trial
for trying to do their best for patients).
The supreme illustration of this principle is Christmas itself. God showed
compassion for the world by the incarnation, but showed us the value of common
sense in not identifying Himself with any one political solution. I hope that
some of you might say ``amen'' to that. Merry Christmas!
</TEXT>
