<HEADLINE>No merit in isolation?</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749752</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU quote Sir Edward Heath, the former Prime Minister, criticising Mr Malcolm
Rifkind as saying of the Tory Party's ambivalent stance anent the current
antics of the European Union, ``There is no merit in isolation, I hope he (Mr
Rifkind) can modify what he has been saying'' (December 11).
No merit in isolation?
Has age so wearied Sir Edward that he does not remember those dark, desperate,
but heroic days between September 3, 1939, and December 8, 1941, that time of
isolation when Eire hedged its bets and fascist Spain did the same, and Festung
Europa (today, slightly modified, the EU) was engaged in exterminating a
complete race of people and a lot of other odds and sods besides, and this
island home of ours, having withstood in the evil days, prevailed - but only
just?
Of course, Sir Edward remembers those days in which he played his own part to
the full. But does he choose to sweep the legacy of Julius Streicher, that
lives on in those he sired, under the carpet along with that of Irma Greese
(who made lampshades from the flayed bodies of victims taken from the gas
chamber after they were put to death)?
Sir Edward is a pragmatist who prefers to swallow the past's camels wholesale
whilst straining at today's gnats, of which I am one, for the past to me is
still very real, albeit I came to terms with it long ago.
The French, ever a down-to-earth people, pragmatists to a man (or woman), have
a saying, ``Plus que ca change, plus que c'est la meme chose'' - something I
believe fervently.
To whichever ethos Sir Edward may choose to cleave, I myself am a friend of
nearly every individual European of whichever nationality - but no mess of
European pottage can attract, far less buy, my fealty, come what may, and be
damned to ``Frres Jacques'' Santer et Delors, not to mention Master Tony Blair
and his sycophants.
David Rowan Henderson,
Cnoc-Ard, Ardfern,
Argyll.
</TEXT>
