<HEADLINE>New twist to girl's murder inquiry Police investigating death of teenager Mhairi Julyan question victims of obscene phone calls</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749753</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OBSCENE telephone calls were made to school friends of murdered Kilmarnock
teenager Mhairi Julyan shortly before her death. At least four girls were
pestered by the caller, who claimed to know them intimately and referred to
them by their first name.
The calls were all received in the week leading up to Mhairi's murder. One
teenager was subjected to such a call on Sunday - the day detectives discovered
the body of the 16-year-old Kilmarnock Academy schoolgirl in a bus garage yards
from her home.
Another teenager, who received a telephone call four days before Mhairi's
death, lives in a house overlooking the garage where the attack took place.
Police, who revealed this week that Mhairi's murder was sexually motivated, are
questioning the girls about the calls. All are in their early teens and attend
the same school as Mhairi.
One mother said: ``The caller sounded mature and we think he was calling from a
mobile phone as there was a lot of crackling in the background. He asked if my
daughter was still wearing her school uniform then he suggested something
obscene. She slammed the phone down.
``We never thought anything about it until my daughter discovered other girls
at her school were getting the same calls. One girl has been phoned twice by
him.''
Detectives are reluctant to confirm whether they are linking the calls to
Mhairi's murder but say one line of inquiry is being followed up.
Christmas Day prayers will be said for the family of Mhairi. Pleas will also be
made from the pulpit for anyone who has information, or who may be shielding
her killer, to come forward.
As the murder hunt entered its fifth day yesterday, police revealed that
although they had no lead, several women had come forward to say they may have
been followed on Kilmarnock's London Road, where Mhairi was last seen alive.
Officers also said a ``tremendous'' amount of information was flooding in on an
unprecedented scale from the public, showing how the community had united in a
bid to trap the murderer.
Superintendant Louis Munn of Strathclyde Police said: ``I don't recall any
major incident where so many members of the public have responded in such a
positive way. This has really gelled the community.''
Police have traced a caller who may be the last witness to have seen Mhairi
walking home. They have also interviewed a young woman who described a man who
followed her in London Road three days before Mhairi vanished.
Christmas leave has been cancelled for key officers on the murder inquiry, but
Mr Munn said no-one was complaining. ``Christmas will not be a very happy time
for the Julyan family,'' he said. ``We've all got to appreciate this is a
terrible crime.''
The Rev Tom Jarvie, school chaplain at Kilmarnock Academy and Minister of
Riccarton Parish Church, said: ``We will be remembering them in our prayers on
Christmas Day, as will the whole of the presbytery.
``I will certainly make an appeal for anyone who has information, however
small, to come forward.''
Mr Jarvie also revealed that young schoolgirls were now ``shattered and
frightened'' and many would only go out in pairs. ``I heard one of the wee
girls has bought one of those panic bleepers, and she's only 15,'' he added.
Mhairi vanished after leaving the Sleeping Beauty pantomime at Kilmarnock's
Palace Theatre on Saturday night. On Sunday her body was found in a bus depot
close to her home in Samson Avenue. Police described the attack as
``particularly brutal and savage''.
</TEXT>
