<HEADLINE>How cuts hit museums</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749754</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE case that Clare Henry makes for the damaging effect of cuts in the National
Galleries' purchase grant is a telling one (December 19).
Without the ability to provide matching funding neither the National Museums
(purchase grant cut by 57%) nor the Galleries can make effective use of the new
money available from the Lottery. And the vital acquisition of inexpensive but
important historical and scientific material will become impossible.
I wish that her vision of plenty at the National Museums was equally
well-founded. In fact, the #32.5m for the Museum of Scotland, which she refers
to as a Christmas bonanza, is the same #30m that was allocated to the project
in 1990, adjusted for inflation.
And the National Museums, unlike the National Galleries, have had their running
cost grant cut from #11.126m in 1995/96 to #10.702m in 1996/97 at a time when,
as she rightly says, we are having to devote a great deal of time and money to
preparing for the new museum.
Finally, I don't think that the National Audit Office report found us on an
elitist high horse. The survey which the NAO commissioned reports that ``the
Museums are successful in attracting visitors from virtually all sectors of the
population'', including a higher proportion of those in socio-economic groups
C2, D, and E, than any other museum or gallery that I know of.
Mark Jones,
Director, National Museums of Scotland,
Chambers Street,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
