<HEADLINE>The trick is to keep your nerve</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Clay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749755</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF you are one of those people who see the turn of the year as a time to review
your investments and think about policies for the year ahead, remember the
comment by Mark Twain. He listed the ``most dangerous'' months for investors on
the Stock Exchange. He put them in higglety-pigglety order but they added up to
12.
With Wall Street and London having hit a series of peaks in the run-up to
Christmas, it would be surprising indeed if the coming year did not see a fair
bit of volatility in share prices. Some people will decide to cash in fat
profits; others will be buying on the view that there is more to come. The
trick will be to decide if a setback is merely a blip in a continuing upward
pattern and, therefore, a buying opportunity, or if it is the start of a longer
reversal of market fortunes.
Wall Street gave a sharp reminder this week that prices can drop quite rapidly
if anything looks like upsetting sentiment. The quick recovery after interest
rates were lowered by the now fashionable quarter point showed both how vital
interest rates are and how willing the buyers are, for the time being at least,
to remain loyal to shares.
We seem to be in a low growth environment, with the financial authorities
prepared to take action to avoid a slip into a no growth or reverse growth one.
Inflation looks like staying low and the tiny cuts in interest rates have
persuaded the markets that there is more to come. So, in spite of the latter's
high levels, the bulls out-number the bears by a fair margin.
One of the bulls is Ian Harnett, an economist at Societe Generale Strauss
Turnbull. Writing in the latest edition of ProShare's Investor magazine, he
sticks his neck out for 4100 on the FTSE-100 index in 1996 and for Wall Street
to continue its upward march.
Mark White, investment director at Save &amp; Prosper, is a little more cautious.
With an eye on the interest rate trend, he predicts the Footsie should ``climb
towards the 3800 mark''.
So far as individual shares are concerned, he says that with the economists
predicting consumers will be spending a bit more, sectors such as brewing and
retail should lead the way. Political worries may put utilities among the
laggards. Mr White spotlights the attractions of a better-than-average income
when he makes his selection among his group's units for people wanting to
invest in the UK. He picks its High Yield fund which invests mainly in UK
blue-chip companies.
The December survey of fund managers carried out for broker Merrill Lynch also
showed 54% of them prefer the larger companies, a marginal increase from 53% in
the November survey. On a three-month basis they were more optimistic about UK
shares than they had been in November, 40% against 27%, but were more cautious
on a 12-month basis with only 35% bullish.
Japan was top of the pops with 67% optimistic on a three-month forecast and 78%
on a 12-month prediction.
Save &amp; Prosper's Rod Birkett, who runs its Japan Growth fund, predicts Japanese
shares will ``continue to benefit from strong corporate earnings growth, lax
monetary conditions and strong buying by overseas investors''.
The Japanese government is still demonstrating its determination to solve the
crisis in the financial and banking sector there and get the economy moving
from a position of virtually no growth this year. Japan will, it is hoped, be
one of the main forces keeping the world's economies on a growth path in the
coming year.
If you have interests in Europe, the year does not look particularly exciting.
A number of governments are cutting spending to meet Maastricht targets and the
economic slowdown looks like continuing. Analysts have been trimming their
forecasts for UK company earnings and the same is happening in continental
Europe.
Although Germany remains the most powerful force, professional investors
continue to prefer France, even though their confidence has been weakened a
little by the industrial problems sparked by Prime Minister Juppe's spending
cuts.
Emerging markets have been a disappointment this year - none have managed to
beat the impressive and not very well forecast performance of Wall Street.
Maybe they will do better next year. Analysts at Bank of America are hopeful
for Mexico, whose problems reversed the rise and rise of emerging markets as a
whole. They are not too worried about the success of the Communists in Russia
and think Turkey should make progress after its forthcoming general election.
The Save &amp; Prosper team says emerging market share prices are ``attractive not
only in comparison to developed markets but in absolute terms also''.
The members cite Poland, which is on a price-earnings ratio of around six to
seven times the profits projected for 1996, and also point to India, ``valued
at an historically low 13 times''. China is reckoned to have overcome the
problem of rising inflation and this should ``help to improve confidence in the
long-term prospects of what is the world's most exciting emerging market
story''.
Looking at emerging markets as a whole, it is reckoned that while share buyers
have been unenthusiastic, direct investment by multi-national corporations
continues with a record of more than $100bn being committed to these areas
during the year.
Investors will almost certainly need cool nerves in 1996. More than ever it
will be important to keep a close eye on the markets. Mr Harnett, bearing in
mind that people traditionally worry when prices keep hitting new peaks,
suggests there is no reason to fear a crash unless the Footsie reaches 4500 and
the Dow Jones 6000 by the end of next year.
He warns: ``If everybody starts to get positive about equity markets all at
once it is probably time to get out.'' Mark Twain would, one imagines, agree
with him.
</TEXT>
