<HEADLINE>Best policy could be to sell</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E Dundas,Christopher Sims,Aidan O'Carroll</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>personal finance letters</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Cartoon</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749757</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q Having recently been made redundant I have had to carefully consider all my
outgoings, and it is clear that I cannot continue to pay the premiums on a
10-year endowment policy I took out in 1989. I have been advised against
cashing in by the insurance company, but what else can I do if I cannot keep up
the payments?
n There are alternatives to cashing in the policy. You could consider making it
paid up and you will not then be required to pay further premiums. It will
mature as expected in 1999 but at a reduced value. You may, of course, have an
urgent need for the cash and if this is the case, a further alternative to
surrendering the policy would be to sell it on the second-hand market.
To evaluate these options ask your insurance company to quote the present
surrender value and to estimate the value on maturity if it is now made paid up.
q I have been grateful for your financial advice in the past. I believe I am in
a comfortable position at my mid-thirties having 13 years remaining on a
#60,000 endowment mortgage, provision set aside for the children's university
education, good company pension arrangements, and reasonable life assurance via
endowment/savings plans.
You previously gave me advice to follow investment trusts. I make small monthly
contributions to Foreign &amp; Colonial and Murray Smaller Markets. I now have
about #200 a month to invest, and I would be obliged if you would advise me of
the best investment products in today's market. I am guided towards a MIP with
Allied Dunbar.
n You seem well set up, and so long as you are sure you have done all you can
to ensure a good company pension, you should stick with the beast that you know.
Your investments with Foreign &amp; Colonial and Murray Smaller Markets should be
paying dividends, especially with you choosing monthly contributions to build
up your holdings. You may be interested to know that Foreign &amp; Colonial has
just become a constituent of the FTSE-100 share index and that its shares
gained additional value in anticipation of this.
For the small investor, internationally diversified investment trusts remain
the best method of building up capital, especially in the early stages. Other
trusts you might care to try are Alliance Trust in Dundee, Martin Currie's
Scottish Eastern in Edinburgh, and Baillie Gifford's Scottish Mortgage, also in
Edinburgh.
You can subscribe to all of these through monthly contributions. You might,
therefore, like to spread your #200 around these and step up your contributions
to Foreign &amp; Colonial and Murray Smaller Markets.
At a later stage, when you have built up your capital and your financial
position has been further improved by paying off your mortgage, you might like
to think of investment through personal equity plans, assuming they still exist.
q The Chancellor has just increased the threshold for inheritance tax from the
previous rate of #154,000 to #200,000. What would be the position in the case
of a relative's will when, say, the person had died prior to this change, for
example in September, and yet the solicitor says the estate will not be settled
until the middle of 1996 at the very earliest?
n The nil rate band applies to chargeable transfers at the date the transfer is
made. On the death of a person inheritance tax is chargeable as if they had
made a chargeable transfer of the estate immediately before they died. The
estate is valued for tax purposes at that date and the rates of tax in force at
that time are applied. This includes the amount of nil rate band and,
therefore, the date of settlement of the estate is irrelevant for this purpose.
q I have received literature from Invesco regarding its new corporate bond PEP
called High Income Investment with an estimated 8.5% interest rate. If my
memory serves me correctly I think some time ago you advised caution on
investing in corporate bonds. The rate of interest appears to be higher than
the average offered just now and, as I have an old investment maturing soon, I
would be obliged if you would advise me if you consider this a good choice or
whether I should go for something else.
If your advice is against Invesco, would you please give me your preference for
investment for income. I am retired and pay income tax at the standard rate.
n Corporate bond PEPs are fine as part of an income portfolio which includes
other risk-free investments. But it would be unwise for any investor to have
all of his or her money in them.
The problem with corporate bond PEPs is that they are not free from risk,
though they are less risky than straight investment in shares. If interest
rates go up and/or the stock market falls, the value of the bonds will also
drop, leaving you with a potential capital loss.
Generally speaking, the higher the yield, the less likely it is that the
capital will be maintained. If you want to be on the safe side, you could
choose a lower-yielding PEP such as that offered by Whittingdale &amp; Co (0171 623
2444), which has a better risk profile than most.
q Over the past three years, the company I work for has had to suspend pension
premiums due to various circumstances. It is now in a position to restart
contributions to my pension fund. I will retire in six years. In view of the
timescale, would an AVC be the best place for the contributions or should they
be placed in PEPs or a Tessa? If the pension is advised is there a point when
further AVCs at a later date are not justified by the annual amount received.
n It is difficult to give a full reply without knowing more details. It would
seem unlikely that your company would allow you to choose how its contributions
will be applied. In any case, they could not be used for a PEP or Tessa because
tax relief would be lost.
If it is a final salary scheme then the contributions will automatically go
into the pension fund. If it is a money purchase scheme, where a pot of money
builds up for each employee to buy a pension on retirement, or the company
contributes towards your personal pension plan, then there is no point
considering an AVC which is essentially the same thing.
An AVC is an extra voluntary contribution made by the employee which may or may
not be connected to the main scheme. It is used to augment the pension
available from the main company scheme.
q During 1994-95 my company car was off the road for a seven-week period
following an accident. During that time I had to travel by public transport
both to and from work and while on my employer's business as he would not hire
a car for me on a temporary basis. My notice of coding for 1994-95 included a
car benefit for the full year. Am I due a tax repayment on the scaled down
benefit and, if so, how do I claim it?
n On the information supplied your car benefit will be scaled down to
316/365ths of the normal figure. Scaling down of benefits is possible where the
car was incapable of being used at all throughout a period of at least 30
consecutive days.
As you have been taxed on the full benefit you will be due a repayment. Write
to your Inspector of Taxes explaining why you think a repayment is due and ask
him or her to issue a schedule E assessment. It may be worth checking first
that your employer has reported the correct information on the year-end return
form P11D as otherwise your repayment will be delayed until the benefit is
sorted out.
q It was in my mind to invest #10,000 each for my nephew's children who were
born in 1993 and 1995. I would want them to get the total amount when they
reach 21 years of age.
n Over such a timescale an investment in equities would produce the highest
return and well-established investment trusts with a consistent track record
would fit the bill admirably. You could divide each #10,000 and put equal
amounts into Alliance, Bankers, Foreign &amp; Colonial and English &amp; Scottish.
The share certificates should be issued to you (or somebody else) as nominee to
hold for the child as beneficiary. Then tax on the dividends could be reclaimed
if the income fell within the child's personal allowance. Each of the children
could then expect to receive a handsome nest egg when the time came.
Caledonian Newspapers Limited and the editor of The Herald accept no legal
responsibility for the answers given in these columns. Readers are invited to
submit concise questions for answer in the paper. No correspondence can be
entered into.
</TEXT>
