<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Christmas story   Ancient myth and hallowed tradition</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749760</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE English vicar who thought he was being honest and open with the children in
his church in telling them recently that Father Christmas does not exist, soon
found out that such simple truths are far from simple. He was verbally
snowballed by irate parishioners who did not want their Christmas myth to be
melted by such brutal facts. Moderators or bishops who have cast doubt upon the
Virgin Birth or the details of the Christmas story have faced similar
hostility, even from those who would consider themselves to be fairly
sceptical. When they approach Christmas, they must tread gently, for they tread
upon the thin ice of ancient myth and hallowed tradition. Underneath lies icy
disapproval for having broken the common ground upon which so much of our
Christmas celebrations depend. Many of the elements which go to make up
traditional Christmas come directly from the Bible stories of the incarnation
and involve shepherds, angels, a stable etc. Others are products of pagan
mythology such as Yule logs, fir trees, and reindeer. The wise men with their
reliance on astrology seem to have a foot in both camps.
Far from being irreconcilable, these differing traditions have made common
ground in Christmas. Christianity took over and then embraced the pagan
traditions. Now we are witnessing a second wave of syncretism, in which secular
society has embraced the Christian symbols. Hymns are played incessantly in
supermarkets, while jokey advent calendars featuring pop-open windows of a
distinctly non-religious nature sell alongside the more pious originals. This
marriage of convenience is a strong and mutually beneficial alliance. Those who
wish the holy event to be given prominence are aided by the galaxy of marketing
and sales promotion geared to Christmas. They can insist, with integrity, that
we should not lose touch with the original meaning and uphold the spiritual
values of Christmas. Those who simply want to warm the chill darkness of the
winter solstice by eating, drinking, and making merry, are assisted so to do by
the ritual meal which is integral to Christmas. Many of them will even find
themselves in a church on Christmas Eve bellowing out hymns about being
``begotten not created''. Even if their essential beliefs or motives are very
different, both groups are able to profit from the activities of the other.
This may go some way to explain why debunking clerics are deplored by those
whom they seek to liberate from the mists of mythology. We want the mystique of
Christmas and we are prepared to suspend our critical faculties in order to
keep it. Rather than deplore this state of affairs, we should look carefully at
the benefits it brings, not only to the religious and the revellers. The common
ground of peace and goodwill which Christmas occupies is a window of
opportunity for charities and caring organisations to touch the conscience of
the public. In our increasingly fragmented culture, it is one of the few
remaining festivals which command near-universal celebration and retain the
semblance of a unified society. Christmas goodwill - whether forced or simply
formal - can never go amiss in a divided and uncertain society. Even if it is
ice which covers deep social problems, even if it is thin ice - it is still a
common ground upon which we can join groups, nations, and continents in order
to seek peace and goodwill in a divided world. The freezing weather of winter
creates that opportunity in nature. The celebration of Christmas creates it in
human nature throughout the world. We happily use it as an opportunity to wish
our readers the blessings of Christmas.
</TEXT>
