<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749761</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DENTIST drank two bottles of vodka a day and turned to tranquillisers when
his flamboyant life-style became too much for him.
A court heard that Raymond Smith, who amassed a fortune, was unable to cope
with the stress of life in the fast lane and is now a shadow of his former self.
The high flier was not only involved in dentistry but also had interests in
North Sea oil rigs and fishing trawlers.
But when Smith's empire crashed he tried to bolster his earnings by fiddling
claims for the dental work he had carried out, Aberdeen Sheriff Court was told
yesterday.
Over an 18-month period Smith overstated the dental treatment he had given to
68 patients.
While practising in Aberdeen he gave one patient veneers instead of crowns and
claimed he had filled more teeth than he had.
The swindle was uncovered when he submitted the claims for payment to the
Scottish Dental Practice Board in Edinburgh.
Once passed by the SDPB they were then forwarded to Grampian Health Board who
authorise payments to individual dentists.
Smith, 51, who no longer practises and now lives in Garleston-on-Sea, Norfolk,
admitted attempting to defraud Grampian Health Board of #7627.40.
The court was told at an earlier hearing that a number of Smith's patients had
had their mouths examined by dental officers and these revealed discrepancies
in his claims.
The bogus work was carried out between 1989 and 1991 after Smith's business
ventures collapsed, his counsel, Miss Frances McMenamin said.
His surgery had been in Albert Street in the city's West End and he had also
carried out work at Old Mill of Forresterhill, near Oldmeldrum, Aberdeenshire.
But Smith, who has a long list of ailments and now walks with a stick, had no
recollection of committing the crime, she added.
``Due to his medical and pyschiatric problems he had memory lapses for some
considerable time.
``Not least of which is the fact that at about the time when the offences were
being committed he took two bottles of vodka a day supplemented by valium and
diazepam.
``He got to that stage because he had become such a high flier that he found it
hard to cope with the stresses and strains of continuing this way of life.
``He was not only involved in dentistry, he had interests in oil rigs and he
had interests in trawlers.
``It seemed that he had quite an entrepreneurial skill but in the early 1980s
everything fell apart financially and he became bankrupt.''
Miss McMennamin added that Smith had lost everything and was now dependent on
his wife.
``He cannot remember from one minute to the next what is going on. He has no
recollection of being married or of his wedding,'' added the advocate.
Sheriff Alexander Pollock fined Smith #1500 saying: ``The crime to which you
have pled guilty must be viewed seriously by the court especially as it
involved an attempted fraud on the public purse.
``The court must make clear its disapproval of what you did,'' he said.
</TEXT>
