<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>30 cars hit wall in four hours</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749763</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIRTY vehicles in four hours hit the same garden wall after skidding on an icy
Coatbridge road.
Mr Angus Walker, 56, of Horslett Street, watched helplessly as the vehicles
slid sideways down the ungritted hill before coming to a stop when they hit his
wall.
Mr Walker called the council and asked them to grit the road but it took them
four hours to get there.
Mr Walker, said: ``It was like watching dodgems. It wasn't the drivers' fault,
because they were only doing about five miles an hour.
``It's lucky they were going so slowly so there was no real damage done. But if
a car had been coming along my street there could quite easily have been a
crash. Someone could have been seriously hurt.''
He added: ``This is the second time that this has happened. Two years ago a
lorry came right through the wall and caused loads of damage.''
A spokesman for Strathclyde Regional Council said: ``There is an order of
priority for which roads we grit first. That's done on a safety basis.
``Motorways and access to schools and hospitals must take priority.''
</TEXT>
