<HEADLINE>Motoring groups build gender profiles Acid test for the male and female driver</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749765</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S two leading motoring organisations are sponsoring research to build a
psychological profile of male and female drivers in an effort to reduce
accidents.
Yesterday the Automobile Association announced it has commissioned a University
of Reading professor to examine the different behaviour patterns of men and
women drivers.
Psychology professor Frank McKenna will spend three years analysing the
``gender differences'' in hazard perception, speed, and overtaking.
The aim is to tailor the needs of driving courses to men and women, should
differences emerge, dispel sterotypical myths, and ultimately to prevent
accidents.
The study follows recent RAC-commissioned research into aggressive driving and
a novel stunt this week by its author, Glasgow-based psychologist Conrad King,
to counsel potentially aggressive, violent drivers at motorway service stations.
Back at home in Glasgow yesterday Mr King admitted he was exhausted after his
three-day roadside therapy sessions in the South of England. In service
stations off the M25, M11 in Essex, and the M3 in Hampshire he heard
confessions of aggressive driving including a claim by one driver that he
carried a plastic shotgun in his car to point threateningly at other road users.
The purpose of the exercise was not so much to change attitudes over a coffee -
Mr King says only a series of sessions can achieve results - but to raise
awareness of the issues and to allow stressed-out motorists a chance to let off
steam.
Mr King, who is set to publish a book on aggressive driving in the new year,
said the RAC was planning to submit a proposal to the Home Office for a network
of counsellors able to offer help to those convicted of aggressive driving
offences or involved in an accident.
The freelance psychologist said his research had centred round studies of the
attitudes of people at work and in their cars. There was, he said, a noticeable
increase in the amount of aggression when people got behind the wheel.
``People become more aggressive because they feel like they are in a protected
environment and feel more powerful. Being in a car is like having armour and
can have a dehumanising effect.''
Of his roadside therapy sessions Mr King said: ``I got quite a positive
response. Most people want to talk about other people's driving which is why
it's hard to get them to look at their own.''
His own skills were put to the test when, reluctantly posing on a couch for
press photographers on a slip road, a motorists screeched to a halt beside the
sofa believing he could not get past, instantly becoming irate at the
obstruction. ``He had in fact assessed the situation wrongly and could get
past. I was able to mediate.''
</TEXT>
