<HEADLINE>Ashbourne in leaseback deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749766</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW-based Ashbourne is following the lead of US nursing homes groups by
selling and leasing back properties to free up cash for ambitious expansion
plans.
Ashbourne yesterday claimed the first major transaction of this kind in the UK
healthcare sector. It is to raise #16.8m from the sale and lease back of five
of its 25 nursing homes in a deal with Abbey Life Assurance Company.
The proceeds will be used to reduce Ashbourne's gearing to nil and will ensure
the group's development programme can be financed without cash calls on
shareholders.
Abbey Life has purchased Eastwood Court in Giffnock, Glasgow, Warren Park in
Largs, and three other nursing homes in Bromley in Kent, Cardiff and
Leicestershire, which had a combined book value of #14.8m on October 1.
Ashbourne will initially pay aggregate annual rent of #1.65m, on 35-year
leases, with rent reviews every five years.
The nursing homes group will open another development in Middlesex on January
11. It has another four homes under construction and four landbank sites which
have still to be developed.
It is actively seeking further sites near the M25 around London, which it sees
as the major growth area.
Shareholders will be asked to approve the sale and leaseback agreement at an
extraordinary meeting in the new year.
Ashbourne, which last month announced a rise in pre-tax profits from #1.2m to
#6.5m for the year to October 1, envisages that gearing will not rise above 10%
in the current 12 months.
A spokeswoman said: ``When it is offered the right price, Ashbourne is very
keen to do this.
``(Chief executive) Tom Hamilton has looked at the US market and this is the
market which has led the way on this. Most US nursing homes groups work on the
sale and leaseback principle because it provides them with the cash to build
more homes without having to go back to the shareholders.''
Ashbourne is disappointed about the dearth of property investment trusts
covering the UK nursing homes sector because this would provide another avenue
for sale and leaseback agreements. Such trusts are more common in the US.
Shares in Ashbourne, a management buy-out from hotels and casinos company
Stakis in 1993, yesterday lost 1p to 132p.
</TEXT>
