<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Area's milk may be marketed on its unrivalled qualities Ayrshire's cream of the crop</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749767</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Ayrshire Cattle Society's confidence that its breed produces the best milk
has been confirmed by market research as part of a study into the prospects for
a niche-market promotion of Ayrshire milk.
Cambridge Market Research used six countrywide consumer panels involving 49
housewives. In taste, health, and overall impression Ayrshire milk came out
with a top score of 39 out of 50. Any score over 36 is assessed to be a very
good product.
In a ``blind'' tasting using three milks, Ayrshire came out top with 49%
preference.
The market research company's conclusion is that milk from Ayrshire cows was
well received. ``The product itself performed very well .....and we recommend
that this milk is launched nationally,'' they added.
Ayrshire whole milk was described as uniquely sweet and creamy without being
too rich in taste. It also had a smooth texture and a light, rather than thick,
consistency ``giving clean and satisfying responses as a refreshing, drinking
milk''.
An interesting plus from the dairy farmer's standpoint was the consumers' view
that Ayrshire milk warranted a premium price because of its quality and
superior taste.
The consumer results were also matched by scientific work at the Hannah
Research Institute where expert panels compared Ayrshire milk against branded
high-fat milk on four sensory attributes - creamy aroma, creamy flavour, sweet
flavour and mouth-feel. Ayrshire scored highest in all four attributes.
The scientific and consumer research work backs up the market place experience
of Marks &amp; Spencer which sells only Ayrshire milk in its Scottish stores
(supplied by Scottish Pride). Some individual producer/processors have also
proved that there is a niche market for the milk promoted as a superior quality
product.
Earlier this year, the Ayrshire Cattle Society appointed Dr Tony O'Sullivan of
the Agri-Food Consultancy to conduct a feasibility study on the prospects for
establishing Ayrshire milk as an identifiable brand. He forecast then the
possibility of some Ayrshire producers forming their own processing group.
He takes the view that milk should be brought to the customer as fresh as
possible, being collected from farms on a daily basis. ``If you produce high
quality milk, you don't want it sitting around in tanks for an extra 24
hours,'' he said. In Scotland the milk for Marks &amp; Spencer is collected on a
daily basis from 35 farms.
The Ayrshire Cattle Society will consider proposals for implementing the next
stage of the marketing development programme at its council meeting in
February. Details of the findings to date are being passed to the Scottish
Office which has given 50% funding for the research work under the Marketing
Development Scheme.
The society has already registered a trademark based on the word Ayrshires with
a drawing of an Ayrshire cow's head appearing through a capital A.
q.Farmers are increasing the risk of significant lungwork losses in cattle by
cutting out vaccination, according to a Veterinary Investigation Centre study.
Twelve affected UK herds, only three of which carried out routine vaccination,
were observed in the study. Graham David of Shrewsbury VIC said that wormers
alone could not be relied upon for long-term prevention.
</TEXT>
