<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dame Nita Barrow</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749768</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dame Nita Barrow, nurse and public servant; born Barbados, November 15, 1916,
died there, December 19, 1995
DAME Nita Barrow, the first woman Governor-General of Barbados, and a widely
respected figure known as ``the People's Governor-General'', has died in
Bridgetown at the age of 79 after collapsing at a party.
Dame Nita was appointed Governor-General in 1990 after a lifetime in public
service in the Caribbean and on the world stage. She was the elder sister of
Errol Barrow, a former Prime Minister of Barbados, founder of the present
opposition party there, and architect of the island's independence.
A nurse and public health expert by background, Nita Barrow pursued specialist
nursing studies at Edinburgh University in 1951-52 and at Columbia University
in the US a decade later. A series of administrative posts in nursing in the
Commonwealth Caribbean culminated in her becoming director in 1964 of a
research project into nursing in the region. It led to the reorganisation and
upgrading of nurses' training there.
This aspect of public service was complemented by Nita Barrow's international
commitment through the YWCA and World Council of Churches. Her appointment as
associate director of the Christian Medical Commission of the WCC in 1971, and
as director four years later, gave her the chance to promote primary health
care and direct Western thinking towards recognition of traditional medicine.
Nita Barrow's travels as director of the CMC, as world president of the YWCA,
and as president of the International Council of Adult Education also allowed
her to promote the cause of women and the improvement of their status.
Her success as convener of the conference marking the end of the UN Decade of
Women in 1985 led to her nomination as the only woman in the ``Eminent Persons
Group'' set up to visit South Africa the following year and encourage the
necessary process of political change from apartheid to majority rule. She
lived to see, and rejoice in, the establishment of democracy there.
In 1986 she was appointed the Barbadian ambassador to the United Nations, where
one of her first speeches was on the status of women.
She was made a dame by the Queen in 1980 and was the popular choice for
Governor-General of Barbados in 1990. Her last international meetings were
associated with the fiftieth anniversary of the United Nations, appropriately,
for she herself was a widely admired and liked figure on the international
scene.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents await return of body</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749769</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE parents of a British property executive were last night awaiting the return
of their son's body after he was discovered murdered in his Paris flat.
Ian Wootton, 31, was expecting to move to a new job in New York when the killer
struck.
Detectives said he had been hit several times over the head, apparently after
interrupting thieves as they rifled through his belongings.
His father Leonard, 69, a retired bank official, who lives in Brentwood, Essex,
said he had seen his son 10 days ago and they had been due to meet up again
over the Christmas period.
``We don't know much of what is happening at this stage - it is in the hands of
the police in Paris,'' he said. ``It appears from the face of it that it is a
suspected murder case.''
The dead man was a manager with the Hammerson property company. He had been due
to move to America in the new year.
He qualified as a chartered surveyor and took a degree at South Bank University
before studying in Paris.
His father said he was a dedicated employee who spent much of his time at work.
His body was discovered on Thursday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man found guilty of bogus diet claim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749770</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former boyfriend of Samantha Fox was yesterday found guilty of taking part
in a bogus diet conspiracy involving a Young Slimmer of the Year, whose weight
dropped from 22st to 10st.
Marketing executive Peter Foster, 33, an Australian, stood impassively as the
jury returned its verdict after being out for 45 minutes at Liverpool Crown
Court.
Then the court heard that he had been fined for a similar offence last year and
was on bail for an alleged offence relating to a thigh reducing cream.
Judge Richard Hamilton remanded Foster, of Hadley Wood, Barnet, north London,
until January 11 for a pre-sentence report to be prepared.
Foster had denied conspiring with Young Slimmer of the Year Michele Deakin and
others to supply slimming granules under the name Deakin Diet, contrary to
trading standards rules.
Mr Neil Flewitt, prosecuting, told the court after the verdict that Foster had
one relevant previous conviction.
In September 1994 he was fined at Warwick Crown Court for similar offences
involving Bai Lin tea, allegedly a slimming aid.
Foster had left the country in June 1988, on the day he was due to stand trial
at Warwick.
``He stayed out of the country for six years,'' added Mr Flewitt.
``He was on bail to Warwick when he approached Michele Deakin.''
Miss Deakin, 27, pled guilty to the same charge that Foster faced at Liverpool
Crown Court in 1990.
She was given a suspended six-month prison sentence and fined #250.
The court heard during the four-day trial how Foster contacted her when she was
named Young Slimmer of 1988.
He persuaded her to endorse his slimming product, made from Guar Gum, although
she had never used it.
But Foster told the court when he gave evidence yesterday that he never
attributed Miss Deakin's weight loss to the product, formerly called MRA30.
Judge Hamilton told the jury of nine men and three women before discharging
them after the verdict yesterday: ``I wish you seasonal greetings.
``If you over-indulge during Christmas, I hope you will be better informed
about slimming remedies.''
Mr Frank Harper, principal trading standards officer at Knowsley, Merseyside,
who brought the action, said: ``I am very pleased with the verdict.
``I have always been convinced that Foster was behind the scam.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Borderers have RAF low jets in sights</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andy Murray</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749771</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Councillors in Border counties have forced a meeting in Whitehall with
Government officials to discuss low-flying aircraft. Andy Murray reports
TO the purple-faced child who shrieks as a formation of supersonic RAF Tornados
hurtles overhead at 450 knots, LFA 20 (T) is meaningless. Toddlers bothered by
decibels do not know that over much of Southern Scotland jets may legitimately
fly as low as 100 feet.
LFA 20 (T), the Borders Tactical Training Area, is one of only three areas of
Western Europe in which pilots may fly this low. The others are Central Wales
and the North-west Highlands.
Disenchanted campaigners who thought they would get more peace when the cold
war thawed include George Foulkes, Labour MP for Cumnock, Carrick and Doon
Valley, who has tabled 38 parliamentary questions on low flying. The Ministry
of Defence told him this month that compensation paid to farmers for incidents
had almost doubled in three years.
Pay-outs for damage to livestock totalled #182,000 in 1992-93, while in 1994-95
they amounted to #327,000. Over the past financial year compensation paid for
property damage was #86,000; for aircraft crash damage #148,000; for personal
injury #121,000 and for other damage #21,000.
This is for transgressions in the UK by British and foreign pilots. It does not
include payments made by delegated ``Defence Land Agents''.
``A spectacular #750,000 was paid out last year. The conclusion to be drawn is
how dangerous low flying is,'' says Foulkes.
``Even with no major incidents they are still causing a lot of problems. There
have been pay-outs totalling more than #3m over the last six years.''
Earl Howe, Under Secretary of State for Defence, assured MPs in Southern
Scotland recently that he would seek ways of reducing the frequency of sorties
in LFA 20 (T).
``But all the brass hats will be trying to pull him in the other direction.
That is our fear,'' says Foulkes.
Meanwhile, the Inter-Authority Group on Low Flying, which comprises councillors
from thoughout Southern Scotland and Northern England, has secured an
unprecedented showdown in Whitehall with Earl Howe on January 10.
Its chairman, Councillor Denis Male, vice-convener of Dumfries and Galloway
regional council, said: ``Low flying is a problem which has plagued communities
in the Border areas for too long. We are not against training, but we want to
make pilots accountable.
``Some of them have a gung-ho attitude and they do not seem to give a damn
about people on the ground.''
The group says the RAF should be made aware of galas, common ridings,
equestrian events and agricultural peak periods. It accuses pilots of
deliberately ``targeting'' rural schools, hospitals and other landmarks, and it
will press Earl Howe to confine low flying to wilderness areas outwith national
parks.
The group will criticise the secrecy surrounding exclusion zones and
investigations. ``We want alert statuses and perhaps a charter on low flying,''
says Male. ``We want on-board flight monitoring equipment to record heights and
target lists and we want an Ombudsman on low flying.''
Malcolm Spaven, an Edinburgh-based defence consultant, researched low flying
for the Economic and Social Research Council. ``There is a general concern
that, despite the end of the cold war the intensity of low flying, particularly
in the Borders, is not going down,'' he says.
``The RAF says more hours of low flying are needed per pilot. Spending on the
MoD's Civil Service has been transferred to frontline units. Although the
number of sorties has gone down the number of hours of low flying has gone
right up. There is more emphasis now on realism, and pilots are expected to
have more low flying in their training.''
Health problems caused by the sudden appearance of a jet which clocks up 125
decibels have never been properly gauged in the UK. A report published last
month by the University of Leeds, however, concluded: ``There is no doubt that
noise from military low-altitude flights is a stressor. The literature
catalogues numerous suspected health impacts.
``With the exception of noise-induced hearing loss and possibly blood pressure
effects these health impacts remain unproven and, sadly, are likely to remain
that way.''
Another study suggests that children living in tactical low-flying areas
perform more poorly in school and are more susceptible to anxiety disorders.
German studies suggest that frequent exposure by children to low-flying
aircraft can lead to headaches and nightmares.
In 1990 a survey conducted at RAF West Freugh in Galloway revealed several
instances of jets flying at 128 decibels, although the MoD had long adjudged
125 decibels to be the level above which there was a health risk.
An MoD official argued: ``In height-judging competitions held in 1987 at Battle
of Britain open days most people underestimated heights. More than 70% of
people were more than 100 feet out in their estimates, and 45% were more than
150 feet out.''
Pilots had to be able to fly as low and fast as possible to have a reasonable
chance of penetrating enemy defences. Flight simulators were not good enough.
Apparently ``specially designated, sparsely populated areas'' such as LFA 20
(T) are.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Royal Bank ups its Spanish stake</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749772</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Bank of Scotland has upped its stake in Banco Santander SA to 2.4%
with the #50m acquisition of 1.6 million of the Spanish bank's capital stock.
The banks entered into an alliance strategy in 1988 which allows each to hold
up to 2.5% of the other's stock. Two representatives from each bank sit on
their partner's board.
NFC drops talks
NFC has pulled out of negotiations with Lep Group to buy its freight forwarding
business, Lep International, which it is understood will now be acquired by its
management for a nominal sum.
The business has assets of #68m and made operating profits of #6.5m in 1993 but
is saddled with debt.
Taylor-made post
JOHN TAYLOR, 48, a European vice-president of Exxon Chemicals, has been
appointed chief executive of state-owned British Nuclear Fuels, operators of
the Sellafield site in Cumbria. He takes up his post in March.
Broadgate deal
BRITISH Land has spent #121.5m to take control of Broadgate Properties. The
property developer is buying the 50% of Broadgate, which helped build the high
profile office development of the same name in the City, it did not already own.
Mercury man
ROD OLSEN, finance director and acting chief executive of Cable &amp; Wireless, has
been appointed chairman of its Mercury telephone subsidiary. The business has
been without a chairman for a month since Lord Young stepped down as chairman
of both Mercury and C&amp;W.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cairn Energy raises #4.88m for drilling</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW MULLINS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749773</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH-based Cairn Energy has raised #4.88m through a share placing to fund
a solo offshore drilling venture in Bangladesh and projects in the Netherlands,
UK, US and China.
The main action for Cairn is in Bangladesh, where it is targeting the offshore
Sangu-1 well on block 16.
Unlike Semutang on the adjacent onshore block 15, where the company is working
with Midlands Electricity, Cairn is going it alone with Sangu-1.
Chief executive Bill Gammell has not ruled out bringing in a partner along the
way, but he believes it is in the best interests of shareholders for the
exploration to remain a solo venture for the time being.
Cairn, the first Western company to sign a production-sharing contract in
Bangladesh, now has an interest in four million acres in two blocks. It is
hoping to construct a power station, with Midlands, which would be fuelled by
gas from the Semutang well.
The company has recently exercised its option to puchase a 30% stake in the
power project even though it has not agreed on a price for the conversion of
gas to electricity with the Bangladeshi government.
Construction of the power station, which Cairn hoped would begin in the second
quarter of next year, will not now start until the end of the year. Cairn is
trying to negotiate a financing package with the World Bank.
The new shares, which were placed by SG Strauss Turnbull at 111.5p, represent
5% of the company's issued share capital prior to the deal.
</TEXT>
