<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#900,000 given for cancer care</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749774</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH hospital has secured #900,000 out of #13m unused NHS capital
spending to assist the development of its cancer services.
The Western General Hospital in Edinburgh, a world renowned cancer treatment
centre, has earmarked several items which are needed for its work.
The news of the funding came after a visit to the Western General Hospital
yesterday by Scottish Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton.
Lord James said the Scottish Office would redistribute the rest of the #13m to
various other hospital projects.
Hospital trusts from all over Scotland have submitted bids for the cash, with
priority being given to bids which focus on cancer services, mental health, and
cardiac and cerebral vascular services.
Among the items to be purchased by the Western General Hospital is a #90,000
machine which enables computerised analysis of DNA sequences to identify the
genetic likelihood of developing conditions such as Huntingdon's Disease.
During the tour of the hospital Lord James said: ``Let me make it clear at the
outset that this is not new money but arises from slippage in the NHS capital
programme.
``I will come to a decision on other individual bids very soon.''
Lord James said the Western General's submission was an ``impressive'' one.
Mr John Connaghan, chief executive of the Western General Hospitals NHS Trust,
said: ``This is a timely announcement of capital funding that will enhance the
services we provide across a range of specialities, including cancer services,
neuro-sciences, clinical genetics, and imaging.''
</TEXT>
