<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clyde yard wins fisheries order</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749776</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at a Clyde shipyard were told yesterday that they had won a #19m order
for a fishery research vessel which will help secure their jobs.
The order placed with Ferguson Shipbuilders, of Port Glasgow, was announced by
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth. It gives the yard its first order since it
was taken over by millionaire Frank Dunnet earlier this year.
The new ship, a replacement for the FRV Scotia, is due to be completed by
autumn 1997.
Ferguson won the contract in face of fierce competition from the UK, Europe,
and America.
``It is excellent that a Scottish shipyard and its workforce should be judged
fully capable of meeting all the demanding technical requirements of such a
sophisticated, hi-tech vessel,'' said Mr Forsyth.
``This contract represents excellent value for the taxpayer, having been won as
a result of a competitive process.
``It also demonstrates the Government's support for the long-term interests of
the fishing industry.''
The yard is currently finishing off two tugs and is working on a ferry and an
offshore supply vessel.
</TEXT>
