<HEADLINE>Putting Santa in the shade</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>business diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749777</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEN Allen, managing director of Kellock, a subsidiary of the Bank of Scotland,
has been acting as a modern day Santa Claus since December 1, travelling 5000
miles to visit firms in Scotland, England and Wales.
Allen, who founded the factoring company in 1976, calls unexpectedly around
Christmas time bearing gifts. This year he visited a record 189 of his 500
clients, beating last year's total of 144 visits and covering the UK from
Aberdeen to the south coast of England. He arrives at his client's offices in
his Jaguar with a gift of a bottle of red and a bottle of white wine.
He finished his tour in Glasgow yesterday, and I spoke to him just as he was
about switch off the office lights and head home to Reading to enjoy Christmas.
``It's great fun but because I don't make appointments I miss about 20% of the
clients, but if I made appointments it would take me much longer as I would
have to spend more time with each one. I enjoy it very much. I have only missed
doing the tour on three occasions since the company started in 1976, and one of
those was 1990 when we were making a loss, and I didn't think you could give
gifts in a loss making situation.''
Postgraduate
skills in demand
THE British Council in Edinburgh is looking for companies interested in
participating in the Scottish International Resource Project. Every year it
works with a group of around 80 people selected from postgraduate courses
throughout the country's universities.
Companies should let Sheila Lumsden, the project manager at SIRP, know about
any particular requests they may have, and what nationality or discipline is of
interest. The postgraduates come from key overseas markets, and are keen to
develop business contacts during their stay.
There are now more than 2000 SIRP participants back home in 50 countries who
are willing and able to assist Scottish exporters. If you are interested in the
scheme, or would like to contact a SIRP person in a particular country to help
you on the ground, call Sheila Lumsden on 0131 452 9789 or e-mail her on
Sheila.Lumsden britcoun.org.
Masked men are
just the ticket
BUSINESS Diary readers have the chance to start the New Year in style with a
bottle of champers and a pair of tickets to see Phantom of the Opera at
Edinburgh's Playhouse Theatre courtesy of Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
The accountancy firm held a Christmas party earlier this week, and as it
sponsors Phantom of the Opera it decided it should be themed round the show. As
well as a guest phantom playing favourite tunes, there was a competition to win
the best seats and anovernight stay at the Caledonian Hotel. The 100 or so
guests certainly got into the spirit of things and raised more than #700 for
charity.
To keep the fun going, and to make sure Business Diary readers don't miss out,
we have organised a little competition of our own. All you have to do is
identify the Coopers &amp; Lybrand partners behind the masks (pictured left), and
fax your answer to Julie Moulsdale on 0141 221 8256 by Friday, December 29.
The winner will receive a bottle of Coopers &amp; Lybrand champagne and a pair of
tickets for the show. Employees of the firm need not apply!
Lunch with a
European theme
THE Scottish Council of the European Movement lunch in the Sheraton Grand Hotel
in Edinburgh on January 18 should be an interesting occasion. Sir David Simon,
chairman of BP, will address the meeting on the subject of Building a European
Company.
We are told the talk will reflect his vision of a single market for oil
products, and it will be intriguing to hear what he has to say about the
proposed Euro. If you would like to attend the lunch, which costs #35, give
Barbara MacLeod a call on 0131 220 0377.
Chamber gets
the travel bug
SCOTTISH Chambers of Commerce is organising two trade missions during 1996. The
first, planned for April, will visit the United Arab Emirates and Kuwait, while
the second will travel to Israel in July.
The UK is the third largest supplier to the UAE after Japan and the US, and
half our exports there are to the rapidly growing manufacturing sector.
According to the British Embassy in Dubai, the priority sectors include
construction, medical supplies and power generation. In Kuwait opportunities
exist for companies in the oil sector and fine quality durable goods.
Anyone requiring further information on the missions should contact the
International Trade Division on 0141 204 2121.
Soviets march
on the SECC
A CONFERENCE and exhibition aimed at improving trade with the former Soviet
Union countries is coming to Glasgow's SECC in the spring. The Spectra 96
Anglo-Scottish Eastern Europe Business Conference will be held from March 12 to
14 and will include a mix of exhibitors from the UK and the former Soviet Union
targeted at key sectors such as electronics, textiles, engineering, oil and gas.
To get involved, contact AR Trade Fairs, Suite 6, Mostyn Hall, Penrith, Cumbria
CA11 7XR; tel 01768 899739 or fax 01768 892259.
Royal affair at
the institute
IT WILL be a right royal affair at the West of Scotland Branch of the Institute
of Petroleum annual dinner on March 28 when Their Majesties King Constantine
and Queen Marie are to be the principal guests.
There will be more than 900 guests at the dinner in the Hospitality Inn,
Glasgow, and King Constantine will be the main speaker and propose the toast to
the institute. Gilbert Gray QC will respond, and Bill Beaton chairman of the
West of Scotland branch will chair the proceedings.
This is another nice little coup by Beaton and his committee, which every year
produces a speaker just a bit out of the ordinary. At this year's dinner it was
Pik Botha, the South African Foreign Minister.
</TEXT>
