<HEADLINE>Rail bid consortia may face inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STARRS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749778</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHADOW transport spokesman Brian Wilson has called for a halt to the sale of
British Rail's freight arm after allegations about the background of companies
involved in bids.
Mr Wilson has also demanded a full investigation of the main shareholders in
two US-led consortia which hope to take over the three regional companies which
make up the service.
He said that one company involved, the US construction firm Kiewit, paid $415m
in 1990 to settle a law suit which alleged it had used a computer to identify
and lay off workers just before they qualified for pensions.
The same company, which is involved in a consortium led by the Denver based
firm Omnitrax, is now at the centre of an FBI investigation over problems with
a multi-billion dollar subway in Los Angeles.
Last night, the president of Wisconsin Central Transportation Corporation,
which is leading the second bid, faxed a letter to Mr Wilson asking for a
meeting with the Labour MP.
Mr Edward Burkhardt said he was concerned about press reports of a tax
investigation into the corporation's New Zealand merchant bank co-investors,
Fay Richwhite.
Mr Wilson said: ``I would be delighted to meet with Mr Burkhardt.''
A spokesman for the Department of Transport said last night: ``We haven't
actually said who the bidders are and we won't until we annouce who has won the
contract.
``We are satisfied with the quality of the bidders. We will be announcing the
sale early in the new year.''
</TEXT>
