<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Exit, glass in hand</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>television</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749779</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Cook drank himself to death and it was perhaps not the funniest thing he
ever did. Neither, on the other hand, was it a joke capable of much repetition
- no encores to speak of - and as Drinking Yourself to Death gags go,
``Cookie's'' must be one of the best. He exited, as it were, glass in hand.
It was never clear in the latter part of his life, when his comedic inventions
were limited to the role of reliable, and reliably squiffy, chat show guest, if
he much cared. Omnibus: Some Interesting Facts About Peter Cook (BBC1, Tuesday)
spent a good deal of time trying to discover of his old comrades whether the
comic was a man whose hopes had been disappointed, or someone who had never
hoped for very much in the first place.
Jonathan Miller was as pompous as ever; Alan Bennet vaguely wistful; and Ian
Hislop still the loyal fan eager to please. It was thus left to Dudley Moore to
inject some life into the proceedings and explain why the ``legendary''
partnership broke up. Art had nothing to do with it; trying to perform nightly
with a man who had taken precautions to render himself utterly incapable simply
drove little Dud up the wall.
What seemed obvious from the clips, each as glorious as ever, was that Cook's
comedy was an intrinsic part of him, the unpredictable stream of his
consciousness. Witness after witness, some of them the most garrulous in the
business, remembered a man who, in the beginning, could talk anyone under the
table. The booze put an end to that, as this thorough but unimaginative
portrait made clear. If, at the end, Cook affected not to care about all the
potential he had squandered, that was simply because he had no choice in the
matter.
To speak of squandering is to speak, invariably, of our beloved institutions.
Thus it was that the BBC at its most deferential could waste valuable resources
on a portrait of the royal yacht (Britannia, BBC1, Wednesday), itself a
floating symbol of the monarchy's conspicuous consumption of state cash and
public gullibility.
The excuse, such as it was, was that Her Majesty has at last condescended to
part with her gin palace, the supposed ``hospital ship'' that never saw a
patient and served Britain only by servicing the arms salesmen who give us all
so much cause to feel proud. Produced by the team who made the immensely dull
record of a year in the Queen's life, Britannia was a desperately
old-fashioned, utterly servile piece of television.
Elizabeth did not put in an appearance herself - it's the mystique you see -
but her husband explained what a wrench it would be to lose the boat (commanded
by her very own admiral) that has served the nation through some of the most
gruelling excursions to tropical paradises any freeloader has ever had to face.
Given the conditions on board, each gaudy detail lovingly observed during a
state visit to South Africa, you could see why the old boy was cut up. Equally,
you might just have understood why others among us might wish the same fate on
the boat's passengers. This sort of dire, antique advertising was precisely
what the royals don't need just at the moment.
Equally, you might guess, Ray Davies probably doesn't need to be known as ``the
godfather of Britpop''. It's rather like giving Louis Armstrong credit for the
silvery tones of Herb Alpert, or thinking the Beatles were important because of
their influence on Take That. Naff and daft, in other words, an intended
compliment that is actually a fairly substantial insult, not least when you
compare the sheer craft of Davies with the elementary noodlings of some of his
young admirers.
But as I'm Not Like Everybody Else - The World of Ray Davies And the Kinks
(BBC2, Wednesday) felt obliged to remind us, the singer was young himself once.
It was the songs, whose genesis he explored ably enough, which were
astonishingly mature from the very beginning. And if, as with Cook, Davies
could never repeat the successes of the sixties, that doesn't diminish his
achievement. Anyone who could write Days or Waterloo Sunset has nothing more to
prove.
It was a good piece nevertheless, with even Dave Davies, the singer's eternally
squabbling sibling, making a useful contribution.
Eschewing nostalgia, it managed to demonstrate that the complexity of Davies
the man, in no way like everybody else, was directly related to the complexity
of his art. He made it sound simple, but the good stuff never is.
Hence, perhaps, the astonishing success of Michael Barrymore, even when
confined to a vehicle as deeply awful as Michael Barrymore's My Kind of People
(ITV, Thursday). The contrast between his seemingly effortless professionalism
and the straining performances of amateurs in a shopping mall in Dudley (hell
is many things, and this was only one) was the comedian's best advertisement
for himself.
No format could have been worse, no setting more unappealing, yet Barrymore
sailed through it all, coaxing the kids, partnering a ``singing receptionist'',
and generally adding fresh dimensions to the word ``multi-talented''. It was
pointless even to try to hate it, but one visit to Dudley, even in this
company, was probably enough.
One visit to the Christmas schedules should also be sufficient for any
reviewer, but this week at least the networks were fairly restrained.
Granted, the BBC2 planners who allowed Yes Virginia, There is a Santa Claus
(Monday), perhaps the worst film even Charles Bronson has made, on to the air
deserve a thorough basting. But since they were presumably the same folk who
decided to give James Stewart's marvellous Mr Smith Goes to Washington an
airing the following day, it is hard to be harsh.
That may be the heart of the annual festive TV problem, however. All judgment
is suspended, it seems, when a programme has ``Christmas'' in the title. Any
old tat, and much brand-new tat, is slung on to the schedules with the gems.
Viewers are presumed to have lost such discrimination as they had and the
schedulers give their imaginations a holiday.
You know its Christmas, in other words, when the desire to drown Jilly Goolden
and Oz Clarke (Food and Drink, BBC2, Tuesday) in ``the best alcoholic seasonal
offers available'' becomes overwhelming. But don't let me put you off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A RETURN TO DISHONESTY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Steve Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>herald essay</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749780</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Steve Bruce argues that it is perverse to lay claim once a year to a liturgical
tradition and a theology which most of us disdain and deny the rest of the time
THIS week I have done two things: sung carols and spent money. The latter
caused some pain but the former caused disquiet. The carols themselves were
refreshingly old-fashioned. Thirty years ago I enjoyed church-going because I
loved the grandeur and the elegiac tones of the Presbyterian and Methodist
hymns we sang.
To this day massed voices slowly climbing up the last line of ``For those in
peril on the sea'' or walking through the bass part of The Lord's My Shepherd
bring a tear to my eye. But I gave up church and I gave up the music because I
felt deceitful delivering with gusto words I did not believe.
As will have been the case for many of us, my return to dishonesty was
occasioned by the school. The children have a carol service; parents and
younger siblings are invited. To deprive my children of a pleasure enjoyed by
their chums would be a tad precious. So I sing carols.
Even if the school had not contrived their socialisation, my children would
acquire some knowledge of Christianity from the iconography of the impending
Christmas. Having children forces us to contemplate our beliefs. Just what do
we want them to believe? Which fond fantasies do we wish to challenge? The
tooth fairy and Santa Claus are easy enough. Disabusing our children of those
notions is a matter of timing; when, not if.
But Christianity is a bigger problem, because grown-ups believe in it too. Not
many, it has to be said. The recent Scottish Church Census showed 14% of
Scottish adults in church on a typical Sunday. Perhaps a further 20% believe in
a personal God.
The weight of irreligion is such that I could remain politely reticent when my
children talk of the baby Jesus and wait until they realise that Christians are
in a minority. But should I sing carols now?
Should any of us outside the small circle of committed Christians sing carols?
Should those who never attend any other kind of Mass celebrate the ``Mass'' for
Christ?
Is it not perverse to lay claim once a year, in however a feeble and befuddled
way, to a liturgical tradition and a theology which most of us disdain and deny
the rest of the time?
There are obvious secular virtues to a grand midwinter blow-out. We can mock
the forced conversation and supressed feuds of ghastly Christmas dinners with
relatives we do not much like, but a society is improved by an annual
requirement to renew social bonds and to place convention above personal
preference.
We can denounce the enormous sums often ill-advisedly spent on presents but
there is much to be said for spending a few hours thinking about what our
spouses and children might like. We can deride the superficiality of our annual
outburst of charity. It is indeed pathetic that we open additional hostels and
soup kitchens for the homeless and run them for four days, before lapsing back
into our cold indifference. But four days is better than a kicking.
We might think the stretch between Christmas and New Year a trifle (and a cake
and a pudding and some chocolates) over long but it allows us to attack the new
year with a renewed enthusiasm for our working lives.
Anything which brings us together for a week has got to be a good idea. The
great Trades Weeks, when Glasgow and then Edinburgh and then Dundee emptied its
working class ``doon the watter'' or to the Isle of Man or to Blackpool, belong
to the era of black-and-white photographs. We now take our summer holidays as
families or with very small numbers of friends. Economies are no longer so
localised that a city can just close down. Except when the rest of the
``Christian'' world does. At Christmas.
The case for the defence of the unreformed Ebeneezer Scrooge would begin with a
critique of the mass media. Much of what we think, feel, see, and do at
Christmas is second-hand. This life at one remove is not received ``through a
glass, darkly'', as St Paul put it. It comes through a glass with stunning
brightness; a hyper-reality more real than our own lives. We both celebrate
Christmas by watching fictional characters celebrate Christmas and we allow our
own celebrations to be stage-managed by the media.
The schedules will include a large slice of nostalgia topped with clotted
sentimentality. The Yorkshire Dales of the 1930s (All Creatures Great and
Small), the Yorkshire moors of the 1950s (Heartbeat), any place and any time
past can stand for a more authentic life when people had fewer presents and
shorter holidays but enjoyed them more. But the cloying is nowadays accompanied
by the corrosive.
The school of grit-in-the-mince pie realism, that probably began with that
truly awful Christmas with Alf Garnett in Till Death us Do Part and lives on in
EastEnders, will provide us with enough dysfunctional families to satisfy the
greediest social worker. The criticism is not that the mass media present us
with images that are false in the sense of the big lie (although the preference
for the past over the present comes close to being a big lie).
It is that the hyper-reality of mass media worlds (so better scripted, filmed,
and acted and so much more to that point than our lives) dissuades us from
dodging Christmas ourselves. It is more exciting to watch other people doing
Christmas. Festive season mass media promotes voyeurism. As with the sexual
perversion, for the truly sad, television Christmas is a substitute for the
real thing; but even for us normal folks it is an unhealthy discouragement from
a real sex life.
Even when we prefer our own circumstances and relations to those of hyper-real
TV communities, we may allow the mass media to provide the basic material for
our celebrations. The many choral services are a pleasure to both churchgoers
and to the wider audience of people for whom watching fresh-faced choirboys in
surplices is the nearest they came to a shared act of religious worship.
At yet a further remove from reality, the special mass media events of the
Christmas period, instead of being a reflection of Christmas, or an aid to
celebrating Christmas, themselves become the event. The Queen's Speech, the
Agatha Christie adaptation, the pile of blank videos, and the carefully
marked-up Radio Times; these are what we celebrate. We know it's Christmas
because Scrooge is back.
There is, of course, a truckload of truth in the above critique but it
exaggerates the importance of the mass media and it mistakes the target. Try
turning it into a positive proposition. At our major annual holiday, when the
days are short, cold, and wet, when most facilities are closed, and when most
people have a chance to relax, television and radio should put on their
dullest, cheapest, least interesting programmes. Of course not. It is the big
holiday. Push the boat out. Put on the best.
If there is something wrong with the part that the mass media play in
structuring our Christmas holiday it is the same thing that is wrong with our
attitude to it all the year round and there is no-one to blame for that but
ourselves; there is an off switch. If we have become a nation of voyeurs we
cannot blame our dirt merchants for selling us an extra juicy morsel at
Christmas time.
Having roasted the media, counsel for the defence of Scrooge would go on to
decry the vast sums spent on presents. He would speak wistfully of the days
when children were thrilled with an orange and a few nuts in a darned sock. But
again try putting that in the form of a positive proposition. At our main
present-giving time of year, people should exchange gifts worth far less than
they spend on themselves every day. Silly.
Anyway, we are wrong to think that our grandparents appreciated small things
because they had a better sense of proportion and knew what really mattered in
life. They appreciated an orange and a few nuts because oranges and nuts were
expensive and rare. But even if we did believe that people with few posessions
are more authentic than us modern consumers we could hardly promote economic
decline.
Counsel for the unregenerate Scrooge would then turn his attention to the
``Christ'' part of Christmas; and here he would have my sympathies. He could
argue that our present midwinter festival is damaging to the nation's soul
because it is dishonest and dishonesty diminishes a people as much as it does
an individual.
The corresponding case for the ersatz tartanry of the tourist Scotland is well
known. Our local capitalist dairy farm makes wonderful luxury ice cream (that
is, it leaves all the fat in). It recently added a new brand called
``Highlander'' and in its promotional material discovered previously unremarked
geological features in our gently rolling rich farm land. The Bens and Glens
have moved east and south!
I can recall a marvellous Billy Connolly monologue in which he ruminated on the
significance of little ``Hairy Highlander'' dolls on sale in a Scottish tourist
resort. He rhetorically asked if we could imagine American blacks selling each
other golliwogs!
Intellectuals, especially of a nationalist persuasion, are prone to view the
tartanry of Bens and Glens as a perversion, a ``pathological discourse'' which
prevents us appreciating what modern Scotland is really like and acting in a
clear-minded and rational way to pursue our real interests. From that
perspective, tartanry is not a harmless bit of fun. It is cultural oppression.
I am not entirely persuaded by this criticism. Apart from anything else it
implies that there is a real authentic Scottish culture which should replace
the bastard creations of the Scottish Tourist Board and the American film
industry. My guess is that modern societies, even those of small nations, are
so fragmented that the search for a real national culture is a pointless grail
hunt. If lowland Scots find that wearing tartan makes them feel ``Scottish''
then I am not going to try to talk them out of it.
But the dishonesty with regard to Christianity is greater because a religion
carries more social and behavioural significance than a mistake about national
history and poor fashion sense. A religion supports a theory of how and why the
world is as it is and a theory of how we know about it.
Christianity has a theory of origins (Creator God, Six Days etc) and a theory
of truth, Holy Spirit and either Holy Writ (Protestant Version) or Holy
Catholic Church on Holy Writ (RC version). It sustains a body of moral values
and an ethical system. Most people no longer believe these things. Even
churchgoers have largely abandoned hell (which one would have thought was
essential to the enforcement of the ethics).
So why do we not have the courage of our convictions? Why do we mislead all
those poor clergymen who hope that our annual visit to church might just be
turned into something more enduring?
Which brings me back to where I started. However any of we non-believers
personally reconcile ourselves to the disingenuity of annually paying lip
service to a religion we no longer take seriously, surely we should have some
consideration for those who do believe it. Although the Christian references
are being scaled down (``Yuletide'' for ``Christmas''; Georgian coaching inn
prints for scenes of the Magi; Charles Dickens in place of St Mark; robins and
penguins in the place of Gabriel and the shepherds) we could go all the way,
strip out the last vestiges, and leave the symbols of the primary Christian
festival to the Christians.
The rest of us could simply enjoy a much-needed and much-appreciated midwinter
festival of rest and recreation without debasing a faith which still means
everything to the small band of those for whom it means anything at all.
n Steve Bruce is professor of sociology at Aberdeen University. He is the
author of many books including No Pope of Rome: Militant Protestantism in
Modern Scotland; The Rise and Fall of the New Christian Right; The Red Hand and
God Save Ulster: The Religion and Politics of Paisleyism. He is a regular
contributor to The Herald.
</TEXT>
