<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Enterprise agency chairman to stay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749781</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Donald MacKay, the chairman of Scottish Enterprise who agreed a
multi-million pound cut in the agency's funding last week, has been asked by
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth to stay on as chairman for another four
years.
It means that the partnership of Professor MacKay as chairman and Mr Crawford
Beveridge as chief executive will continue until at least 1998, confounding
rumours that the two highly active businessmen had difficulties in working
together.
The reappointment comes at a difficult time for Professor MacKay. He had to
offer the Scottish Office a 7!s% cut in funding, worth #33m, earlier this month
in order to save the enterprise network from even deeper cuts.
He said afterwards that Scottish Enterprise and its group of local enterprise
companies would still be able to deliver a high-quality service despite the
cut-backs. The individual enterprise companies will find out what their budgets
are going to be next month.
In theory Professor MacKay, who is also chairman of the Pieda consultancy,
works at Scottish Enterprise for only two days a week, but his hands-on style
means he spends considerably more time than that on Enterprise business.
It is this involvement which many observers felt would lead to a clash with Mr
Beveridge. However, it is believed that both men have worked out the areas each
should stick to, and now have a good working relationship.
Mr Forsyth said he valued the clarity of vision and positive leadership which
Professor MacKay had brought to the job.
``He has applied much time and energy to the task of developing the enterprise
network and seeking out opportunities, and most of all he has sought to focus
Scottish Enterprise's efforts on its central task of promoting the
effectiveness of Scottish business,'' he added.
</TEXT>
