<DOCNO>GH951223-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EU cash role for councillors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749782</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Office has given in to demands for local councillors to be
involved in deciding which projects are to benefit from Objective One funding.
In another change to the way the EU funds are to be distributed, 70% will be
allocated to the most disadvantaged areas, an increase from 50%.
Projects from all areas will also now be able to compete for the remaining 30%.
The moves follow complaints, especially from Highland regional councillors,
that the decision-making process was too involved.
The Scottish Office has agreed that informal partnership groups should be set
up to advise on projects to be given the green light.
Critic of the administration of Objective One, and the sharing out of funds,
Western Isles MP Calum Macdonald, said it was an improvement, but was still
baffled as to why all of the money is not being targeted at the poorest areas.
</TEXT>
