<HEADLINE>Chief executive to leave group with #400,000 as rivals Fyffes and Wibdeco pay #147.5m for fruit trade Geest sells off banana business</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749784</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEEST has agreed a price of #147.5m for the sale of the banana business with
which it has been associated for more than 40 years.
The buyer is a joint venture between Geest's rival Fyffes and Wibdeco, which is
owned by the governments and banana growers of the Windward Islands whose
economies are heavily dependent on the fruit.
Geest shares, which hit a low of 107p last month, jumped 39p to 192p as the
price was higher than expected. The chief executive, David Sugden is to leave
the group, with an expected pay-off topping #400,000.
Geest decided to throw in the towel after a volatile period during which its
banana supply was hit by disease and hurricanes. This year its margins were
badly hit by a sharp fall in prices in Europe as a result of oversupply from
Central and South America.
The company's banana business includes a ripening depot at Garrion Bridge, near
Wishaw, which supplies Scotland and employs about 30 people.
Geest warned in November that profits would be well below market estimates and
this caused analysts to slash their forecasts from #14m to #9m before
exceptional costs of #12m. Profits of #12.8m were earned in 1994.
The Geest name is not to disappear. The business will continue to be run
independently of Fyffes and Wibdeco, though it already has a close relationship
with the latter. Geest was instrumental in setting up the banana industry in
the Windward Islands, beginning in 1954.
The industry is now a leading employer and revenue earner in the islands, with
20,000 growers producing fruit. Wibdeco looks after the Windward Islands end
whilst Geest deals with shipping, ripening, marketing and distribution.
Geest will use the cash to reduce debt and concentrate resources on its fruit
and vegetable processing business which has better growth prospects.
The banana trade in the European Union is controlled, with relatively high cost
fruit from the Caribbean and the Pacific given a protected market and the
cheaper Latin American produce subject to quotas.
Prices fell sharply in November, touching 19p a pound retail because further
Latin American bananas were allowed in because of hurricane damage.
The lower prices stimulated consumption and bananas have overtaken apples to
become Britain's favourite fruit. It is also very popular in Germany which
would like unrestricted entry for Latin American fruit.
Geest has a Costa Rican business and Fyffes believes it can improve its
performance.
Dublin-based Fyffes believes it will benefit from the joint venture and
acquisition through the development of a closer relationship with Wibdeco; the
increase in the scale of its Latin American business; the opportunities
provided by the successful banana boat operations which transport general cargo
on return runs; and a rise in the return on its cash resources as part of them
are invested in Geest.
Shorn of bananas, Geest reckons it can achieve significant cost savings in its
fresh foods business, where it intends to increase new product development,
maintain technical innovation and consolidate its leading market positions.
Excluding recipe dishes, it has more than 20% of the prepared foods market in
areas like fresh dips, sauces and pasta.
Analysts were pleased with the bananas sale, pointing out that Geest will now
be focused on growing markets with considerably greater resources to expand
through acquisition. In view of its commanding market positions it could also
easily attract predatory interest.
</TEXT>
