<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A world of difference in law of the lands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Daniels</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749785</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Daniels talks to top Scottish lawyer Ross Harper about his hectic year
of globe-trotting as president of the International Bar Association
THIRTY countries, six months abroad, and enough horror stories and anecdotes to
last a lifetime. A year after donning the prestigious mantle of President of
the International Bar Association, one of Scotland's leading lawyers, Ross
Harper, believes Scots law, warts and all, can still be described as the best
in the world.
Yesterday Harper was back in London keen to relate some of the new initiatives
undertaken by the international Bar this year and some of the enormous problems
faced by lawyers operating in some of the 167 member countries.
The second Scot to be elected president in 50 years, Harper has this year had
the opportunity to examine first-hand legal systems as diverse as the Japanese,
with its astonishing 99% conviction and 95% confession rates, to the abuses of
the failing Nigerian legal structure. He has spent more than half the year
abroad, addressing lawyers' conferences and meeting senior government figures.
The experience has confirmed his faith in Scots law, reflected, he says, by the
high esteem with which the system, in spite of its flaws, is regarded abroad.
There is, he adds, also a lot of interest among Scottish lawyers in
international law and an enthusiasm for broadening horizons and experience.
The IBA's main role is to bring together the international law fraternity to
meet and discuss issues of common concern in areas as diverse as family law,
patent law and maritime law. The organisation also attempts to assist lawyers
struggling to protect the rule of law in countries where abuses are common. In
addition, there is a twinning scheme - the Scottish Law Society is twinned with
a similar organisation in Lithuania - allowing lawyers to exchange information
and ``shrink the world''.
Moves have also been made by the IBA to persuade the Foreign Office to withhold
aid from countries who abuse human rights.
According to Harper, one of the biggest achievements of his presidency has been
the foundation of a Human Rights Institute in the IBA's new London headquarters
just over a fortnight ago. The institute, funded by contributions from members,
will specialise in monitoring cases involving lawyers in the dock as well as
the trials of non-legal accused whose own lawyers have run into difficulties in
securing a fair trial.
Lawyers from any of the IBA's member countries who volunteer will, says Harper,
be trained in trial observing. They will then be sent to monitor a trial
providing, in effect, the legal eyes of the world. While playing quite a
specialist role, the institute will build on links which already exist between
the IBA and organisations like Amnesty International.
``We have already had one observer at a murder trial in Malaysia where normally
these cases last about half an hour. In that particular instance the trial
lasted three and half days, and the outcome was a lot more favourable than it
might have been.''
With this year designated African year, Harper has paid vists to Uganda,
Swaziland and South Africa and despatched an American lawyer to Ghana. In
general, the picture is of improving legal systems. The highlight came in
Johannesburg, a meeting with fellow lawyer South African President Nelson
Mandela. The most depressing trip was to Nigeria and the brief glimpse Harper
was allowed of Nigerian justice. ``It was a most fearful experience, travelling
past armed guards. The rule of law is being completely ignored.''
Japan's legal system came as one of the biggest eye-openers. Invited by the
Japan Federation of Bar Associations, Harper was given an account of the
substitute prison system where the accused can be held in custody for 23 days
without access to a lawyer, without an indictment being served and without bail
being granted.
Only through direct approaches to the Japanese Government can the basic rights
of a suspect be enshrined in law, a task which Harper says foreign Bar
association members are better placed to fight for than home lawyers.
Looking forward to his second and final year as president Harper hopes that a
number of Scots will volunteer to work for the institute in the role of trial
observers.
Next year has been designated Latin American year and for Harper will include a
trip to Argentina. ``Lawyers tend to be all-pervasive in Latin America, so we
will have access to the top. One of the problems in the past has been language,
but I think now it is generally recognised that English is the international
language of the law.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000088</DOCNO>
