<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council rejects site for new hospital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749786</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN appeal to the Scottish Secretary could follow a council's rejection
yesterday of plans for a new community hospital for East Ayrshire.
The controversial proposal to provide general daycare and residential
accommodation for the elderly and handicapped was knocked back after Cumnock
and Doon Valley councillors visited the site on Ayr Road.
The application by Ayrshire and Arran Community Health Care NHS Trust was
rejected five votes to four, mainly on the grounds of road and public safety.
The outcome has surprised trust officials as well as officers of the council's
planning department who had recommended approval subject to 25 conditions.
The proposal was tainted with controversy this year when plans were submitted
by the Health Care Trust for Cumnock and by South Ayrshire Hospitals Trust for
Ballochmyle near Mauchline.
Doctors and health professionals, including GPs, backed their local
applications and the debate, polarised between the two sites, was often
acrimonious.
Then the board decided unanimously that the Health Care Trust should get the
nod and plans for a greenfield site near the centre of Cumnock were submitted
to the district council.
Meanwhile it was disclosed that private finance would be used to build the
100-bed hospital although the trust stressed it would only be for NHS patients
and would be run by NHS doctors and nurses.
The applicants are now left with the options of applying once again, with these
conditions met or agreed, or appealing to the Secretary of State for Scotland.
They can also hope the full council will suspend standing orders and consider
the matter again, possibly overturning yesterday's decision.
It is understood that council leader David Sneller backed the application and
that he might favour another look at the whole question.
Councillor Anna Boyd, believed to be a supporter of the plan, left the meeting
before the vote and the planning chair, Councillor Robert Taylor, would have
cast his vote in favour should it have been tied 5-5.
The trust's vice chairman, Mr Scott McConnell, who attended yesterday's
meeting, said: ``The councillors made their decision against the advice of
their chief planning officers apparently on road safety matters.
``We are desperately disappointed that the councillors chose to reject the
application but we will continue to try to work with them and their officials
in an attempt to solve this problem.
``Unfortunately the council's preference for Ballochmyle as a site is
well-known, but this option has been rejected on various grounds by the health
board in favour of Cumnock which is at the centre of the 30,000 population
which the hospital will service.
``Failing a favourable result to negotiations after the New Year we will be
forced to submit an appeal to the Secretary of State for Scotland. We believe
the site is right and will be happy to meet any conditions attached to the
planning application.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How to sweep away hypocrisy which surrounds lottery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>George Birrell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749787</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the Greek island of Mykonos, a glittering haven for the world's hedonists, I
met Yannis Pasolikis. He is somewhat of a celebrity there; a big spender, bon
vivant, night-club habitue and he was invariably accompanied by the most
outstanding blonde available which is quite a feat in this shifting community
of beautiful people. He is also 68 years old. His fame, or more accurately, his
noteriety, is a result of him winning the national lottery.
This stroke of luck propelled him out of the grey depressing city of Larissa,
central Greece's equivalent of Rotherham, where he was an odd-job man with a
wife, family of three, and a lean-to shack which he called home.
Now the family have a splendid villa on the outskirts and a way of life of
which formerly they could never even have dreamt. They don't see Yannis as
much, however. After his win he suddenly found a job in ``shipping'' which
necessitated him purchasing a bachelor pad in Athens and travelling far and
wide returning home only for special occasions - Christmas, Easter, or one of
the numerous celebratory Saints' days.
Yannis, however, has a dark secret. He doesn't have a job but has shrewdly
invested his money in businesses which, remarkably, have excelled. This allows
him to live the life of an ageing, yet well-preserved, playboy. ``My family
need never find out and when I die they will be rich,'' he says simply and
without guilt. ``Life is for living,'' he smiles, as he slips his arm around
his companion's 22in waist.
Such a tale in Britain would guarantee at least six pages in the Sun. On
Mykonos it was an open secret and no-one cared. Winning the lottery is expected
to change your life, for better or for worse. No soul-searching. No anguish
about how many drachma goes to charity. No angry letters in the press from the
Peleponnese Women's Co-operative Theatre Workshop about lack of funding.
Contrast this with our lottery, fast becoming one of the most successful in the
world yet one of the most criticised. There is something deep in the British
psyche which shies against it but at the same time participates in the general
mania. It has always been thus. Even in 1808 a select committee of MPs had
concluded that, as a result of lotteries, ``Idleness, dissipation, and poverty
are increased, domestic comfort is destroyed and madness often created.''
George Orwell was to return to this theme in his book Nineteen Eighty-Four. He
wrote: ``The lottery with its weekly pay-out or enormous prizes, was the one
public event to which the proles paid serious attention. It was probable that
there were some millions of proles for whom the lottery was the principal, if
not the only reason for remaining alive. It was their delight, their folly,
their anodyne, their intellectual stimulant. Where the lottery was concerned,
even people who could barely read and write seemed capable of intricate
calculations and staggering feats of memory. There was a whole tribe of men who
made a living simply by selling systems, forecasts, and lucky amulets.''
Some would argue that this has come to pass although the usual grounds for
complaint are that less is spent on bread than circuses and that there is an
unfairness in gathering money from the poor to spend on amusements for the
wealthy.
These objections are specious. The lottery cash is for the ``extras'' of life,
the fundamentals are and must continue to be provided by the Government through
our taxes. As for the poor paying out a higher proportion of their income every
time they purchase a lottery ticket, this applies whether they buy a pint of
milk or a loaf of bread.
No matter to which cause the cash is allocated the wealthier groups gain most.
Research shows that those in the socio-economic groups A, B, and C1 (those in
white-collar jobs) are more likely to play sports or pay to watch them than the
groups C2, D, and E (blue-collar workers and pensioners). When it comes to
pastimes such as visiting beauty spots or museums, the middle classes come out
tops again, even more so with theatre, opera, classical music concerts, or art
galleries.
The lottery, however, could be made fairer. The Government should have made a
start by sacking Peter Davis, the lottery regulator. The Heritage Secretary
Virginia Bottomley forfeited an opportunity this week to do just that - and not
for Mr Davis's silly decision to accept hospitality from an American lottery
operator. That was just bogus indignation from the Labour Party. Mr Davis
should have gone because of the abysmal way the lottery has been regulated.
For Camelot to be making #50m a year after tax - an annual profit they can
expect until their licence runs out in six years - for a total investment of
just over #45m is unacceptable. If it was the result of efficiency it would be
justified. It is not. It is the result of monopoly which has seen Camelot keep
the scratch-card game in-house, which is hardly surprising since it was they
who were given the right to scrutinise bids and, lo and behold, they chose
themselves.
The regulations on this and other aspects needed to be framed to encourage
competition. Mr Davis had failed to do so.
However, the Government could by allowing reputable companies the right to run
big charitable lotteries in opposition to the National Lottery. This would give
everyone a greater choice about where to put their money. We would, at the same
time, be able to sweep away so much of the hypocrisy which surrounds the
lottery. A multiplicity of consumer-driven lotteries would mean punters could
buy a ticket for the one they considered funded the worthiest cause or they
could play the one with the biggest jackpot. Want to bet on charity or the life
of Yannis Pasolikis?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Innovator steers a profitable course</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>trailblazers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749788</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS week's Trailblazer is the long-established Simpson Lawrence. For more than
80 years, since it set up in the basement of a tobacco merchant's house in
Glasgow's Merchant City as a manufacturer of wooden packing cases, the company
has held firm.
Now, as the production arm of one of Europe's three largest wholesale yacht
chandlers, Hillington-based Simpson Lawrence Engineering is blazing a trail
across the oceans as an exporter of high-quality yachting equipment to more
than 60 countries.
No-one produces the same range. It includes the whole anchoring package, says
commercial director Chris Lang - horizontal and vertical windlasses, capstans,
anchors - and yacht toilets. And its long history of listening to the market
and innovating has resulted in a number of awards for its products and steady
growth in its international reputation.
Simpson Lawrence's current success is the result of decades of far-sighted
management insistence on research and development. Since the founding owner's
interest in the sea first led to its diversification from packing cases to
yacht equipment, it has continued to chart new waters.
Fifty years ago it supplied the legendary C-Q-R anchors which held the Mulberry
Harbour in place on D-Day. Today it manufactures the only genuine drop forged
C-Q-R plough - the Rolls-Royce of anchors, and the saviour of many a yacht
caught in the fury of a Caribbean hurricane.
In 1980, in response to US demand for more adaptable windlasses, it was the
first to design one whose gypsy could cope with both chain and rope, and since
then there have been constant improvements to ensure better handling of ropes
of different sorts under various conditions.
In 1990 Simpson Lawrence saw a shift was taking place: power yachts were taking
an ever larger share of the market. This meant there was increasing demand for
remote control, automation and press-button equipment.
One-piece anchors, which were easier for power windlasses to handle and neater
to stow, were what premier powerboat builders wanted, so it designed and
launched another new product - the Delta. This has received more acclaim from
the world yaching press than any other anchor in recent times.
More recently still, it has developed a power windlass with a completely new
widget component. This eliminates the need for an electrically operated brake
and allows powerful and fast chain drop and retrieval, all remote from the
foredeck and at the touch of a button. It has been so successful - 3000 Horizon
500s have been sold this year - that a whole new range of power windlasses are
to be launched at the London Boat Show.
Still more important for Simpson Lawrence is the Miami Boat Show in February.
More than 90% of the company's total output is exported, and a large proportion
goes to the US, either directly or installed on British-built boats.
In all its products the firm strives for excellence. And a 50% growth in
turnover over the last two years is solid vindication that it is steering the
right course.
The award and entry
The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young, business and
financial advisers, to recognise organisations which demonstrate innovation and
ingenuity in their operations and procedures. Forms can be obtained by sending
in the coupon below.
Entries should be based on one or a combination of:
innovation/ingenuity
business performance
product/service quality
management calibre
marketing flair
contribution to the local/Scottish economy
Rewards
The monthly winner will be presented with an award certificate and will be
featured in an article. The overall TrailBlazer of the Year will send a company
specialist on an agreed specialist management training course at the renowned
Harvard Business School.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
