<DOCNO>GH951223-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jury discharged in dog row death trial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749789</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE jury in the trial of a man accused of a neighbour's murder in a row over a
barking dog was discharged yesterday after failing to reach a verdict.
The panel of six men and six women had spent over six hours discussing the case
of 32-year-old Nicholas Farnell, of Waterlooville, Hampshire.
Mr Farnell, who now faces a retrial at Winchester Crown Court at the earliest
possible date, denies murdering 56-year-old Willy Pottage, but admits
manslaughter.
After the jurors, who retired on Thursday to consider their verdict, sent in a
note Mr Justice Turner said: ``I understand you to be saying that you have
reached the stage where you are quite simply unable to reach a decision where
at least 10 of you agree upon a verdict.''
The prosecution had alleged that Mr Farnell struck Mr Pottage with a crowbar
after losing his temper during the argument, which happened last May. Mr
Pottage suffered a fractured skull as he fell to the ground, and died four days
later.
It was not suggested Mr Farnell had intended to kill Mr Pottage but he had
intended to cause him serious harm, the prosecution contended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Konrad Zuse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM HENEGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749790</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Konrad Zuse, computer pioneer; born June 22, 1910, died December 18, 1995
KONRAD Zuse, the German engineer who built one of the world's first computers
and lost it in the wartime Allied bombing of Berlin, has died of heart failure
aged 85 at his home near Fulda.
Experts argue over who invented the electronic brain that revolutionised life
in the late twentieth century but Zuse's ``Z3'' model built in 1941 is
considered the first automatic and programmable computing machine. Fleeing
Berlin to protect his ``Z4'' model from the bombing, he refused Nazi orders to
hide the computer at the mountain caves of Mittelbau Dora when he found that
slave labourers were building the V1 and V2 rockets there.
The machine, eventually hidden in southern Germany, was later set up in Zurich.
Zuse founded his own computer-building firm after the war which was bought by
Siemens AG in 1966. Despite his pioneering work, he always had to struggle for
recognition. After a 26-year legal battle, a German court ruled in 1967 that a
later version of the ``Z3'' was ``not an invention worthy of a patent''.
``He was a brilliant inventor and tinkerer,'' Raul Rojas, a computer scientist
and historian, told Reuter. ``In contrast to the others, he was all alone.''
Among other pioneer computers were the Mark I built by Harvard University
professor Howard Aiken in 1944 and the ENIAC machine built at the University of
Pennsylvania in 1945. Aiken had major funding and staff help from International
Business Machines (IBM) while ENIAC was developed by the US military, said
Rojas, a Mexican-born professor of computer science at Halle University in
eastern Germany. But, added Rojas, only a mixture of all these limited models
led to the first real computers as we know them now.
Zuse was only 28 when he built his first model, the ``Z1'', covering four sq
metres (43sq ft) in his parents' living room. He built it ``out of laziness''
because he hated adding up the long columns of figures he calculated as an
aircraft designer. The machine was programmed by punched tape, stored only 64
characters, and took up to two seconds to do simple addition. His first three
computers were demolished in bombing raids but Zuse rebuilt the ``Z1'' from
memory more than 40 years later.
During the war, Zuse tried to get support from the Nazi government for a
two-year project to develop a large new computer to help improve anti-aircraft
defences. ``And just how long do you think it will take us to win the war?'' he
was asked when the project was rejected.
Only weeks before the Third Reich fell, Zuse moved his only remaining computer,
the ``Z4'', to Goettingen in central Germany to protect it from advancing
Soviet troops. Hermann Goering's Aviation Ministry ordered him to hide it in
nearby Mittelbau Dora, an underground concentration camp.
``It was there we first learned of the terrible conditions under which the V1
and V2 were being built,'' he wrote in his memoirs. ``We refused to leave the
machine there and, with the help of Werner von Braun's staff, we managed to get
hold of a truck to transport it elsewhere.''
After selling his company to Siemens, Zuse, who called himself a ``failed
capitalist'', turned to theoretical computer research and was active until his
death. ``He still had a lot in his head that he hadn't yet written down,'' said
Rojas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A Blair government would not ditch Conservative legislation Labour pledge on Tory policies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749791</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair said yesterday that he had no intention of overturning
all the changes brought in under 16 years of Tory rule.
He said there would be no revolution the moment a Labour government took
office, and he instead offered a process of gradual change.
``Of course it is the case that the world is not going to be revolutionised the
moment Labour comes to power. That is only sensible,'' he said in an interview
he recorded with BBC Radio 4's Today programme before leaving for Australia.
``The country doesn't want a revolution - it doesn't want the barricades up at
the end of the street after Labour comes to power. They want a fresh start and
a new direction.''
On the economy he offered caution, ruling out ``quick fix'' solutions aimed at
raising short-term growth at the expense of stoking inflation.
``The progress that we will make is not going to be progress that is some great
dash for growth or attempting to overthrow everything that the last 16 years
have done,'' he said.
``It is attempting to set a decent direction for this country based on what I
call modern, one nation politics - radical but recognising that it is only if
this country works together and keeps together united as a nation that we will
make progress.
``The policies that we are putting forward - for example in the field of
technology and industry - are policies that will transform people's lives over
time and over time is not a bad thing to have.''
Mr Blair's essentially cautious message, while unlikely to please those on the
left of the party, marks a further step in his campaign to woo the middle
classes and reassure them they have nothing to fear from a Labour government.
He said Labour would be pressing hard for an early General Election, following
the Government's latest Commons defeat on Europe - although he expected
Ministers would resist pressure to go to the polls for as long as possible.
``If we can possibly bring about an early change of government then we will do
so, because it is in the interests of the country,'' he said.
He was scathing about the problems that the Government now faced with a tiny
majority and - with two by-elections looming - the prospect of a further cut.
``Although it is difficult to see them wanting an early election, I really
don't know how the country can put up with another 18 months of this,'' he said.
``In the House of Commons business has virtually ground to a halt. I don't know
what is happening in government any more.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
