<DOCNO>GH951223-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lambs killed by thieves</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749792</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIEVES have butchered three young lambs in a callous bid to get rich for
Christmas.
Police said that their remains were found in a field below Stirling Castle. The
animals' throats had been cut, probably with a kitchen knife.
SSPCA inspector Gordon Stanforth said: ``They would have died in agony and
terror. ``They'd have been chased round the field and cut by people not knowing
what they were doing.''
The remains were found by their owner, Jack Bain of Queenshaugh Farm, Stirling.
A spokesman for Stirling District Council's environment health department
warned the meat could be offered around pubs and clubs as a cheap Christmas
treat.
He added: ``This meat has not been properly slaughtered or butchered. It may
well be contaminated and poses a health hazard. Anyone being offered cheap cuts
should contact their local police.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Triumphant in testing times</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749793</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the critical points in the Lanark Blue cheese saga was the Sheriff's
telling comparison, in his 32-page judgment, of rival tests for listeria
monocytogenes on samples of the cheese by the Scottish Agricultural College and
the Analytical Services Centre.
The college had carried out its tests for Clydesdale District Council, the
results prompting the council's officers to serve notices on Humphrey
Errington, the cheesemaker, condemning the batches as unfit for human
consumption.
Analytical Services Centre is the laboratory testing arm of D&amp;M Clark, a group
of companies headquartered in the Motherwell Food Park specialising in a wide
range of food-related consultancy services. ASC has carried out testing work
for Errington since he started making Lanark Blue, and its sister cow's milk
cheese, Dunsyre Blue.
In his judgment, Sheriff Douglas Allan compared tests for listeria done by the
college last February with those done by ASC on the same sample cheeses in May.
The ASC results showed that no listeria was found in two samples, while in the
rest the count in each case was below 100 cfu (colony forming units) per
gramme. The college results ranged from 45,000 to 5,100,000 cfu/g.
The Sheriff decided the difference could not be explained by the fact the
samples had been frozen in the interim. In his final judgment, rejecting the
council's application, he went on: ``No reason for the disparity in these
results emerged from the evidence and, since the evidence did satisfy me that
the Analytical Services Centre results could be relied upon, the doubt remained
as to the reliability of the SAC results.''
Later he described the ASC results as ``reliable and accurate''. The outcome
was a vindication for the Motherwell lab, which, at one stage, had six staff
attending the inquiry. Three took the stand to give evidence. One of them was
Maureen Howard, who as supervisor in the microbiology lab, had been directly
involved in testing Lanark Blue samples for years.
``Listeria is always going to be there in that kind of cheese,'' she says now.
``They were saying the count was too high. We had found listeria, but at low
levels. We had also sent samples to the Pasteur Institute in France and they
got the same results we did.''
ASC has another reason for having confidence in its findings. Since December
1993 it has been NAMAS accredited for both microbiology and chemical analysis,
the only lab in Scotland to be quality controlled in this way. Under the NAMAS
system unidentified samples arrive at regular intervals to be tested, as part
of an ongoing independent audit.
The last time I met the man who, with his wife, founded D&amp;M Clark was five
years ago, in the middle of the great salmonella scare about eggs. David Clark
told me then that a little bit of food poisoning could do you good by
stimulating the development of microflora in the gut. But a lot more has
happened to the business in the past five years than a switch of focus from
eggs to cheese.
The creation of the separate ASC identity was a deliberate move to reduce the
focus on David Clark himself. ``With my name above the door, everyone wanted to
talk to me. But, with the role I'm now trying to play as chairman and MD, I
can't be involved in every day-to-day activity,'' he argues.
Although laboratory food testing remains at the core of the group's work, with
up to 600 samples a week being tested compared with just 200 a year ago, it has
steadily diversified into other areas. For example, since the mid eighties, D&amp;M
Clark has been involved in every commercial mineral water development in
Scotland.
Clark and fellow director Denise Johnstone play a part from the start, even
masterminding the sinking of boreholes to tap the right reservoirs. ``We got
involved initially in the water analysis,'' says Clark. ``But we soon realised
that, if the bores were drilled in the right way, our clients would get better
quality.''
From working with Highland Spring and the ill-fated Lovat Water venture, Clark
and Johnstone have taken their expertise to manufacturing companies which
require large quantities of clean water.
Some of the semiconductor fabricators, such as Motorola and National
Semiconductor, as well as general industrial concerns like Anaplast, have used
D&amp;M Clark to draw their own water from the ground. The group is also involved
with water treatment for hotels and swimming pools.
Another natural diversification was into managing the funding and construction
of new food processing plants. Clark is involved with two cooked meat plants,
one in Dumfries and the other in Glasgow.
``We do everything from the business plan and grant applications, to putting
the funding package together, instructing the architect, overseeing the
construction and training the staff. It's a full turnkey operation, and we
don't need to do an awful lot of them in a year to feel the effect,'' he adds.
The latest diversification is a joint venture - Alimek Clark AEIE - in Spain,
which opened a few weeks back. It covers the same spectrum of activity and
involves D&amp;M Clark and two women based in Spain, one of whom used to work at
the Motherwell lab.
``At the moment it's all go with faxes and e-mail to Spain virtually every
day,'' Clark says. ``But, in five years, the deal is we'll be out of it and it
will be self-supporting.''
Now into his late forties, with two sons - one in medicine, one in engineering
- who show no inclination to join the business, David Clark has set himself the
task of bringing good people on and building the business in ways which will
allow him, one day, to withdraw from it, confident that it will run on without
him.
He recruited Alastair Fleming, ex-Rowats and Greenmeadows, to head up the lab
operation and, in July, Fleming became a director. Another step in that
consolidation which will ensure a 20-year-old business playing a vital role in
the Scottish food sector has plenty more years ahead of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>J.P. Loach</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749794</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACTORS and actresses don't have much of an image in Britain. Unlike Americans,
for whom fame is the prime justification, we mistrust people who think of eight
hours strutting in front of a camera as a hard day's work. I was given a chance
to test this when I got an audition for Ken Loach's film which is being shot in
Glasgow.
The production team invited me to their office which was in one of the old
wards in Knightswood Hospital. Ken (as I call him) met me there and I was shown
into one of the old doctors' rooms where I went through an acting exercise.
This involved a real actress called Anne Marie who played the part of a rather
upset mother who was giving a doctor (me) a hard time over the treatment her
son had been given.
If I looked convincingly perturbed and apologetic, this was less to do with
acting than it was to do with the fact that she was so convincing that I felt
perturbed and apologetic. Her distress was so real that even Ken Clarke would
have felt sorry for her.
At 7am last Thursday I was back in Knightswood getting kitted out for my debut.
The wardrobe girls triumphed in finding a white coat to fit me, which is what
hospital laundries fail to do, and by the time I had my pockets stuffed full of
scrap paper, I was Frank Boyle, the young intensive care doctor.
Having a whole day's filming, I thought Frank must be pretty important to the
plot. Should he be moody, or jovial? Kind or brusque? I wondered what qualities
I could bring to the role, then I realised I hadn't seen a script. Mildly
non-plussed, I got into the car to be driven to the set.
The driver was effusive in his praise for Ken. Apparently he ``doesn't work
like other directors,'' in that he likes the actors' reactions to be unforced
and natural (this avoids pratts like me trying to ``be'' the part.) The
production assistant spent 10 minutes telling me to ``unblock the creative
channels and be the natural self'' before I realised he was taking the rise. No
luvvies here.
The car stopped at the Southern General's car park. We weren't rushing to get
to work, we were rushing to get breakfast from the catering van. What a skate
this filming is, I was thinking: not a stroke of work done, and here I was
standing around tucking into hot coffee and a roll and bacon liberally dowsed
in tomato sauce.
When I got to the set, Ken Loach gave me a welcoming but vaguely quizzical
look, I thought he was amazed at how right I looked.
My scene was quite simple, culminating in a few lines of dialogue with the main
character played by Bobby Carlyle. It looked so simple, that I thought we'd get
the lot done by morning tea break and perhaps get home by lunchtime. Tea break?
At 2.30 we were still filming, trying to get the last bit just right.
Admittedly it was partly my fault. You might think that writing your name on a
sheet of paper, putting the pen in your pocket, picking up a folder, saying 10
words and walking off is simple. It should be. But throw in a 20-man film crew
and a famous actor and it feels like brain surgery by numbers.
Ten times on the trot I had to endure the same routine: clapperboard, camera,
lights, action. ``OK JP, walk and talk!'' Three times I tripped over the table
leg, twice I stuttered during my lines, and four times I picked up the paper in
the wrong way.
Everyone was really nice; not once did anyone demand my immediate sacking. The
professional actors, meanwhile, managed to produce carbon copies of their
actions time after time. The worst actor in the place (apart from myself) was
probably Ken Loach himself, who had to say ``Great JP, it's coming along fine''
about 10 minutes before he sounded serious.
After I'd eventually got it right, everyone was very nice. On my way out, Ken
thanked me, as did the writer, Paul Laverty (I think they were just relieved
that they could get rid of me). As my day was finishing, the crew was preparing
for at least another six hours filming. That night I slept soundly, dreaming of
the Bafta's ``and the award of Best Cameo Appearance As a Young Doctor goes to
. . .''
No-one's sure what the film will actually be called, but the working title is
Carla's Song. If you get the chance, go to see it, and look out for Frank
Boyle; he's the doctor with no acting ability, and a large tomato sauce stain
down the front of his white coat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
