<DOCNO>GH951223-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leeson faces appeal deadline</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749795</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER Barings trader Nick Leeson has until next Saturday to decide whether to
appeal against his six-year jail sentence in Singapore, his lawyers said
yesterday.
If he gambles on an appeal he is likely to be in court by the end of next
month, but he risks having his sentence increased to the maximum seven years,
according to legal sources in Singapore.
His lawyer, Mr John Koh, has now received the judge's written explanation of
the sentence.
``He's going to take the Christmas holidays to review the document and then see
Nick Leeson about it and decide whether to proceed with the appeal,'' said Mr
Koh's legal assistant, Ms Frances Silverayan.
Leeson, whose unauthorised dealings caused the #860m crash of Britain's oldest
merchant bank, was jailed after pleading guilty to two charges of cheating.
He lodged notice of appeal against the six-year sentence on one of the charges,
but did not appeal against the concurrent six-month sentence on the other
charge.
He received the written judgment on Wednesday. A 10-day period is allowed to
take an appeal to the High Court under Singapore law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Good news</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749796</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOLK with an eye to a Christmas present bargains would do well to visit their
local newsagent this month where the shelves are filled to overflowing with
festive editions of their favourite magazines, most of them carrying a special
free gift which the canny shopper could wrap up and pass on to an unsuspecting
friend.
Healthy Eating for instance, comes with a useful recipe book worth #2.50. Dogs
Today offers a sample pack of light menu dog food while Your Cat has, not only
a packet of ``delightfully crunchy'' catfood but free cat calendar as well.
Bridal Guide comes with a handy wedding budget planner, Wedding and Home offers
a tiny bottle of perfume, People's Friend has a cassette of Christmas carols by
Paisley Abbey Choir and the home decorating magazine, Inspirations, carries a
miniature wall basket for readers to decorate.
Other free offers from publications like Crafts Monthly, Good Woodworking and
Sega Pro, include embroidery sets, stencil and brush kits (``valued at
#5.99!''), a guide to the world's worst B movies, a book of training secrets
for runners, a 200-page tool catalogue, packs of five Christmas cards featuring
your favourite football players, salami sticks and a mini pack of cornflakes.
The teen magazines carry free novels and pairs of tights along with the usual
badges and posters while kids' comics are giving away everything from stick on
earings and felt-tipped pens to plastic toys and Highland toffee.
Competition among the increasing range of computer magazines is fierce at any
time of year. No matter the month, they all carry one or more demo discs taped
to their covers to attract readers. So it's no surprise to find that most of
the Christmas issues are offering at least two of these freebies, with the
current crop including Where Does it Hurt?, a taster for a new computer
programme which lets you check the state of your health.
Just the thing for a hypochondriac friend or relative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>World markets close on a high note</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749797</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARE markets around the world were closing on a high note yesterday in the run
up to Christmas and the New Year.
At home, the FTSE 100 Share Index led by futures though in thin trading
finished up 25 points at 3658.3, just 22 points short of its high for the year
at the beginning of the month.
There have been hiccups along the way, but it has still risen 20% since the
start of the year, fuelled in part by Wall Street, which is almost always a an
important influence, but also by corporate activity and, in particular, bids
and bid speculation in several leading sectors including banks and utilities.
Wall Street has had an up and down experience over the past few days with the
Dow Jones Index sliding 51 points on Wednesday only to bounce back with a 37
point rise the next day. Yesterday Wall Street was ahead in early trading.
At present the main influencing factor in the US is the impasse over the
Federal Budget, which has meant a delay in publication of US economic data.
However, observers believe this is likely to be resolved soon. If so, it should
be bullish for share prices.
In Tokyo, foreign investors' purchases of blue chip stocks helped share prices
reach their highest level of the year, though it was still the worst performing
major equity market over the year.
In economic terms, Japan is now becoming more optimistic after going through,
unusually for that country, a troubled period. Certainly the outlook for share
prices next year is thought to be more enouraging.
``With no negative incentives in sight, we can hope for a brighter end of the
year than we have seen in a long time,'' was the view of one trader.
Brokers generally expect the Nikkei Index to maintain its current firm tone for
the rest of the year with the upward trend likely to extend into the New Year.
The outlook for shares in the UK must continue to be influenced to some extent
what happens in the US but the Federal Reserve recently sliced a !f-point off
interest rates to provide some stimulus to the economy, as did the UK, and the
trend in rate is downward.
This is a definite plus. And although the British economy has slowed, both the
Treasury and many leading economic gurus expect this to be temporary as
consumer spending increases. Also in the UK the high level of market liquidity
and corporate activity cannot be underestimated.
Brokers Henry Cook Lumsden suggests that it is no concidence that the run,
which has seen the FTSE rise more than 400 points in a little over six months,
began when institutional investors received the #6000m of cash from Glaxo's
takeover of Wellcome.
Assuming that all the current bids on the table succeed the total value of
take-overs in 1995 will be approximately #50bn according to Lumsden, a return
to the heady levels of 1989, which saw the peak in merger activity.
Topping the bill at present is Granada's bitterly contested #3300m bid for
Forte which took the market by surprise. And it is far too early days to judge
what the outcome for this will be.
Of course, if the equity market as a whole is to continue to perform, there has
to be a revival in the domestic economy. In the short-term, there are likely to
be further individual company profit warnings and downgradings by analysts.
The Chancellor has pencilled in 3% growth for next year, but if the economy
does not pick up as expected, then some further stimulus in the form of another
!f-point of interest rates - which many analysts feel is in prospect anyway -
would seem inevitable, particularly as inflation is not thought to pose a
threat at this time.
The importance of corporate activity is also stressed by Scottish Amicable.
Most significantly, cash consideration as opposed to paper remains high.
Against this, though, demand for funds from new issues and rights has remained
relatively subdued.
Strong corporate balance sheets and historically low interest rates have
encouraged cash bids and this is likely to continue to provide support for
equities at the beginning of next year.
However, as the year proceeds, attention will be focused on the broader economy
and this should impact on equity markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Museum tours at flick of a switch</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749798</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE finest in Scotland's art will be on display in tourist information centres
if discussions between the Scottish Tourist Board and the Scottish Museums
Council on a computer database project are successful.
The click of a mouse button will conjure up images of treasures housed in
museums, galleries, and heritage sites scattered all over the country.
The ultimate aim is a database that consists of 100,000 digitised images of
important Scottish collections. This will be accompanied by text explaining the
historical background of the artefacts.
An official of the Scottish Museums Council confirmed that the STB was very
interested in the project - which is initially to be set up in schools through
cable and CD-ROM networks
The information technology project is part of Scran 2000, the Scottish Cultural
Resources Access Network that has been set up by the Scottish Museums Council
along with the National Museums of Scotland and the Royal Commission on Ancient
and Historic Monuments of Scotland.
The Millennium Commission awarded #7.4m to Scran 2000 in October of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>OIS rejects #8.25m takeover bid as `wholly unacceptable'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749799</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN-based OIS announced yesterday its rejection of drilling company Abbot
Group's #8.25m takeover bid.
OIS, which provides technical inspection services for the oil, petro-chemical
and power generation industries, said in a statement from its board members
that Abbot's offer was unacceptable.
``The board of OIS, which is being advised by Beeson Gregory, believes that the
offer does not reflect the potential of OIS and does not represent full value
for OIS shareholders,'' the statement said.
No-one from either OIS or Beeson Gregory was available to explain why they
regard the bid as a ``wholly inadequate offer''.
Abbot had approached OIS with an offer six weeks ago. After receiving no reply,
Abbot decided to go ahead with its bid launch anyway.
The drilling company is offering one of its own shares for every OIS share,
which values OIS at 27.5p per share. There is also a cash alternative of 24.5p.
Abbot chairman Alasdair Locke said on Thursday that disappointing profit and
dividend performances delivered by OIS since its floatation on the Stock
Exchange three years ago were unlikely to improve under the company's present
management.
The inspection services company was floated at 50p but has been below 25p for
the last three months.
The announcement of Abbot's bid, which came just before market closing
Thursday, pushed OIS shares up 7p to 25p while Abbot lost 3p to 52p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opera loses out on lottery funding</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749800</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HERITAGE Secretary Virginia Bottomley has brought the wrath of Wales down upon
herself after bringing down the curtain on plans for a new Welsh Opera House.
Hopes for the #86m showpiece in Cardiff's docklands were dashed after the
Millennium Commission refused to fund it.
The 1800-seat opera house was to be the ``jewel in the crown'' of Cardiff Bay's
#3000m programme to regenerate the economy of the Welsh capital and South
Wales.Supporters were confident of a #40m grant.
Lord Crickhowell, opera house trust chairman and a former Welsh Secretary,
described the rejection as ``a tragedy for Wales''. He was dismayed that the
Millennium Commission was not even prepared to risk #2.75m to take the project
on to the next stage.
He said: ``If it had been in London it would have been built.''
The opera house, planned to open on March 1, St David's Day in the year 2000,
was to have been the new home for the Welsh National Opera whose present base
in Cardiff will be demolished because of city redevelopment work.
Welsh opera stars Dame Gwyneth Jones and Dennis O'Neill were left
``dumbfounded'' by the decision.
The commission turned down the bid on the grounds that the opera house was too
big and did not offer value for money.
Mrs Bottomley, the chairman of the commission, said: ``We share the
disappointment because it was an exciting project with an impressive site. But
the business and financial uncertainties were such that the commission did not
feel, in the light of the professional advice we received, that we were able to
take it forward.''
The Shadow Heritage Secretary, Welsh Labour MP Ann Clwyd, said the decision was
``inexplicable'', adding: ``The Millennium Fund can find #55m for the Royal
Opera House, Covent Garden, and yet a vital scheme for Cardiff is rejected.''
Iraqi-born architect Zaha Hadid, based in London, whose controversial Crystal
Necklace design won an international competition for the Cardiff project, said:
``It's incredibly disappointing and very sad.''
Welsh hopes for lottery cash had to switch from song to the other passion,
rugby. The Welsh Rugby Union's bid for nearly #50m to help rebuild Cardiff Arms
Park will be considered by the commission in February.
</TEXT>
