<HEADLINE>Paper looks at further sheep scab measures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749801</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE possible new measures for helping farmers to control sheep scab are
outlined in a discussion document issued by the Earl of Lindsay, Scottish
Office Agriculture Minister, writes Robert Ross.
Until 1992 there were regulations on compulsory dipping and since their
withdrawal scab has re-emerged as a serious problem for sheep farmers. There
are now health concerns over the use of organo-phosphorous dips and many
farmers have gone over to using injections.
The spread of scab has been a source of concern to vets, farmers and
auctioneers. It also affects the value of pelts damaged by the scab.
One proposal from the Scottish Office is that local authorities should be given
powers to require common grazings or open, unfenced land to be cleared of sheep
for a minimum period where there is evidence of scab.
Such powers would generally be used where the grazier's association was unable
to resolve the problem by a consensus approach. When sheep were allowed back on
to the land only stock which had been treated against scab would be permitted.
It is also envisaged that it would become an offence to offer sheep with
detectable scab for sale, other than for direct slaughter. This would go
further than present provisions and would also apply to sales of sheep made
away from markets - the main route now believed to be adopted by the minority
of farmers and dealers who still continue to sell scab-infested sheep.
It would also become an offence not to treat sheep with detectable scab within
a reasonable time or after service of a notice by a local authority.
Lord Lindsay said: ``The sheep industry is very important to Scotland and I
hope that many people will take the opportunity of giving us their views on
these proposals.''
Although all secondary legislation detailing control measures for sheep scab
were revoked in 1992, it remains a ``disease'' under the Animal Health Act of
1981 and is technically notifiable to a police constable. The Government plans
to withdraw that provision next year but has promised consultation before any
action is taken.
</TEXT>
