<HEADLINE>MP accuses hospital trust of partisan behaviour after `strong lobbying' letter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749802</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR MP is to lodge an official complaint with the Scottish Health
Minister, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton, and the chief executive of the NHS in
Scotland over what he claims is behaviour that has broken the rules of
political neutrality.
Mr Brian Donohoe, MP for Cunninghame South, said a press release issued on
behalf of South Ayrshire Hospitals NHS Trust, detailing comments by Mr Phil
Gallie, MP for Ayr, amounted to ``totally unacceptable behaviour''.
In the three-page release trust chairman Douglas Brown welcomed increased NHS
funding for Ayrshire and Arran Health Board for 1996/97, attributing it to
``strong lobbying by the trust, the health board, and local MP Mr Gallie''.
Mr Gallie had said: ``Over recent years, the Government's aim has been to make
sure that everyone benefits in equal proportion from the ever-increasing amount
of cash injected into the NHS. I am delighted this week's news indicates the
success of the Government's policy and its determination to strengthen the NHS
whenever possible.''
Mr Donohoe said yesterday: ``It is incredible that we have an NHS trust using
quotes from a Tory MP defending a highly marginal seat in a press release
praising the Scottish Office for giving more money to the local health board.''
Mr Donald McNeill, chief executive of South Ayrshire Hospitals NHS Trust,
responding to the criticisms, defended the right to make the local community
aware of the Government's plans for public expenditure in the NHS in Ayrshire.
He said: ``It is entirely correct and in the public interests for this
information to be made available. The national picture was outlined in
Edinburgh last week, and it is important that the wider Ayrshire community
understands its implications for their local services.''
Meanwhile, Labour yesterday highlighted the ``relentless'' cuts in hospital
beds which it said were causing patients to suffer.
More than one in six NHS acute beds had been cut since 1990, said Labour, and
7664 beds were removed in England last year alone.
In that time the number of beds in private hospitals had grown over the past 15
years by 66%.
</TEXT>
