<HEADLINE>A party to forget -- if only they'd let you</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Linklater</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749803</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT is the office party all about?
SEX (a): Photocopiers, staplers, Tippex, over the desk, the much-missed library
cuttings table.
SINCE new technology arrived, nobody gets to have the office party in the
actual office. Which is a great pity and a terrible waste of seclusion behind
the filing cabinets, but never mind. Our library cuttings table was a great
favourite. Underneath was like a four-poster. On top was like a wondrous divan.
It didn't just feature in our office party fantasies, but in the movie Heavenly
Pursuits, filmed in this office, when Helen Mirren and Tom Contie tried it out.
That's what you call pedigree.
But these days you can't have Davie the new sub pouring his can of lager down
the Power Mac. Well, you could all too easily, which is the point. Inland
Revenue allows companies #50 a head for the employees' Christmas bash, but the
insurance company is less benevolent. Hence the annual restaurant search for a
booking, and the difficult task of getting one that doesn't remember the fracas
of three years ago.
SEX (b): The Ride Home.
THE depressing truth has been revealed recently that 20% of males hope to have
casual sex at the office party, and only 1% of females. So most of this wishful
thinking is statistically improbable. Worse. Your office section doesn't even
employ 100 women, so at best there's only one female at your party who
entertains even a modicum of interest. And it isn't going to be for you, is it?
It's going to be for one of the 80% who isn't interested in her. Some party.
So, how come they're all sharing taxis together, and shoving #10 tips at the
driver?
SEX (c): Incapacity.
IF you got this far, incapacity would be the reason. Mutual incapacity. She'd
be incapable of telling you to ``sod off''. You'd be capable of sod-all. What
you had in mind was a party-popper climax to the evening. What you've got is a
crumpled cracker, and little understanding of how to get it pulled. Your party
hat is squashed. Your charm is crap. But there's always the motto, and the
motto reads: Go home. Or, like DJ Chris Evans, you'd better phone in and have
the PR department say something diplomatic after your 17-hour bender, like:
``He and the team have worked like maniacs for eight months so they deserved a
night on the town.'' Then get sacked.
HOME TRUTHS (a): A've Alwaysh Fanshied You.
YOU'VE been waiting all year for the chance. The office party, once the
inhibitions come down, is where what always needed saying gets said, at last.
With disastrous consequences.
HOME TRUTHS (b): You're a Shit!
DITTO!
CAREER MOVES (a): Toadying.
YOU'VE seen him. He's the one who laughs at all the boss's terrible jokes,
helps young Gerry to the toilet to be sick, sticks to Perrier, calculates the
division of the bill, organises search parties for giggling Elsa from accounts,
is still talking about the corporate plan for 1996 at the bitter end, and then
ferries the worst of the inebriates home in his Rover. The tragedy is he never
went in for social work.
CAREER MOVES (b): Hitting the Boss.
IT is always the quietest one in the office, the one who never complained and
just did all that was asked with stoical endurance. Friends said he/she was
looking a bit drawn in those last December weeks, and right up to the fateful
moment was hardly heard to utter a word.
CAREER MOVES (c): Snogging the Boss.
SHE says she never planned it, but just catching him there underneath the
mistletoe, it was like seeing him in a different light - he was almost human,
and why shouldn't bosses have fun, too? She is so generous, so charitable, so
capable of seeing the best in anyone useful, she is bound to make it to the
top. And she does, eventually. She calculated each step, office party by office
party, boss by boss. She got there. That's why you're snogging her now.
BEAN FEAST: And then we had turkey with cranberry sauce...
THEY take you through it course by course. They remember precisely what Geoff
ordered, and Pat and Mrs Taylor from reception, and what it looked like on the
plate, and what came next. They'll take you through to the After Eight mints
and the coffee, if you'll allow them, and this is three days after the party
when everyone else is desperately trying to forget the little they can recall.
THE SINGSONG: Sloop John B, Michelle, Yesterday.
THEY never know the words to anything that charted after 1968, and the tunes
were always lost. They were boring the backside off everyone after office
parties many years before Karaoke was ever invented. In fact, they were
probably responsible for inflicting it on modern uncivilisation. You suspect
they must rehearse in the bath in the weeks leading up to this fag-end event. I
mean, is it reasonable for anyone to know the entire lyrics to American Pie or
want to run through the full score to West Side Story?
THE LAST THING I REMEMBER...
THE blessing is you do forget the worst of it, the most embarrassing bits of
it. That's human nature. Regrettably, it's also human nature for everyone to
want to help remind you a week later. You hear bits of it second or third-hand,
and the galling thing is that this is going into the annals of office lore, to
be repeated and re-dramatised every time the next party comes up. Ultimately,
that's what the office party is all about: wonderful, amateur, helpless,
extravagant indiscretions.
</TEXT>
