<HEADLINE>Salmon farms may need more support</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749804</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Fisheries Minister Raymond Robertson has called for an investigation
of the salmon market to determine whether further action is required in
addition to the imposition of a minumum import price for salmon announced
earlier this week by the European Commission.
While welcoming the commission's move, Mr Robertson expressed concern that a
minimum import price could not, in itself, address the underlying difficulties
of the market.
Mr Robertson said that he had explained to the fisheries council the importance
of salmon farming to the economy of the Highlands and Islands - and the
difficulties which had faced Scottish producers in the wake of a sharp fall in
prices.
``The introduction of a minimum import price should help put a floor on the
market, and I am sure it will bring some relief to Scottish salmon farmers,''
he said. ``However, it will not address the underlying problem and it will not
bring about a more stable market in the medium to long term.''
There were no easy solutions and that was why a full investigation of the
salmon market was required, he added. ``It is important that the Scottish and
other European salmon farmers co-operate in this study. The commission will
need hard facts and solid arguments.
The Scottish Salmon Growers Association have welcomed the minimum import price
as a first stage in tackling the problem of massive over-production by Norway.
SSGA chairman Phillip Thorn has suggested that the price control should not be
restricted to whole fish but should cover fillets as well. The association has
indicated that it will be pressing for further medium and long-term measures
including volume control on Norwegian exports to EU countries.
</TEXT>
