<HEADLINE>Straw fears knife adverts fuel culture of violence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749806</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday called for a crackdown on advertisements for mail order knives
as Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw sent examples of the pictures featured in
military and martial arts magazines to the Advertising Standards Authority.
He said he was shocked to see some of the adverts for weapons such as 10in
knives called Rambo Sidearm and Rambo Shortsword.
The adverts stated no age limit and Mr Straw asked the authority whether they
contravened its code of practice.
``There is a real risk that such advertisements encourage a culture of violence
- particularly amongst young people.
``Labour argued during the passage of the Criminal Justice Bill last year that
these sort of advertisements ought to be properly regulated.
``In response the Government said that the Advertising Standards Authority had
sufficient powers to make sure that they neither condoned nor incited violent
behaviour.
``That is why I have written to the authority's chairman, Lord Rodgers of
Quarry Bank, to ask him whether he thinks such advertisements contravene the
authority's code of practice,'' he said.
Mr Straw told BBC Radio 4's Today programme: ``There is a knife culture at the
moment. These are openly advertised, then openly bought, then openly carried,
and we have got to hit the knife culture at every point.''
Tim Riffley, editor of Combat and Survival magazine which features some of the
controversial adverts, bluntly dismissed Mr Straw's complaints, accusing him of
portraying a ``caricature'' of the adverts.
``Our reader (is the) average British soldier who wants a knife to go to Bosnia
to cut up wood or cut up his meal,'' he said.
``If you were having an affair with your secretary and you went home and your
wife found out, she would not pick up Combat and Survival and think `I need a
knife'.
``These are practical people who want to use knives for totally legitimate
purposes,'' he told Radio 4's The World At One.
Tougher laws on carrying knives and enlarging police search powers are to be
introduced following the recent death of headmaster Philip Lawrence at a west
London school.
The new legislation, to be introduced in a Private Member's Bill, will be
backed by the Government and Labour, and is expected to be passed next month.
</TEXT>
