<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Town that gambled away its privacy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>radio</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749808</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TGIF, Radio Scotland's light-hearted end-of-the-week programme, was, as befits
the season, even more loopy than usual yesterday. We had a Los Angeles promoter
of singing dogs and moggies, howling their way through Queen's Bohemian
Rhapsody and howling their way through Jingle Bells. These records apparently
achieved some chart success, but we have no reason to be snobbishly superior -
the results were rather better than our soap celebs' ghastly renditions which
would turn the most sentimental Christmasites to Schoenberg Scrooges.
Austin Lafferty doesn't really sound like a lawyer, in fact maybe he's not and
that's why the BBC can afford him. Not that he fails to give good advice. On
the contrary, but he claims to send possible clients away when they approach
him with a libel suit. His colleagues consider such cases the prostitution end
of the market, and seemingly wouldn't touch them with a Gold American Express
Card. He laughed and said poor misguided folk call it ``deformation of
character'' but I've never heard of a lawyer who turns down business because a
potential client doesn't talk right.
You don't get legal aid for such matters, and the two guys currently taking on
McDonald's are representing themselves, with the help of a borrowed word
processor - and they're getting all the sympathy. Unlike David Ashby whose
libel action action against the Times brought more ridicule than the offending
article ever did.
I did miss a good source of defamation and gossip this week because yesterday's
TGIF did not include the latest from The Split Ends Salon. Kate Donnelly and
Clare Hemphill normally do a very funny line in lasciviousness amid the setting
lotions and cultural commentary among the curlers. Hope there are more
appointments booked for them in the New Year.
The humour of the Shargorodsky brothers, the subject of Samovars and Cuckoo
Clocks (R4) was blacker and more bleakly brilliant. Presented by Matthew Reisz
and produced by Virginia Crompton, the account of this Russian-Jewish satirical
duo made for captivating listening. This irreverent double act were kicked out
by the communist regime in 1979 as it became plain that the authorities found
them as funny as David Ashby found his wife shouting ``Poofters'' through his
friend's letterbox. Instead of getting their wallpaper shredded by talons that
obviously needed the attention of the Split Ends expertise, they were instead
relocated to Geneva, where the surviving brother Lev (Alex died some years ago)
still plies his wry trade in the local cafes, and sales of their material
continue to thrive.
One of their stories, So you're Jewish? Prove it!, read by comedian David
Schneider, found their grandfather in the novel situation of having to prove
his Jewishness, finding that his name, religious observance, and circumcision,
did not add up to non-Gentile status. Beautifully ironic and with the serious
undertow that is contained in the best humour, the story perfectly conveyed the
bewilderment of a man whose attempts to prove the patent truth of his identity
led him to parody his natural self.
Nothing could be less natural and more weird than the architecture of Las
Vegas. Tony Palmer, on Radio 4's Night Waves, conjured up a place so far beyond
tastefulness as to be surreal. The Luxor Hotel, an Egyptian pastiche,
four-fifths the size of your actual pyramid, with its own Nile running through
it, made claims to be educative, its displays putting Cairo to shame. There are
plans for a replicated Paris, with its own half-size Eiffel Tower. ``I have to
ask you why?'' said Palmer, and the reply came quick as a thrown dice -
``Because it's never been done before.''
A grotesque confusion of styles and a weird sense of Las Vegas as a historical
and amoral place where the redefinition of self becomes as possible as instant
wealth, have metamorposed what only 30 years ago was a ``private little town''
(a little secret of Sinatra, Dino, and Sammy J) into the American adult
equivalent of Disneyland.
This is a world of no clocks and few windows, which is slowly sinking into the
sand, a few desert miles away from the planned nuclear waste site. Las Vegas
has coined a new word - Signage - for its neon cityscape. There is even a
neon-sign graveyard for the discarded signifiers . . . I think if I won some
unearned money, I'd rather go to Paris, Paris France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
