<HEADLINE>Fate of the foolish fowl</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGinty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749809</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Turkey - Profile
DECORATED in its Christmas costume of roasted skin, plumped out with sage and
onion stuffing, and served with a dollop of cranberry sauce, the turkey has the
image of a happy beast of burden. Children's cartoons often show them
high-kicking in a long line, the chorus in a curious Busby Berkeley number. The
line last Christmas numbered 10 million birds, found on 87% of tables - that's
a lot of little top hats and canes.
In America, where turkey is the Thanksgiving meal, devoured in honour of the
Pilgrim Fathers, the originators with the native Americans of the noble art of
the turkey shoot, the percentage rises to almost 100%. In fact, the first meal
on the moon, eaten by Armstrong and Aldrin, was cold roast turkey.
While factory farming has reduced the price per pound of turkey to less than
dog food - 29p per pound in Asda - there are always people willing to pay more.
Linda McCartney, for example, paid #95 per pound for Noel or Henley (depending
on which tabloid you read), a 28lb turkey which had been destined to feed the
customers at a Birmingham restaurant.
Her daring rescue mission was launched the same week as Free As A Bird, the
first Beatles single in 25 years - and a less-fortunate turkey, according to
some critics.
However, it was the first blow in a battle of the birds which went on to
involve ``Bootiful'' Bernard Matthews. Newspapers alleged that birds in the
great man's food factory were being maltreated, a point he denied but said he
would investigate.
As more people become aware of the conditions in which most turkeys are kept,
tastes may change.
But it remains a confusing market with choices available from: fresh, farm
fresh, traditional farm fresh, fresh frozen, frozen oven-ready, frozen with
water and ready basted. It is no wonder the British Turkey Information Service
Turkey Talkline - yes, there is such a service - took a call from a women
wanting to know how to thaw a fresh turkey.
This makes turkey even more complex dead than alive. Bernard Matthews once
said: ``All they need is food and warmth. They do not need to be taken to the
cinema twice a week.'' It is a fact that turkeys are so stupid that, one expert
pronounced, if asked to vote for Christmas they would. A professor of poultry
science at North Carolina State University discovered that they think entirely
in the present, with little or no concept of the future.
In fact, Turkeys can be so mesmerised by rain that they stand, beaks open in
awe, until they drown. New drinking containers are a mental challenge beyond
their limited capabilities, with researchers having to tug their heads down to
drink, and should just one fall in, the rest will foolishly follow. It's nice
to feel superior to something - even if it is only your Christmas dinner.
The turkey is also as pretty as it is clever. And so it resembles a vulture
with a hangover, one which has lasted 10 million years to be precise. Although
there exists a turkey vulture, they are not related.
The common turkey originated in Mexico where the Aztec Indians saw the large
local bird as an alternative to human flesh, and not as salty. So by the time
Cortes gate-crashed the dinner table in 1521, the domesticated bird could be
shipped to Europe.
One version of its English debut has it boxed and sent from Spain with a
consignment of bulbs. Another tale is of an enterprising cabin boy, young
Yorkshireman William Strickland, who sailed around the coast of North America
in 1526 and traded with the natives for six turkeys, selling them for tuppence
each in Bristol. Upon later voyages he soon racked up enough profit to charter
his own ship, buy a title and, as Sir William, have a turkey mounted on his
coat of arms.
Though the native Americans called the bird ``furkee'' it's current title was
as a result of a mix-up. Upon its arrival in England it resembled African
guinea fowl which had been imported through Turkey. At the time the guinea
fowls were called ``turkey'' by poultry merchants.
When the difference was noticed the birds were given separate names. The New
World birds acquired, incorrectly, the name ``turkey'' while the guinea fowl
was given its present name.
Despite problems of nomenclature - ``I don't know what it's called but it's big
and squawks and I'll eat it anyway'' - turkeys proved popular, especially among
the royals. During James I's reign the price of turkey was fixed at an
astronomical six shillings. Henry VIII enjoyed turkey, while Edward VII dined
on it at Christmas. The idea of eating certain foods only at Christmas was a
legacy of the mid-winter feasting.
To satisfy the growing festive demand, over the centuries a bizarre form of
``Wacky Races'' took place with farmers driving flocks of turkeys and geese
from East Anglia to London. The journey often took up to three months, and each
bird was fitted with little sackcloth footwear to prevent lameness. An actual
race in the seventeenth century resulted in the geese winning by 24 hours.
While the noble bird has poked its beak into the works of Tolstoy's Anna
Karenina, Marcel Proust's Swan's Way, it was Dickens who was the ``first to
find out the immense spiritual power of the Christmas turkey'' said Mrs
Oliphant, a critic at the time. It was a symbol of the bird's high regard and
expense that Scrooge replaced Bob Cratchit's goose with a turkey. Today he'd
have a fight on his hands.
In France a ``Jesuit'' was common slang for a turkey, because the religious
order raised thousands near Bourges. Thankfully a request for roast ``Jesuit''
was, in 1815, years after the Reformation. In fact, the French love their
turkey, but are wary of the beak.
Alexandre Dumas wrote in his Grand Dictionnaire De Cuisine of a turkey attack
on Nicolas Boileau, the literary critic, who was pecked on a particular point
that rendered him ``no longer capable of becoming an erotic poet''.
Yet the beast of yesteryear is distant from today's generation. Readers who
still wish to savour Monday's sweet taste may exit now - for the turkey remains
a beast of burden whose burden is, in fact, itself. Selective breeding, using
the heaviest birds, has bloated them to the point where they can no longer
procreate unaided or carry their own weight.
The factory-farming methods, introduced and encouraged by the Government in the
fifties, which have resulted in affordable turkey meat for all, has been at an
appalling price for the birds themselves. In December, Compassion in World
Farming highlighted the current problems.
A turkey's death is a two-stage process with the birds being shackled up-side
down on a moving line, the first stage is stunning in an electrically charged
waterbath, then, while unconscious, their necks are cut. However, up to 50% of
the creatures receive pre-stun shocks as their wings enter the bath, the
shackles are severely painful, and more than 35,000 birds enter the scalding
pools, which remove their feathers, alive.
The CWF are campaigning for a reduction in the time spent in shackles (up to
six minutes currently), a law stating that their necks must be properly cut,
and a more adequate system of stunning.
They seem so peaceful, cling-film wrapped and chilled in the superstore's
refrigerator that few people consider how they got in such a state. Yet from
the top down the tide is turning. Among the upper-classes duck and geese are
rated tastier, while a small but growing number of people, in light of recent
poor publicity, are demanding free-range turkeys. They still die, but first
they live.
</TEXT>
