<HEADLINE>Viscount Watkinson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749811</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Viscount Watkinson, PC, CH, businessman and former politician; born January 25,
1910, died December 19, 1995
VISCOUNT Watkinson, who has died aged 85, was the Conservative Minister of
Transport much concerned with the planning of the M1, although the first
section did not open until November 1959 after he had left that office.
He had an engineering background which was of help to him in assessing remedies
for the growing problem of traffic congestion in towns, the construction of an
underpass for Hyde Park, and modernising British Rail.
Although a member of Harold Macmillan's Cabinet from 1957 until 1962, when he
was one of those purged in the famous Cabinet Night of the Long Knives as
Macmillan tried to give his Government a new look, he attracted little public
notice.
He was more of a businessman than a politician and had a businessman's
frustration at the way politics often diverted ministers from taking what
seemed obvious decisions. Although he was colourless as a politician his
colleagues valued his advice on matters outside his own responsibilities for
its sensible bluntness.
Harold Arthur Watkinson was born in 1910. His father ran a small builder's
business at Walton-on-Thames. From Queen's College, Taunton, Watkinson went on
to study engineering at King's College, London.
After working in the family business for some years Watkinson concentrated on
engineering and became managing director of a machine tool company. During the
Second World War he served in the RNVR on Channel convoys and then as a
lieutenant commander in charge of training at the main naval anti-aircraft
gunnery school.
On demobilisation he extended his engineering experience to shipbuilding while
taking an increasing part in Conservative party affairs in Surrey. When he was
elected to the Commons as MP for Woking in 1950, his knowledge of industry and
defence matters won him quick advancement. After the 1951 election Churchill
appointed him Parliamentary Secretary to the Ministry of Transport and Civil
Aviation.
A year later he was moved to the department of Labour and National Service
where his experience of industry and good relations with trade union leaders
were a great help to his Minister, Sir Walter Monkton, who had a brief from
Churchill to avoid industrial strife but whose experience of labour affairs was
limited.
Watkinson made good contacts with both employers and unions and contributed
much to the relative industrial peace of that period, chairing a national
committee which produced a report on Human Relations in Industry.
Given a department of his own in 1955 he found his status elevated two years
later when he became the first Transport and Civil Aviation Minister to sit in
the Cabinet. What was technically the country's first motorway, the Preston
by-pass, opened in 1958. He had much to do with the planning of the M1.
In 1959 he became Defence Minister at a time when the forces were being reduced
in size and faced closer integration, leading to service rivalries with which
he had to cope.
With the Defence budget under fierce financial pressure the decision to abandon
Britain's own Blue Streak missile in April 1960 was seen as another admission,
following the Suez affair, that Britain could no longer play in the same league
as the two world super-powers.
Watkinson flew to Washington and began the negotiations which were to lead to
Britain's acquiring Polaris as a substitute missile. But by the time the deal
was finalised, in December 1962, he was no longer Minister, having been sacked
along with six Cabinet colleagues.
After leaving office he went on to hold several top-flight business
appointments, being group managing director Schweppes 1963-8 and chairman of
Cadbury Schweppes from 1969-74 with other directorships including the Midland
Bank. He was president of the CBI 1976-67.
Watkinson's belief in Government's co-operating closely with industry and
unions was out of step with the Thatcherite approach. Just after her arrival as
party leader he published in 1976 a study of British industry since the war,
arguing that politicians rather than management and workers were mostly to
blame for current problems. In 1987, long after his retirement, he surprised a
CBI council meeting by encouraging them to continue to resist Thatcherite
solutions.
He became a Privy Councillor in 1955 and was made a Companion of Honour in
1962. He married Vera Langmead in 1939 and they had two daughters. Thus his
peerage, created in 1964, is now extinguished.
</TEXT>
