<HEADLINE>Europe is on agenda</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Derek Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749813</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUGBY
SCOTLAND'S top 10 clubs have arranged another meeting next week when they will
again try to hammer out a consensus on the issue of clubs or districts in
Europe next season, write Derek Douglas.
The meeting, to take place at Meggetland on Thursday, will debate alternatives
to the Scottish Rugby Union's plan for districts to fly the saltire in Europe
and for the make-up of the domestic season.
Even the top 10 remain split on the European issue with Hawick, Gala,
Jed-Forest and, apparently, Heriot's FP adamant that it should be districts,
whereas Scottish champions Melrose, and their director of rugby Keith
Robertson, have been among the principal campaigners in favour of club
representation.
Robertson has been a tireless campaigner in favour of clubs, and some
indication of the heated nature of the debate can be gauged from the fact that
the pro-districts lobby in the South are now privately suggesting that the
former Scotland star's work in favour of clubs - which he maintains is the only
realistic route for the the game as a whole - is incompatible with his position
as assistant coach with the South of Scotland district side.
</TEXT>
