<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aitken's main wish</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749814</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
\ROY Aitken, the Aberdeen manager, has a festive wish for for his young
players, and that is to put extra pressure on the club's established stars.
Aitken urged his Pittodrie youngsters to follow Stephen Glass into the first
team to strengthen their challenge for the top honours. ``I don't have a
fortune left to bring in new players,'' said Aitken. ``This must largely be
done through wheeling and dealing.
``It is vital for this club to keep producing our own talent. I know that
talent is there in our reserve and youth sides. I want them to pick up the
gauntlet and stake their claim. I realise it is a hard task to make the step up
and compete at this higher level. But Glass achieved this and the challenge is
there for these youngsters to follow his example.''
Scotland striker Scott Booth will make his comeback in the reserves today and
be pitched into the firing line at Falkirk on Boxing Day if he proves his
fitness.
``I now have all the first-team squad available apart from Colin Woodthorpe,''
said the manager. ``I'm happy we are in such a strong position going into the
demanding holiday programme.
``We have come a long way since last season. I am reasonably satisfied that we
have a trophy in the boardroom and lie fourth in the league with 26 points.
However, I have told the players I expect them to do better in the second half
of the league, show more consistency, and take a greater percentage of the
points.
``We have a good record at Brockville but will take nothing for granted. They
have had changes in personnel since our last meeting.
``Their manager, John Lambie, has been through the premier division survival
route before. He will have his players fired up for the task and it will be a
difficult game despite their league position.''
q HUNTLY manager Doug Rougvie will miss the festive double-header against Cove
Rangers - giving his understudy the chance to shine again for the scouts.
Rougvie had a motorbike accident a fortnight ago and has been off work ever
since.
The manager's absence has opened the door for young Mike Newlands to fit into
Rougvie's boots and alert the senior scouts to Christie Park. Aberdeen have
watched him and Celtic are reported to be interested.
Newlands' recent good form has led to speculation that 41-year-old Rougvie may
be set to retire and concentrate on managing the team.
Cove have won eight in a row, and victory in the festive games would cut the
gap at the top to one point with a crucial game in hand. If Cove fail to break
their recent hoodoo against Huntly, black-and-gold ribbons will surely be back
on the trophy.
The Buchan derby pits cup specialists Fraserburgh against Peterhead and both
will be looking to take advantage of any help Cove may throw their way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
