<TEXT>
q STIRLING Albion hope to have the chance today to move within three points of
East Fife at the top of the second division, but first they need a sufficient
thaw for Forthbank to be playable for today's scheduled match against bottom
club Montrose, writes Bill Sutherland.
Albion manager Kevin Drinkell will warn his men against a repetition of their
performance against the strugglers earlier in the season, when they threw away
a two-goal lead at Links Park.
Stirling last week hammered Queen of the South 5-1 at Palmerston and Drinkell
reckons he is finally getting the rewards for his patient dealing in aim. They
will have defender Paul Livering back after suspension.
the transfer market. Now, there are goals to go with the good football.
In the third division, Albion Rovers are once again managerless following the
resignation of Jimmy Crease. Joe McBride will take charge today against
Caledonian Thistle, but the player-coach will remain at the club only until a
new appointment is made. McBride's request for a free transfer has been granted
- but he obviously wants a shot today at becoming Rovers' manager of the month.
Chairman David Shanks said: ``Both have worked hard in a difficult situation
and I would thank them.''
If today's match beats the weather, Caley striker Iain Stewart is aiming to add
to his goalscoring tally before he jets out on a family holiday.
The 19-goal striker will miss three games, including next week's derby against
Ross County and the Scottish Cup tie against third-division leaders Livingston.
</TEXT>
