<HEADLINE>Tomba back with a bang</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749816</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKI-ING
LIFE is never dull with Alberto Tomba around, and the Italian, who boycotted
the giant slalom on the Podkoren course in Kranjska Gora, Slovenia, on
Thursday, stormed back into the limelight yesterday to collect his second
Alpine World Cup slalom success in four days.
The win was the forty-sixth of Tomba's often turbulent career, moving him past
Luxembourg's Marc Girardelli into second place on the all-time victory list
behind Sweden's Ingemar Stenmark, who won 86 times in the 1970s and 1980s.
Tomba, who recorded his first victory of the season on home snow in Madonna di
Campiglio on Tuesday, recorded a time of 1-36.84 to beat local favourite Jure
Kosir, whose home is only 10 kms from Kranjska Gora, by 1.21 seconds, with
Frenchman Sebastien Amiez third in 1-38.43.
There was talk of Tomba boycotting yesterday's slalom, furious as he was at a
decision to restart Thursday's race from scratch after fog forced an
interruption. Tomba, one of 12 racers to ski before the fog descended, refused
to go back up the slope for a second start, saying lack of snow made the course
dangerous.
The controversy appeared to fire him up yesterday and he charged through the 57
gates of the first run, setting the best time by half a second. In typical
Tomba style, he refused to ski cautiously in the second run, battling his way
down the hill again to extend his lead.
Despite the win, the thirty-first slalom victory of his career, Tomba was still
fretting about recent events. ``This is a great win but I'm not happy,'' he
said. ``Too many things have happened in the last 24 hours.
``People sometimes don't understand my reactions. They don't see that my
purpose is to defend ski racing and that I had nothing to gain with all that
happened yesterday.''
He then went on to accuse the Slovenian fans of trying to disrupt his final
run. ``There were whistles on the course,'' he said. ``In Italy we are always
nice when Kosir is racing. But I knew I was in winning form, it was just a
matter of putting two good runs together.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A bit of a pantomime with the Large-Mouthed Bass</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Paul Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749817</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dragging himself out of drag is, well, a bit of a drag for Paul Young this
Christmas
THERE was an old Goon Show joke. Neddy Seagoon cried, deep from the heart,
``Christmas Eve, and still no offers for pantomime!'' As an actor, one knows
how he felt, but this year I am to be found dragged up as one of the Ugly
Sisters . . . oh yes I am . . .in Cinderella at the King's Theatre in
Edinburgh. Andy Gray and I are Agnes and Senga, the ``Sisters from Hell'' we
hope you love to hate. We even manage to get a couple of fishing jokes into the
script, and that is the fascinating thing about panto.
You can be in Inverness doing Dick Whittington, a story set in London, or
Aladdin, a story of old Peking, performed, perhaps, in Perth and you can still
get away with doing local jokes. Andy Gray's ``What does Inverness stand for?
It's no very exciting, right 'nuff. Even Saturdays and Sundays'' seems to
capture the mood.
Organised anarchy on stage is panto, and, I may say, very different from the
filming of our new series of fishing programmes to be seen early in the new
year on Scottish Television. Mind you, I suppose there are also similarities.
We had some wonderful days in Scotland but also travelled further afield than
we have done before in making the programmes, sampling the delights of fishing
in Alaska, Florida, and Northern Ireland, but always when away from home, there
was the Scottish comparison to be made.
In Alaska, we were fishing for salmon. Well, I've done that for a few years in
Scotland, but not for Pacific salmon, which behave in different ways from their
Atlantic brethren. Not only that, there are several species to be caught.
We arrived at the end of the Chinook or king salmon run, and halfway through
the numbers of chum or dog salmon - and just at the beginning of the silvers,
the Pacific salmon that looks most like our fresh-run fish. But I know of a few
rivers in Scotland where you can fish the equivalent of a well-greased
Muddler-type fly in bright pink where the salmon will follow and slash at it on
the surface. Or rivers where you can peer into the pellucid waters and see
groups of 30 or 40lb fish waiting to take your fly at the end of a sink-tip
fished on a nine-foot single-handed rod. It happened on the Alagnak Rivers and
what followed wasa bit of a . . . well, pantomime.
In Florida, we fished for large-mouthed bass. Sounds a bit like another panto
character, perhaps, but these are highly prized fish in America and we found
ourselves in a boat on a lake outside Dundee, Polk County, Florida. Would the
jokes travel? Yes. Dave Hoy, my angling partner, was on for it and though we
came from very different angling backgrounds, if he'd been in our Dundee, we
still had that essential point of contact in that we both just loved fishing of
any kind . . . Oh yes we did!
Then, out from the Keys at Islamorada, we met another band of strolling fishers
who differ from us Scots only in that they have the sun on their backs all year
round.
Telling them of night shore fishing competitions on the Clyde estuary in winter
elicits paeans of praise for our fortitude, but they know why we do it. They'll
tell you what hell it is quartering the deep blue ocean between the Keys and
Cuba week after week looking out for shoals of fish to keep the anglers happy
and trying not to get too much sun on their backs.
I was one of those anglers for a couple of days and was I happy? Oh! yes I was!
Northern Ireland after the ceasefire was brilliant. Optimism was three-feet
deep in the street. The anglers we fished with were brilliant but their rivers,
like Scotland's this summer, suffered from lack of water. We caught fish,
however, and made lots of friends.
But despite our journeys far afield, the biggest fish was caught in Scotland. A
beautiful late autumn morning in the Sound of Mull saw another Dave, Dave Holt,
put me on a spot where big skate are known to rove. A couple of mackerel on a
large hook, 400ft down, proved too much of a temptation for that rare
commodity, a common skate. An hour or so later, I got it to the surface. The
heaviest fish of my lifetime,
So making fishing programmes is a bit like pantomime. It can make all your
dreams come true. Oh yes it can!
</TEXT>
