<HEADLINE>Berries and red men</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH OUSTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>39</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749819</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON a fine morning at the end of October, the period when such calamities were
almost always to be apprehended they found the Highland thieves had been down
upon them and swept away ten or twelve head of cattle. Rob Roy was sent for,
and came with a party of seven or eight armed men. He heard with great gravity
all that could be told him of the circumstances . . . and expressed his
confidence that . . . he should be able to recover them.
As with so much that Walter Scott wrote, that autumn morning is as fresh as
yesterday. But did it happen? The mining of Walter Scott's library which is
just beginning may strike the ore of historical truth from which the
introduction to Rob Roy is fashioned. However, that story of cattle thieving
and blackmail is already a primary source, told in person to the Laird of
Abbotsford. Scott knew as well as anyone the difference between the sparkling,
unpredictable stream of oral history and the sieved and channelled clarity of
the printed page. It is as sharp as the Highland Line itself.
On a fine morning at the end of October we crossed the Highland Line. The road
from Callander to the west takes you over the Border. Today there is no
language, no culture, no social and economic structure to distinguish highland
from lowland, but within a hundred yards of Kilmahog the form of the land is
utterly changed.
The road that took the blackmailers to the lowland cattle now takes the tour
buses to the highland coffee shops. The precariousness of the income may not
have changed as much as its nature, despite the Scottish Tourist Board's
promise of autumn gold. This October it was a promise fulfilled, because of the
gold that the sun had poured into the glens in the long summer and which now
fragmented into the browns and reds of leaves and fruits which shone above our
heads and fell among our feet in the woods of Balquhidder.
The trees were spreading their genes with a natural superabundance. No more
than one in a million seeds would germinate, just as each birch along the
burnside descended from one seed in a million scattered in Rob Roy's autumns.
The patches and strips of broad-leaved woodland catch the sun and throw it back
in your eye because they stand out against the tide of dark forestry that
washes up the braes of Ben Vorlich, Ben Ledi and Balquhidder. It was not always
thus. Walter Scott's informant had gone with Rob Roy to fetch back the cattle.
No shelter. No woods. Yet this October the glens were once again deep in trees.
The fat resilient nuts sit in their thimbles on stalks; these are pedunculate
oaks, not the sessile oaks of the Caledonian forest but a species any textbook
will tell you is an English oak. The landscape of Balquhidder today is quite
artificial - just as artificial, in fact, as the bare moors of the eighteenth
century.
We pay Rob Roy attention because he was the last example of a doomed way of
life.
After the '45 the meeting of the tales of the clans and the books of the
cities, which had begun with Tacitus in the first century AD, came to its
inevitable conclusion. The neolithic farmers, the Celts themselves, the red
soldiers and now the Forestry Commission: all had come from the south, like the
seeds of birch and willow after the northward retreating ice. It's just the
shape of history in Balquhidder, natural and human.
</TEXT>
