<HEADLINE>Going down a bomb</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra paperbacks</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749820</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEAN CITY, Ron McKay (Hodder &amp; Stoughton, #9.99).
n.Glaswegians, and that includes me, have a wary civic pride in their city's
reputation as a hard hoodlum burg. We like the grim tales of gang wars and the
Runyonesque anecdotes that go around about our own local Dave the Dudes and
Harry the Horses, though most of us would run a mile if we met them, if they
let us run. This is where fiction comes in handy - for example journalist Ron
McKay's tough, intelligent, and exceptionally well-written gangster-dynasty
thriller Mean City, which takes up where McArthur and Long's No Mean City left
off in the 1930s and carries on to the present day in a blaze of gunfire and
gallows humour. It lights up its subject like a firebomb through a pub window.
I COULDN'T PAINT GOLDEN ANGELS, Albert Meltzer (AK Press, #12.95)
n.WHEN Jessica Mitford was in the Communist Party she always misheard the line
in the Internationale about ``the final conflict'' as ``a fine old conflict'';
and allowing for the lifelong anarchism that makes it unlikely Albert Meltzer
would ever have sung the Internationale, he's been fighting the fine old
conflict all his life. At various times a signwriter, boxer, printer,
copy-taker, bookseller, and a great deal else, he's always been there or
thereabouts in every working-class struggle of his long lifetime. His memoir is
cantankerous, dogmatic, fascinating, generous, and wonderful.
DELICATE MATTERS, Vickery Turner (Warner, #5.99).
n.JANE Hampton is 13 years old and lives in shabby-genteel London squalor with
her distraught and dumped-on mother, and a photographer lodger called Freddy.
Father, separated, plans to become an MP if his wife doesn't kick up too much
fuss. Mother works for a yob laundromat king called Vincent (a name and
profession right out of Martin Amis, if ever you saw one). A wry, mousy child
who reads like a cross between Adrian Mole and Candide, Jane reports on their
lives for a school project on love and sex in a manner that is undignified,
comical, and highly unlikely - which sounds just about right.
THE HORSEMAN ON THE ROOF, Jean Giono (Harvill, #8.99).
n.Don Quixote meets Albert Camus's The Plague in this marvellous
nineteenth-century French metaphysical adventure (coming to a cinema near you
next month, directed by Jean-Paul Rappeneau of Cyrano de Bergerac fame), a
picaresque tale of love, loyalty, and contempt for death.
</TEXT>
