<HEADLINE>Routine brush with mortality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749821</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Clare Henry meets an artist with a morbid fascination            for medical
equipment and discovers how an Italian scholarship will take her back to basics
FOR such a nice girl, Julie Roberts has a morbid fascination with mortuary
slabs, hypodermic needles, straitjackets, tourniquets and operating tables! And
despite the subject matter, her paintings, exhibited in Paris, New York,
Hamburg, Stockholm, Lucerne, Budapest, London, and at the prestigious art world
Olympics - the Venice Biennale - have had great success. They are sobering
images, painted in a meticulous fashion - but gruesome they are not. No blood
and guts here.
Clean, clinical, shiny, stainless dentist chairs or operating tables float on
flat, plain, subtly stiped backgrounds as isolated objects, realistic but in a
vacuum, unattached to the surface of the canvas. She does them one at a time,
depicting the fearsome in an objective, routine, dispassionate way.
Unusual subjects for an unusual career. Roberts is a straightforward painter
who started as a graphic artist doing a lowly HND at Wrexham in Wales, and only
came to Glasgow later.
``I was doing a Design postgraduate at St Martin's and decided to apply to
Glasgow. I couldn't paint. I've never had any formal training. They must have
accepted me for my potential! We were all guinea-pigs, the first lot to do a
Master of Fine Art: Craig Richardson, Jim Hamlyn, Ed Stewart, Peter McCaughey,
and me. It was 1988.''
Roberts quickly became successful, and there are disadvantages to this. ``I've
been exhibiting ever since I graduated and so I've had to make my mistakes in
public.''
I went to see her in her sunny, well-lit WASPS studio high up in King Street
just as she was packing to leave for a year's residency in Rome. (``Before I
had this studio I painted in my bedroom, remember?'') She and her boyfriend
will drive a van there loaded with #2000 worth of canvas, paint, and stretchers.
``It's expensive abroad.'' One of the joys of that #4500 plus free board and
lodgings scholarship - other than 12 months in one of the most beautiful cities
in the world - is that, as Roberts puts it, ``I can **** up a bit; have enough
time to develop my work in private in the studio. I want to try watercolours
for my show at Glasgow Print Studio next October.''
Now 32, Roberts, who has been teaching at Glasgow since 1992, is the first
recipient of the Scottish Art Council's scholarship to Rome which supplements
SAC residencies in Amsterdam and Australia. The British School at Rome was set
up in 1901 as a top centre for research in architecture, archaeology and fine
art, and has a long tradition.
The facade was designed by Sir Edward Lutyens in grandiose classical style
based on the upper storey of St Paul's - but behind it, things are more casual,
even ramshackle. It caters for about 25 scholars in studios and apartments
around a central courtyard where in summer meals are, in my experience, great
fun.
It's ideal for visiting artists like Kate Whiteford, Will Maclean, and Paul
Neagu who, like Roberts, have taken advantage of its interdisciplinary aspects.
The school occupies a splendid site beside Rome's largest park, the Borghese
Gardens. Nearby are the Gallery of Modern Art, the Villa Guillia Museum of
Etruscan Antiquities, and the Faculty of Architecture.
In Rome Roberts plans to investigate ``the weird spiritual societies which
flourished there, the Italian obsession with stigmata and medieval bones in
cases. All medicine was done in the confines of the Catholic Church. And think
of all those paintings of the Resurrection. It will be amazing for me!''
The Vatican Museum, look out. Here she comes.
Rome is very unlike King Street, although the studios there are not so
different - however, I think Roberts could paint anywhere, for she often
obtains her reseach material via books.
In the UK she began with household objects around the house: scissors, metal
cooking equipment etc, which she painted on the walls of the Castlemilk
Womanhouse in 1990. For Windfall 1991 she had a go at buildings, painting the
walls with homes as shown by estate agents. ``It didn't really work.'' By the
time of her solo show at the CCA in 1992 she had found her topic: medical
instruments.
She isn't squeamish, she says. ``After my Nana died I did more medical stuff. I
did miss her. It was like I kind of did it for her. Some of the images are sad,
isolated, but others are very positive, such as the wheelchair for a
special-needs child. It shows something to help a kid sit more comfortably. My
work is less clinical, less hard, than when I began.''
At first she relied on up-to-date sales catalogues, selecting her tubular
chrome trolleys, stethoscopes, microscopes, and forceps from them.
Gynaecological items featured prominently. Then she visited the University's
Anatomy Department and local hospitals to see the real thing. In recent work
she has resorted to researching antique medical apparatus which she finds in
museums, some from Edinburgh's Hall of Surgeons, and from the Bedlam Royal in
Kent.
``I had gone as hi-tech as I could. I had to go backwards in time. A bit like
my studies. I'd never sketched, never done formal drawing. Now in Italy I'll be
able to go as far back as looking at the Romans!''
Roberts's objects include a First World War stretcher which she found in the
studio; old metal beds from hospital stores, a nineteenth-century field kit
complete with saw for amputations, and recently, old strait-jackets. ``The ones
for women are like a tapered bolero jacket tied with a thin string that a child
could break. I got it from Montrose. The other male version is huge, borrowed
from Bedlam Royal. I showed it in the Persistence of Painting show at Glasgow's
CCA in November.''
The new paintings are richer in colour than before; more iconic. ``I was
trapped in cream and grey monochrome! Now I try to get my feelings across.''
Drapery has become important, sheets on a bed, Freud's Couch (``It looks as if
it belonged to an old hippy''), scarlet plush and leather on an old-fashioned
dentist chair, coverings over a dead body, a positively lush table draped with
gold-fringed velvet, Irish linen, and chiffon on emerald or violet. ``I use
Venetian turpentine, like Rembrandt did, to give it                        a
kick.''
The first drawing Roberts did in Scotland was skeletal, ``on a big bit of
paper. I've gone round in a circle''.
I left the cheerful Roberts merrily packing. Her concern with the supportive
machinery which helps us when our bodies start to collapse and fail us, or the
complex interaction of medicine and the individual, may make some feel uneasy.
But then mortality usually does.
</TEXT>
