<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749822</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT three years ago German businessman Hans Nagel-Hayer was persuaded by a
friend to promote a jazz concert in his native Hamburg - now Nagel-Hayer, after
that first tentative involvement, is running a flourishing record label of his
own.
In two-and-a-half years he has issued more than 20 CDs and others are scheduled
for issue - all of them featuring a mix of the best European and American
mainstream stylists.
The roster of artists includes reedmen Kenny Davern, Bob Wilber, Alan Vache,
Danny Moss, Harry Allen, and Ken Peplowski; trumpeters are Warren Vache, Randy
Sandke, and Ed Polcer; trombonists include George Masso and Dan Barrett, while
among the pianists are Mark Shane, Brian Dee, and Johnny Varro.
Nagel-Hayer explains: ``I only got into this business by accident. A friend
asked me if I would promote one concert here in Hamburg using a band which was
being led by the trombonist George Masso. I did that, made a recording of the
event, and the label was born.''
Nagel-Hayer's interest in the music began at school when a liberal music
teacher played jazz records in class. Nagel-Hayer grins: ``I was only 15 years
old and in class one day the music master decided that we should broaden our
horizons a little and he played the Eddie Condon recording of Maple Leaf Rag,
the one where Ralph Sutton played the piano.
``From that time onwards I was hooked on jazz.
``After the first promotion, with George Masso's group, it was the trumpeter
Randy Sandke who asked if I would be interested in backing a Bix Beiderbecke
tribute he was putting together to bring to Europe on tour.
``I agreed, recorded that band, and everything went so smoothly I have
continued. The Bix project was a major artistic success and the record I issued
is one of my own personal favourites. Ken Peplowski solos on clarinet on China
Boy and that is just wonderful.''
There was a tribute to Buck Clayton, too, with Sandke as leader, and another to
Eddie Condon where Ed Polcer, who used to front the house band at the last
Condon's club on West 54th Street in New York, was in charge of a group which
had a clutch of British musicians including Roy Williams and John Barnes on
board.
And, as Nagel-Hayer said the other day, there are more albums to come. One of
these will be co-led by Masso and Peplowski while another will be an
all-European affair to celebrate the 65th birthday of trumpeter Oscar Klein.
Nagel-Hayer says: ``What Oscar has done for this CD is round up musicians he
played with in the different groups, Werner Keller from the Tremble Kids, for
example, is involved and there are others from the various groups he has played
in over the years.
``Apart from the Swing College, who recorded frequently in their heyday, not
enough albums were made by the various European bands and this one boasts an
all-star line-up.''
The CD will be on the Nagel-Hayer label, of course, just like all the others
which have been produced in Hamburg. The albums are all available from
specialist jazz record shops.
KEN GALLACHER
</TEXT>
