<HEADLINE>Deer, oh deer, it's that time again</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sue Clapham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749823</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SEASONAL problem has reared its head in the North: ``It's always difficult to
fit in all the people who want a reindeer in the lead up to Christmas because
they invariably want them on a Saturday,'' says Tilly Smith, who with husband
Alan runs Britain's only free-ranging reindeer herd at the Reindeer Centre near
Aviemore.
It is not the only problem. Christmas sleighs have to be purpose-built,
surrogate Santas are not always up to the occasion, and the reindeer
themselves, though co-operative and sociable, have a habit of doing what, in
December, comes naturally.
``Around now they begin shedding their antlers, preparatory to growing a new
set in the spring,'' Tilly explains. ``On occasion we have had to resort to
harnessing up two reindeer with only one antler each - one with the left side
intact and the other with the right - in a desperate attempt to keep up
appearances.''
While Tilly works hard to make her busy Christmas schedule a success, she
refuses to extend the season. For her and Alan the real business of reindeer
herding goes on for the other 10 months of the year as the animals range
naturally across the hillside and the annual round of calving, growing, and
shedding antlers and surviving the winter takes its course.
The Smiths' commitment to preserving the ancient traditions and culture of
reindeer herding earned them a place at the First International Gathering of
Reindeer People and would no doubt have met with the approval of the Cairngorm
herd's founder, Mr Mikel Utsi.
Mr Utsi, a Swedish Sami or Lapp, had grown up herding reindeer. In 1947 he
married Dr Ethel Lindgren, a Swedish-American anthropologist, and the couple
came to live in England. A trip to Scotland inspired them to set up the
Reindeer Council of the UK and embark on a mission to establish reindeer in the
Highlands.
On April 7, 1952, eight Swedish mountain reindeer arrived in Glasgow from
Narvik.
The early years were not easy. The journey itself took its toll and the first
grazing area was not ideal - too low-down, it left the reindeer susceptible to
midges, mosquitoes, and flies. However, in 1954, 2429ha (6000 acres) on the
northern slopes of Cairngorm became available and by the end of the 1950s the
herd was becoming firmly established.
It was Mr Utsi who began the daily guided visits to the hill and by the time
Tilly and Alan, who used to work for him, took over the herd in 1989, it was
clear that this was where the future lay.
``We have made the visits very much a hands-on affair,'' says Tilly, who can
put a name to each of the 100-strong herd. ``People are able to feed and stroke
the reindeer and even the most apprehensive are soon won over by the gentleness
of the animals who are amazingly at ease with visitors.''
And the visitors come in increasing numbers, often becoming involved in the
adopt-a-reindeer scheme and returning year after year to see ``their'' reindeer.
Meanwhile, anyone wanting to book one or two for Christmas has to do so well in
advance, as the lady who has already inquired about their availability for the
millennium clearly realises. Still, at least she wants them on a Sunday.
Looks like reindeer are still a popular part of the Christmas tradition. Sue
Clapham meets a couple who care for real-life Rudolfs all year round
</TEXT>
</DOC>
