<HEADLINE>Airdrie must `dig in'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH McKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749824</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT sounds a contradiction from what some folks regard as the real world of
football to say that Airdrie are not finding success in the first division all
that easy.
And when coach John McVeigh admits that part of the problem seems to be that
they are not ``digging in hard enough,'' the cynics, as well as those not too
well up on the hard facts that surround the first division battle, may well
mock such a statement coming from a club whose past on-field reputation still
has a habit of going before them.
So be it. And if the tight confines of Kilbowie Park survive the weather today
- frost, fog, and now possibly flood being the enemies - the rearranged meeting
against Clydebank will go ahead with an Airdrie squad arriving with a
kindergarten look about them.
With Sean Sweeney and Steve Cooper suspended, and only a first-team pool of 15
to start with - and that includes the long-term injury to Paul Jack - Paul
Bonnar, John McClelland, Gerry McKenna, and Gordon Connolly, all 18, and Tony
McPeek, at 19, will travel with the squad.
McVeigh admits that it's time Airdrie began to pick up the odd three points or
so, and with his side on 23, ahead of Clydebank only on goal difference, today
would be a good way to start.
Bankies, of course, have the same aim . They will have defender Paul Livering
back after suspension.
</TEXT>
