<HEADLINE>Ibrox defender walks in water on the road back to fitness Wright's painful wait for a dream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>this sporting life</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749825</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR seven years Stephen Wright kept it a secret, but in the last five months he
has been free to admit the truth: he was a Rangers fan as a boy in Hamilton. It
would not have been a prudent revelation when he was signed, nurtured and
matured by one of the Ibrox club's greatest rivals, Aberdeen, but after Walter
Smith paid #1.2m to bring him south from Pittodrie the Rangers affection could
be confessed without incurring the wrath of the gangs in the stand.
That deep-seated enthusiasm for the Govan team was the main reason why he did
not have to think long and hard when Smith made his desire clear. The other
factor was just as obvious, the chance to join the biggest club in the land.
If the thrill of that move is still easy to detect in the 24-year-old's
demeanour, it is also true that it was perhaps better that he could not foresee
what was to become of him after only four months savouring the new life in
Glasgow.
In a game that has become notorious for other reasons, the Champions' League
meeting with Juventus at Ibrox last month (it ended 0-4, but for obvious
reasons it seemed a good idea not to dwell on the scoreline), Stephen went down
in a tackle and knew immediately something in his knee had ``gone''. The injury
turned out to be severe damage to his cruciate ligaments, the same kind of
problem which afflicted Ian Durrant and Andy Goram, two of his new team-mates
at Ibrox.
After such a short time in Glasgow when he was still establishing his
credentials in the side, it was a desperately tough blow for the player but, if
it upset him at the time, there was soon a return to that phlegmatic acceptance
of the situation which seems to be a hallmark of the player's nature. He would
admit to being a bit laid-back and that very quality has helped him cope
sensibly with the damage, mental as well as physical, such a serious injury can
have on a player.
Stephen has been to America for surgery, following on Durrant and Goram, both
of whom were able to assure the new boy that he had every reason to be
optimistic. He is also grateful Rangers have allowed him to get the best
possible treatment from the experts in the field and reckons that this is only
one benefit of being with a club as significant in standing as the Ibrox lot.
``It is only when you come here that you realise just how enormous this club
really is. Ten or 15 years ago, though, even Rangers might have not been able
to do much about this kind of injury and I have to be very thankful that
technology is available to tackle it.''
Wright is aware that not so very long ago damage such as he sustained would
probably have ended his career. Now after his operation all seems to going
according to plan, but even at that he has had to count off this season totally
in terms of playing for the top team again. His daily routine in the meantime
involves keeping in trim by taking to the pool at Ibrox where he walks in the
water to strengthen his leg. The club physiotherapist has set no targets,
preferring to let nature take its course, but Stephen is delighted with
progress, especially now that he has been able to discard the crutches.
A naturally fit young man, Wright has at least one consolation at being
sidelined in that he can give Christmas dinner some dedicated application,
unlike his mates who will be in action on Boxing Day.
That will not prevent him feeling extremely frustrated on the day for, like
most footballers, he is not the best of watchers. However, his pragmatism comes
in handy at these times as he shrugs his shoulders and waits for the healing
time to pass.
It was not what he had envisaged when he made the move from Pittodrie where
last season he had to endure, along with the rest of the Aberdeen regulars, the
nerve-jangling race against relegation.
``The difference this season has been incredible,'' he says. ``As well as
leading the league there has been the Champions' League and big crowds all the
way. The demands are tremendous, too, because you are expected to do well all
the time.''
He will have to hang on a touch before he can attempt to perform that difficult
feat but in the meantime he is also free to let us know that his schoolboy hero
was a man whose death proved to be the saddest moment of 1995. Davie Cooper, he
of the feinting hips and devilish control, was the fellow Hamiltonian who stood
above them all for the young Stephen Wright. ``I can remember my dad, who knew
Davie's father, arranging a visit for me to Davie's home. I was only small but
I can remember it clearly.''
In due course the Cooper fan had to become a Cooper opponent and in this case,
a direct opponent. Wright had to try to shackle the great man when Motherwell
met Aberdeen. ``He maybe wasn't as good as he had been but his skill was still
tremendous,'' he recalls with admiration, ``but I think I did all right against
him. It wasn't easy to play against somebody you idolise.''
It was not Rangers who spotted the teenager with Eastercraigs but Aberdeen and
he signed from them as a 16-year-old. Within two years he had broken into the
first team, taking over from the injured Stewart McKimmie and more or less
staying in the top squad ever after.
Now as a Rangers player he has had to try to handle, among other things, the
ferocity of the Old Firm derby, but maybe his view of that is a little
surprising. ``To be honest I didn't think it was any different from games
between Aberdeen and Rangers. The atmosphere is fantastic, of course, but on
the field the competitivenes is much the same. I enjoyed it.''
He still keeps contact with some of his ex-team-mates at Pittodrie but, while
he is pleased for them that they won the Coca-Cola Cup, he would much preferred
it if he had been the one picking up a medal. Any medals will have to wait as
Stephen goes walkabout in the swimming pool, dreaming of the day he can put on
that Rangers shirt again. ``All I am thinking about just now is getting fit and
then getting back into the Rangers team. I don't want to look beyond that.''
If he hadn't been injured his thoughts might occasionally have strayed towards
next summer and the possibility of making it into the Scotland squad.
Capped twice already, Wright one day perhaps will be the natural successor to
his old Pittodrie colleague, Stewart McKimmie, in the Scotland team.
For the moment he will take the recovery programme stage by stage . . . and
have a Christmas dinner to remember with his wife Liska in the new house they
moved into a few days ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
