<HEADLINE>Figures show that boot is route to victory Kicking to win is more than a passing fancy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749827</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STATISTICAL analysis of the 1995 World Cup suggests that you kick the ball
rather than pass to win rugby games, and Scotland don't play the right way to
help themselves.
But first, an award has been given for the best communication of this summer's
World Cup, and it has gone to a little eight-year-old New Zealand boy from
Wellington, who made his father fax the All Blacks with the following endearing
message: ``Remember, rugby is a team game. All 14 of you, pass the ball to
Jonah ..... Yours, etc.''
Remember the World Cup? It was six months ago that we lucky people in life went
there for six weeks to watch it and write about it. Now, the facts and figures
have been compiled to give a real insight into the way rugby is going, and the
way the game has changed over the three competitions, 1987, '91, and '95. Alun
Carter and Gareth Potter, of the Centre for Notational Analysis of the Cardiff
Institute of Higher Education, examined all the games, and they come up with
some funny old statistics. Some of them give us a fright.
Excluding extra time, the average game in the 1995 finals had the ball in play
for under 27 minutes of games lasting an average of 84 minutes. The average
match featured 179 passes, 96 kicks, 37 lineouts, 27 scrums, and 25 penalties
or free kicks.
Only three games broke the 30-minute barrier when it came to ball in play.
But do you know one of the most significant bits of statistical analysis that
has come from the World Cup '95? No? Well, it happens to be that the numbers
say that the winning sides kicked the ball more than the unsuccessful ones, who
appeared to pass more.
Taking a pass/kick ratio as a starting point, the losing sides in the last
eight matches passed the ball more than the winning ones. You have to take
France out of that equation, because they pass the ball even when they are on
their death-beds. But if you take, say, Scotland versus New Zealand as an
example, then you see that Scotland passed 94 times and kicked 50, whereas New
Zealand passed 93 and kicked 52. It's close, but it works.
When New Zealand stuffed England, the English made 120 passes but kicked 45
times, the Kiwis passed only 72 times and kicked 54.
In the final, New Zealand, and we all remember this, kicked 53 and passed 107.
The South Africans kicked about the same, 56, but made only 67 passes. It seems
to stack up, doesn't it? Losers pass the ball more than winners. Frightening,
and it's been the same for all three finals.
But a big question is: If the ball was in play for an average of just under 27
minutes in a game, then what the heck was going on for the rest of the time?
The answer is that the teams were preparing. Yep, preparing. Of the total rugby
time in the World Cup, about 2700 minutes, the ball was in play for
approximately 850 minutes and out of play for 1860.
Of that time, 312 minutes were spent preparing for scrummages, 502 waiting for
lineouts, 152 preparing for restarts, and 474 preparing for kicks at goal.
Scotland, believe it or not, spent more time preparing for kicks at goal than
any other team - with Gavin Hastings attempting 28 penalties in four matches
which took a total of more than 34 minutes, which is 73 seconds per kick.
Another proud statistic the Scots have is that we took the longest time, on
average, to prepare for scrummages at more than 25 seconds. On paper we top the
league of average total preparation time per game at 29 minutes, but that's
distorted because of the number of tries scored and therefore lining up
conversions is included.
However, a point worth considering is this then: we, in Scotland, make our
players jump through hoops to get fitter and leaner than the opposition, but in
games we let our opponents take a rest. It doesn't make sense to do that but
that's what the numbers say we do.
But how has rugby changed over the three sets of finals? My favourite statistic
is the one that shows how the teams that won in '87, '91, and '95 have changed
the general style of play, on average, at the knock-out stages. And do you know
the biggest change? They kicked more and passed less in '91 and '95 than they
did in '87, despite all the law changes.
In 1987, on average, New Zealand, the winners, kicked 48 times and passed 94.
In 1991 Australia kicked 61 and passed 66, and in 1995 South Africa kicked 55
and passed 65.
So my little message to those at the top is: the competition was wonderful, but
it could be better. I want to see more passing and less kicking. And I want to
see Scotland hurry it up on the field, too.
</TEXT>
