<HEADLINE>Man who took the chequered flag for courage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LORN MACINTYRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749828</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARCHIE AND THE LISTERS
Robert Edwards
Patrick Stephens, #17.99
ARCHIE Scott Brown had the looks of Errol Flynn as he sat in the racing car,
but he used only his left arm for driving and his tiny legs could barely
support his weight. Archie was born handicapped after his mother had German
measles in 1927. An orthopaedic surgeon, Naughton Dunn, broke and reset the
boy's legs to straighten them. His feet had to be virtually amputated, rotated,
and re-attached the right way round, without damaging the nerves.
Archie and the Listers is a story of guts, a fight not only against deformity
but family troubles. His father, a First World War flying ace who was in the
motor trade in Paisley and Glasgow, became an alcoholic and the boy had to find
his own feet. ``By 1933 Archie was walking, after a fashion. His method,
encumbered first by plaster casts, then callipers and surgical boots, was
simplicity itself. He would trot, bottom sticking out, body leaning forward and
close to toppling over, arms waving to retain balance. By the time he was eight
he had mastered locomotion, but it became clear that his lower legs were not
going to grow any more.''
His parents bought him a pedal car, and he discovered a new form of speed where
the power came from beyond his legs. When Archie was sent to Merchiston Castle
School in Edinburgh his maternal granny thought he looked odd, and insisted
upon an artificial hand.
The boy wore it, but it ``crippled and humiliated him,'' and the headmaster
urged its removal. Archie went up to St Andrews University, but instead of
economics textbooks he absorbed himself in the Autocar, becoming a
``moustachio'd cavalier, quick with a joke, very handsome, a little on the
short side, right arm inevitably shoved into the pocket of a nicely-cut tweed
coat''.
His mother Jay separated from her husband and went south with her son to his
post as a sales rep in East Anglia with George Dobie and Sons, the tobacco
company. The cruel granny, who had imposed the artificial hand, left Archie
#1000, which he invested in an MG TD.
The story accelerates. Brian Lister designed the cars, Don Moore developed the
engines, and Archie Scott Brown raced them in the heady 1950s. Despite his
handicap, he had notable wins and his mother was his greatest fan. He was in
the lead in the Belgian Sports Car Grand Prix at Spa-Francorchamps on May 18,
1958, when he came off the wet track in his Lister-Jaguar, which somersaulted
into straw bales and burst into flames. He died as a result of severe burns.
Robert Edwards, his sympathetic biographer, writes: ``With an interval of
nearly 40 years, it is hard to believe how popular Archie was. He enjoyed a
relationship with the racing public and, more importantly, his peers, that
virtually no British driver, before or since, has ever approached.'' His father
scattered Archie's ashes on the Clyde side of the Isle of Arran, overlooking
the waters they had sailed together, on a hill known as the Sleeping Warrior.
This isn't only a story of motor racing: it's the story of a man taking the
chequered flag for courage, an example to the handicapped, and a lesson to the
sound of limb never to write a person off.
LORN MACINTYRE
</TEXT>
