<HEADLINE>England decide on European free-for-all</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749829</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE English Premiership yesterday threw a considerable spanner into the works
by scrapping their own restrictions on European Union players as the two major
governing bodies in world football, FIFA, and UEFA, remained firmly behind
their three-foreigner rule in the face of last week's Jean-Marc Bosman judgment
in Europe.
The consequence would seem to be that UEFA is standing by a set of rules for
its competitions which the top English league authorities believe is against EU
law and cannot be enforced in England.
Until yesterday, only three non-British Isles players were allowed to appear in
any one game in the Premiership, but the decision by the European Court last
Friday, which ruled that UEFA's ``foreign players'' rule was illegal, led to
the league taking legal advice about whether the rule could still be enforced.
That rule was challenged by Manchester City, who asked for permission to field
new Danish loan signing Ronnie Ekelund alongside German duo Eike Immel and Uwe
Rosler and Georgian Georgiou Kinkladze.
Premier League chief executive Rick Parry announced: ``We have advised our
clubs that, with immediate effect, the restrictions which govern foreign
players can no longer be applied to citizens of the European Union.
``Clubs are therefore free to play as many European Union nationals as they see
fit.''
If that is taken to its logical conclusion that would mean that in the
Premiership's opinion, Nottingham Forest, their last European contenders in the
UEFA Cup, could not be forced to stick to three foreigners (and two assimilated
players) in the quarter-final next March, even though UEFA have insisted that
the rules of the competition cannot be changed halfway through.
Parry went on to say: ``The legal advice we have received makes clear that
rules which attempt to limit the number of EU nationals are unenforceable in
the light of the Bosman judgment. We have accepted that advice and are now in
the process of informing our clubs of that position.
``In due course, relevant rule changes on these matters will be brought forward
following consultation on possible limits governing non-EU citizens.
``We believe that in offering this advice, we are acting sensibly and
appropriately. We have stressed throughout the discussion on the Bosman case
that sports governing bodies must proceed properly and with the right legal
advice. These principles have guided the Premier League's approach to all of
the issues relating to Bosman.
``We are, of course, aware of the statement issued today by FIFA and UEFA. We
accept fully that in the interest of continuity and fairness, competition rules
should not be changed part-way through the season.
``However, our legal advice is clear - current rules on EU nationals, even if
maintained, cannot be enforced.''
The chief executive said that the League would be having further discussions
with the EU and in the meantime take legal advice on the rule governing
transfers.
The hope is that the divergence of views will have been ended by the time the
European tie comes around, but after their meeting yesteday, FIFA and UEFA made
their position clear, saying that the current three-plus-two rules would remain
in operation for the rst of this season.
``It is in the interests of continuity and fairness in every sporting
competition that the regulations are not changed during the course of the
competition.''
The advice may be good, but already football folk are paying close attention to
the new game that is taking place off the field. Celtic manager Tommy Burns
demonstrated that when he talked of his approach to the transfer market since
Bosman won his case.
``The freedom of players to move at the end of their contract has put
everything into a different light, from everybody's point of view,'' said Burns
who has been abroad this week, ``It affects both the buying club and the
sellers because you can go and look at a player just now who might be worth #2m
but can be got for nothing at the end of the season.
``We are looking at players because it is part of our job but we are not
desperately hunting for new men. We are lucky that way because the players we
have here are motivated and determined and playing very well.
``If I think we still need a certain player we will still buy him but we go
into negotiations in a different position now. We can go in knowing that the
other club are going to lose him for nothing at the end of the season anyway.''
Meanwhile, FIFA and UEFA insist that they are working to reach an agreement
with the international players union to combat the new ``free transfer'' era.
Immediately, however, the two bodies have decided to try to prevent clubs
taking advantage of the situation with a ``back door'' scam to get players for
nothing.
If for instance, an out-of-contract Rangers player was wanted by Liverpool, he
could be signed by a French team and then transferred for nothing to Liverpool,
leaving Rangers with nothing for a player who might have been a #2m man. ``We
will act to ensure that artificial international transfers are not misused as a
means to dismantle domestic transfer regime ``by the back door.''
</TEXT>
