<HEADLINE>The little gadget with a lot of byte</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749830</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n.THIS little gadget is probably how today's hi-tech Santa Claus manages to
remember, with miraculous accuracy, which child should get what present this
Christmas. It's a Pereos mobile storage unit from Datasonix, and it's small
enough to fit into a pocket. What makes it different is the amount of
information it can store. It takes a cartridge that's the size of a postage
stamp, and in that tiny space it can hold more information than a shelf of
encyclopaedias.
Quite remarkably, the little cartridge         can store the equivalent of 968
floppies, or about 1000 reasonable-sized novels. The system has been designed
to meet the needs of portable computers, and the makers            say it's
ideal for architects, executives, lawyers, accountants, editors, and engineers.
Ideal too for elderly philanthropists in red suits.
The Pereos eliminates the need to decide what information to download on to the
laptop. The bottomless well of a cartridge can store every fact they need to
have on hand. While mobile computer users are using the most powerful laptops
these days, they still have to carry around bags of documents and floppies. The
Pereos is designed to cut down on the baggage. It holds an astonishing 1.25
gigabytes of data, runs on two standard A   batteries, and needs less space
than a can of Irn-Bru.
Selling for about #700, it automatically backs up to protect data, has a system
to track misplaced files and has a transfer time of 1 meg every six seconds.
Datasonix says that transferring a 100 megabyte file would save almost a full
day.
And just in case our message is not stored on Santa's system, we'd like one of
these in our stocking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
