<TEXT>
Old School Rap 2; Eighties Garage Classics Volume 2; Electro Classics Volume 2,
various (all Deep Beats/Castle)
q Knowest where thou cometh from, dude: only then wilt thou be able to advance
righteously with a properly-chosen groove. This ongoing archival series traces
the roots of dance music in the early eighties. Old School Rap focuses on the
grist created at New York's Sugarhill and Sleeping Bag labels in 1981-82.
In addition to the timeless Adventures On The Wheels Of Steel by Grandmaster
Flash, there is plenty of sinuous synth-bass and perkily-mechanical rhythm. The
Eighties Garage collection is distinguished by Cuba Gooding's Happiness Is Just
Around The Bend.
It's Electro Classics which comes up trumps, however, from the ironic
Latin-tinged mechano-funk of Konk's Your Life to Nairobi's camp,
Kraftwerk-derived version of Soul Makossa. Plus there's the blank-eyed
electro-rap of Whip It by the Treacherous Three; Reggie Griffin and
Technofunk's bleepy Mirda Rock, and last but not least electro's crowning
glory: Nunk by Warp 9. What do you mean, you missed it back in 1982? Make up
for lost time. It's never too late to realise that everybody gotta nunk to the
new-wave funk.
Oh Brother Where Art Thou?, the Legendary Jim Ruiz Group (Minty Fresh)
q Who is Jim Ruiz, and why are he and his group legendary? Jim Ruiz is plainly
the wee nephew of Jonathan Richman, while his band have listened long and hard
to Astrud Gilberto and the Swingle Singers. And to tell you the truth, guv,
neither Jim nor his band are yet legendary, but if you buy this album - as you
must - they will reign in your heart forever.
``Who will drive my Yugo when I die?'' is one of the many poignant (yet
practical) questions Jim asks, before going on to allude to the automotive
tragedy which befell showbiz folk who opted for flashier means of getting
around. Aye, whaur's your Porsche noo, James Dean? Alas, Marc Bolan: you should
never have bought that swanky Mini 1275GT.
If you heed my words and invest in this album, you will actually never need a
car: you will be content to stay at home, jitterbugging in a frantic (yet
ironic) fashion with Jim Ruiz and Co, legends in your living room.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Smith can call on Salenko and Gazza Mikhailichenko will not be rushed into a decision</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749832</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS midfielder Alexei Mikhailichenko will discuss his future with
Wolverhampton Wanderers manager Mark McGhee next week before any financial deal
is settled by the clubs.
The move, worth about #500,000, now depends on the former Soviet Union World
Cup man who has been at Ibrox since 1991, when he was Walter Smith's second
signing after taking over as manager (Andy Goram was the first).
Mikhailichenko, who cost #2m then, could not have played in the English club's
festive games as the deadline for the transfer had passed and so there is no
rush to get a move sealed.
However, the Ukrainian has been happy in Glasgow, even if he has not been able
to maintain a weekly place in the top team and McGhee might need to be
particularly persuasive to get him to move south.
In the meantime, he will be part of the pool from which Smith will choose his
teams for the crucial period coming up, when Rangers, champions and league
leaders, take on Kilmarnock at home on Boxing Day, then Hibs at Ibrox next
Saturday, and last, but certainly not least, Celtic at Parkhead on January 3.
Smith will be without Ally McCoist and Stuart McCall for the first of those
games, but Alex Cleland and Gary Bollan could be fit to take part. Definitely
back in action will be Paul Gascoigne and Oleg Salenko, both free to play again
after suspension.
Kilmarnock manager Alex Totten had hoped to use two players in reserve games
this week to prepare them for a return against Rangers, but the weather forced
both matches off and he now has to consider whether Ray Montgomerie and Tom
Black should go straight into the side. Montgomerie has been out for 12 weeks
after breaking his nose while Black has missed the last two games after
suffering from tonsillitis.
The manager points out that his team, which has been in good form at home, can
collect some reward from their away match. The fact that Killie have scored
five goals more than they managed at this time last season explains why they
have recently climbed up from last place to fourth bottom spot.
For Totten and the three managers below him, Murdo MacLeod of Partick Thistle,
Alex McLeish of Motherwell, and John Lambie of Falkirk, the festive period
could be vital in their bids to outdo each other in the race to escape
relegation. Each has a tough set of fixtures to tackle.
Kilmarnock, for example, take on Rangers at Ibrox, then Aberdeen at home, and
Motherwell at Fir Park, every one a demanding task. Thistle will find it no
easier with their programme reading as follows: Hibs (h), Raith Rovers (a), and
Falkirk (h).
Nor will it be a comfortable time for bottom club Falkirk, who face up to
Aberdeen at Brockville on Tuesday, Motherwell at Fir Park, and then Thistle at
Firhill.
They will have a new man on their side, however, after manager John Lambie
yesterday signed an Englishman of many clubs, Andy Gray. The former Crystal
Palace, Aston Villa, QPR and Tottenham player negotiated his own transfer from
Spanish team Atletico Marbella.
Gray, 31, began at Crystal Palace before moving to Villa for #150,000. After 15
months in the Midlands he switched back to London when Queen's Park Rangers
paid #475,000 for him, but after that he returned to Palace for #500,000 before
Spurs bought him for #900,000.
Motherwell, the fourth member of the quartet near the bottom, must take on
Hearts at Tynecastle, then Falkirk at Brockville, and Kilmarnock at home, but
after their draw with Rangers on Tuesday they will tackle the job with a will.
They hope to have Dougie Arnott fit after a virus and will make a late decision
on Brian Martin, who has had a hamstring injury.
Celtic have no injury worries for their visit to Kirkcaldy to meet the
dangerous Raith Rovers, but the really good news for their fans is that Brian
O'Neil, the brilliant young defender who has not played for seven months
because of knee ligament damage, could return in a closed doors game against
Dumbarton, if conditions permit, today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
