<HEADLINE>The ghosts of birthdays past</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Marcella Evaristi</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749833</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Writer and playwright Marcella Evaristi, in a story      specially created for
Weekend Extra, presents
a seasonal remembrance of saints, separations,
and aquamarine eyes
CHRISTMAS comes but once a year, and once a year, my birthday disappears:
dissolves like a snowflake, melts like brandy butter down the side of the
seasonal pudding, dribbles away and down like the candles on that cake: ``Many
Happy Returns, Jesus. You are Zero Today.'' Where my cake should have been.
My birthday disappears on the twenty-fifth of December, imploding inside
itself, like a self-obliterating cracker, like a kamikaze space in the calendar
- I know one simile would have done, you probably got the idea at
``disappears'', but I'm waiting for someone, so to pass the time I'm spreading
this out, as the high days and holidays of my year are not.
Besides I am addressing this to myself, the ``you'' that is you is rhetorical,
I am addressing this to myself as I used to address birthday cards to myself,
and balance them in front of the competition on the mantelpiece. Being without
existence, like my birthday, you are not free to patronise my self-pity; so
listen, nobodies at my non-party, and consider. (You won't have to for long, he
is rarely late, not without phoning, and after all it is my . . . Christmas.)
This is the line I got as a kid from Sister Imelda - ``Deirdra, darling, you
are a very lucky little girl. Other children can look up which Saints Day
coincides with their own birthday. Find themselves attached to St Jude, for
hopeless cases maybe; or St Anthony who helps with lost things, and that's very
nice, very nice indeed, but nothing compared to your luck, for you are honoured
to share a birthday with the Baby Jesus Himself. All of God's children get a
visit from Santa, but you get an extra present, more precious than any bicycle
or doll, and that's a special blessing from He who invites the whole human race
to the holy celebration of his birth.''
So when I opened the Christmas day flap on my Advent calendar, I fully expected
to see my own incredibly blessed face beaming out at me. But it was always a
crib. I couldn't figure out how come if He shared my birthday, He never got any
older, whilst year on year I aged visibly, invisibly. And how could I compete
with someone who's already invited the entire population to His party?
``Dear Deirdra, Birthday Greetings! I will be able to attend, crossed-out, I am
very sorry I cannot attend, underlined, your party on the twenty-fifth. Love
and kisses, Alice.''
``Oh please come to my party, it's going to be great - Alice? - ah, please
pals! - I'm going to have musical chairs, and butterfly cakes and pin the tail
on the donkey and Mr Bonzo, a real live circus clown is going to do tricks.''
``Sounds fun, but round at the Son of God's we're getting to walk on the
Liffey, the Tizer's going to turn into wine, Dominic McLafferty is going to get
his squint fixed, and there's a Mr Chaplin booked for the cabaret.''
``Well, I hope when you look inside the party bags you'll find an Immaculate
Medal and plenary indulgence to suck on!'' Imelda must be the patron saint of
atheism.
Mummy did her best. One year she tried giving me a party the week before; we
all went to the panto we were booked to go to anyway, and all my birthday
presents were wrapped in Christmas paper with the sleighbells felt-tipped out.
But it was better than the year I got my party the week after.
In the days before recycling, I was the recipient of four boxes of bath cubes,
those chalky little blocks you never see now, distant festive relatives of the
Brillo Pad family they must be, the kind that scoured your bottom in the bath
if you sat on them.
I also got a hanky with the initial ``F'' embroidered on it - `` `F' for
`Deirdra','' I said. ``Thanks for the personalised present. Fatima. It's
dabulous.'' ``It's an `F' for Friendship handkerchief,'' said Fatima Maguire,
fibbing through her brace.
Given my mood I quite liked the rat-a-tat machine gun I got from Steven whose
Daddy was nice, English, nervous, and active in CND. The worst was a pale
green, luminous, 15-inch high statue of Our Lady, who up until then I always
believed was more inclined to favour pastel blue cloaks, white shifts, and
snake-entwined sandals. Must have been Our Lady of the Celtic. Had me roaring
and screaming, anyway, when its creepy jade glow pitched itself into my dreams
and Mummy had to come and take it away in the middle of the night, and after
that we reverted to . . . - I though that was him at the door there. But it was
just some carol singers. He's still not what you'd call late. Travelling on
Christmas Day is always a nightmare.
When I reached my teens I went from being sad to being mad about the situation.
I adapted carols for myself, and sang them as loud protest songs at midnight
mass. ``Come All Ye Fortgetful'' I bellowed, feeling betrayed by the faithful.
And twisting the Latin as my fate had twisted me, I decibelled to the tune of
Adeste Fidelis, ``At-test te yir fail-yirs -.'' Lord, how devastatingly
sardonic I thought my strained unheard revisions, which were still too subtle
to resist the deluge of sentimental Christmas bonhomie that swirled around me,
insultingly all-inclusive, and quite promiscuously unspecific.
Like all young girls I decided I had been born in the wrong place, to the wrong
parents, and, most importantly, at the wrong historical moment. BC - that was
the time I should have been conceived in. Among the ancient Egyptians I could
have reappropriated my birthday. On the twenty-fifth of whatever they called
December, the ancient Pharaohs could have decked my young pre-Christian body
with golden links ornate with rubies, rubbed heady unguents into my midnight
blue-black hair, and given me 15 of the dumps beside the pyramids. And capital
F-you, Fatima, as yet unborn. Stuff your hanky.
Once I waited till the family had sat down to Christmas lunch before my
entrance, dressed as Cleopatra. This was when I was still in my AD denial
phase. I'd used up to half a bottle of black eyeliner, and made this dinky
crown affair with a little snake curved above my fringe. It's amazing how
inventive one can be with a whole packet of fuse wire, (although later, after
the fairy lights had blown, I stayed silent as a Stoic, repressing my
Catholic-conditioned instinct to confess). It just shows how little notice you
take of me, I thought, shaking my fuse-wired head, whilst everybody searched.
It's getting dark now, I will light the candles and suppress all thoughts of
accidents, black ice, and the contingency of brakes.
``More cranberry sauce, Cleo?'' said Daddy, cosmically missing the point. Then
they all started to discuss Elizabeth Taylor's diamonds, Richard Burton's
boozing, his poor abandoned wife, Cybil, the ruined childhood of his daughter,
Kate, the racial characteristics of the Welsh compared to the Irish, National
Velvet, and the visit I might have to make to Dr Sweeney if I couldn't prise
out the costume jewel I had pasted to my belly button.
Eight o'clock. I won't have a second port. I don't want to be out of synch with
him, when he arrives. There's nothing worse than having some mini-disaster,
some deeply frustrating, but not fatal, contretemps completely cocking up your
day, then coming home to find your should-be confidante is so far gone ahead of
you, that your intended anecdote evaporates before you've raised your glass.
There is one thing going for us No-Birthday No-els - Now, that's reminded me of
yet another injury inflicted on my lot. The names. I got off quite lightly,
thank God, with ``Deirdra'', but pity the Hollys and the Rudolphs. Robin is
borderline and Natalie is OK, but I swear I know a Bethlehem. Jeez, I'd rather
be called July.      Or Sunburn.
My theory is that his mother, whilst consciously thinking she was calling her
beautiful wee Christmas baby something cute and apposite, was actually wreaking
her subconscious revenge for being in labour, screaming for oxygen, panting her
way through the Queen's speech, episiotimised like a turkey under poultry
shears, while her spouse, poised to be a proud father, raised endless glasses
in celebration of a Virgin Birth.
But maybe not. This waiting is making me nervous and more cynical-sounding than
I really feel. Perhaps it's the coffee.
The one thing going for us, as I was about to say, before I sidetracked myself,
my ghostly birthday party guests - I can see you all cavorting,
semi-transparent, with dusty paper hats and blowing on those tooters that,
crinkling, turn and curl upon themselves like paper scorpions - the solitary
advantage is that, if you're heading for a melancholic Christmas, the wallow is
satisfyingly squared. If you're feeling masochistic, you get a double de
profundis.
But it seems such a long time since I felt that way. I've been looking through
my photograph albums to pass the time. Strange expression that, ``to pass the
time'', as if alternatively, you could cross the street to avoid the time, or
dodge into an alleyway so time passed you, and left you where you were.
There's me and Steven on the march he invited me out to. I used to fancy him
like mad: my first kiss from him coincided with my New Statesman being
confiscated in class. He told me he was proud of me and that I reminded him of
Nathalie Wood. My twenty-first birthday party, Boxing Day, nineteen eighty one.
Also my engagement party. Alice's pretty face, a picture of appalled affection.
Daddy's making his speech there. ``I'd like you all to know it was Deirdra who
insisted on the two celebrations being on the one day. After all these bloody
years of griping at us! So be warned, Christopher.'' But there he is dancing,
his arms wide open, the alarm bells drowned out by the band.
The phone is ringing from the hall now. But to get there, I have to run through
a marriage-long catalogue of calls like this, however fast I am, no matter how
quickly my body moves. (If there's a hell after death, mine would include a
house where the chime of the doorbell and the sound of the telephone were
indistinguishable. Who's there? Who's not coming?)
At first, I am running to a pay-phone down a fusty corridor in a guest-house
called the Buena Vista in Tufnell Park, London.
The fact that the call is for me is a slightly grudging disappointment to some
of the other Vistans, who open their doors and peer theatrically round in my
direction, and although their faces are like stop-watches already clocking the
length of my conversation, they are not hostile. Most of them are theatricals,
in fact, and programmed to waiting for things. Three are currently playing
Wombles in a Christmas show, and in the evenings I can hear them singing round
the piano in the front room, which they have effortlessly appropriated.
``I went to a wonderful party . . . '' they stress, as if a Noel Coward song
could turn sweet sherry into whisky sours and effect a transformation scene
where the Womble world of Wimbledon Common quick-changed forever into Drury
Lane.
The Vistans do not have too long to wait. It
makes more sense for me to come back home to Ireland in a week or two, instead
of him arriving here, I made the digs so dreary sounding, so hilariously dire,
but of course it's hardly that just. He saw the swans at Bantry Bay at dusk, I
would have wept, I would. He's just half-finished a letter to me, quite
ridiculously long. Now he's running short of change. And sorry this last-minute
change of plan is painful, but there was work and working out to do, he
realised, but honestly our love's a feast that's moveable. So let's not get
ourselves too short-term sad, and all hung up on dates.
Kiss you all over, he said softly, hanging up. So Merry Birthday, I thought,
sipping on a Womble sherry. Happy Christmas Next.
And next I'm racing across our mortgaged kitchen floor five years ago, and it's
not the doorbell that's ringing. I know what's coming. Then I'm giving it -
``Yes.'' Briskly.
``Yes, but it's nine now. Fine. I know these things happen, but why wait till
nine, when you said you'd be back, to tell me 10.30, when you definitely will
be back, yes, but you must have known before now, before nine, I wouldn't mind
- I just don't see why.
``Listen, if this crisis has just happened this minute, how come you weren't on
your way home already? If you'd been on your way home already, you'd only have
been half an hour late, hardly late enough to even bother phoning to say, and
that way the crisis would have been forced, amazingly enough, to solve itself
without you.'' (I wonder who that was? I recognised his voice, but not the
harridan, not hers.) We eat at 10.45. The meal is hardly ruined, perfect
really, apart from a charred crust, but I removed that, sauced it over, as you
can do, up to a certain stage.
At 12 when I am technically my new age he opens the champagne, and sitting by
the fire I pose for the automatic camera which stands by the cards and the
candlesticks on the mantelpiece. He sets it up, a little light goes on and he
dashes to my side, his arm around me just in time, and then we smile. Flash,
and we're caught together. Perhaps we won't need a third party anymore, now we
have technology.
I reach the phone now, and simultaneously the buzzer sounds and I try to answer
everything, but the ghosts of all my ghost-birthdays populate the hall and
holding hands surround me in a ring.
There's Steven in the corner firing a starter's gun to start the singing -
``For she's a jolly good fellow, for she's a holly good fellow, for she's a
jolly dude fe-e-stive, and so pray all for us . . .''
So strange, without the volume fading on the chant it's quite enough to ask him
how he is. ``Greenpeace. One child, separated, trying. Me, I mean, not the
child. The child's fab.''
Fatima is big as a whale and grinning. ``Writer. Required to do a story about
guilt for a creative writing class at Queen's. Started with that hanky. Never
stopped. Been looking back ever since. Ducking morning sickness still. And due
today.'' ``Ah, a Christmas day baby, how divine.''
Alice is not as pale as the others. ``Overdose. July, 1976. Optimism too
painful.'' The reveller with the camera lowers it from his face. ``Overworking
still. Remarried from you. But you know that anyway because I keep in touch.
Odd times. That was me on the phone just now. Smile, gentles, smile.''
If you're telling me the truth, and you didn't start without me - for which I
would not have blamed you - could you then tell me, please, why you are
kneeling on the floor smiling at the umbrella stand? he asked me, when he
finally despaired of me opening the door, dropped his luggage and parcels and
fished out his own keys.
I can tell how cold his face is, but not because of the usual signs. He has
barometer eyes, and it's a very rare condition, though that's not the official
name. One in a million his doctor told him a long time ago. His eyes change
colour when he loses body heat. It's just me that calls him barometer eyes, and
of course no-one believes me, unless they meet him. If love is blind, then why
not colour-blind? they think.
It was snowing that first time I saw him and my heart sank. Heavens, was he not
beautiful, but thank God, there's salvation - would you look at the fakey
coloured contact lenses, almost neon beneath the black lashes? Naff flash
bastard, I'm as safe as igloos. Then he began to explain, and the melting
started.
``That's fascinating,'' I laughed. ``Do they turn pink when you're warm? I had
a wee statuette of a poodle like that my auntie brought back from Rimini or
somewhere.''
Shut up, sweet Jesus, shut up, Deirdra. Oh Fellow Birthday Boy, could you not
arrange an avalache for me? (And didn't he just.)
His normal eyes are blue, not light - but the blue when he's cold, becomes
stronger. Like dark aquamarine, but bright-bluer than that sounds, startling.
No, I haven't found the words yet. I live on the cusp of description when I
think of him, and when I look at him I always have to start again. Be tempting
the gods, to     say God's gift of found gold, frankinsence and more. Parcels
left till morning, no guessing . . . getting warm.
</TEXT>
