<HEADLINE>A grey day</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE and GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749834</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE Man attempts to bridge a 26-year gap and deliver King George VI Chase
success for his trainer Gordon Richards at Kempton on Boxing Day.
In the shadow of Desert Orchid, four-times winner of the prize, the new white
hope faces the most important race of his career so far in the first big test
of his Cheltenham Gold Cup credentials.
A triumph in the Tommy Whittle Chase at Haydock, where his athletic jumping
bore comparison with Desert Orchid, brought consolation for having to miss the
Hennessy Gold Cup.
But 10 of the fiercest rivals he has met will bid to ensure there is no One Man
show for new jockey Richard Dunwoody and no repeat for Richards of Titus Oates'
1969 victory.
Richards has his chaser in perfect shape for the task, the one question mark in
connections' minds being the likely state of the going at Kempton, where One
Man suffered a fall in February when the ground was heavy.
Four days before the big race owner John Hales can't wait to get the race over.
``I'm a bag of nerves,'' he said. ``I just hope the weather is kind to us. If
it's soft he should be okay but if it got heavy then we'd have to think about
whether to run.''
</TEXT>
