<TEXT>
DUTCH international winger Marc Overmars will not be facing Scotland in next
summer's European Championship finals in England. The Dutchman has been ruled
out by torn ligaments in his left knee.
The Ajax player was injured in a league match on Wednesday and the problem was
found to be worse than feared during an exploratory operation at Amsterdam's VU
hospital.
EVERTON have been told they must release Nigerian striker Daniel Amokachi for
next month's African Cup of Nations tournament.
The Merseyside club, startled to learn Amokachi could miss as many as 10 club
games, called in the FA after experiencing problems contacting Nigeria for
clarification of the situation. They established that FIFA rules stipulate
players must be released 14 days before the tournament, which begins in South
Africa on January 13.
Nigeria play their first match 24 hours later against Zaire in Durban so
Amokachi could miss the third and fourth rounds of the FA Cup as well as
important Premiership fixtures against Arsenal and Chelsea.
Wimbledon face a similar dilemma with Efan Ekoku, who is also in the Nigerian
squad. Leeds trio Tony Yeboah, Phil Masinga and Lucas Radebe also will be
involved, along with Nii Lamptey of Coventry.
PARTICK Thistle and Raith Rovers have each been fined #100 by the Scottish
League for fielding ineligible players in reserve matches. One of the players
was involved with both the clubs.
Partick included Billy McDonald and Paddy Atkinson, who was looking for a club,
without the required clearance. And Raith also included Atkinson when he did
not have the necessary clearance.
STRANRAER striker Billy Ferguson has joined Hong Kong club Happy Valley for a
small fee.
Ice hockey
FIFE Flyers jumped into seventh spot in the Premier Division with back-to-back
wins over fellow strugglers Slough Jets and Milton Keynes last weekend and now
player-coach Mark Morrison hopes to make it a treble when they meet league
anchormen Newcastle Warriors tonight.
In the first division, third-placed Dumfries Vikings face big-spending
Manchester Storm, who sit one place above them on the table, while Paisley
Pirates are minus net-minder Dave Rook, who is on a two-game ban, for their
weekend double-header with Swindon.
MILTON Keynes Kings have won the race to sign 30-year-old Canadian defenceman
Scott Young, who was released by Humberside at his own request last week.
Golf
MIKE Thomson (Torwoodlee) and Craig Watson (East Renfrewshire) will represent
Scotland in the Lake MacQuarrie Open in Australia next month. The duo,
respectively winner and runner-up in the 1995 Claremont Scottish Mid-Amateur
championship, will play at the Belmont International course in New South Wales
from January 26 to 28.
Scottish amateur champion Simon Mackenzie (West Linton) had hoped to attend,
but work committments prevented him making the trip Down Under.
Basketball
INVERNESS will stage the Home Countries junior men's championship next April 12
to 14. The event, the first British and Irish Federation championship to come
to the north, will take place at Inverness Sports Centre.
The SBA are still looking for a coach to take charge of the Scotland team. The
senior women's Home Countries event goes to Spelthorne, near London, while the
junior women travel to Ireland.
Boxing
THAILAND'S Samson Gym successfully defended his WBF junior bantamweight title
with a ninth-round technical knock-out of Thembinkosi Ntyinkala, of South
Africa, in Sakhon Nakhon.
NIGEL Benn's tragic world title fight with American Gerald McClellan won the
1995 battle of the sports television ratings. ITV, who screened seven of the
top-10 sports programmes this year, had 13.1m viewers tuning in to the WBC
super-middleweight contest in February. That was over a million viewers more
than watched the BBC-screened Grand National in April, which came in second.
Top 10: 1, The Big Fight - Live (Benn v McClellan), ITV (Feb 25) 13.1m; 2,
Grand National, BBC1 (April 8) 11.9m; 3, The Big Fight - Live (Bruno v Marin),
ITV (Feb 18) 10.1m; 4, The European Match (Arsenal v Real Zaragoza), ITV (May
10) 9.9m; 5, The Big Fight - Live (Hamed v Liendo), ITV (Mar 4) 9.4m; 6, Sport
Review of the Year, BBC1 (Dec 12) 9.0m; 7, The Match (Liverpool v Crystal
Palace), ITV (Feb 15) 8.9m; 8 (equal), The European Match (Sampdoria v
Arsenal), ITV (April 20) 8.7m; The Match (Crystal Palace v Liverpool), ITV (Mar
8) 8.7m; The FA Cup Final (Everton v Man Utd), BBC1 (May 20) 8.7m.
</TEXT>
