<HEADLINE>Relief at a homecoming, and       a spot of gratuitous wrecking</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>dispatch from the front the '45</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749837</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DRUMLANRIG, December 23 - The Jacobite army is back in Scotland, and still
marching rapidly northwards in an effort to rendezvous with reinforcements.
Three days ago, which was also Prince Charles Edward Stuart's birthday, the
clansmen held a wild celebration after they crossed the border at Longtown on
the River Esk. The river, in flood as a result of heavy rain, would have been
impassable for a conventional army. But several hundred Highlanders plunged in
and formed a human barrier against the torrent, allowing the rest of their
columns to pass over.
The scenes of joy then took place on the Scottish bank of the Esk. Bonfires
were lit, the pipers began to play and the soldiers danced Highland reels till
they were dry. One officer said: ``We have carried the standard of Glenfinnan
150 miles into a country full of foes, and now we have brought it back
unscathed, through the accumulated dangers of storm and war.''
The next day the Jacobites captured Dumfries, a strongly Presbyterian and
therefore hostile town which had already raised a company of volunteers to
fight them. In the event, there was no violence apart from the clansmen's
plundering. But Charles laid a tax of #2000 on the citizens and demanded 200
pairs               of shoes besides, since many of his troops         are
barefoot.
The Highlanders then marched up the valley of the Nith. They are tonight
bivouacked at Drumlanrig Castle, seat of the absent Duke of Queensberry. They
are wrecking it. While they drank up the wine and spirits from the cellar, they
slaughtered 40 sheep inside the house rather than in the cold outside. After
their meal, they laid straw in all the fine rooms, and entertained themselves
before going to sleep by defacing portraits with their swords, especially one
of King Billy.
It is obvious how glad they feel to be at home after their hardships in
England, which their chieftains never wanted to invade anyway. They can also
expect an improvement in their military situation. During their absence,
recruiting drives for Prince Charles have gone on in Perthshire and
Aberdeenshire, while a French force of 800 under Lord John Drummond has landed
at Montrose. The Jacobites may be able to boost their present strength of about
4000 men by another 2000. From the headwaters of the Nith, the prince intends
to cross to the valley of the Clyde and descend again into the Lowlands.
There is little immediate prospect of the Government's forces which followed
him from Derby continuing their pursuit. In the end the two sides fought only a
skirmish on English soil, but the Jacobites came off better.
Their general, Lord George Murray, conducted the rearguard, the regiments of
Glengarry and of Colonel Roy Stewart with the artillery and heavy equipment,
over the Cumbrian hills. Hindered by the local militia, they were in danger of
being caught up by units of cavalry sent ahead on the orders of the royal
commander, the Duke of Cumberland.
Murray had to put a stop to the harassment, and on December 18 he arranged an
ambush. From Clifton, near Penrith, he sent the baggage forward to join the
main Jacobite column. The Glengarry men scattered some nervous patrols of
militia, and ran down others at Lowther Hall nearby, the home of Lord Lowther,
Lord-Lieutenant of Cumberland. When prisoners reported that Cumberland was
approaching with a force of 4000, Murray sent to Prince Charles for
reinforcements to attack the English army before it could have time to deploy
properly.
This request was actually refused because the prince thought the rearguard had
only militia to confront. It says a lot about the state of Jacobite discipline
that two regiments, of Cluny Macphersons and Appin Stewarts, came back of their
own accord to help Murray, who was then able to arrange his ambush anyway.
They arrived an hour after sunset to find him under fire from 500 enemy
dragoons round the village of Clifton. In the gathering dusk, the fresh
Highland troops crept close under the cover of hedges and stone dikes. At the
shout of Claymore, they cut their way through the thickets, let off a volley
and fell on the English cavalrymen. More than 40 dragoons were killed or
wounded, and the rest forced back. In the darkness, the four Jacobite regiments
reformed and hurried on to Penrith. Despite his superiority in numbers,
Cumberland chose not to pursue them.
The next day, December 19, the Jacobites regained Carlisle, which they left on
the first stage of their invasion less than a month ago. Here Prince Charles
took a controversial decision to garrison the city while the rest of his army
marched on. Lord George Murray opposed him on the grounds that this would mean
a useless sacrifice of men. It would be better to blow up the castle and walls
of Carlisle, which were anyway in too poor a state of repair to be defended.
But the prince expects to return this way once he is reinforced. If his own
troops hold a strongpoint on the Border, it will be easier for him to enter
England again. He called for volunteers, and 400 came forward, including his
only English regiment, raised in Manchester under Colonel Francis Townley.
Cumberland has now laid siege to Carlisle. As he has called up heavy cannon,
which are being brought by sea to Whitehaven, the Jacobite garrison is unlikely
to hold out long. But for the time being, it has halted the pursuit of Prince
Charles.
n Another dispatch next week.
JIM Fowler, co-ordinator for Scotland and Ireland of the Pagan Federation which
has 5000 members
n ``At this time of year, pagans look forward the rebirth of the sun which we
celebrate on December 21/22 with a little ritual symbolising light coming into
darkness. Contrary to what some people think, the festivities don't include a
mass orgy. Officially we don't recognise Christmas Day but my partner's father
usually joins us then and we make a special meat meal for him and our two cats
who, unlike Charis and me, aren't vegetarian. Decorating a living tree is very
much in keeping with the pagan ethos of love and respect for nature.''
