<HEADLINE>Ticket hotline closed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749838</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE SFA yesterday pulled the plug on their Travel Club ticket hotline after
fielding thousands of calls from the Tartan Army.
A week ago the memberships of the SFA Travel Club stood at 5500 - ahead of
Sunday's Euro '96 draw, which matched Scotland with England, Holland, and
Switzerland.
Now officials are processing applications which will take the membership to
between 10,000 and 11,000.
``We are closing the hotline as we don't want to mislead fans who think by
joining the Travel Club now they will get tickets for Euro '96,'' said SFA
spokesman David Findlay.
``The response has been incredible and we will revert to written applications,
but fans should realise they won't necessarily get European Championship
tickets.''
If Scotland receive more than the 7000 tickets guaranteed for each visiting
nation, they will go to Travel Club members who have had their applications
date and time-stamped this week.
Meanwhile, Scotland manager Craig Brown's preparations for Euro '96 will not
stop over Christmas. He will take in a game in England today and the
Leeds-Manchester United match tomorrow, as well as another fixture on Boxing
Day.
</TEXT>
