<HEADLINE>Early cries of `Humbug!'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Hewitson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>scotching the myths</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749839</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MYTHS: Master Acheson, you are one of a number of traders in the burgh who have
already declared they will pay no heed to the king's command that Christmas Day
should be observed throughout the land this year as a holy day. The market, if
you don't mind me saying so, is going like a fair today. Will you be at your
stall as usual tomorrow?
ACHESON: Hold on a second boss, duty calls. Yes missus, goose eggs - fresh this
morning. Half a dozen. Sure thing. There ye go, love. Goat's cheese? Should be
in from Dunlop this afternoon. Aye you were saying - this nonsense about
shutting up shop for Christmas Day - crazy. Do you know that Christmas, or any
other holy day, doesn't rate a mention in the scriptures? Honest. Huv a swatch
yersel.
MYTHS: But King James is said to be of the opinion that Scotland is losing
track of the real meaning of Christmas, seeing it merely as a commercial
opportunity rather than an important religious celebration.
ACHESON: Two points worth making there, son. Hell, where's ma cheeses. Where
did that wee wumman disappear tae? Aye, two points. Firstly, the kirk decided
long since that Christmas was a beggarly festival and should be abolished along
wi' popery. Now the king is trying to help us back doon the road tae Rome and
basically, we'll no' wear it. It's a' politics.
MYTHS: But on the point of the commerciality of this time of year. If you don't
mind me saying so, it seems you're trying to get the best of both worlds . . .
having your Christmas cake and eating it. On one hand you want to make a
killing from the event while refusing to celebrate it in what the king sees as
an appropriate manner.
ACHESON: Finnan haddies, straight oot the smokehoose! If you don't mind me
saying so, son, that's crap. Look at last year. The king ordered Christmas
observance in Edinburgh and whit happens? I'll tell you, in fact, better, I'll
show you. Here's a clipping fae the evening paper. See, there you are, ``the
Great Kirk was not half filled and dogs played around the floor,'' and that
bampot Patrick Galloway denounced non-attenders saying that lameness, deafness,
and blindness should fall upon them. It's him that's lame-brained. Every
luckenbooth was open. The truth is the Scots want Christmas as a normal working
day.
MYTHS: Then can you predict what is likely to happen tomorrow in Ayr?
ACHESON: Well, like almost every burgh, at least here in the west, it'll be
``business as usual''. I don't know a stallholder who'll be away from their
stance. This past half-century it's been our busiest day of the year and there
is no chance of us backing away from our responsibilities to the public -
bananas missus, no, you'll huv to come back next century - aye, I wis saying,
you'll notice that King Jamie has refused a referendum on this 'cause he knows
fine well that his hin' end would be oot the windae, if it cam' to a vote.
MYTHS: So you'd be prepared to answer to his majesty's commissioners?
ACHESON: Let's put it this way, wee man. They'll need a helluva big dock to try
20,000 traders. But maybe they're thinking of hiring Murrayfield. It's as
simple as this - we've a living to earn whether it's selling goose eggs, wally
dugs, black puddings, or lottery tickets. Actually I'd like to see Christmas
expand. It may sound a bittie radical but we could start our promotions a full
week before Christmas, couldn't we? Anyway, there's a queue building up here.
You'll have to forgive me. A merry Christmas to you.
Jim Hewitson reveals that the Christmas break was not always
universally acclaimed
</TEXT>
