<HEADLINE>Forced to stay at the inn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749840</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Christmas traditionally is a time for home and family and to be without a place
to rest your head is particularly cruel. Kirsty Scott meets a family for whom
temporary accommodation is gradually becoming a way of life
JACK'S not scared of strangers. Not when they come into the house that he
thinks is home and sit themselves down in the bare lounge under the limp
strands of Christmas bunting. He's up at your knee instantly, patting,
proferring toys, strangely calm with unknown company.
It's not surprising that new faces hold such little allure; he's seen maybe a
dozen come and go during the past year, strangers moving in then moving out. At
the moment it's Danny and Claire and their five children, and Danny smiles
easily and is willing to play; but in a couple of months it might be someone
else, someone a little less friendly.
Across the room, Sherry and Dave watch their 15-month-old son with anxious,
eyes, calming restless hands with a succession of cigarettes. They know this
halfway hostel will be home for another 14 to 18 months and they've been
homeless for a year and a half already. Three whole years in limbo. A life on
hold for a home of their own.
They're both 22; Dave, thin and gentle with a deep stretch of lines across his
frequently furrowed brow. Sherry is gray-pale with deep dark smudges under each
eye and shoulders weighted low with worry. She's just been diagnosed with a
heart murmur, caused, she says, by the stress of their situation and she's been
on medication for as long as she can remember. Throughout the interview they
both perch on the edges of a chair, never settling back, never relaxing.
This was not how they envisaged their life together when they met in the April
of 1993. Dave was in his late teens and had moved down to Devon to look for
work, booking himself into the bed and breakfast run by Sherry's mum.
They moved back to Scotland the following December when Sherry was pregnant
with Jack and she gave birth to him in September while they were staying with
Dave's mum in East Kilbride.
They had first put their names down for a house when they moved up in December
1993, but by January of 1995, life was becoming a little too crowded and they
moved into the homeless unit in Greenhills.
Shortly afterwards, Sherry was hit by a bad attack of post-natal depression
and, unable to cope, took the family down to Devon to stay with her mum. When
they returned some four months later, they assumed they would still be in the
same situation for getting a house, but say they were informed that because
they had been away for so long, they were almost back to square one in their
search for a home and were facing a wait of between 14 months and 18 months.
The policy had apparently been introduced in 1991 and neither Sherry nor Dave
were aware            of it.
``We went from 88 on the list to 219 and now we're at 131,'' says Sherry. ``It
was devastating, just devastating, it just felt as though you were falling
apart, the thought that we were going to have to stay here for another 14
months or so, the thought that Jack will be brought up here. He's never had a
stable home since he's been born. It's unhealthy. He's in the same room as us,
he should have his own room. He's going to be totally clingy towards us. He's
not going to be independent enough. It's more distressing for the kids.
Different people all the time. They get used to someone then they go and
someone else moves in.''
From the outside the homeless unit is only distinguishable from the other
buildings in the quiet cul-de-sac by the extra layer of peeling paint around
the door and the total absence of anything that might mark it as a real home.
No name on the door, no doorbell, no well-chosen curtains at the window, no
tended garden.
Inside, the communal lounge has the stagnant air of a waiting room, sparse with
its sofa, two chairs, and a cardboard box of toys in the corner. There's
muffled noise everywhere, the wail of a child, a faint-mumbled conversation in
another room, dunts and bumps on floors and ceilings.
Dave is apologetic about the thin strings of glossy paper hanging from the
sitting room ceiling and the plastic Santa face stuck to the wall. ``You've got
to do something for Christmas, don't you, got to make a bit of an effort,'' he
says when he catches you looking at it.
But deep down he's quite glad that Jack is probably too young to pick up on the
idea of Christmas Day. ``We'll be at my Mum's on the day but in the back of
your mind is the thought that it's not your house and you can't really
celebrate. You've got to be back in the unit at a certain time, before 11pm or
12am. If you stay out overnight, you've got to tell them you won't be back that
night.
``In a way I'm glad Jack's not really old enough to know about Christmas. I
wouldn't like him to remember this. I don't think kids should be brought up in
this situation.''
Two of Danny and Claire's offspring have been drawn to the interview in the
lounge; a tiny child in a green romper suit, nappy hanging low out of the gap
at the back; and Robin, a sturdy child of five or six. His wellies have the
face of a frog raised on the front of each foot and he's demanding to know
where Stephen is. ``Where is he? Is Stephen here?''
Like Jack, he doesn't appear even remotely curious about these new incomers to
the house. ``Stephen was one of the kids who used to live here,'' says Danny.
``It's difficult for the kids to get used to. Jack will probably be the same
when we go. He'll want to know where Robin is. They don't understand where
they've gone''.
Jack hasn't settled, wandering from one person to the next, trying to elicit a
game or a reaction from them in turn. Sherry worries that he's already
developing hang-ups nurtured by the general uncertainty of his life and his
parents' deep sense of unease.
``He has tantrums a lot. If you tell him off he will sit there and scream at
you. Now he's starting to change. We can see it in him. He's not got any
routine whatsoever. He's in the room with us, we're lucky if he goes to sleep
at 11pm. I think he does have a lot of stress.''
She takes us up to the one room they can call their own. There's a smallish bed
for the three of them and some furniture for their belongings. A couple of
Christmas cards have been stuck on top of the wardrobe, but there's no sign of
the familiar clutter that collects around families. ``It's so difficult,'' she
says. ``Each day, we get up and that's it really, you feel so down all the
time. We feel as though we've just been forgotten. Stuck away in a homeless
unit and that's us.''
They may feel isolated, but they're not alone. Over the past years the use of
temporary accommodation has more than doubled in Scotland, from 2123 households
in 1990 to about 5000 in 1995. The homeless charity Shelter which is conducting
research into the issue say there is well over a million bed nights spent in
temporary accommodation in Scotland in any given year.
``The temporary accommodation use mirrors the increase in homelessness,'' said
Gavin Corbett, Shelter research officer. ``At the same time as homelessness has
increased there are more and more council houses sold.''
Corbett said he can understand why those in temporary accommodation feel, like
Dave and Sherry, that they are a forgotten breed.
``We would like to see local authorities strive where possible to avoid the use
of temporary accommodation by providing homeless people with secure
accommodation as quickly as possible. But if they have to use it to avoid
certain types, like bed and breakfast, and to keep in mind the ongoing needs of
people, not simply to allocate temporary accommodation and then leave them for
a year. To frequently review it and to talk to people rather than just
depositing them in temporary accommodation. Not all authorities are very good
at that yet.''
Back at Greenhills, Sherry is pointing out the grimy upstairs bathroom that
serves all 10 of them with a separate toilet downstairs. There's also one more
room in the house they can't use. It's known as the emergency room and it needs
to be empty for those last-minute, sheer desperation cases. It's a house, but
it's not a home and Dave, in particular, seems to find it well nigh impossible
to settle here. He doesn't sit still for longer than a few minutes at a time.
``I don't like to stay here during the day,'' he says, rising yet again from
his perch on the edge of the chair, one eye on Jack. ``So we go out, out for a
walk to get away. But it makes it harder this time of year when you walk by
everyone else's houses and they've got the decorations out and the presents out
and the tree.
``And you're still in here with other people you hardly know and the stress is
always in the background. There's no privacy whatsoever. I'm not really in that
much, I don't like staying in. It gets even more depressing. We'll go out for
walks just to take the edge off the boredom.
``I don't think you can bring a family up like this. You can't concentrate on
trying to plan for the future, you don't know what's going to happen then. It's
not a normal life and we haven't got anything to look forwad to at the moment.''
He stops himself suddenly, apparently embarrassed as this outpouring of
desperation. ``It's an alright place here, but it's not our home.'' He pauses
again and curls his fingers around Jack's head. At his side Sherry lights
another cigarette and drops her head a little lower. ``I'm glad we're not out
on the street,'' he says finally. ``But what we have here it's just an
existence, it's not a life.''
A spokeswoman for East Kilbride District Council confirmed that they operate a
policy where those on the council house waiting list can only move up to 15
miles away from the town. Any further and they will be taken off the list. The
spokeswoman said that Sherry and Dave had been informed of the policy, and that
after the returned from Devon, the council had only taken five months off the
time they had waited for a house. ``That appears to be very reasonable, because
they did move about 500 miles away and it was a permanent move as such.''
</TEXT>
