<HEADLINE>Irish want an early solution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749841</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REPUBLIC of Ireland officials may be ready to appoint a successor to Jack
Charlton as early as January 15.
Charlton resigned as manager on Wednesday and already a host of names have been
suggested as potential inheritors of his throne.
Mick McCarthy of Millwall and Wimbledon's Joe Kinnear are the front-runners,
but others in the frame include former Denmark and Turkey manager Sepp Piontek,
ex-England supremo Bobby Robson, Kenny Dalglish, Brian Kidd, Ron Atkinson,
Kevin Moran, and Liam Brady.
FAI chief executive Sean Connolly confirmed: ``The job will not be advertised.
Our executive meeting will take place on January 2 and set out the terms of
reference for the man we want. Essentially it will be a head-hunting
operation.''
It is expected that two senior FAI officers will start the interviews early in
the New Year and then report back to a full FAI council meeting on January 15,
which would be a rubber-stamp approval.
``We would very much like to have the new manager in place by January 23, when
our World Cup fixtures meeting takes place in Liechtenstein,'' explained
Connolly.
The Republic have what appears to be a relatively comfortable qualification
path to the 1998 finals in France after being drawn against Romania, Iceland,
Lithuania, Macedonia, and Liechtenstein last week.
The lure of a salary of #150,000, plus the remarkable sponsorship bonuses
available, means the Irish are in a position to talk to all the top managers.
McCarthy remains the favourite, but he said: ``I haven't spoken to anyone from
the FAI and I am wary of that tag. We all know what can happen to favourites.
``All I would say is that I would do my best if I got the job. Like any other
manager, I would look at the players available and make decisions on that.
``But to be honest, my first priority at the moment has to be Millwall. We have
gone from top of the first division table to tenth in five games. Speculation
about the Irish job is taking attention away from that.''
</TEXT>
