<HEADLINE>Murray leaping up ladder of success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749842</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OPPORTUNITY knocked for Scott Murray two years ago, when he was scheduled to
represent Scotland at different sports on the same weekend.
The 19-year-old Edinburgh Academical, who has capped a story-book season with
his selection to play for Scotland A against the Italians a fortnight today,
had been chosen to play in an under-17 basketball tournament for Scotland. That
same weekend he was in the Scotland under-18 rugby team and it was time to make
a tough decision.
``I hadn't realised that the two things clashed, but when the basketball
coaches found out, they wanted me to play for them on the Friday night and on
the Sunday, and fit the rugby in between,'' said Murray.
``I couldn't do both and so I decided to go with the rugby. It seems I made the
right choice.''
Murray has played the game for just three years, but his rise through the ranks
has been meteoric. Standing 6ft 7in, but tipping the scales at just 15!s-stone,
Murray has been one of the finds of the season. He has represented Scotland at
under-18, under-19 and under-21 levels, and played, too, for the senior
Edinburgh district side.
With Scotland under-19 at the Junior World Cup in Bucharest last spring, it was
immediately apparent that Murray possessed a special talent on the touchline.
Bringing the basketball player's athleticism and ball-sense to touchline duty,
the youngster has been the most outstanding lineout jumper in Scotland this
season.
He has played front-line rugby for only two-and-a-half seasons, first with
Preston Lodge and then under the tutelage of David Sole and Jeremy Richardson
at Edinburgh Academicals, where he is midway through his second season.
Murray, who is currently taking highers at college and hopes to go to
university to start a sports science degree next year, is without doubt a star
in the making but is far from the finished product.
As a lineout leaper he is out of the top drawer, but elsewhere he is still
learning his trade and SRU director of rugby Jim Telfer, very much an admirer,
is keen that he be given space to mature in his own time.
``Scott is an exceptionally talented rugby player, but I would appeal to the
media to hold back a bit,'' said Telfer. ``He is very young and very light and
still learning the chores of a lock about the park.
``We don't bring a 19-year-old into the A side lightly, but he has showed that
he can handle each step up so far, and not only handle it, but be outstanding.
He must, though, be allowed to develop without intrusive attention.''
The taciturn Murray said yesterday: ``I've come a long way in a very short
space of time and I have to admit that I didn't expect it to come so soon. Jim
Telfer phoned me to tell me I had been picked on Wednesday night and the letter
came the next day.
``I'll approach the game with the same kind of attitude that has got me through
this far and, hopefully, it will be OK.''
Murray, who is now involved in an intensive weights programme and has put on a
stone in the past year, is already the subject of approaches from rival clubs
now that Edinburgh Academicals have been relegated to the second division.
However, he wants to stay at Raeburn Place next season. ``I have benefited from
the help given to me by David and Jeremy and I would like to stay at Accies.
Hopefully, that's the way that it will work out.''
q.LAST night's inter-district championship match between Edinburgh and North
and Midlands, which was originally scheduled for Meggetland, with Murrayfield
on weather stand-by, has been postponed and a new date will be arranged.
Meggetland was unplayable, as were the back pitches at Murrayfield. The SRU say
is was not possible to bring the main pitch, with its undersoil heating, into
play because it had been used for the Schools international between Scotland
and France earlier in the day.
</TEXT>
