<HEADLINE>A land between two countries</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOREEN TAYLOR-WILKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749843</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE BORDERS BOOK
Edited by Donald Omand
Berlinn, #16.99
THE title says it all. This is a wide-ranging exposition of the Borders of
Scotland, ranging from its geology and very early history to such niceties of
modern times as rugby, the distinctive dialect, or dialects, and the King's Own
Scottish Borderers.
That breadth of interest is both the book's strength and its weakness. For in
his obvious desire to look at many aspects of the Borders, the editor, Donald
Omand (head of the Department of Adult Education at Aberdeen University), seems
unable to decide whether the Borders Book should be an academic work, or an
account of this unique area and its people, written from a human point of view,
with the distinctive ring of the Border voice coming through.
The early chapters are authoritative, comprehensive treatises on archaeology,
landscapes, prehistory, etc, using the correct academic terms and descriptions
as befits their subject matter. But they make heavy reading.
Not until chapter six, written by the self-taught historian and former
fencing-contractor Walter Elliot, does the book come alive. The Borderers have
a long tradition of story-telling and balladry - think of Hogg and Scott and
many more who wrote down and perpetuated the ancient oral tradition - and the
words of Elliot and other Border contributors, such as Judy Steel and Brigadier
Frank Coutts, are fine reminders of the art.
Elliot covers the period between early medieval times and the Union of
Parliaments in three vivid chapters which still have great relevance to the
area today. Among his most interesting revelations is the story of the Selkirk
Papers, some of which had lain in the attic of Selkirk's Commercial Bank since
the sixteenth century until the Second World War. Then, an edict that
``wastepaper'' must be burnt to reduce the danger of wartime fire sent a
zealous bank manager to clear them out.
Fortunately, next door were the Mason brothers, bakers, who persuaded the
odd-job man who was delegated to burn the old records, to let them have a quick
look. Despite the bank manager, the brothers determined to save what they could
and, in fact, managed to rescue around a fifth of these wonderful documents
from the flames. On his death, Walter Mason willed the papers to Walter Elliot
and, after years of study, a trust set up by Elliot has published some of these
remarkable archives as The Selkirk Protocol Books 1511-1547.
Judy Steel, with a claim to Border history in that she and her husband, David,
restored the old Border peel, Aikwood Tower, contributes chapters on Borders
traditions in general and the annual common riding festivals in particular,
still local events rather than anything staged for the tourist trade. She also
writes on Border folklore and James Hogg.
The final chapter, contributed by Borders archivist Ros Brown on the Border
Regional Archive and Local History Centre, indicates that there are many more
sources still to be tapped in addition to that rich oral inheritance.
</TEXT>
