<HEADLINE>Seeing red puts Ernie in fast lane</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749844</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS a blind man, Ernie Plimer holds his own in a personal world of dark
confusion; blind drunk his life was black chaos. He was, he admits, a liability
to himself, his family, and his employers. Sober these past 32 years, Ernie
concedes at the age of 78 that Alcoholics Anonymous, then running, made life
worth living again. To prove it, he will make a personal statement, lining up
as the oldest competitor in Edinburgh's New Year athletics meeting.
When the hospitality flows with traditional profusion at the Meadowbank meeting
a week today and tomorrow, Ernie will touch not a drop. In 1974, when he made
his running debut, the meeting was sponsored by a brewery - the first time
drink had ever done him a favour.
Since then Ernie has missed only two of the annual footracing festivals. Last
year a poisoned mouth - dentistry gone wrong - kept him out; and in 1987 he
went to the World Veteran championships in Australia where he reached the final
of the over-70 100 and 200 metres, finishing fifth and sixth respectively.
``More than 30 people ran each event,'' he says.
Ernie has won the Scottish 70-plus title at both 100 and 200m for the past four
years, and the British titles from 1992-'94. When he went to defend his UK
crowns this year the train broke down, and he was abandoned at Carlisle for
three hours, missing the race. He is eagerly anticipating the world event in
Britain four years from now: ``provided my eyes hold out that long.''
Red all-weather tracks are all he can run on now. ``I used to run in the
Queen's Park, but kept bumping into things, and until six years ago I did the
highland games, but I can't make out white lines against the green, any more,''
he says.
Even technology could not alleviate an affliction which makes even dim light
blindingly bright. He had 26 fittings for contact lenses during the '60s, in
the days when they were made of glass. Now lenses are of plastic, to which he
is allergic.
``I can see only a couple of metres - enough to make out the white lines
against the red,'' he says. ``Running in lanes, knowing there is nobody there
to bump into, gives me the confidence to run.
``Nervous? Not at all. On the track I am free - the only place I am at ease. I
feel tense just crossing the road, or alone at the bus stop, when I don't know
what number of bus is coming. There is a lot more tension there. I refuse to
carry a white stick. It just advertises your disability and makes you
vulnerable to thugs.
``I get off the bus and the glare off the pavement is unbearable. I like dull
days, and when I get on to the track, the stand gives a bit of shade from the
light.''
Ernie became blind when put in an orphanage, aged five, during the Depression.
``We lived in Alloa, and my mother took ill. My father could not give up his
job, and my sister and I were sent to an orphanage in Aberlour. By the time I
could go home a year later, malnutrition had ruined my sight.
``From the age of six to 12, I had no schooling at all. It would never be
allowed to happen now. I was in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary, and passed the time
playing hymns on a wee trumpet. A man training for the ministry was in for an
operation which went wrong, and he went stone blind.
``Later he qualified as a minister, found out where I lived, and told me how my
hymns had helped him through a difficult time. It was he who got me admitted to
the school for the blind. I was educated there till I was 18.''
Ernie worked as a rep, selling articles made in the asylum. But drink
eventually became his master. ``I was on the booze for 25 years, and was a
complete wreck by the time I was in my forties - in the pub all the time.
Eventually I couldn't concentrate at all, got found out, and lost my job.
``The guys at the AA showed me the way - I clung to every word. I could not
face that again. I would go swimming, then walking and climbing, with a camera.
It was 10 years before I started running - thanks to a chance remark from a guy
at the pool who said he was training for the New Year meeting.
``As a teenager, the old ped who trained Edinburgh Police wanted to prepare me
for the big sprint, because I showed some ability. I never did go, but I once
stayed sober for a week and won five bob (25 pence) in a long jump contest. I
immediately drank the winnings. But that one chance remark got me thinking.
``I was 59 when I started running. The strength had come back to my legs, and I
felt clean again, like it was a new beginning. You lose your own identity,
drinking, and when I started running it was using an assumed name, Ernie
James.''
The nom de guerre was in the best pro tradition, but it suited him for another
reason. ``I was disgusted with myself, ashamed of my name, of letting the
family down.''
His wife and daughters stuck by him, but he admits people would cross the
street to get out of his way. ``But running gave me a new start, and respect.''
He has twice won the veteran sprint, and has entered that as well as the big
sprint next weekend. Wherever he finishes, Ernie will be a winner. ``I just aim
to do my best, and not make a fool of myself. The benefits are for my whole
body, and my outlook psychologically. I would be plunged into depression
without running in my life.''
</TEXT>
