<TEXT>
The Given Note, Liam O'Flynn (Tara)
q The uilleann pipes-meister returns, pumping blood through the Irish, Scots,
and Galician traditions and presiding over the gloriously rambunctious, the
frankly romantic, and the elegiac alike. Andy Irvine and Paul Brady, chirpy and
wan respectively, contribute a song each; Sean Keane plays superb earthy
fiddle; Shaun Davey provides arrangements both warm and spiky; and Seamus
Heaney contributes the title and an enthusiastic sleeve note which the contents
live up to with ease.
Lunar Spell, Andrea Vicari (Thirty-Three)
q Vicari's well-received debut, Suburban Gorillas, featured her writing for an
11-piece. A year on, this follow-up finds her still-developing piano talents at
the heart of a quintet including the robustly creative saxophonist Mornington
Lockett. The reward principle seems to be at work for both musicians and
listeners - get through the initial tense intricacies and the overdrawn title
track, and there's some celebratory Africana, a latin romp, and a sturdy blues
to enjoy at the end.
</TEXT>
