<HEADLINE>Lullaby  of laughs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KENNETH WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749846</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BULLETS OVER BROADWAY (rental, cert 15).
n COMING from any other director but Woody Allen, his 1982 grouchfest Stardust
Memories could have been a great career move towards early retirement; never
has any popular artist dissed his audience as thoroughly as Allen's alter-ego
Sandy Bates, with his mean moans about the fans who ``loved all your movies -
especially the early, funny ones''.
Fortunately for us all, however, Woody and the Muse of Comedy have gradually
come to kiss and make up, and Bullets Over Broadway finds their rapprochement
almost complete. They've moved back in together, but - if the third act is any
guide - he still reserves the right to sleep with her sister Tragedy at the
weekends.
For its first hour, Bullets Over Broadway is the best Woody Allen for 20 years.
With the amiably hangdog John Cusack in the obvious Allen role as a deep and
meaningful young 1920s playwright having trouble getting his latest play put
on, saved eventually by a gangster angel at the cost of a big role for his
talentless Brooklyn moll (Jennifer Tilly), it flies through 60 minutes of
breezy backstage comedy at a hell of a lick.
Driven by superb performances from Dianne Wiest as a Great Actress and Chazz
Palminteri as Tilly's mob minder, the dialogue sings like a stool pigeon. The
grim contrasts between the razzmatazz of the Great White Way and the offhand
brutality of Palminteri and his fellow goons stays just the right side of
repulsion, while the central-plot device of having Palminteri turn out to be a
better writer than Cusack works brilliantly.
Two-thirds through, however, there's an awkward shift in tone: the laughs
disappear and it all winds up on a hasty romantic resolution justified by
nothing that's happened before. Flawed as it is, however, this is a damn fine
little lullaby of old Broadway.
ED WOOD (rental, cert 15).
n THE great thing about Edward D Wood Jr that Tim Burton's sweetly strange
biopic recognises is that he wasn't (just) a talentless bum with access to a
movie camera; he was the McGonagall of cinema, utterly sincere in his art and
convinced of his genius despite all public and critical evidence to the
contrary.
That's what gives Ed Wood its tenderly humorous tragi-comic tone. Burton, the
auteur-angel of oddball sympathy from Pee-Wee's Big Adventure to The Nightmare
Before Christmas, sees the crippled artist behind Z-grade movies like Glen or
Glenda and Plan 9 from Outer Space and respects his dreams.
Shot in shimmering black and white, Ed Wood concentrates on the nearest Wood
came to having any golden years - 1954-56, when he befriended Bela Lugosi.
Johnny Depp plays the role of his life as Wood, radiating optimism and charm in
sharp suits or angora drag as he hustles money for his loser movies, the
recreation of whose filming is terribly funny and terribly sad. But it's Martin
Landau who steals the movie with a heartrending performance as the half-mad
Lugosi, and the film loses a lot of steam after Lugosi dies.
KENNETH WRIGHT
</TEXT>
