<HEADLINE>Magic you can believe in</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joe Donnelly</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Frontiers</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749847</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Joe Donnelly speaks to scientists who not only believe in Santa, but have
proved exactly how he delivers presents to millions of children around the
globe in just one night
IT CAN fly in any weather, circle the globe overnight, carry millions of pounds
of cargo, and make silent, rooftop landings with pinpoint accuracy. Is it a
stealth bomber? Maybe even Space Station Alpha? No, it's Santa's sleigh, one of
the engineering wonders of the modern world. And a US scientist thinks he's got
it sussed.
Dr Larry Silverberg at North Carolina University speaks our language, and he
puts his mind to some problems that other scientists don't have the imaginative
capacity for. There are few doctorates or major grants in working out the
mechanics of Santa's sledge.
That does not bother Silverberg. He's a believer, and he tells us: ``Santa
clearly is ahead of the game when it comes to applying advanced scientific
theories to his sleigh's design. Children shouldn't believe others who say he
isn't real because there's no way he could deliver toys all over the world in
one night. There is a way, and it's based on plausible science.''
As an academic exercise in fun, and as an aid to beleaguered parents who are
asked many an awkward question at this time of year, Silverberg, who's a
professor of mechanical and aerospace engineering and a member of Nasa's Mars
Mission Research Centre, set his students to work.
They came up with answers to the questions most often asked about Santa's
operation.
How can Santa's sleig
How can one sleigh carry all those presents? It doesn't have to. Thanks to
state-of-the-art nano-technology, which was developed in 1988, Santa can now
use a hierarchical distributed mobile manufacturing system to make the gifts on
site in each child's home. Silicon-chip-based machines, so tiny they can fit on
the head of a pin, are loaded with a code containing the child's toy list.
Using large-scale algorithms similar to those that make DNA work, the machines
literally grow the toys, atom by atom, from bits of snow and soot that Santa
collects along his route.
How can Santa's reindeer fly? It's in their genes. After centuries of selective
breeding and (more recently) bio-engineering, the volumetric displacement of
their lungs is of such a proportion that when filled with an appropriate
mixture of helium, oxygen, and nitrogen, they become buoyant.
What is Santa's sleigh made of? Since it's never been analysed in a laboratory,
we can't be sure. But it is likely to be made of a Kevlar-like composite fibre
encapsulated in an epoxy resin matrix. This would make it very strong,
lightweight, durable, and cold-resistant.
Silverberg's team missed out a couple of other important questions which we at
Frontiers have investigated with equal vigour. What makes Rudolph's nose shine
so? Professor Ken Killham of Aberdeen University recently found the answer in
the ``lux gene'' which enables some organisms to glow in the dark. These genes
can be grafted into other organisms, and this has obviously been the case with
the reindeer.
And as far as getting down the chimney is concerned, that's an easy one.
Einstein's theory also allows for the expansion of matter at acceleration
nearing the speed of light. Under the aforementioned conditions, while Santa is
working in a stasis period, the conditions enable his own atoms to contract
just enough.
And why does he live in the North Pole? Because he's one cool dude, of course!
And he needs the peace and quiet.
</TEXT>
