<HEADLINE>Bradford injunction on Megson move</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749848</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GARY Megson was last night halted from taking over as manager of Norwich after
former club Bradford were granted an injunction against the Norfolk outfit.
Megson walked out on the second-division club on Thursday to return to Carrow
Road, where he had been caretaker manager following John Deehan's resignation
last season.
But Bradford chairman Geoffrey Richmond accused Norwich counterpart Robert
Chase of making an illegal approach to 36-year-old Megson, after he had sent a
fax to the Canaries saying they could speak to Chris Kamara's assistant only if
they agreed to pay #100,000 in compensation.
The two chairmen became embroiled in a war of words during the day, with
Richmond accusing Chase of ``a flagrant breach'' of Football League regulations
and Chase responding by promising a vigorous defence.
But last night Richmond and his club were granted a High Court restraining
order for the next seven days by a judge in chambers.
The order means Megson is legally prevented from taking up his post for
Norwich's Christmas fixtures at Portsmouth today and at home to Southend on
Boxing Day.
q ANDY Linighan steps out of the Arsenal shadows to take on British football's
most expensive player Stan Collymore at Anfield today, with Highbury manager
Bruce Rioch telling him: ``This is the chance you've been waiting for.''
The 33-year-old Geordie was a Wembley hero for the Gunners in 1993, scoring the
last-gasp FA Cup winner against Sheffield Wednesday. But his career has gone
into reverse, and under new manager Rioch he has made just one fleeting
appearance as a substitute.
Now, with Tony Adams and Steve Bould both suspended, Rioch is forced to change
his defence for the first time this season, with Linighan drafted in to partner
Martin Keown in the centre.
The Liverpool line-up is likely to be the one which beat Manchester United on
Sunday, with Rob Jones again at left back in the absence of Phil Babb.
While Liverpool and Arsenal both need a win to lift themselves back into the
championship race, Newcastle could find themselves 10 points clear of the pack
if they can overcome Nottingham Forest at St James' Park, where will be a pitch
inspection this morning.
q SIMON Osborn yesterday completed his #1m move to Mark McGhee's Wolves - and
fired a parting shot at his old Queen's Park Rangers manager Ray Wilkins. The
23-year-old midfielder will make his Wolves debut away to another former club,
Reading, after falling out of favour with the Loftus Road manager.
IN ENGLAND
</TEXT>
