<HEADLINE>Officials hopeful of staying out in front</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAIN appears to be running neck and neck with frost in the race to become the
most disruptive influence to the National Hunt programme on Boxing Day.
The weather people have predicted a thick band of rain pushing south during the
weekend, followed by further cold nights as the country limbers up for a full
sporting programme on Tuesday.
``There has been some heavy rain up and down the country, but that has now died
out,'' commented a spokesman for the Met office. ``However, on the tail of the
rain which is moving south - reaching the south coast on or around Sunday -
there will be sleet and snow and colder weather.''
A further warning by the weather centre for snow on the hills in the north will
not cause Kempton's clerk of the course, Michael Webster, any sleepless nights,
but the threat of further rain is another matter.
``We have had two inches of rain in the last five days and further showers
forecast,'' said Webster. ``But the forecast is for colder, brighter, and drier
weather until Boxing Day and my only worry at the moment is the forecast heavy
frost for Christmas night.
``We will take the precaution of covering the take-offs and landings. At the
moment there is some good ground but a lot of soft.''
Ayr's Boxing Day fixture is in jeopardy due to an expected freeze. Course
manager Mark Kershaw said: ``The course is raceable at the moment but there is
a severe frost forecast for Saturday and Sunday night, and in view of that we
will hold a precautionary inspection at 11.30 on Sunday morning.''
Ian Renton, track official at Wincanton, is optimistic of racing taking place
at the Somerset track. ``I am confident and the prospects are very good,'' he
said. ``The going is good to soft, but the threat of severe frost has receded
with only a light frost forecast for Christmas night.''
Newton Abbot had water lying on top of heavy ground yesterday, but a spokesman
reported: ``We don't have to race until Tuesday and the forecast over the
weekend is for drier weather.''
Hereford, Market Rasen, Wetherby, and Wolverhampton report no problems and are
confident the weather will not beat their attempts to race.
And although Sedgefield has frost in the ground, clerk of the course John
Cleverly is hoping that predicted favourable weather for the Durham area
materialises over the weekend.
q TRAINERS David Nicholson and Gordon Richards have nominated horses for
sponsored charity bets on Boxing Day. Nicholson selects Shankar (Kempton 12.45)
and Richards's choice is One Man (Kempton 2.20).
</TEXT>
