<HEADLINE>Oldham plan to cash in</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PLAYER from Iceland and Oldham may seem unlikely bedfellows in the pioneering
post-Bosman era, but that combination could test the theory that domestic
transfers can operate as per normal, despite the EU ruling, writes Ian Paul.
The English League have instructed their lawyers to examine the full
implications as Oldham seem prepared to cash in on the European Court ruling by
signing out-of-contract Stoke midfielder Toddy Orlygsson for no fee.
The Latics could become the first club to benefit from the European Court of
Justice's declaration that the current transfer system contravenes European
Union law.
Oldham made a #100,000 bid for the 29-year-old Icelandic internationalist, with
Stoke demanding #400,000 following the midfielder's decision to reject a new
deal which would have kept him at the Victoria Ground.
Oldham opted to sign the player - who joined Stoke on a free transfer from
Nottingham Forest in August 1993 - and let an independent transfer tribunal set
the fee on January 9.
By then, though, UEFA are expected to have made a definitive announcement on
the Bosman case and Oldham are aware that it is possible Orlygsson's status as
a free agent could see the player arrive at Boundary Park for nothing.
Oldham manager Graeme Sharp said: ``It looks like there might be a precedent
set, but we will just have to wait and see what UEFA say.
``We have done everything right. Stoke put a valuation and we told them what we
wanted to pay.''
Football League spokeswoman Sheila Andrews said: ``We have not encouraged
Oldham to take this stance in any way because we cannot say where we stand on
the matter until we take legal advice.
``The tribunal on Orlygsson is due to meet on January 9 and by that time our
lawyers will have advised us on the legal implications of the Bosman case.
``Oldham will obviously put forward the Bosman ruling as part of their case,
but we cannot really comment on that until our lawyers have examined the ruling
in full.''
However, Stoke manager Lou Macari is confident that the Bosman ruling will not
save Oldham from having to pay a fee for Orlygsson.
Macari said: ``I don't know what everyone is getting so excited about. I expect
the tribunal to go ahead on January 9 and we will get a fee for Toddy.''
His club's chief executive, Jez Moxey agreed. He said: ``I've spoken to Graham
Kelly (FA chief executive) and David Dent (Football League secretary) and both
have asured me it's business as usual.
``Oldham have given every indication they are prepared to pay a fee and have
followed the rules which govern the tribunal procedure.
``They have already paid us #50,000, which is half their bid of #100,000,
although we are looking for substantially more than that.''
</TEXT>
