<HEADLINE>College starts with passes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749851</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKI-ING
THE newly unveiled Edinburgh's Telford College Developing Excellence (DEX)
programme, integrating education, career, and sports for athletes, has had
double cause for celebration.
In recent slalom, giant slalom, and Super G races in North America, four of the
five Scottish skiers on the pioneering course skied to personal best
world-ranking points scores, ahead of their early season targets.
The capital initiative offers a mix of coaching facilities and academic courses
from higher grades to many diverse qualifications.
The initial experiment with Finlay Mickel yielded favourable exam results and
allowed him time on the snow. Last week, Mickel, pursuing qualifications at
Telford, recorded one of the better British Super G results of the season.
Ski-ing is an acid test of the course's flexibility. The Scottish squad of 17
and 18-year-olds will face 190 days on snow this year - 160 at least abroad, a
schedule which even for the pre-university student would mean a choice between
missing a year's ski-ing to attain higher results, or skiing and trying to get
higher results at a college later.
With four sports involved - Ski-ing, rugby, football, and badminton, it is the
college's course tutors who are responsible for accessing the highest level of
cross training and fitness monitoring, while a management team take
responsibility for modules in lifestyle management, nutrition, psychological
preparation, and fitness.
Scottish ski coach John Clark has two main targets for the development of the
course. He would like to bring on younger, school-age skiers quicker through
the college - 16 and 17-year-olds - and wants to be able to build connections
with other colleges in Europe.
</TEXT>
