<HEADLINE>A master plan for  festivities</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG PRITCHETT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WILL you go for the ``Grand Master'' on Christmas Day, followed by a ``Russian
Defence''? Or will you stick to a more modest ``Minor Piece'', followed by a
nice ``Danish Gambit''? If you choose any of these, you no doubt visited Oban's
Boxtree Restaurant during last month's splendid Oban Congress.
The ``Grand Master'' is otherwise known as Scotch smoked salmon, served up with
creamed horseradish with ginger. The ``Russian Defence'' is a fine halibut
steak, with light creamy mustard sauce. The ``Minor Piece'', cheapest of the
``Openings'' on the Boxtree's menu, is unfussy cream of vegetable soup. The
``Danish Gambit'', a good Boxtree ``Middle Game'', is succulent pork steak,
with apple and almond sauce.
As you can see, the Boxtree Restaurant got into the swing of things to welcome
the chessplayers to Oban. Their lengthy menu of ``Openings'' and
``Middlegames'' also proved an entrepreneurial success, with chessplayers
packing out the place throughout the Saturday night during the congress.
I hope all your celebrations next week go down as well as the Boxtree's bash. A
word of caution, however - just go easy on the ``Poisoned Pawns''!
This week's game is also a firecracker. Vladimir Kramnik and Boris Gelfand won
the recent super GM tournament in Belgrade. Kramnik, in great form, destroys
Vassily Ivanchuk's defences in a brilliantly played King's Indian Attack.
White: V. Kramnik
Black: V. Ivanchuk
Investbanka International, Belgrade 1995
Reti's Opening
1 Nf3 d5 2 g3 c6 3 Bg2 Bg4 4 0-0 Nd7 5 d4
This is a relatively new idea against Black's system. The usual move is 5 d3,
aiming for a later e4 or c4. It looks strange apparently not to contest control
of e4. But White still has prospects of a later break with e4 in the centre, as
we shall see.
5 ... e6 6 Nbd2 f5?!
This is a typically uncompromising Ivanchuk plan. Rather than play the solid 6
... Ngf6, he tries to frustrate White's intention to break with e4 utterly.
Kramnik, however, throws doubt on this ambitious strategy.
7 c4 Bd6 8 Qb3 Rb8 9 Re1 Nh6?!
I am not sure where this knight was meant to be heading, but it certainly fails
to get there following Kramnik's next few moves. Perhaps 9 ... Ngf6 was better,
although Black may have feared 10 cxd5 cxd5 11 Ng5, and if 11 ... Qe7 12f3 Bh5
13e4 with good play.
10 cxd5 cxd5 11 h3 Bh5 12 e4!
This superb break takes full advantage of the dark side of Black's plan. The
move 6 ... f5, lost a development tempo and above all weakened the e6 square.
12 ... fxe4 13 Ng5!
There seems to be no good reply to this move, e.g. if 13 ... Qxg5 14 Nxe4 Qe7
15 Bg5 Qf8 16 Nxd6+ Qxd6 16 Bxd5 or 13 ... Qe7 14 Ndxe4 dxe4 15 Nxe6 with a
vigorous attack.
13 ... Bf7 14 Ndxe4 dxe4 15 Nxe6 Bxe6 16 Qxe6+ Qe7 17 Rxe4!
This quiet recapture emphasises the terminal nature of Black's weaknesses in
the e-file. If 17 ... Qxe6 18 Rxe6+ Be7 19 Bxh6 gxh6 20 Rae1 and wins.
17 ... Kd8 18 Qd5 Black resigns. Or if 18 ... Qf8 19 Bg5+ Nf6 20 Rae1 with a
winning attack, eg 20 ... Nf7 21 Bxf6+ gxf6 22 Re6 H5 23 Rxf6 Rh7 24 Ree6 and
wins.
</TEXT>
