<HEADLINE>11-month-old shows how to `select' best team Luke touches down top prize</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749853</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF the Scottish Rugby Union wish to improve the quality of the national XV,
they could do worse than sign up 11-month-old Luke Greer - as a selector,
rather than a player.
For Luke has won The Herald's Selector Rugby competition - or at least it was
his name which was on the winning entry, one of many filled in by his dad, Mark.
Remarkably, 15 of the teams which Mark completed (in his own name and that of
his son, plus wife, Victoria) finished in the top 50 of more than 5000 entries
for the contest, which was run in conjunction with Scottish Rugby magazine.
They tell us that five of the top 11 were Greer entries, and nine of the top 20
if you include one from Mark's brother, Simon.
The Greer family, from Glasgow's Kelvinside, have chosen to receive the #5000
cheque, which they will use to fly as a family to see Scotland play the All
Blacks in New Zealand next year.
Even more remarkable is the fact that Mark and Victoria were winners of
Scottish Rugby's contest earlier this year, which resulted in them going to the
World Cup in South Africa, where the then four-month-old Mark was Scotland's
youngest supporter, featuring on TV before the Scotland v France match.
Luke obviously went on a fast-learning curve, absorbing more than just the
rudiments of the game, to come up with a winning XV of his own so young.
``The real secret,'' confided his father, who played scrum half for Allan
Glen's until he quit to start his own business, ``is to spend a lot of wet
Saturdays at Old Anniesland, paying #6 to watch national league rugby.''
This is not even Luke's first success in a rugby competition. An entry in his
name won two VIP tickets to the Scotland v Wales match at Murrayfield, his
dad's thirtieth birthday. And entries from all three of the family are
currently in contention for a major prize in an English-based selector-rugby
style contest.
``We're not constantly ripping labels off baked beans cans,'' said Luke's mum,
artist Victoria Cassidy. ``We're not competition freaks, just rugby freaks.
Yes, we have a system, but let's not give everything away.''
The family won by just two points, from Mr N Anderson, of Edinburgh. Currie
stand-off Ally Donaldson, who topped the final player scores, and his wife,
Elaine, had three entires in the top 20.
Luke's winning team - it contained only two of the top-10 points scoring
players - was:
