<HEADLINE>Kick in the retro, it's  the Oxfam roadshow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anna Burnside</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Charity shops are in the vanguard of fashion's constant plunder of the past.
Anna Burnside trawls round the racks of ladies' blouses and double-breasted
suits
DESPERATE for a Reader's Digest condensed book? Short of the glasses petrol
stations were giving away four years ago? Morningside Road in Edinburgh would
be a good place to start. With its 13 charity shops, it's a mecca for bargain
hunters, junk junkies and all the other people who are prepared to make the
effort to find something cheap and different.
It's also a half-mile example of the economic realities charity shops find
themselves facing. They're all competing for the three things they need to keep
going: customers, volunteers and donations. The recession, fashion's constant
plunder of the past and the age-old appeal of a bargain provide a market for
5500 charity shops throughout the UK, with an annual turnover of #200 million.
This represents 0.2 per cent of national retail sales and a lot of ladies'
blouses.
The Oxfam shop has fallen into Hoover and Biro territory, it has become a
generic term for any charity shop. The clear market leader, it began with two
shops in 1960. Now it has 842 shops in the UK, 68 of them in Scotland, putting
it in the national retailing top 10. Oxfam's nearest rival, the Imperial Cancer
Research Fund has 470 shops, 59 in Scotland. They keep on coming - around 35
new charity shops opened in Scotland last year, with tiny local organisations
just as keen as the established names.
The regular, predictable income that comes from shops is very attractive to
charities, giving them a reliable source of funds to cover their long-term
work. It also gives them a presence on the High Street and a drop-off point for
donations and cash for emergency appeals. Simon Hodson, who used to manage an
Oxfam shop in East Kilbride, is now the charity's Scottish press officer. He
reckons that their 50 years of experience in this specialised corner of
retailing will help them keep their number-one slot.
``We've been doing it longer than everybody else and we're trying to stay ahead
of everybody else. We started by default but have developed from that. Having
got to the top we're trying to think of ways to make sure we stay there. We
only run secondhand shops because they make a profit but that doesn't mean we
shouldn't do it well and efficiently.
``We're trying to get away from the down-market image, saying you can buy quite
trendy things in Oxfam shops if you know what you're looking for. It's
particularly good in retro periods such as now, when people can actually get
genuine seventies stuff - if our volunteers don't chuck it out because it's out
of date.
``It's a really complicated process, keeping up. Our volunteers don't go
clubbing on Friday and Saturday nights, they don't know what's trendy for a 14
or 15-year-old. With our volunteers being a different age group we've got to
help them so we give training, price guides, and send out newsletters to tell
them to look out for certain things.''
The shops with storage space have been saving the winter clothes handed in
through the summer to fill their shelves in the coming months. The single
biggest seller is ladies' separates in large sizes but the vagaries of style
mean that previously unsaleable items burst into fashion at unpredictable
moments.
``We couldn't give double-breasted suits away in the early part of the 1980s.
They would get handed in all the time, you could hang them on the rail but
no-one would even think about buying them, then suddenly Jonathan Ross starts
wearing them and that's it. Waistcoats came in and out - we were taking
waistcoats off the hanger of a three-piece suit and selling them for a fiver
when you couldn't get a fiver for the suit.''
Donations are taken straight to the sorting room, where volunteers sift through
the goods, price them, and get them ready for the rails. Around 80 per cent of
donated clothes are never sold and go for recycling. Volunteers are encouraged
to specialise in different areas, such as linen or books, and interesting items
will be kept aside for them to deal with. Microeconomics, especially the
housing market, affects the level of donations, as the charity shops benefit
from the major clear out that accompanies a move. The growth of car boot sales
has increased the competition for bric-a-brac. Hodson reckons: ``With boot
sales and The Antiques Roadshow, people are less likely to bring in things that
are of value than they used to be.''
Attracting reliable, committed volunteers is a constant worry for all charity
shops. Hodson says some Scottish Oxfam shops are struggling with 15 people -
the ideal number is 40. Some charities, such as Cancer Research Campaign
Scotland, have always had professional managers to run their 30 shops and look
after their precious volunteers. Oxfam has one manager for its two Glasgow city
centre stores.
Scottish trading manager Donald Easson says:``Historically, we have enjoyed
very good support from long-standing, committed volunteers. The difficulty is
that they're ageing and replacing them is more and more of a challenge. The
Glasgow shops may well be the way of the future but we're trying to resist it
because it will strongly hit our income and smaller shops could not sustain the
cost of a manager.''
Oxfam has been able to use its powerful position to combine selling some fair
trade goods with the tracksuits and tea sets. Last year in Scotland it made #1m
on recycled notepaper and Cafe Direct coffee, and #3.5 million on donated
goods. Oxfam argue, that, although they are new, these goods are an integral
part of its aid work, so should not affect the shops' charitable status.
``Selling the goods from an income-generating project for women        in
Bangladesh is          different from selling Christmas cards which have no
intrinsic value to our work,'' says Simon Hodson. ``They are very profitable
and we sell more than anybody else so we'll continue to do that but we are not
looking to develop that market, we want to develop the other side of it.
``The people giving us stuff tend to be the ones who buy the fair trade goods,
people buying secondhand clothes don't. We don't make profit on new goods, we
are supporting people in the projects but not making spare cash to allow us to
do anything else.''
Cancer Research Campaign Scotland sells no new goods except Christmas cards;
for the ICRF pot-pourri, cards, vases and other gift items account for between
two and eight per cent of their stock. Some traders are unhappy when charity
shops, with their tax concessions and rates relief, sell new goods. Carol
Stewart of the ICRF says they attract new customers, boost the donated stock
and help the shops make a profit. Simon Hodson reckons High Street shops have
no need to worry. ``If you're selling craft goods you've brought in from China,
I'm sure you can sell them cheaper than Oxfam. We're trying to persuade people
to spend more money so that the person who produced it is not being ripped off.
``People will pay a premium price. They say, `I've got to buy Christmas
presents so I may as well buy something out of Oxfam'. If they're going to
spend that money they might as well give it to us.''
</TEXT>
