<HEADLINE>French victory spoils Royal occasion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scottish Schools 12, French Schools 18
I BLAME David Sole, myself. In 1990, immediately after Scotland had completed
the Grand Slam by beating England, he handed over his blood-stained jersey to a
kid in the dressing-room. The boy, the Queen's grandson no less, was back at
Murrayfield yesterday winning a schools cap, the first member of the Royal
family ever so to do.
Not only did we have Peter Phillips. His mother, the Princess Royal, her
husband, Commander Tim Laurence, and his sister, Zara, were there too, sitting,
not in the Royal box but up in the top tier, the gods as it were.
All of this attracted about three times the normal attendance at a schools'
international and a fairly hefty delegation from the world's media. Indeed, in
another match which went on simultaneously, the story-seekers and
picture-takers fought a pitched battle with the security forces of the Scottish
Rugby Union.
There is nothing the old yellow jackets like better than imposing a ban on
media activities. With a jolly shout of ``Get back - you can't film there''
they soon sent the Christmas spirit soaring.
Even the president of the Scottish Schools' Union, Tom Robertson, took 15
minutes before he found anyone who would let him into the ground. ``More than
my job's worth, sir.''
Master Phillips, a bright young man studying for his A levels at Gordonstoun,
qualifies to be Scottish on residential grounds. He is said to dislike personal
publicity but with relations like his, he had better get used to it.
How did he play? Enthusiastically, would be my summing up. He is a great
encourager of others, a slap on the back there, a ruffle of the hair here, he's
a tactile lad. Once in the first half he was hit after the ball was long gone
and there was a flash of a Royal right hook which, probably just as well,
failed to find its target.
Peter tackles stoutly, he burrows well and likes to have the ball in his hands.
I am not at all sure that he is going to make it as a flanker in the senior
game - a little bit light and short on pace - but he is very determined. He
earned his cap.
Tom Robertson fielded the questions at the press conference. ``Peter's a bit
down like the rest of the lads because of the defeat, but he'll bounce back. I
thought his performance was whole-hearted - he gave everything he had.''
Will he play against Wales in the next match. ``Ah, that's for the selectors to
say.''
The game? Well, it was not exactly scintillating in the lachrymose conditions
and most of the bright spots came from the French, big boys, most of whom
looked as though they had been shaving for at least 10 years.
Scotland kicked four penalty goals, all from the boot of Gordon Ross, who is a
considerable fly-half prospect. I liked the cut of Tom Lightoller's jib - he is
one of PP's pals at Gordonstoun - and Telfer Boyd did well to take some decent
lineout ball.
The Scots actually led 6-5 at the interval, two penalties to a try from flanker
Benoit Jezequel. Fly-half Romin Teulet missed the conversion and several
penalties.
Ross booted us further in front but the French sparkled to life with a try from
winger Christophe Heymans and Silvan Kosdik added a third touchdown. Teulet
astonished everyone by kicking a goal and though Ross had one more shot in the
locker, it was not enough.
As the camera scrum around the tunnel was ruthlessly cleared by the guardians
of the stadium, a rumpled hackette enquired: ``What was the score?'' That the
Royals can still draw a crowd, I would say.
And will he present his jersey to D Sole?
Scottish Schools - S M Connell (Strathallan); S W Walker (Dollar Academy), G J
R Hood (Heriot's), T C Lightoller (Gordonstoun), A J Raistrick (Watson's); G
Ross (Heriot's), captain, R S Christie (Hawick High); M Welch (Dunfermline
High), S F McKinnon (Queen Victoria School), C B Buchanan, J P R White (both
Watson's), T M Boyd (Hutchesons'), P M A Phillips (Gordonstoun), R K S Muir
(Fettes), G J Howieson (Hutchesons').
French Schools - J Laharrague; C Heymans, A Dumas, P Bosque, S Kuzdik; R
Teulet, N Morlaes; C Califano, O Terryn, J Sandre, R Cartillier, D Gerard, B
Jezequel, J Bouilhou, M Dieude, captain.
Referee - M Whyte (Ireland).
</TEXT>
