<HEADLINE>Russell set to move up</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE final day of England's match against the South African students was washed
out and the contest abandoned as a draw, but meantime Jack Russell is back on
alert to bat at No.6 in Tuesday's fourth Test at Port Elizabeth.
Until his exploits on this tour, where his first-class batting average is
nearly 80, the wicketkeeper was criticised for failing to score enough runs
against top-class opposition. But his finest performance came in Johannesburg,
where he kept captain Mike Atherton company while the second Test was being
saved.
Manager Ray Illingworth and Atherton would like to confront South Africa with
five front-line bowlers on Boxing Day - particularly if the pitch is
spinner-friendly. The inclusion of all-rounder Mike Watkinson for his first
Test of the trip would give some batting insurance lower down.
But such a move would still represent a remarkable change in fortunes for
Russell - and confirm that he is now regarded as an all-rounder himself.
However, the 32-year-old Gloucestershire player insisted: ``I wouldn't try to
change how I'm batting. I play my own game these days and that's the way I must
continue.''
England will not decide until they have seen the Port Elizabeth pitch,
satisfied themselves about Peter Martin's fitness - he has a sore right
shoulder - and worked out whether Jason Gallian is ready to bat at No.3 after
just one innings in South Africa following his arrival from Pakistan.
The choice for England is whether the inexperienced Gallian, who also offers a
little medium-pace bowling, represents a better all-round bet than Watkinson's
off-spin plus lower-order run-making.
If they go for the second option in Port Elizabeth, then Robin Smith looks
favourite to move up to No.3 - with Russell happily accepting promotion to No.6.
q.DISCARDED all-rounder Greg Blewett gave the Australian Test selectors a
reminder of his ability with a century as West Indies struggled for form again
at The Gabba yesterday.
Blewett, who was dropped from Australia's Test side before the start of the
current three-match series against Sri Lanka, punished a weakened attack, and
scored 115 before the Australia XI declared their first innings on 323 for
seven.
West Indies openers Stuart Williams and Phil Simmons survived the final hour to
guide the tourists to 37 without loss at the close of play.
CRICKET
</TEXT>
