<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Always a pleasure</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Joe Donnelly</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Frontiers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GO ON ..... enjoy yourself! That's the kind of encouragement that keeps your
Frontiersman happy, especially when it comes from a serious scientist who has a
lighter side. His prescription comes just at the right time of the year.
Our festive philosopher is Professor David Warburton who is a founder and
co-ordinator of Arise, the Associates for Research Into the Science of
Enjoyment. Exactly our kind of people!
The Associates study pleasure and the quality of life, and debate issues on
alcohol, chocolate, coffee, tea, tobacco, and most other legal pleasures. They
believe that pleasurable experiences play a central role in human life and, in
moderation, can be beneficial to health.
Warburton, who's Director of Human Psychopharmacology at Reading University,
tells us: ``We want to put science into pleasure and we came together as a
group of academics who discovered that pleasure itself is a very
under-researched subject. The emphasis is on science, but we do enjoy our work.
``Pleasure is undervalued, and that is unfortunate from any point of view. We
know that pleasure is moderated by a common pathway in the brain. In cases of
depression, this malfunctions and people lose the pleasure in everything from
music to basics like organised sport or sex. They don't get enjoyment in music,
food tastes like cardboard.
``As they recover, they get the pleasure back. Tastes and smells activate the
pleasure pathway. We get the input from nice tastes and some things which
people drink. We know from lab studies that a few pieces of chocolate, a glass
of wine, a few puffs on a cigarette, a couple of cups of coffee, all make
people calmer in tests which we use for evaluating anti-anxiety conditions.
``Going back to science we know that pleasure strengthens the immune system and
reduces the stress hormone action on it. Pleasure is an antidote to ills.''
So how does a scientist advocating pleasure research the subject? What does
Warburton do for enjoyment?
``My own pleasures? I have normal healthy appetites. I enjoy wine ..... it's
good for relaxing. Stresses are inevitable. And we all suffer from them to a
degree. The important thing is how quickly you can unwind after it.''
Arise is taking its campaign for general happiness beyond Christmas and into
the New Year which, they say, after all the fun of Christmas, is a depressing
time of the year, and one riddled with guilt as New Year resolutions are broken.
``Happier people live longer. Our New Year resolution should be really to enjoy
to the full the only life we are likely to live.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
