<HEADLINE>Mysteries of the  sacred  valley</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JULIE DAVIDSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749860</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POWER PLACES OF KATHMANDU
Keith Dowman. Photographs
by Kevin Bubriski
Thames &amp; Hudson, #24.95
n AS moths to the flame, go climbers to the Himalayas, and there are few holier
spots where you can die. In Hindu tradition the great mountains of the Indian
subcontinent are the thrones of divine authority, and the antechamber of the
gods is the beautiful, elevated ellipse of the Kathmandu Valley.
Here, even the least sensitive of Nepal's trekker-tourists get some glimmering
of the intricate fabric of the valley's religious life, where the ancient
practices of animism and shamanism coexist with the high cultures of Hinduism
and Buddhism, each finding different expression in a multiplicity of temples,
shrines, and holy places.
Power Places of Kathmandu (Thames and Hudson, #24.95) is a rich pictorial
celebration of the ``focal points of divine energy'' where mighty pagoda
temples, solemn stupas, and unhewn sacred boulders permit human communicants to
make contact with the gods. The complexity of Keith Dowman's scholarly text is
simplified by the potency of Kevin Bubriski's colour photographs.
Their detail of sculpture, carving and relief is stunning. Here are Buddha
offering his flesh to feed a tigress on the Namo Buddha stupa, terrifying Kali
Mai with her necklace of skulls on the Golden Gate at Bhaktapur, noble Lord
Vishnu on his mount Garuda in the inner shrine of Changu Narayana, a gibbering
Hanuman, a Babar-like Ganesh.
Here, too, is the blood sacrifice of goats to the Mother Goddesses at Dakshina
Kali - a ceremony which sanguinary Western tourists enjoy snapping. The
Kathmandu Valley is under pressure from tourism and development. The authors of
this eloquent work let it make its case for ``the gods of the valley, the
magic of sacred places, and the unique creativity of the people''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Veteran scores an ace for the last time</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME golfers never score a hole-in-one, others are a little luckier, but good
fortune finally ran out for veteran American player Peter Sedore in California
yesterday when, after having recorded his eighteenth ace, the old man suddenly
dropped dead.
But the 83-year-old's son did not appear too upset at his father's passing.
``There was no other way he would have wanted it,'' said Sedore's son, Dennis.
``Maybe God wanted him to do it one more time before taking him.''
Sedore Jr added that is was fitting his father died while playing the game he
loved. And the happiness that came from the hole-in-one made it easier for his
family and fellow golfers to accept his death. Playing partner Bill Rutledge
said their trio did not know the ball landed in the hole until they looked in
the cup. He said Sedore Sr used a driver for the ace. ``He lifted his arms and
said, `Hooray, No. 18,'.'' Rutledge said. ``He was real happy.''
The group played one more hole. Rutledge signed the scorecard to verify the
shot. He called Sedore over to initial it, and Sedore collapsed in his arms.
Jack Pawling, president of the golf club, was playing behind the group. ``I
guess, if you have to go, then that's the way to go,'' he said.
GOLF
</TEXT>
