<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The writing's on the wall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CARL MacDOUGALL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is a truth universally accepted, that one should keep one's name - not to
mention one's work - away from lavatory walls and doors. Traditionally, this is
the place for fantastic descriptions, where aspiring short-story writers relate
tales of pliant women and enormous men, which easily sit alongside advertising
slogans of which Maurice Saatchi could feel proud - Large Chest for Rent, Jig
and Tool Rigger, terms available or, best of all, from the men's lavatory at
Glasgow Central Station, Demolition work to hand, temporary erections a
speciality.
I first read about graffiti when I was 15. I knew what it was, but didn't know
it had a name. At the end of third year we were allowed to read what we liked
in the English class. I read a war novel. In the opening pages of Unbroken, by
Alistair Mars, a submarine commander comes north on a crowded overnight train
from London, arrives in Central Station needing what Americans call facilities,
and rushes into the first cubicle he can find. In it someone has written:
This bloody roundhouse is no good at all,
The seat's too high and the hole is too small.
Beneath which was added in a different hand:
To which I must add the obvious retort,
Your arse is too large and your legs are too short.
Cubicle walls and doors were best because one had time to read. Walls outwith
the cubicle were usually given over to shorter, snappier slogans. The condom
machine stalwarts - This is the worst chewing gum I have ever tasted, and
Remoulds, only used once - had just been replaced by the advertising slogan of
a Scottish Sunday newspaper - If it's going on it's going in - when the
government decided something should be done.
Aids arrived and everything became serious. Condoms could be mentioned in
public, the word was news, could be printed in the papers, and the items
themselves became respectable enough to be sold in places other than chemists'
shops.
Health requisite shops went out of business or became health food stores.
Something for the weekend? and Three in a packet, ye cannae whack it became
politically incorrect mentioned in hushed breath, if at all. People were
risking their lives and gentility was replaced by safe sex.
Now students at two Dundonian seats of learning, the Universities of Dundee and
Abertay, are being used as guinea-pigs in a health education scheme which is
laughingly described as innovative. All that's happened is that the Health
Education Board for Scotland has persuaded a number of writers to have extracts
of their work tastefully reproduced on A4-sized posters, and these extracts
from contemporary fiction will be pasted on to lavatory walls.
The approach is hardly novel. The basis of selection seems to be the mention of
a condom and circumstances under which it could have been bought or used. The
most famous of all, Stan Barstow's account of Vic Brown's failed encounter with
a chemist's assistant in A Kind of Loving - which even works in the film when
Alan Bates emerges with a bottle of Lucozade - is not the sort of thing at all.
This is the 1990s, and a thrusting new approach is called for; anyway, Lucozade
is now a sports drink. So the Dundee students will be treated to extracts from
Trainspotting by Irvine Welsh, Foreign Parts by Janice Galloway, The Rachel
Papers by Martin Amis, The Crow Road by Iain Banks, and High Fidelity by Nick
Hornby.
There is obviously a serious side. Young people, it seems, are reticent about
discussing condoms and even in long-term relationships know little or nothing
about previous partners. It's part of a wider scheme which includes a
publication for parents on teenage sexuality and a magazine ``packed with
practical advice for young people''.
So now that the impossible has happened, and advertisers have convinced writers
that a good cause can be served on lavatory walls, one question remains: ``Why
Dundee?''
I fancy going back in a few weeks' time, say around February or March, to see
what additions, amendments, corrections, slogans, or simple statements have
been added. I bet there's been some changes made.
CARL MacDOUGALL
</TEXT>
</DOC>
