<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ward hopeful of a dream return</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE dream of playing against Celtic this afternoon could end a nightmare for
Dumbarton's Hugh Ward.
He was involved in a freak, fatal car crash five months ago in which his friend
died. Ward, who fractured an ankle in the incident, has been struggling since
to recover and shake off the gloom that has hung over him since.
However, he is now back at work as a postman and training hard to recover the
form which enabled him to score 14 goals for Dumbarton last season.
Although he is on the mend, the memory of Martin Simpson and the accident in
August will not leave him. ``I just could not see the end of the tunnel,'' said
Ward. ``My family and friends and all at Boghead have hauled me up and given me
real hope.
``I do not know what I would have done without their help and support.''
``I was always a Celtic supporter and I've always dreamed of being in a match
with them. I was supposed to play, but now I don't now know whether the game
will be off because of the bad weather - and I've picked up a calf muscle
injury.
``I'll be at the ground for a fitness test in the morning. It's disappointing
because I would love to take part in the match.''
</TEXT>
