<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951223-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Everyone must wait and wonder</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SUTHERLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974749864</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN FOOTBALL:
COMPLICATED is an understatement. There is hardly a soccer scenario imaginable
which could match the ifs, buts, and maybes attached to the web of
possibilities which annually accompanies the last-minute scramble for places in
the National Football League play-offs.
With eight of the 12 places spoken for, the final round of regular-season games
this weekend allows 10 others to fight for the four remaining berths. For some,
victory will be enough; others must win while hoping that their rivals lose -
or perhaps that just some of their rivals lose.
Take the Miami Dolphins, for whom all-time great quarterback Dan Marino may not
get many more chances to win a Super Bowl. The Dolphins will be hoping that
Seattle win - or maybe that Seattle lose. Miami can clinch a play-off spot with
a win and one of the following:
l An Indianapolis loss or tie, or a San Diego loss or tie, or an Oakland loss
or tie, or a Seattle win.
l Or an Oakland loss and a Seattle loss, OR an Indianapolis win and a San Diego
loss, and either an Oakland loss or a Seattle loss.
The problems arise because there are different tie-break mechanisms which come
into play if teams have identical records. If teams are level within a
division, their records over all eight matches against divisional rivals would
be the yardstick. But in the chase for wild-card places, teams compete across
the whole American Football Conference, or National Football Conference, and,
when level, the records for comparison are similarly extended to all AFC (or
NFC) matches they have played over the season.
The paradox, basically, is this: the team above you in the division may not
come out of it too well if the comparison is extended to include non-divisional
matches, in which you happened to have fared better than they did. Thus, the
pecking order can change depending on which teams end up with identical,
overall records.
The standings (see below) show that Denver need an almighty amount of help
because of their 7-8 record in the AFC, but it is still possible for the
Broncos to make the play-offs. However, the Carolina Panthers, newcomers to the
NFC who also have a 7-8 record, cannot qualify because all possible tie-breaker
comparisons would be unfavourable.
Even those who already have qualified for the play-offs have something to play
for this weekend. In the AFC, Kansas City (12-3) and Pittsburgh (11-4) have
clinched first-round byes, but the Chiefs must stay one win ahead of the
Steelers in order to ensure the valuable, home-field advantage, which means all
their matches being played in KC.
In the NFC, San Francisco have the tie-break edge over their fierce rivals, the
out-of-form Dallas Cowboys, if they finish with identical records.
San Francisco remain favourites to win the NFC championship, and all the other
contenders will be hoping that Dallas, seen as softer, somehow manage to win
home-field advantage. The 49ers, the Super Bowl champions, are formidable at
their own Candlestick Park and the general opinion is that Detroit - with six
straight wins since coach Wayne Fontes was told he would lose his job if they
failed to make the play-offs - have the best chance of stopping the 49ers.
Pittsburgh and Kansas City are the AFC favourites, but many neutrals will want
Miami to qualify in the hope that Marino's golden arm will work better than in
1985, his only previous Super Bowl appearance. The opponents that day? The
49ers, of course.
Divisional standings of play-off hopefuls (teams in bold have qualified):
