<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS came early for the 23 of us who have been given contracts by the SRU.
With the potential to earn #25,000 this season we are not in the same pay
league as the New Zealanders, Australians and South Africans, who will be on
more than #100,000, but it's a start and, personally, I'm just glad that the
whole thing is over.
There's no doubt that the negotiations have been a distraction, but it was an
inevitable part of the road to professionlism. It's been difficult sometimes,
with all the to-ing and fro-ing over cash and with the rows going on over next
season's European Cup, to remember that first and foremost this is supposed to
be all about playing rugby.
The other point that has to be made is that now we're to be paid there's a very
real danger that the special relationship which has existed between the
Scotland team and the Murrayfield crowd might change.
In the days when we were just enthusiastic, but virtually full-time, amateurs
maybe the spectators were more inclined to be forgiving when things didn't go
as well as they might have done out on the pitch. Now, though, I suspect that
if results don't go as we would all want them to then the spectators will be
more inclined to say that you're not worth your 25 grand and you should get out
of it.
That's understandable and it's something that we, as players, will have to come
to terms with. If someone is paying more than 20 quid for an afternoon's
entertainment at Murrayfield and we're on three grand a game, then they are,
for sure, expecting to be entertained. They're not going to come along to see
Scotland beaten.
Of course, the 23 of us who have been given contracts are just the same as we
were before the deal was done. It's a great honour to play for your country and
if the International Board hadn't decided that the game was turning pro then we
would all have been perfectly happy still to play for the jersey. But it wasn't
the players who made the decision to scrap amateurism, it was the
administrators.
There is no doubt, though, that now we're semi-professionals, the fans will be
expecting more from the players and we will have to try even harder to meet
their aspirations which are, in any case, exactly the same as our own.
The Scotland A side to play Italy a fortnight today looks very much like the
real thing. When I heard that the selectors were going to use the A game as a
dress rehearsal for the Five Nations' Championship I can tell you that I was
sitting with fingers, and everything else, crossed until I knew that I was in.
I've had a bit of a fraught start to the season with injuries and illness and I
certainly wasn't taking anything for granted.
The omission of Craig Chalmers is the big talking point. Gregor Townsend has
got the No.10 shirt ahead of Craig. They are both very good players, but I can
tell you that Craig is one of the most competitive people that I know and he
won't give up his place without a fight.
Congratulations, by the way, to Scott Murray, who wins an A cap at the age of
19, which is very young for a tight forward. I've never met him, but he's had
rave reviews this season and he seems to be someone with a bright future.
Twelve red roses arrived at my home this week by special delivery. There was a
card and a telephone number and the message ``call me.'' Stewart Hamilton, you
great big softie, I know you want to kiss and make up, but all you had to do
was give me a ring.
</TEXT>
