<HEADLINE>Relax, it's only a crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANE SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF A marriage is going to split up, Boxing Day is the classic time to do it.
One counsellor tells the story of a Scots family where the husband accused the
wife of having an affair, just before Christmas (she had been invited to dinner
by a visiting director of her company, where she was a manager). Their two
grown-up children, home for the holiday, stayed up late into the night on
Christmas Eve with their father, trying to convince him it wasn't true; by the
morning of Christmas Day the son had disappeared home, unable to face any more.
On Christmas Day itself the husband told his wife he was leaving, but changed
his mind on Boxing Day: ``Maybe we can work it out''. His wife said: ``I'm
leaving, then. You've proved you don't need me. Live your own life.'' Now that
really was a Christmas to remember: and by next December, the wife was in her
own house; by the following year, the divorce had come through.
``Around Christmas time, if a partner is going off a marriage they often choose
Christmas to tell their partner,'' said Sister Mary Ross of the Notre Dame
child guidance centre in Hillhead, Glasgow.
``Boxing Day is a great day for it, after Christmas Day is over and the kids
are settled, they will tell their wife they're away off with the secretary.''
``Women in particular have high expectations of themselves,'' said Deirdre
Bett, of Lothian Marriage Counselling Service. ``They want everything to be
nice for their families.'' The cruel truth is that people in robust, healthy
relationships make the most of Christmas, but fragile partnerships break,
making January the busiest time of year for counselling services.
Money causes extra stress. Ross said: ``We have got families here who are in
debt and trying to spend hundreds of pounds that they haven't got to keep their
children the same as any other child.''
And a death in the family too often goes unacknowledged. ``If there's been a
death in the family - when there will be a contrast between how happy they
could have been - I would advise them to acknowledge it, not to pretend that
everything was the same, to sit down and talk about what that person would have
been doing and saying over Christmas if they were still here,'' said Ross.
It's too late to get away from it all (it's no coincidence the rent of holiday
flats and cottages shoots up at Christmas and by November there's not a bed to
be had in the land).
You could work for others over Christmas; CSV Scotland runs volunteer
programmes during the festive period and would appreciate any help (call 0141
204 1681).
But for those who do have someone to share Christmas with - and a lot of people
on their own may envy even the bickering over the turkey - it's a matter of
survival. Relaxation is the key, says Anne Shearer, director of the Phoenix
stress counselling centre in Glasgow.
She suggests making time for yourself regularly, either by nipping into another
room, or outside, or simply practising good breathing technique, the basis of
disciplines such as yoga and Tai Chi.
Having a bath, even in the middle of the day, is also a good way to make time
and space for yourself. Don't expect too much, and delegate work - don't think
you have to do everything yourself; people are often delighted to be asked to
help, but will not volunteer. Keeping people busy, rather than just sitting
around, will dissipate tension.
If things get really bad, try talking it over with someone from outside the
family circle. Scotland's Marriage Counselling service has started a telephone
helpline manned in Glasgow from 6.30pm to 8.30pm Mondays, 10.30am-12.30pm
Wednesdays (0141 226 4122) and in Edinburgh from 10am-1pm Mondays and 4pm to
7pm Fridays (0131 558 3334, open 2pm to 4pm Wednesday, Thursday and Friday over
Christmas).
And try to keep things in proportion. ``If we are uptight and stressed and
tired, we get into a compulsive, obsessive frame of mind,'' said Shearer.
``We have to learn who is pulling our puppet strings about what we should and
should not do at Christmas.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
