<HEADLINE>Crocodile meets the Cock o' The North</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LIZ TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>31</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749867</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the run-up to the festive season the salerooms went all childish - trains,
toys, and teddy bears dominated the goods on offer. Christie's in South
Kensington decided to concentrate on trains and held two sales a day apart at
which they offered toys from famous makers like Basset-Lowke and Marklin, all
priced far beyond a small boy's pocket money.
Trains are now big business and last December, when Christie's held a similar
sale, a Marklin Swiss ``Crocodile'' locomotive made #35,200. On offer this year
was a gauge 11 armoured train with a gun carriage that Marklin made in 1909
(estimated around #20,000); and a 1937 model of the LNER's Cock o' the North,
one of the great historic trains of the Scottish railway system. The Cock o'
the North was designed by Sir Nigel Gresley who also designed the Flying
Scotsman, and it ran between Edinburgh and Aberdeen which was an arduous,
uphill journey that required nine tonnes of coal for ordinary engines. In those
days, nine tonnes of coal cost the same as a first-class passenger fare.
Gresley's design incorporated a unique coal-saving feature which made the
service much cheaper to run. This device was also carefully incorporated into
Marklin's model of the train which was estimated in the sale at around #20,000.
How many first-class fares is that?
For train fanciers there were also artefacts made by the British-based
manufacturer Basset-Lowke, including tiny water-towers with movable arms and
decorated with advertisements for such 1930s delights as Bovril and the Boy's
Own Paper (estimate between #600 and #800); and replica platforms of Harrogate
and Beaconsfield stations with carefully re-created ladies' waiting-rooms.
Another station lavatory made by Marklin, the German firm, had twin cubicles
marked Damen and Herren and so detailed were the models that the locks on the
doors worked. The men's lavatory was painted blue and the women's pink and the
estimate was also around #800.
Bonhams also got into childhood mood and on December 20 offered a range of
dolls, toys, teddies, and trains. The list contained a Basset-Lowke model of
the Flying Scotsman and the Royal Scot by Hornby. Lovers of the motor car were
not forgotten and a Kingsbury metal model of Sir Malcolm Campbell's Blue Bird
included in the sale with an estimate of around #800.
Less macho toys were dolls and bears which included a Steiff centre-seam bear
dating from around 1910 (estimate about #3000) and a Tete Jumeau doll which was
expected to sell for about #1500.
In Scotland, Phillips included toys, dolls, and bears in two sales held in
Edinburgh. One of the star lots was a Shirley Temple doll, dating from the
1930s, dressed in a floral dress and hat. She had blonde curly hair, green eyes
with lashes, a pouting open mouth, and a jointed composition body and she came
with her luggage - four new outfits, extra underwear, and a Shirley Temple
badge, all contained in the original box. The estimate was around #500.
Among the Christmas presents from not so long ago attracting the attention of
collectors was a Tudor Rose table-top soccer game dating from the 1960s,
estimated at about #30, and a German-made toyshop with a four-drawer cabinet
inscribed with the words ``Rice'', ``Macaroons'', ``Chocolate'', and
``Raisins'', a counter and three-walled backdrop. It was made early this
century and is worth about #60.
Toy soldiers were a favourite at Christmas and in the Phillips' sale there was
a collection of ``Armies of the World'' lead soldiers, Steadfast soldiers, and
military memorabilia including postcards, magazines, and a cavalry jacket.
Because the soldiers were still in their original boxes, the estimated price
was #500.
Another sale of more unusual childhood items was held by Christie's in South
Kensington when they sold a collection of magic lanterns, lantern slides, and
optical toys brought together by a Mr and Mrs Lear who used to tour the
waterways of Britain in a narrow boat giving lantern shows. They started
collecting as recently as 1970 and in 1991 opened Lear's Magical Lantern Museum
in Llandrinod Wells, Wales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
