<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ena McPherson digs around in some odd  corners of the garden  for the best in bulbs Rewards from an  unbound cyclamen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>green fingers</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749868</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE been reading through the garden notebook I used when we first moved into
this house, and am rather ashamed to see how much money I have spent over the
years on bulbs. What has become of them all?
Those white tulips that looked so coolly elegant under the variegated cornus
are no more than a lovely memory. And the frilly pink parrot tulips with the
green streak down all the petals, a perfect colour match for the neighbouring
azalea - all gone.
There are, of course, all sorts of natural explanations. The white tulips
lasted four years, the pink ones only two. Perhaps the pinks weren't planted
deep enough, or the mice ate them, or the urban fox who trots through our
garden every night may have nosed out some bonemeal in that bed and dug up the
lot (though I do think I would have noticed that).
This year I have decided to have one last throw. I have planted 38 tulips,
bought very cheaply from B&amp;Q, and from now on I shall concentrate on more
reliable bulbs.
Apart from the ubiquitous wild hyacinth which, though lovely en masse, does
tend to act like an enthusiastic extra from The Day of the Triffids, and my bed
of Crocus tomasinianus which is locked solid with their bulbs under a blanket
of small-leaved ivy, the bulbs that have done really well with me are all
autumn flowering.
They are the Colchicum speciosum which most of us think of as autumn crocus
though that is not strictly accurate. When grown alone, I used to hate the way
they flowered then promptly keeled over because the slender stems couldn't
support such a large flower head. Now I have them planted in a bed of nepeta,
the plant that sends cats into ecstasy and so gave it its popular name of
catmint.
Nepeta flowers first in tandem with the roses but, once the purple flower
spikes fade, I clip the whole bed back and there is time for it to flower again
in October on shorter stems just high enough to give support to the colchicums.
Grown this way the original three bulbs have increased enough to make quite a
bold statement. Inevitably, a few still sprawl but these are the ones I cut for
the house. Despite their very fragile appearance, colchicums last well in water.
The foliage appears in the winter and disappears in spring. The leaves are
large, bright green and rather coarse looking but, since everything else
including the cut-back nepeta bed is looking so miserable by then, I really
quite welcome it, always aware those big leaves mean a bold show of lilac
flowers next season.
The tiny Cyclamen hederifolium have been generous too. I had one corm under a
tree for years, the sole survivor of a group of three. It was a reliable
flowerer but never increased. Two years ago the tree had to come down and at
the last minute, as the men were revving up their chainsaw, I remembered the
corm and rescued it.
I decided to try it in a raised bed at the kitchen door where I reckoned I
would get maximum pleasure from its few fragile flowers whose back-swept pink
petals with deep mauve base look so brave in November's greyness. The prospect
was so enticing that I added another corm bought in bloom from the garden
centre.
After they flowered last autumn, I found several stems coiled like a bed
spring, each with a large seed at its centre. I had never noticed this when
they were under the shade of the tree, or perhaps it only happens when they are
in a site they are happy with. To help things along I poked the seeds into the
earth, and crossed my fingers.
This year I counted 35 perfect little cyclamen - the stems are no more than
three inches high and the blooms less than an inch across - and dozens of tiny
new leaves just showing above the earth. I was so delighted I promptly added a
pot of the white variety to my expanding colony. The silver-etched green leaves
will last all winter but I must find some way of marking their enlarged
territory so that I don't dig them up inadvertently when the leaves disappear
in early summer.
Undoubtedly the showiest autumn flowering bulbs are the Nerine bowdenii. There
is something rather startling about a show of nerines in October. Possibly it
is because one's eyes have become attuned to the autumn range of colours and
then come these tall stems that end in a burst of sweetie pink, fizzing like
sherbet, real Barbara Cartland efforts. They make brilliant cut flowers,
especially if you can team with some prunings from a red-leaved shrub like Rhus
cotinus.
The leaves come in early summer and have died down before the flowers appear.
They are hardy enough in Scotland but they do need a warm position. I grow them
at the side of the front door by the house wall where they get full sun, and
that bed is covered in gravel. They certainly seem happy there.
From five bulbs, the colony has grown this year to 37 stems, each one bearing
up to nine curling flowerlets. I must now think of splitting them, but that
will be the first bit of attention they have received in five years. That's my
kind of gardening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951223-000171</DOCNO>
