<HEADLINE>'Tis the season to be faddy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Catherine Brown</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Catherine Brown looks back at
trends in the
food industry
PEAK of the year for crazy food buying is Christmas. Caught at our most
vulnerable, exhausted, frazzled, brain-in-a-panic mode, we are in danger of
picking up the strangest items especially if they look as though they might
save time.
Such as this pack of ready-to-microwave baby potatoes - with pat of butter on
top - which the food industry is tempting me to pay extra for because they have
put butter on potatoes. Or will I grab this packet of ready-fried croutons? Not
if I stop to think that at 59p for 40 grams (just over an ounce) I could buy a
whole loaf for the same price.
Now I'm among the loaded shelves of Christmas cakes, Christmas chocolates, and
Christmas biscuits, in eye-catching packaging. Surrounded by bottles of festive
champagne and other drinks, I see the Christmas tag again. Only this time it's
on a packet of tea-bags - M&amp;S tea-bags to be exact.
Christmas tea-bags? On the shelf below, there is Christmas coffee! In the
interests of research I buy the tea-bags, described as the Connoisseur's
Choice. And a very ordinary cup of breakfast tea they turn out to make.
Of course, fads feed emotions in a way that has nothing to do with supplying
the essentials of life, yet they have become exceptionally powerful and,
depending on whether you get hooked or not, extremely expensive. Top of the
queer ideas which the food and drink industry manufacture, year in year out,
are those which feed the good-for-you factor.
A whole range of foods have been promoted on the strength of the idea that a
Mediterranean diet is good for you - while ignoring the fact that our climate
is a tad colder than the South of France. It started with extra virgin
olive-oil and balsamic vinegar which led to the pasta boom. Italian was in.
French, rich, buttery sauces were out. The sun-dried tomato was the signature
of a healthy Italian diet. At treble the price, ready-cooked char-grilled
peppers in olive-oil were hailed as the good-for-you alternative to native
baked potatoes and              butter.
This year has also seen a boom in jars of pasta sauces, not just based on
tomatoes, but also on a variety of other ingredients such as cheese. As far as
I understand it Italians usually grate cheese on their pasta and sometimes stir
an egg in to make                                  a sauce. As good-for-you
fads come and go, there has now been the discovery that the trans-fatty acids
in polyunsaturated margarines are not good for you at all, according to
American research revealed recently. So un-messed-about butter is back in.
Then there was the case this year of SmithKline Beecham, who make Ribena and
who thought they would jump on the good-for-you bandwagon with Ribena Juice and
Fibre. Their motivation, however, was a little less noble than the desire to
improve the nation's bowel movements.
In order to avoid paying VAT on a beverage, they tried to pass it off as a
``functional'' food which got them involved in a test case with Customs and
Excise. They tried to convince the officers that the characteristic Ribena
flavour was something they had added to the fibre. Of course, it was a health
food, they said, supermarkets should put it on the cereal shelves. No, said
Customs and Excise.
But this has been a year when drinks in general have had more than their fair
share of tampering by the fad-merchants, from alcoholic lemonades to the
good-for-you boom in sports drinks.
Some have claimed to be a replica of your blood, to prevent you feeling
exhausted (needing a spoonful of sugar?) and dehydrated (needing a drink of
water?)  The sophistications of this fad-market have been extended to producing
powders to mix into water or fruit juice. One, Glycosport, costing #14.95 for
25 servings, was described by a sports dietician as being ``of less use than
the water or  fruit juice it's mixed into''.
Clear,  flavoured-waters were another drink fad, developed to appeal to those
who had sussed out the disadvantages of artificial, brightly coloured
additive-loaded drinks. So while the offending colour was removed the unnatural
flavour was left in, producing a crystal-clear, looking good-for-you drink,
tasting artificially of fruit.
Supermarket fad of the year must be their appeal to our emotions to stay loyal.
``Loyalty cards'' have taken a number of subtly different forms, though not all
supermarkets have invested in the necessary large set-up costs. The cards have
been the supermarkets' reaction to our promiscuity, when they discovered from
market research this year that we were shopping-around too much for their
liking. I wonder why.
SEASONWATCH
IN A last minute fill-up of the fruit bowl, there are Cox's Pippins to go with
cheese, a pile of citrus fruits to eat after rich foods, a mango or papaya to
go with salty, smoky, cured meats. This is the time of year when fruits with
character can work as trouble-free accompaniments.
``The fashion in foreign fruits,'' says Garth Gulland of Roots and Fruits in
Glasgow, ``has moved away from strange, difficult to eat fruits, and back
towards less exotic tastes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
