<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>If you can't stand the cold, come into the kitchen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lesley Duncan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lesley Duncan visits a Georgian extravagance where, at the
festive season, geese are well
and truly cooked
IF you can't stand the heat keep out of the kitchen, goes the transatlantic
admonition. The Georgian kitchen at Callendar House, Falkirk, is certainly hot
this particular morning. A cavernous, high-ceilinged hall, it has a giant coal
fire burning at one end, sending out sparks and cheer in defiance of the most
dreich of December days.
The early nineteenth century is much in vogue these days after the success of
the televised version of Pride and Prejudice. All those sprigged muslins and
heaving bosoms! Jane Austen's heroines may be too preoccupied with affairs of
the heart and the search for husbands to notice the servant classes, but modern
fascination with Regency/Georgian ways of doing things extends below stairs.
As it happens, this kitchen is on the ground floor of the mansion, which is
owned by Falkirk District Council and sits in acres of wooded parkland, its
turreted Scots-baronial exterior concealing earlier buildings. It boasts the
only working Georgian kitchen in Britain. It's the centrepiece of Callendar
House's celebrations of the spirit of Christmas.
The fire is being stoked for the cooking of a goose later in the day, explains
Kate Erskine, who with her team of five ``interpreters'' demonstrates the
workings of the place. Mrs Erskine is in period costume - gingham dress with
chaste neckline, white bonnet tied firmly under the chin.
She indicates the big wooden table where the trussed bird is awaiting its turn
on the spit. There are more instantly edible things laid out, too. The
temptation to nibble need not be resisted. Visitors are encouraged to sample
this nineteenth-century Christmas fare. Of course, historical accuracy
indicates that Christmas wasn't generally celebrated in Scotland in these days.
However, William Forbes, then owner of Callendar House, did entertain friends
from the South in the 1820s, so a little licence with the comestibles seems in
order.
First stop - the mincemeat pies. They look like M&amp;S specials but they contain,
authentically for the time, real mincemeat (``brisket,'' volunteers Mrs
Erskine) in addition to fruit and spices. The Scotch Christmas bun is very like
granny's black bun - dark and rich with fruit, spices, and brandy. The
Pitcaithly bannock is delicious - a shortcake mixture with the addition of
almonds and fresh orange and lemon peel.
Then there is the yule bread, made simply of oatmeal and water on Christmas
morning. It was cut in four as a sign of the cross, explains Mrs Erskine, and
each member of the family was given a quarter to keep till after the festive
meal. Good luck was meant to ensue in the coming year. A harmless fancy -
though quite how it fits in with the Presbyterian ethos of old Scotland isn't
clear. The same applies to the 12 ingredients of the plum pudding, symbolising
as they do the 12 Apostles, and the stirring of the pud mixture three times for
the Three Wise Men.
No doubt such colourful detail charms the many school children who have visited
the kitchen since it was opened to the public two-and-a-half years ago. The
recipes change every three months to suit the seasons.
The great iron range is authentic (was it made in the Carron Ironworks
nearby?). It's ideal, says Mrs Erskine, for making chocolate puffs - a kind of
meringue. ``But things that require a very hot oven can be a problem,'' she
adds. A copper pot reveals its bubbling contents. This is plum porridge, made
with beef stock and breadcrumbs, to which are added mustard, mace, plums (of
course), currants, and raisins.
Which meal was it served with? Apparently there's not an easy answer, for in
the Georgian period all sorts of dishes could be on the table simultaneously,
with the main ones - dubbed ``the removes'' - at the corners. There's a
splendid array of working utensils on the scrubbed wooden worktops. Most of the
pots are copper and surprisingly heavy. They are lined with tin - ``to stop
verdigris poisoning,'' says Mrs Erskine nonchalantly. There are also some
pewter pots.
Among the unusual kitchen utensils is a chocolate cutter. Georgians apparently
loved a drink of chocolate, sugar, and claret. The sugar didn't come in Tate
and Lyle packaging in these days but was stored in the form of a great cone.
Other drinks which visitors (over 18) may sample are mulled wine and Old Man's
Milk. The latter turns out to be more appetising than its name suggests, made
as it is from a pint of single cream, a quarter-of-a-pint of brandy, sugar, and
egg yolk. It sounds very much like American egg nog. Td.
A party of disabled young people enter the kitchen and Mrs Erskine starts her
living history interpretation again, immediately catching everyone up in her
enthusiasm.
The festive theme is pursued elsewhere in this imposing building, which is
gradually being returned to life after many years of standing empty. There's a
beribboned Christmas tree at the fork of the great oak staircase and various
Christmassy goods in the shop. The Jane Austen Cookbook echoes the period
flavour with its recipes for ``Ragoo of Celery'' and ``Harrico of Mutton''.
For the more scholarly there's the barrel-vaulted library with its bookcases
protected by trellisworks of brass. A professional archivist is in charge of
this history research centre. Visitors with a sense of the past will also enjoy
the exhibition charting the story of Callendar House from its origins as a
medieval keep 600 years ago. Mary Queen of Scots, Bonnie Prince Charlie, and
Oliver Cromwell put in a mandatory appearance. In deference to the 250th
anniversary of the '45, another room has a temporary exhibition devoted to the
Battle of Falkirk - complete with a specially commissioned picture of the fight
(which went the prince's way) by Chris Collingwood.
Jack Sanderson, the curator, points to a staircase where a reproduction of an
original early eighteenth-century ceiling painting is about to be put in place.
Its theme? ``It's as though you're at the bottom of a well, looking up at
little putti,'' he explains. It could be by the same artist who worked in
Hopetoun House at that period.
More mundane - but every bit as fascinating - are ``Presents from the Past''.
This annual exhibition is ``a way of saying thank you'' for donations to the
locld-fashioned washing machine, a garden plough, and lots of evocative old
photographs of local industries vie for attention.
A much more ambitious exhibition, due for completion in two years, will plot
the transformation of Falkirk during the Industrial Revolution from 1750 to
1850. Callendar House's owner William Forbes, himself a copper merchant, was
involved with leading innovators of the time such as Matthew Boulton, Dr John
Roebuck of Carron, and steamboat pioneer William Symington.
Beyond the pleasant seasonal celebrations at Callendar House, such long-term
initiatives to bring the mansion into imaginative public use must be admired.
n Despite its grandeur, Callendar House can be elusive to find for people
unfamiliar with Falkirk. It's off the A803 on the east side of the town.
Parking is some distance from the house, though the walk through tree-lined
avenues is most pleasant. There are also outdoor attractions for the family.
The house will be open next week from Wednesday to Saturday, 10am to 5pm, and
on the same days and at the same times in New Year week. In the winter season
it's open normally from Monday to Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
