<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oils on the water</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MYRA PATER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974749875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE'S nothing quite like the scents of Christmas, especially the aromatic
smells of pine or spruce needles. However, if your tree is not of a natural
type and you're looking for something a little more subtle than the
pine-scented plug-in room freshener, why not try a simmering pot-pourri?
Most people associate pot-pourris with dried leaves, petals and spices, but a
pungent, spicy mix can be simmered at the back of the stove or even in a foil
container in a cool oven with the door left slightly open.
The basic mix I use consists of four ounces each of whole allspice, star anise,
cardamon, chopped root ginger and broken cinnamon sticks mixed with eight
ounces each of orange peel, lemon peel, rose petals and lemon verbena leaves.
To this add 30 drops of juniper or rosemary oil and mix well. Make a simmering
mix with the ratio of one cup of pot-pourri, to two to three cups of water. The
ingredients can be found at most natural beauty shops, health food stores and
delicatessens specialising in unusual spices.
``. . . They presented him with gifts; gold, and frankincense, and myrrh.''
These, the most quintessential of nativity gifts, were fitting offerings for
the infant Jesus with gold representing wealth and the herbs being of precious
value for their healing, aromatic and cosmetic properties.
The frankincense tree, also called olibanum, produces ``tears'' or beads of
white sap from the bark when incisions are made. They gradually turn yellow and
harden; and after four months are harvested and distributed worldwide,
particularly for use as incense.
Myrrh was no less valued and sought-after as far back as the Egyptians, for it
possessed properties ideal for use in embalming, as well as cosmetic
applications. It is used now in folk medicine for the treatment of mouth
infections, ulcers, and for bodily stimulation against septicaemia.
The very names of frankincense and myrrh are evocative of the Christmas story,
but there is also a range of plants which, over the centuries, have become
known as the advent or manger herbs.
Costmary, also known as Our Lady's balsam, was said to have been used as a
healing ointment by Mary Magdalene, and horehound, a token of good health,
which was taken from its native North Africa, Asia and southern Europe by
emigrants and distributed throughout the world, is still a constituent in many
preparations in the treatment of respiratory infections including bronchitis,
colds and sore throats.
Our Lady's bedstraw belongs to the group of plants popular for growing in
``Mary Gardens'' which includes Our Lady's mantle, smock, garters and thimble
among others. This is said to have lined the crib.
Juniper was included for protection, sage represented life and immortality and
thyme symbolised courage, particularly in relation to the Holy Family's flight
from Egypt.
If you are looking for a festive decoration with a difference, what could be
better than several of the manger herbs fashioned into posies or wreaths which
really are appropriate to the season?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
