<DATE>951223</DATE>
<HEADLINE>To the sound of taped Christmas carols, Jane Scott  discovers what the well-regarded  pet is likely  to receive With lots of love from Santa Paws</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749876</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS you read this, the loudspeakers at the Burnside Pet Hotel in Denny are
playing the Christmas tape - Jingle Bells, Have Yourself a Merry Little
Christmas and, possibly, Santa Paws is coming to town.
Because Santa won't forget even those poor pooches and moggies who spend the
holiday in kennels while their owners are off enjoying themselves.
``We once had someone who got a Chinese meal delivered to their dog at
Christmas,'' says owner Neil Murray. ``It was a Basset hound. And it really
liked Chinese food.''
In the true spirit of being kinder to your animals than to your children,
Britain's pets are due to receive a bumper crop of presents this year.
The big presentation stack of Special Friends Christmas stockings which
dominates the front of Alex Mair's Pet and Garden Shop in West George Street,
Glasgow, sold out in the early days of December. ``It's just been frantic this
year,'' said manager William Jenkins.
But the 99p net bags of Pedigree Chum Schmacko snacks and chocolate drop
treats, the #1.25 cardboard crackers of Crunchy Kitbits (beef and chicken) and
Tender Kibits (rabbit and turkey), not forgetting the Funball toy, are merely
the stocking fillers of the animal Christmas.
Harrods knows how to do it in style; the Knightsbridge department store
produces a Christmas list of ``Gifts for Pets'' for puzzled owners which
includes the #65 cat bed - ``cotton with fur lining in the style of the Harrods
building'' and the Harrods indoor kennel for #140. There are also jewelled dog
bowls (name your price) and, for the owner who wants to say it all, and has #9
to say it with, T-shirts (100%) with two designs: ``Wreck the Hall and Eat the
Holly'' and ``Oh Come Sit Stay All Ye Faithful''.
Visit a pet shop nowadays, and you could be forgiven for thinking you'd ended
up in a health food store. Some truly extraordinary dog treats from Hagen are
selling themselves to responsible owners this Christmas on their nutritional
content, with the ingredients for the five lurid red and yellow Doggie Gourmet
kebabs on a plate listed as protein, oil, fibre, moisture and ash. Keeping you
dog's teeth healthy, Nylabone brings you the Dental Dinosaur, ``irresistible to
dogs'' in caramel-coloured Tyrannosaurus Rex shape, ``naturally
flavour-enhanced'' and shelf-mate to the Gummabone Plaque Attacker,
Stegosaurus-shaped this time in clear yellow plastic.
A #2.99 bird stocking presents Chit Chat snacks and honey seeds in
scientific-looking foil packets, together with a tasty ``budgie sandwich'' of
honey, seeds, and wafer biscuit. Birds do well at Christmas, apparently; from
the Pet Love ``see-saw on perch with balls'' (#1.79) to the mini Hagen plastic
steam engine with space for budgie passenger (#2.39) there is a toy for every
pretty boy.
And there is, at the very least, a stocking for everyone. Altons Christmas
selection for horses (#1.99) offers Apple Horse Bix, Mint Horse Bix and
Equimints, while the #1.50 Pip net bag for rabbits and guinea pigs gives them
yoghurt and milk treat buttons, along with three different flavours of
delicious nibble sticks.
But it is the hamsters who really clean up at Christmas. Habitrail is a
remarkably popular line of low-rise hamster housing starter units which have
cornered the market in gifts for the rodent in your life. Reading the sides of
the boxes, however, induces much of the same thoughtful guilt as a browse
through an Early Learning Centre.
The #8.39 Sky Spinner, for example, a green plastic attachment which allows
your hamster to whiz round to his heart's content, is described thus:
``Delights hamsters with its orbiting motion as they scamper back and forth.
This quiet external extension offers another avenue for exploration and a
challenge to the hamster's natural agility.''
The Villa, with wheel and solarium, is ``the ideal mini home which satisfies
hamsters' needs for exercise, recreation, and exploration''.
Also in the range are the Sky Restaurant (a splendid pink revolving affair),
the Snack Bar (could be misused by malevolent young ones hoping to be
laboratory scientists, relying as it does on well-trained hamsters pressing on
the yellow dispensing bars to get their treats from the purple box) and, glory
of glories, the hamster Drag Racer, which places the beastie in a giant plastic
ball contained in a streamlined, car-shaped frame.
But don't worry, said Mair's manager William, you can set the wheel so it goes
round in a circle rather than straight out the door.
Meanwhile, back at the Burnside Pet Hotel, the tapes that keep the dogs happy
have moved on to White Christmas - ``Although I think that's more for the staff
than for the dogs,'' said owner Neil Murray.
All the dogs get diced-up turkey on Christmas Day, along with their normal
diet, and in the true spirit of Christmas, all the animals share. ``If
someone's got a wee Chihuahua and have given it a big Christmas stocking, we
ask them if they'd mind splitting it - a lot of the old age pensioners who have
to leave their animals here can't afford presents. We put all the treats into a
pool. And every dog gets a present.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
