<HEADLINE>Porridge and blinis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LEILA FARRAH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra a slice of life</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749877</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sir Fitzroy Maclean, diplomat and historian tells LEILA FARRAH about his eating
habits
n.BREAKFAST rather depends on where I am. At home I'm apt to have a continental
breakfast of China/Indian blended tea and toast with honey or marmalade, or
sometimes an attractive roll such as a croissant. If I'm away, or about to have
a long day, it will be porridge, eggs, and bacon.
One of my principles is that I never eat between meals. At lunch, I'm quite
happy with a sandwich but if I'm at home I'll have meat and two veg - we have
our own lamb - and I do like potatoes.
I own the local hotel here, the Creggans Inn, and my wife and I take a lot of
interest in the food there. We have a lot of malt whiskies and a good cellar. I
spent two years at our embassy in Paris where I learned a lot about food, and
also in Russia where I grew very fond of Boeuf Stroganoff, blinis (pancakes)
and borscht, and smoked fish with vodka. I like zakuski (hors d'oeuvre) and
shashlik (kebabs) of all kinds. And I like to have a glass of sour cream -
smetana - with a little sugar.
When we're in Russia, my wife and I always have caviar and blinis for a first
course, then Chicken Kiev or Boeuf Stroganoff. I still think that the best food
is French although they don't have such a monopoly as they had before the war.
People here are more interested in food and that produces better results: the
intake of foreigners into the United Kingdom has also made a big difference.
I drink tea in the afternoon but rarely eat anything although I love egg
sandwiches, Christmas cake, and scones with jam - but I resist these out of
greed because I don't want to spoil my appetite for dinner.
I'm very fond of fish, particularly salmon and black (Dover) sole. If you've
got really good sole, meunire is as good a way as any of preparing it.
We're on the shores of Loch Fyne and are lucky enough to have wonderful oysters
that come straight out of the sea which is simply marvellous. The langoustines
are particularly good although we have to compete with Spanish lorries that
sweep them away with the lobster and prawns.
Favourite dishes owe much to nostalgia which is why I like nursery food,
particularly chicken and bread sauce.
I like really good, simple cooking and am very much in favour of getting what's
best locally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
