Gaultier
Cartoon print satin dress from JPG by Jean-Paul Gaultier, #198 at Corniche,
Jeffrey Street, Edinburgh.
What do you give the woman who has
everything? More, says John Davidson
What do you give to the woman who has everything? The absolutely fabulous
answer is quite simple. More. And here to advise you on the top ten or so
wonders of the present world this Christmas are leading fashion guru, Patsy
Stone and PR supremo, Edina Monsoon. Or a close approximation.
Their advice? As ever, "Names, names, names. . . all big designers like
Givenchy, Lagerfeld, Saint Laurent". They are the basis of an absolutely
fabulous Christmas, darling. For, when you rummage under the tree in eager
anticipation of that token of glamour and extravagance, which - let's face it,
sweetie - you've earned, nothing is quite so instantly gratifying as the glint
of a gilded logo on a really smart giftbox.
Don't those intertwined letters - Y, S, and L - send a shiver down your spine
which no amount of hollistic massage or rebirthing can match? And that double-C
monogram? Well, doesn't the word `Chanel' mean anything to you?
You could be joining the fashion pack's front-row elite. All it takes is a
little bag, shoe, belt, frock . . . anything, in fact, from Prada. But perhaps,
sweetie, you are the sort of absolutely fabulous person who would prefer the
appalling but loveable kitsch of Moschino's festive red and green felt flower
jewellery.
You might swoon over Valentino's most intimate secrets (just a black lacey bra
and matching briefs, actually). And from Chanel - well, it has to be No. 5, the
only thing which Marilyn Monroe ever wore in bed.
Just one name stands head and shoulder-pads above all others in terms of
absolute fabulousness. ``Lacroix'', Edina screams, ``Christian Lacroix!'' And
if Edina could die for his dainty knitted suit in multi-coloured boucle yarn,
one of his printed silk scarves might bring on a jolly serious throat
infection. At the very least. But, of course darling, you knew already that
Christmas shopping can seriously damage your health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
