<HEADLINE>Wrapping up for beginners</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Anvar Khan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749880</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Anvar Khan looks at the colourful book which examines the history and lure of
the sari
BEAUTY Box is in receipt of a beautifully illustrated book all about the Indian
sari. I could hazard a guess as to why I alone got this tome through the post.
There's a lot to be said for combing through Press Agency cuttings, and asking
the researcher to look out for Asian surnames. But let us not be churlish.
While it is a lengthy book, if you are desperately keen on Indian culture and
history, it's worth having a wee flick through it.
India's saris evolved out of a complex environment. India is intense with human
beings, and its tens of millions of uneducated, poor, and often ignorant
inhabitants pollute the already furious soup they call life. The country's
pastures and plains have always been prone to heavy flooding with the
temperamentality of the weather. A bad storm can wreak havoc on the heart, when
lives are dependent on crops.
India acquired a common knowledge of life and art, by a continual trample of
people leaving one place to pick up skills in another, as if all the genetic
and cultural information needed to be reborn in another place was transported
via the mud on their feet.
The subcontinent's regions have deep roots. By 2000 BC, the people of the Indus
Valley were making bread from wheat, and wearing dyed cotton clothes, while a
thousand miles away, Neolithic inhabitants of present-day Bihar were growing
and eating rice, but cotton had not appeared there as a crop. The Indus valley
left one of the most significant legacies, the domestication of cotton and the
technology to dye it.
Early Islamic invasions resulted in various Muslim dynasties ruling Northern
India, culminating in the Mughal Empire (1526-1765) whose court textiles
influenced the fabrics worn by most northern and central aristocrats until the
early twentieth century. Only the poor wore saris, the upper classes created
suits from patterns, as there was the superstition among the lower castes, that
anything created using a needle could not be good. In the late eighteenth
century, Mughal political and military power was superseded by the British, who
got their paws on tribal designs. Parlour curtains all over Europe unwittingly
displayed Indian fertility symbols.
The sari is a length of cloth from about four to eight metres, and how you wear
it, how you cross it around the body, depends on which region you are from. We
won't bore you with technical details, suffice to say, that every Indian woman
toiling under a religion which equates purity with chastity, has managed to
devise a modest way of wearing the yards of see-through cotton - doubling it is
a must.
Saris are often woven by hand - there are more than three million handlooms in
India employing six million people - or by powerlooms in textile mills. Sari
production accounts for an estimated 25.5% of all textile production in India.
Handwoven saris are highly prized and most Indian women, apart from the
poorest, wear both kinds.
A woman's ethnicity and caste background influence her choice of fabric and
colour. In Northern India a widow is expected to wear white, the colour of
mourning, as bright colours are regarded as the prerogative of young, married
women, with bridal red being seen as the colour of joy, energy, and marital
bliss. Older married women are expected to wear dark blues and other jaded
tones. They do that here, too.
Women in the Indian south are less likely to cover their head with a veil, and
add garlands of fresh flowers for modesty instead, which allude rather
uncomfortably to the practice of ``de-flowering'' a woman on her wedding night.
Among tribal cultures, naivety in a woman is desirable, and virginity is best
expressed with untouched pink orchids in full bloom in the hair.
n.The Sari: Styles, Patterns, History, Techniques by Linda Lynton Published by
Thames and Hudson Ltd, price #32.
Whose sari now? The Banaras kincab wedding sari of a Punjabi lady living in
Uttar Pradesh in 1970.
</TEXT>
