<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749882</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Clare Henry hears the story behind the Hutton gems
WHAT to give the lady who has everything? Take a tip from the Woolworth
heiress, millionairess Barbara Hutton. Her idea of a trinket for her secretary
was to say the least, unique. No mere box of chocolates here, but a row of
rocks, knuckleduster ring, necklace or something like the beautiful diamond and
pearl ear-clips by Van Cleef et Arpels which Edinburgh jeweller Joseph Bonnar
is currently offering for the perfect Christmas present, a snip at #15,000.
It's one of several antique pieces which come with an exciting - and true -
story attached. Barbara Hutton's secretary was Scottish and like all
conscientious, transatlantic Celts, often worked late. If Hutton was
entertaining, sometimes she would ask her to stay on, with the instructions
that she was to ``dress up''. When her secretary returned wearing small,
tasteful pearl earstuds, Hutton would reach for her massive jewel box, fling it
open and clunk on some sparkling diamonds, exclaiming, ``they look much
prettier on you, dear, so just keep them''. This was during the 1940s when
Hutton, then in her thirties, threw memorable parties at her house near Tangier
together with Cary Grant, then Prince Igor of Lithuania, just two of her seven
husbands.
When Hutton's secretary died her sister, still living in Scotland, inherited
the jewellery with no idea that these glitzy 1940s pieces were very valuable -
until she tried to insure them. Bonner also has a French flower spray brooch
and a 2.5 carat diamond and cultured pearl ring (#3950) from Hutton's
collection - together with many other special antique pieces: a Georgian seed
pearl bracelet with a miniature-set clasp, Regency cut steel earrings,
Victorian diamond tiara (which conveniently converts to a necklace and brooch),
art deco brooch by Lacloche of Paris - and much more.
So how to display such lavish opulence? Bonner hit on the bright idea of
draping young ballerinas, complete with tutus - white for diamonds; blue with
sapphires and pearls - garlanding them with rows, loops and chains of gems and
holding a special Christmas party for his clients in the luxurious Secret
Garden of the Witchery restaurant. ``It's such a beautiful, romantic setting -
but it was hard for the dancers to be on points on the stone floor.'' So why?
``Being displayed on catwalk models doesn't work for this kind of jewellery,''
explains Bonnar. ``Using the Edinburgh Theatre School's teenage students solved
the problem because they didn't conflict with the jewels.''
I had assumed that antique jewellery was timeless, but Bonnar, who has been in
business in Edinburgh's Thistle Street for nearly 25 years, tells me that the
market is not immune to fashion. ``When Lady Di appeared, before her
engagement, always wearing a classic string of graduated pearls, they instantly
revived and became the ideal gift for every 18 or 21-year-old - and still are.
Previously they were impossible to sell. Jurassic Park made for a comeback in
amber and the Australian soaps also have had an effect. All the women on them
seem to wear their grand-father's gold Albert watch chain around their neck, so
now they are fashionable too!''
Bonner has an eye for the unusual and stylish, (``I had things from the Elton
John collection -though not the Duchess of Windsor!'') and also makes
commissioned pieces. ``Jewellery is such a personal thing. It's to do with
emotions and sentiment. You have to get it right.''
Having always had a keen eye for the most expensive thing in the shop, I
immediately lusted after the art deco sapphire and diamond necklace which
converts to a brooch and                 earrings (#12,850) and a
nineteenth-century           Etruscan revival necklace designed by the
leading Italian goldsmith, Palotti.
Hutton's gems are merely some of Bonner's lavish display, a delight to the eye
if not for the cheque-book! If I win the lottery it's certainly one shop where
I could easily go wild.
</TEXT>
