<HEADLINE>When Santa met the Tooth Fairy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Charlotte Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHAPTER ONE
MARK was moaning. Nobody cared about him and his tooth was agony. He simply
wished it would hurry up and fall out. Then he'd get money from the Tooth Fairy
and the pain would be over. Plus he'd be able to show off his gap to Paul. He
could really show him that he wasn't the only one with missing teeth!
Mark sighed and slumped over his toy police car. He'd had enough of the bitter
orange juice and was growing sleepy.
``Mummy, can we go home now?'' he whined, tugging silently at her skirt. Mark's
mother put down her coffee cup and stared down at the little unhappy face. She
looked sympathetic but simply smiled and murmured: ``Not now darling. Hang on a
minute and we'll go soon. You're being very patient.''
Mark stared open-mouthed. He couldn't tolerate any more of this drag. His mum
was obviously enjoying herself, however. She'd had an enjoyable Christmas shop
with her friend Helen, and now she was stopping off for a coffee. Everything
was very busy. It seemed to Mark as if the whole wide world was out last-minute
shopping for Christmas Day tomorrow and the little cafe seemed very popular,
although he simply couldn't understand how they could bear the overpowering
smell of black coffee wafting in from the kitchen.
Mark stared bleary-eyed into the dark High Street but turned away quickly when
he caught sight of the bright Christmas lights which made his eyes sore.
Absent-mindedly he reached his hand into his mother's handbag, pulled out a
toffee, unwrapped it, popped it into his mouth and CRACK! that's when it
happened - his first-ever tooth fell out of his mouth and on to the napkin laid
out at his place. Mark simply couldn't believe it! The tooth that had given him
so much pain had finally fallen out!
``Yesss!'' he gasped aloud, brushing his police car out of the way to examine
the precious tooth lying so still in a tiny pool of blood. This made him
somewhat worried but, after consulting his mum, he found out it was perfectly
natural and held back his approaching tears. For the first time in this long,
boring day he began to smile and he thought about the next day that was going
to be so exciting!
Christmas was coming!
CHAPTER TWO
``We're back,'' shouted Mark's mum as she shut the heavy wooden door leading
into the Howards' house.
Mark's dad, who was preparing some presents of his own upstairs, murmured
something before thumping down the stairs to say hello properly. Mark wandered
in to the kitchen and sat by the fire. He was very happy. He just loved the
atmosphere of the farmhouse-type kitchen with the simple wooden table and the
roaring fire. Of course he was too young to know exactly what it was he liked
about the kitchen, but he knew he liked the feeling when he sat near the fire.
He loved the warmth and the comfort of it and now that his tooth was out, he
enjoyed it even more!
As he whizzed his beloved police car up and down the rug, he heard his mum
telling his dad about how their son's tooth fell out in the cafe. Mark grinned
to himself. It was Christmas tomorrow (and he couldn't wait for that!) and as
well as everything else, the Tooth Fairy was coming tonight as well as Santa! .
. . The Tooth Fairy was coming as well as Santa?! That's when the thought
struck him. They'd both be in his room for different reasons, but they could
well be there at the same time. What if Santa and the Tooth Fairy met up?
CHAPTER THREE
Mark just could not sleep that night. His heart was pumping hard in his chest.
He was even more nervous and excited than he normally was on Christmas Eve and
his eyes simply refused to close. He decided to try a trick that his mum had
taught him two years ago when he was four - counting sheep.
Yes, he tried that but it didn't work and he stayed wide awake until after
midnight, much to his mum's disgust.
MEANWHILE, in a land far away, Santa was setting off for a long night's work in
his colourful sleigh. His elves were tired, but had to keep working, loading
all the many toys on to the sleigh - computers, books, bikes, hi-fi systems,
teddies, rollerblades and tons and tons of knick-knacks, so popular with the
children.
Pixpax, one of the less-intelligent elves, was joking around. ``Hey, Leps!
Careful with that bike!'' he yelled, taking it easy on a stool. ``That was the
end result of a hard shop at John Lewis, heh heh!''
Santa, big, fat, chubby, jolly Santa walked on to the scene, for once looking
rather annoyed.
``Pixpax,'' he began, ``I'd like to remind you that my name is Mr Santa Claus
and you must try and take orders from me. I know all this is hard work, but I'm
sure you'll agree that it's most definitely worth it to see a smile on every
child's face. And Pixpax, I don't care if that bike was the result of a lazy
shop at John Lewis or, as it should be, a week of hard constructive work, Leps
was handling it perfectly and it's simply not up to you to order him around
when you're slacking off yourself! Now get back to work!''
``Oooh, Santa, who's getting angry now?'' Pixpax murmured scornfully to
himself, but old Santa, with perfect hearing, turned around and shot Pixpax an
ice cold glare, leaving him feeling rather humbled and obliged to try his
hardest once more.
Fifteen minutes later, all the hundreds of presents were loaded on the giant
red sleigh and the reindeer perfectly positioned in order - Rudolf, of course,
at the front.
Now, just between you and me, Rudolf got his name because he is in fact
incredibly rude! This is, of course, why he's at the front - because he's so
amazingly pushy and won't let anyone else in! He just has to be the leader,
although, of course, if Santa was given any say in it - he could go!
Anyway, as I was saying, when everything was ready, it was time to go! Santa
was back to his old jolly self, having quickly recovered from the Pixpax
incident, and he was positively raring to go. Another thing that night, which
added to his jolliness, was his new super jet-powered engine in the sleigh to
give his reindeer a hand. After the successful test drive a week ago, Santa
loved it and couldn't wait to try it out properly. And now was the time! As
Santa gave a shout, the reindeer gave a huge leap and after starting the
jet-powered engine, there was no stopping them! They were off at exactly 225mph
on the speedometer
The pack of 20 elves watched as the sleigh pulled away and Santa shouted with
pleasure as they pulled off into the cold and drizzly - but, in a way,
refreshing - night.
CHAPTER FOUR
Although all this was happening there was, of course, space and time for more
action. In another land far away called Dentagumtoothland, where the Tooth
Fairy lives, there was plenty happening!
Sally Rose Ishbel Daphne Serendipity Betty Dentagum - otherwise known as the
Tooth Fairy - was rushing around like a mad thing. ``Lizzie dear, have you seen
my golden sequinned evening gloves? I've had an unexpected call from a little
boy called Mark and it's essential that I look my best.''
Lizzie Toothbrush, Sally Dentagum's official maid, looked up startled.
``A call? On Christmas Eve? How unusual . . . Remember in that survey we
conducted last year, December 24 was the most uncommon day for calls . . . ?''
``Yes, my dear, but as I'm sure you'll agree, we can't let this poor boy, Mark,
down. It would be a disgrace on our part. I must get myself up and about but I
just can't find these gloves . . . ''
``Let me assist you, Miss Dentagum,'' smiled Lizzie, beginning to look around
Sally Dentagum's General Purposes Chamber where most of her numerous belongings
ended up. She wandered over to a wooden treasure chest where mostly jewellery
was stored, heaved the heavy lid open and there they were! Sally Dentagum's
gold sequinned evening gloves!
``Why, here they are!'' cried Lizzie, taking Miss Dentagum's arm and leading
her to the chest.
``Oh thank you, thank you!'' came the cry from inside the chest as Miss
Dentagum brought her gloves out holding them daintily by the smooth white
buttons made from teeth.
``Do you know, Lizzie,'' Miss Dentagum announced, bringing her small blonde
head out of the chest and adjusting the pearly white tooth tiara, ``I'd really
be a lost cause without your assistance!''
Lizzie simply smiled for she knew only too well that that was perfectly true!
TWENTY minutes later, Miss Dentagum had finally achieved the flashy look she
was after and was ready to go. But there was one last thing to do - insert the
megajets into her shoe heels so that flying became easier and then once that
chore had been completed, it was action time! Off she flew into the dark night,
leaving Lizzie and the other servants, maids and helpers far behind.
CHAPTER FIVE
It had started to snow in Mark's home town of Bemburgh and as Santa's sleigh
pulled up on the roof, Santa felt thankful that there was a cover over the
hundreds of interesting gifts.
Santa arrived on the roof and quietly turned off the super jet-powered engine
before anything drastic happened. Rudolf was being his usual rude self and
protesting about having to stop so much but Santa, being jolly old Santa,
refused to take any notice and proceeded to cram his large frame down the
chimney of the white 1930s house.
Conveniently enough, the fireplace he came out of was in Mark's own room. Santa
quickly shook the snow off his large red coat and looked around him. Mark's
room was painted pale yellow and all over the walls were many different
posters: a poster advertising Pingu, Thomas the Tank Engine, a footballer, a
rugby player, a judo team poster, a poster showing the inside of an aeroplane,
a puppy poster and, bang right in the middle, was a large police car poster
torn out of a newspaper article. Santa smiled. He really loved young people and
was curious about their hobbies and interests.
Just as he was about to fill up the stocking hanging empty and limp on Mark's
bedpost with all the goodies little Mark had asked for, he heard a noise! A
kind of grating noise as if someone was hauling a hammer over a stone surface!
It all seemed very near and Santa, usually rather courageous, felt a lump in
his throat! Nervously, he turned round, his black beady eyes searching the
room. And then they fell on the window. A young woman, who seemed about 25 or
30, was climbing in! She had long, wispy blonde hair and a strange white tiara
on her head. Her eyes were deep blue and her lips bright red and pouty. Santa
thought she was very pretty, but was determined to know why she was climbing in
the window! Slowly he approached her and spoke.
``Er . . . yes, hello,'' he began, ``I was really . . . I mean, I really wasn't
expecting company tonight. Don't take it the wrong way, you don't need to go. I
just, well . . . I thought it rather strange for someone dressed in a pearly
white tiara and evening gloves to come climbing in this window!''
The young woman smiled. ``There's no need to worry. I'm the Tooth Fairy, you
see, and this young fellow lost a tooth this evening. And . . . well, you must
be Santa?''
``Yes, that's right. I suppose everybody knows who I am. Obviously I'm here to
fill Mark's stocking with all the goodies he asked for. I like seeing children
happy. It fills me with a kind of joy, I suppose you could say. I love the
sound of a child's laughter.''
``Yes, so do I,'' started Miss Dentagum, ``which is why I do what I'm doing
tonight. Children like money - which is perfectly natural because it gives them
so many opportunities and so I feel that giving it in exchange for teeth is a
great system! It makes me happy because of my obsession for old milk teeth -
and it makes them happy because they receive a little money!''
Santa smiled and stared at Miss Dentagum as if in some trance. Moments after he
realised and quickly shook himself out of it. After excusing himself to fill
the stocking, and then chatting (although slightly awkwardly) to Miss Dentagum
for a few more minutes over the mince pies and sherry left by Mark, Santa
realised just how much he enjoyed Miss Dentagum's company and how much he would
like to spend the rest of his days with her! But how could he ask? It's a very
difficult thing to do when you're over twice the woman's age and have a duty
like being Santa!
But, on the other hand, if he didn't ask he would never stand a chance and this
could be the last of Miss Dentagum in his life! So, crazy as it might be - he
asked. (Don't think it was as easy as I have just made out there - no way! On
the contrary, it was by far the most difficult thing Santa's ever had to do!
But it paid off because . . . she said YES!!!).
CHAPTER SIX
It wasn't easy for either of them - as I've just said it was very hard for poor
old Santa to ask and probably even harder for Miss Dentagum to decide on an
answer! But after realising they had so much in common, they both knew it was
the right thing to do and to compromise on where they would live, they decided
to bring both their kingdoms together as one and - guess what? - they called it
Marksland as it was little Mark who brought them together! He was even invited
to the official wedding ceremony in Marksland and to this day he still keeps in
touch with this charming couple - Miss Dentagum, now Mrs Claus, and, of course,
Santa.
Eighteen years later and Mark is a                      professional matchmaker!
THE END
It's a fulfilling life for Father Christmas handing
out largesse to the world's children, but it can be lonely. But when young Mark
conjured up a young blonde . . .
A seasonal tale by Charlotte Wilson, 11.
Illustration by Harry Wilson, 9
</TEXT>
