<HEADLINE>Drum up a taste for turkey</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lady Claire Macdonald</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>lady claire's kitchen</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lady Claire Macdonald prepares for
a hassle-free day of festive celebrations
THE day after tomorrow is Christmas Day. I hope that you feel full of joy, and
are not too fraught with the arrival of family and friends to share this most
wonderful festival with you.
Two weeks ago I told you how I make and freeze the stuffings for turkey, and
also the bread sauce. If you, too, have turkey for your Christmas celebration
meal, whether at lunchtime or in the evening, I do hope that you have your
stuffings out of the freezer and thawing.
Select a volunteer to peel the potatoes and trim the brussels sprouts. The
potatoes will be perfectly fine peeled today and kept in a bowl or saucepan of
cold water, providing that the water is changed tomorrow.
My idea of a good Christmas Day does not include peeling potatoes, besides
which I think that to a great extent potatoes taste of the fat they are roasted
in. The giblet stock for the gravy to accompany the turkey can be made today.
Put the giblets from inside the turkey into a saucepan. Put in as many pints of
cold water as you will need, depending on your guest numbers. Add two or three
onions, cut in half, a couple of stalks of celery, a leek or two, a handful of
peppercorns and two teaspoons of rock salt. Cover the pan with its lid and
bring the water to a rolling boil. Turn the heat down so that the liquid
simmers very gently and cook for 2-3 hours.
If you have an Aga or a Raeburn, cook the giblet stock inside a cool oven.
Strain, and when the stock is quite cold store in the fridge in a covered
container. Providing you do this, there is no need to reboil the stock
tomorrow, Christmas Eve. It will have a good boil when the gravy is made.
I have always felt that a first course is quite unnecessary before a
traditional Christmas lunch or dinner. I could never manage to get a Christmas
lunch ready, and besides that I would feel completely comatose following such a
lunch. Whereas in the evening, with curtains drawn and candles lit, and until
this year a strangely leisurely day to enjoy, with talk around the fire, with
chilly walks, and with, at some point, sticking the bird in the oven to cook
and the pudding on to steam, the dinner is the high point of the day.
I have said until this year because for us here in Skye who are Roman Catholic,
as we are, because our priest lives on the mainland our Christmas Day mass has
always taken place on Christmas Eve - there being no ferries on Christmas Day.
Now with the bridge to Skye open I suppose we will have the opportunity to go
to mass on Christmas Day in Dornie, the church on the mainland. Times change!
Now all that remains is for me to wish you all a very happy, peaceful and
joyous Christmas, and to leave you with a recipe for leftover turkey, a recipe
for a turkey fricassee, a much maligned dish which, when properly made is
utterly delicious.
TURKEY FRICASSEE
n Serves 6-8.
About 3 tablespoons dripping saved from the turkey.
2 onions, skinned and finely chopped
1 clove of garlic, skinned and chopped - optional
2 leeks, washed and trimmed and sliced thinly
4-6 rashers of back bacon, smoked or unsmoked, sliced thinly
2 teaspoons medium curry powder
2 tablespoons flour - fairly level tablespoons
1!s pints milk, or the jelly from under the dripping and milk combined
Salt, freshly ground black pepper
2 tablespoons raisins - optional, but very good
1!s-2lbs leftover cut-up turkey meat
n Melt dripping in a large saucepan and cook onions till soft and turning
golden. Add garlic and leeks, and bacon and continue to cook till leeks are
soft. Stir in curry powder and flour, continue to cook for a minute before
gradually adding the milk, stirring continuously till the sauce boils. Stir in
the jelly if you are using it. Add raisins, salt and pepper. Not more than 10
minutes before reheating the sauce to serve, add the cut-up turkey and simmer
very gently in the sauce. If you like you can stir a couple of tablespoons of
finely chopped parsley through the fricassee before serving. Serve with either
baked jacket potatoes or boiled basmati nice.
</TEXT>
