<HEADLINE>Ambiguities of angels</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John LInklater</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Looking to the heavens, John Linklater is inspired
by the miraculous nature of the host
Ezekiel saw them as frightening beasts but Raphael found it politic to portray
them           as rose-cheeked innocents. What is the inside track on the
heavenly host?
PATIENT cherubs is what it says on the back of the Christmas card I'm brooding
over. This is the caption title. You've seen them before a hundred times, this
pair: on cards, on calendars, soap adverts, labels, baubles, bangles, tattoos,
album sleeves, diaries, key-rings, ties, aprons, oven mitts, on watch dials,
alarm clocks, scrapbooks, jigsaws, CD Roms, underpants, flags, carrier bags,
and all the other rags, tags, and jingling bobtails that threaten to gift-wrap
you out of your senses at this vicious time of the year.
God love them. Two little faces above what looks as if it is the edge of the
paddling-pool, or the sweetie counter, or the chemist's dispensary waiting to
steal something to turn their innocent little minds savage, but you're not
allowed to think that because this image of Patient Cherubs belongs to the
realm of saccharine sanctimony, and the clouds behind them, the three moth
wings they share between them like a vehicle with a lost hubcap, the fact they
are naked in the bath but nobody is going to bring charges, alert you to be on
your best behaviour because they are two sweet little angels.
Except that they look suspiciously like pudgy middle-aged men wearing sandy
wigs. It could be Nigel Lawson and Arthur Scargill at the sauna, plotting their
relaunch as a comedy duo. The one on the left has a fat hand over his face, one
ringless finger sealing petted lips, and his curiously bicepped arm seems to
have shrugged off the missing wing. He has evidently been working for years as
a circus midget, coveting the high-wire girls.
The one on the right has his flabby arms crossed, and although he is also
gazing upwards with appalling smugness, it is with a different focus. They are
not actually looking at the same thing. Which makes them doubly dangerous.
They're covering all the angles, these streetwise angels, waiting for their
chance. I'd watch them if I were you. Loitering With Intent, is the title that
might have been used.
What they are supposed to be looking at, gazing adoringly upwards, is the child
Christ in the arms of his vacant-expressioned mother, attended by a couple of
groupie saints, Sixtus and Barbara. You think our little angels are the full
picture? They are just a detail from Raphael's Sistine Madonna. They are at the
bottom of a nine-foot canvas, the artist's marginalia, a footnote, a supporting
act. This explains the expression of sickened envy on their sagging faces,
sheer glum dejection.
The legend goes that Raphael was working on this commission in 1512 for the
Church of San Sisto in Piacenza when two little boys climbed up to one of the
windows of his studio and gazed at him as he worked. This is unlikely. Children
of that age don't gaze in passive admiration. They want a shot.
I remember seeing this painting for the first time in Dresden, at the
Gemldegalerie earlier this year, and being struck by how malcontented these
two actually appear when you confront them face to face. You meet them at eye
level, though their eyes wander upwards in mock reverence. That they are
studiously ignoring the supernatural babe Christ is evident. He is some
distance behind them in the arms of Mary.
She, like the two precarious saints, each on either side, has found an
improbable foothold among banks of clouds that, if studied closely, reveal
angel faces. They are like forms coming through a big effect of dried ice, an
impression amplified by the theatrical curtains that frame the painting. Either
way, and disconsolately unimpressed, the two cherubs are staring into space.
In which posture they have been unaccountably admired, indulged, and feted for
centuries. It is not that I don't appreciate them. After all, superior art
critics, and tastes more delicately refined than my own, have claimed a
perfection for Raphael's painting unrivalled by any other in the history of
art. No accounting for that claim. My objection to these cherubs, in common
with most Christmassy angels, is that they are a complete commercial fraud.
No doctrine has ever suggested that cherubim, the second-highest order of the
heavenly hierarchy, looked like tubby babies with wings. On the contrary, they
were awesome creatures of the Ever Turning Sword, guardians of the Tree of Life
(according to Genesis). Theodorus speaks of cherubim as ``beasts which might
terrify Adam from the entrance of Paradise''. Ezekiel in 1:4 gives one of the
Bible's most graphic accounts of cherubim. There was a tempestuous wind coming
from the north, Ezekiel says. It made a great cloud mass and a quivering fire,
with brightness all around like electrum. In the middle there were four
creatures. Each had four faces and four wings. They were gleaming like copper
and the soles of their feet were like calves' hooves. Their faces were quarter
human, quarter lion, quarter bull, and quarter eagle. Their appearance was
``like burning coals of fire''.
Paint that, maestro.
Since the Middle Ages popular culture has been swept by angel fever. Their
bright squadrons, choirs, and bands have excited more piety than the
evangelists. By the fourteenth century the kabbalists put their angel count at
precisely 301,655,722 of whom a regrettable 133,306,688 had fallen. Odd, then,
that so few ever got a name. After Archangels Michael and Gabriel most
struggle. Lucifer is probably the third-best-known angel, thanks largely to
Dante and Milton who gave Hell's Angels all the best lines.
The ambiguity of angels has always presented a problem. That a High Renaissance
painter such as Raphael should hesitate over the depiction of Ezekiel's
frightening beasts is not surprising. He found it politic to provide his
patrons with a pair of harmless innocents, two cherub babies to harmonise with
the infant Christ. This is just an early stage in what has been a continuing
and unceasing industry to provide us with packaged angels.
Angels are a fraud, yet we go along with them because they represent brilliant
marketing. Few actually believe in their presence. It is as purely spiritual
beings that they are upheld in Jewish, Christian, and Muslim theologies.
Calvinists dwell morbidly on bad angels while the Catholic Church has adopted
the position of Thomas Aquinas that angels are pure intellect and therefore
without physical form. This is confirmed by science. The Marxist geneticist J B
S Haldane calculated that in order to propel themselves by means of their
wings, angels would require breast muscles projecting four feet and legs
reduced to the slenderness of stilts. G K Chesterton's article of faith on
angels was as elegant as it was singular. He said angels could fly because they
took themselves lightly.
Certainly, we take them lightly, as well. They give their names to confections
from angel cakes to Angel Delight, or to delicacies such as angels on
horseback, oysters wrapped in bacon. An angel in the fifteenth century was a
coin worth 10 shillings (a mere 10-bob note, a 50-pence piece, for a guardian
of the throne of glory!), and an angel today is any member of the nursing
profession, after the 1976 BBC television soap. Or an angel is an Edinburgh
Festival award made by this newspaper, after Charles Wesley's Hark! The Herald
Angels Sing. The most likely place to find a recording angel today is wherever
they pick up their royalties.
It has been estimated that angels feature in the lyrics of one pop song out of
every 10. Angels want to wear the songwriter's red shoes (Elvis Costello). Or
they are playing with their heart (Eurythmics). They are of the morning (P P
Arnold). They step out of heaven (George Jones). They don't lie (Jim Reeves).
They are grievous (Gram Parsons) or special (Bobby Helms) or blue (J Geils
Band). It is their eyes that identify them as angels (Roxy Music) or their face
(Glitter Band) or their fingers (Wizzard). Sometimes they are just Angel
(Aretha Franklin/Rod Stewart/Carolyn Franklin).
If Humphrey Bogart and James Cagney can play angels on screen, albeit with
dirty faces, then there must be hope for us all. Cary Grant (The Bishop's
Wife), James Mason (Forever Darling), Warren Beatty (Heaven Can Wait), Claude
Rains (Here Comes Mr Jordan), Jack Benny (The Horn Blows at Midnight), Peter
Falk (Wings of Desire), Harry Belafonte (The Angel Levine), and Robert Cummings
(Heaven Only Knows) continue Hollywood's male slant on a species of heavenly
being that was supposed to be considered androgynous.
Jeanette MacDonald (I Married an Angel) provided an exception, but most of
these screen angels are whimsical and fey, culminating in everyone's favourite,
Clarence Oddbody, Angel Second Class, played by Henry Travers in It's a
Wonderful Life.
Every time you hear a bell ring, it means that some angel's just got his wings
in that 1946 film directed by Frank Capra, and Clarence's mission is to gain
promotion by saving James Stewart from suicide. It might be what James Agee
called the ``most efficient sentimental piece since A Christmas Carol'', but it
is accurate about at least one aspect of The Ministry Of Angels, its sheer
bureaucracy.
There are more grades of angels than in the Civil Service, and doubtless more
increments in the wages of virtue and sin.
Yet all authorities are agreed that elderly Clarence really was on the very
bottom rung. The retirement age of angels is unclear, though, they are never
depicted as veteran as Clarence, so he has a lot of catching up to do to rescue
his career. Gaining his wings would be a start. He could aim for Archangel
status, and climb up through the ranks to Principalities before trying to get a
transfer into the next triad of Powers, Virtues, and Dominions.
It is tragic that the rising career of a hard-working angel, against a
difficult contraflow of falling brethren, should be confronted at the top by
the realisation that he cannot go any further because he is no longer a baby.
Blame Raphael for the injustice. He might not have invented fat infant cherubs,
but he made sure they went into the repertoire of every painter of religious
scenes from Rubens and Van Dyck, with their beer-belly cherubs sporting thighs
like rugby prop-forwards, to photographer Joyce Tenneson's babyworld angels
viewed through a gauze lens .
Rarely have these excesses of artistic licence met with protest. The
nineteenth-century French realist Gustave Courbet was one of the few. He could
not abide Manet's idealised angels, and commented: ``So you have seen angels,
then, and know that they have backsides?'' Maybe someone should have put that
to Raphael.
</TEXT>
