<TEXT>
THE HOLY LAND
David Campbell
Everyman Guides, #20
IN one way, but one way only, Palestine and the Land of Israel offer the
guidebook editor a relatively simple task. The Holy Land covers less than half
the area of Scotland.
Scenically and architecturally, it is probably rather less interesting. But in
every other way the country is the supreme challenge for the guidebook.
Secular, sacred, and scholarly interests overlap, as holidays and pilgrimages
have always done. Politics intrude, as they always did. And no-one's approach
to the Holy Land and experience of it can be quite the same as anyone else's.
Jerusalem and Galilee are not just marked on the map but in private worlds of
faith and doubt.
The editor of the guidebook, Catherine Foure, describes the country as one
which looks small from outside and yet seems ``so vast from within''. As she
says, writing about dubious holy places of the Land (some so tawdry, some so
touching), it reflects ``an encounter between a God in search of humanity and
pilgrims in search of their God''.
Even if our reflections about revelation were not so often distracted by
politics - and there is a Messianic quality even to secular Zionism - it would
be hard to meet the needs of people who care about the Land in such different
ways. A modern guidebook to the Holy Land cannot avoid the fervour of Zionism
which, more than anything else, has given a sharpness and bitterness distinct
from the wider sense of Arab identity. Such a guide, unless it excludes much of
its potential market, has also to attempt an ecumenical and inter-faith
approach involving tortuous paths and sitting on uncomfortable fences.
No country offers such difficulties in preparing a guide for ``Everyman''. But
the daunting series title may, quite inadvertently, mislead older British
readers, especially as the publishers use the old Everyman's Library quotation:
``Everyman I will go with thee, and be thy guide''. The book's virtues aren't
those of simplicity and clarity.
The ``numerous specialists and academics contributing'', as well as the
editorial team, seem mainly French. The text looks a translation, with British
typesetting (less than perfectly proof-read), some American spelling, and
Italian printing. Some historical emphases and interpretations have a
distinctly French flavour. There is a friendly but slightly patronising
reference to the Scots church in Jerusalem - ``admirably'' sober - and
inadequate mention of the Garden Tomb and the historic Anglican Christ Church
(originally a cathedral) near the Jaffa Gate.
More important, traditional Everyman virtues of simplicity in typography and
book-design are absent in this mini-encyclopaedia of the Holy Land, ancient and
modern.
It is a vast Aladdin's cave of a book, stored with treasures mixed with
bric--brac, that divert attention from each other, and make it hard for the
reader to concentrate, especially in the practical information section where
four columns are squeezed into each page of an elongated pocket format.
There are 2000 illustrations in all shapes, sizes, and permutations of layout -
the result of diligent and ingenious research as well as enthusiasm for
attempting everything made possible by modern colour printing. But is this the
right balance for a book of this quality? As in many high-class modern
guidebooks and even encyclopaedias, pictures usurp the primacy of facts and
text.
The book's considerable achievement doesn't always match its ambition or
potential. The maps hardly stand comparison with those in the best traditional
guidebooks. This weakness applies to most modern guides - compare current
Baedekers with those of 1910 - and usually involves lack of detail and
insufficient clarity. Anyone tracing the decline of cartography should compare
the adequate picture map of Jaffa provided here with the quality of maps in an
earlier French achievement, the ultra-Catholic Holy Land guide of Father
Barnabas Meistermann. And cartographers who omit Jaffa from Holy Land maps
(treating it as incorporated in the sprawl of Tel Aviv) lack a sense of history.
Fortunately this sense of history and continuity is evident in other parts of
the book, both narrative and pictorial. There is a valuable anthology of
extracts from earlier pilgrims and travellers, though the greatest success of
the book is probably in the publisher's claim to provide ``an art book in
miniature'' as well as a guide.
The book also offers, as far as is humanly possible, the practical information
which visitors need for such a complex small country as the Holy Land. There is
much necessary detail here. But this is an ancient country in which many things
noted in guidebooks go out of date very quickly. That will become even more
evident as Palestinian self-government progresses in the West Bank, with
tensions over East Jerusalem and very different attitudes to Western pilgrimage
and tourism among the Arabs of Bethlehem and those of Hebron or Nablus.
R D KERNOHAN
n.R D Kernohan is author of The Road to Zion: Travellers to Palestine and the
Land of Israel, published by the Handsel Press and Eerdmans.
</TEXT>
