<TEXT>
IT HAD been a bad year for Britain's movie industry. Twelve Oscar nominations -
including illustrious names like Emma Thompson, Anthony Hopkins, and Daniel
Day-Lewis - and what did we end up with? Nothing. Zero. Zilch. Unless, of
course, you counted Nick Park. ``Nick who?'' we asked as one.
Well, it was 1994 and, at the time, we could all be forgiven for being
blissfully unaware of the name (even though it was, amazingly, his second
Academy Award). No excuses now, mind you. Now he's famous. Almost as famous, in
fact, as the 6-inch plasticine figures he created. Suddenly it seems that
Christmas television isn't Christmas television without his wonderfully odd
couple, Wallace And Gromit.
Right now Hollywood executives, cheque-books in hand, are beating a path to the
door of this supremely talented animator's Bristol studio with lucrative offers
for a full-length feature film. But, under these circumstances, Park's
unassuming nature and self-effacing modesty makes him, not his own worst enemy,
but his own best friend. Figures of #30m have apparently been mentioned, but he
steadfastly refuses to entertain Tinseltown's seductive overtures.
A wise move because Wallace, the quirky inventor who always looks on the bright
side, and his sardonic wuffless dog Gromit, would not travel at all well across
the Atlantic. They're so quintessentially ``oop North'' English. Like Park
himself.
He's Preston born and bred - and therein lies the secret of his characters'
success. The inspiration for his animated films, which owe more to the Ealing
comedies of the forties and fifties than they do to the saccharine and schmaltz
of Disney, is drawn from his own childhood memories. A Lancashire hotpot of
old-fashioned humour, quaint custom, and quirky circumstance.
He has shrewdly touched a nerve in all of us, young and old. Wallace and Gromit
cross the barriers of class, intellect, and generation. They are of universal
appeal. A funny- bone is a funny-bone no matter whose arm it's connected to.
Park's interest in film is inherited from his father, an architectural
photographer. When junior was 11, his old man bought a cine-camera for family
use. The inventive son used it to bring his cartoons to life. After art school
in Sheffield, he enrolled in the National Film and Television School where he
worked on his first professional animation - A Grand Day Out in which a man and
his dog attempted to reach the moon. For the characters he went back to some
scribbled drawings he'd made years before when he was trying to write a
children's book about a cat and a postman. The postie, who bore a striking
resemblance to his father, became Wallace and the cat turned into a dog.
Wallace and Gromit were born.
It cost just #12,000 and it was supposed to be his graduation film but, since
it took six years to make, Park had left the school a long time before it was
finished. The Bristol-based animation production house, Aardrman Films, took
him on to make television ads (and allowed him to finish his film during his
spare time). At the same time, Park started working on a second and slightly
shorter film, Creature Comforts, in which animated plasticine animals lip-sinc
with real-people conversations.
Both films were completed in 1989 and, much to their creator's surprise, both
were nominated for Academy Awards. In the end, it was Creature Comforts which
gained the Oscar while A Grand Day Out earned itself a BAFTA. The success
afforded Park the luxury of being able to
write his own cheque (from the BBC) for Wallace and Gromit's next outing. The
Wrong Trousers was a 30-minute film, made on a budget of #600,000. To date it
has won no less than 30 international awards - including Park's second Oscar.
Indeed, it is arguably the most  successful British animated film of all time.
Park's latest offering, A Close Shave, which will be screened on BBC2 on
Christmas Eve, is his most ambitious to date. It cost #1.3m (sounds a lot but,
in animation terms, it's still peanuts) and has been made at the Bristol
studios by a team of more than 50. Park himself deliberately stood back from
the animation work, preferring instead to direct the project.
He explains: ``Like most animators I'd developed a very individual approach
over the years but that's gradually changed. It's not easy because the Wallace
and Gromit thing has evolved in a very personal style which I have had to
`give' to other people. I give them direction and guidance about what I want,
which I find difficult because I'm not an extrovert.
``Still, I suppose working this way has dragged me out of my shell a bit.''
When it came to editing A Close Shave, the team was forced to make some
difficult decisions. ``About five minutes of animation had to be left out,
which was very painful.
``It's very hard to look at a sequence dispassionately and not think about who
animated, how long it took them, and what difficulties they had. But I hate
making decisions on the studio floor so I'm always asking for things to be shot
a bit longer so there's leeway to edit,'' he said.
The smart money is now on Park developing his gruesome twosome into a
feature-length movie but the man himself is worried that, in doing so, his
quirky vision could get lost along the way. But, despite the interest from
America, he's determined that it won't be made in Hollywood.
``Actually, I think the Americans realise, as much as we do, that there's
something very important about being based here. There's a certain sort of
British humour and way of looking at life that we'd risk losing if we went over
there.
``But there's been a lot of interest from Hollywood and I think what's really
caught their attention is the story aspect of our films. That's always been the
weakness of British animation, but the way we develop our scripts seems to work
very well,'' he added.
n A Close Shave will be shown on BBC2 on Christmas Eve. The Wrong Trousers and
A Grand Day Out can also be seen on BBC2, with Creature Comforts shown on
Channel 4, all later in the festive period.
</TEXT>
