<TEXT>
THE first feeling inspired by the grandly named ``social summit'' organised on
Thursday by French Prime Minister Alain Juppe with nine government ministers,
the representatives of five trade unions, and three employers' organisations,
is one of unreality.
The meeting, which began at the odd time of 3pm and went on for nine hours, was
called by the government as a grand gesture to end the month-long public
transport strike and appease public opinion. The unrest had been caused by
government plans to reform the welfare system, French railways, and public
sector pension schemes.
All that emerged from Thursday's long debates, however, was talk of economics,
not social measures. Welfare reform was not even on the agenda. The leader of
the communist-led CGT union, Lewis Viannet, summed up his disappointment with
the popular saying: ``The mountain has given birth to a mouse.''
During that first long afternoon of talks, the prime minister (whose close
advisers had spent four days agonising over what they could put forward to
appease the unions) promised to create 250,000 jobs for young people by the end
of next year. Juppe stressed the importance of ``relauching the economy''
which, stagnant even before the strikes, has been gravely damaged by a month's
transport stoppages.
The prime minister virtually admitted the failure of his earlier plans to
reduce unemployment by announcing that a major question was the reduction of
the working week, currently 39 hours.
News that emerged on Friday morning was even more curious. The government had
suggested modifying stock exchange related savings schemes in order to free
capital and boost spending. Those who would benefit from such measures are the
more comfortably off among the middle classes - not those who took to the
streets.
Here, it seemed, were two groups of people belonging to the same society,
talking a different language and adopting radically different approaches to a
problem - underlining, in fact, the very rift between the excessively educated
governing elite and those whom it governs, which President Chirac had promised
to heal.
For a month, thousands had gone on strike and up to two million people had
demonstrated, regularly and noisily in the streets of French towns, their anger
sparked by the government's wide-ranging package of reforms, presented without
a word of consultation. Now, instead of listening to those demands, Juppe is
trying to calm them down by changing the topic of conversation.
The chaos of recent weeks has been compared to that caused by the student riots
and general strike of May 1968 which almost forced General de Gaulle from
power. Last week's Social Summit, which is to be followed by more talks over a
period of six months, was redolent of the Estates General called by King Louis
XVI, which effectively got the French Revolution underway.
The lid on any number of social problems is being lifted in a similar and
confusing way today. Highly unpopular, Juppe is struggling to regain control of
the situation and his esteem in the country. Yet the government is putting
problems on the table - relaunching growth, reducing the working week, job
creation for young people - which concerned private industry far more than the
public sector, whose workers have been on strike.
Neither management associations nor the more hardline of the trade unions were
even keen on the agenda of Thursday's meeting, the details of which the prime
minister kept secret until talks began, as if trying to stage manage a
particularly difficult party trick. Only the centre-left union CFDT, whose
leadership agrees with many of Juppe's welfare reforms, is interested in the
reduction of working hours, a measure never mentioned previously as part of
this government's programme.
The CFDT, whose leader Nicole Notat was attacked during the strikes because of
his sympathy with the government's reforms, is now determined to push for the
reduction in the working week. Madame Notat will ask the government to oblige
firms to offer half their jobs to people under the age of 25. Her union also
wants to revise an agreement signed in September by having pre-retirement age
lowered to 57 when it means leaving a job free.
Reactions yesterday to the social summit from opposition parties, who had held
back from comment during the strikes apparently frightened of political
involvement, was negative.
``This summit will not put an end to mobilsiation. If the government thinks the
purpose of this meeting is to bury problems, they're making a big mistake. The
backlash will be painful next year,'' Communist Party leader Robert Hue said.
</TEXT>
