<TEXT>
THEY are the most famous lugs in the universe, if not the world. No, they don't
adorn a Windsor but that enigmatic Vulcan, Mr Spock. Only the most earthbound
readers will be unfamiliar with Spock (not to be confused with the
paediatrician) who boldly went with Captain Kirk of the Starship Enterprise
where no man, or indeed Vulcan, had been before.
His alter ego is the American actor Leonard Nimoy who in the seventies
alienated fans by publishing a memoir I Am Not Spock. He has now repented and
decided that he is.
Nimoy analyses this symbiotic relationship with the aid of imaginary dialogues
with the Vulcan - whose logical thought processes as well as solemn voice he
mimics exactly. Of much interest to Trekkies will be Nimoy's description of the
beginnings and evolution of the Star Trek TV series and subsequent films. Not
surprisingly, there was a great deal of creative tension behind the scenes -
not to mention rivalry among the actors. William Shatner (Kirk) of the melting
smile and expanding waistline is evidently an irrepressible joker.
Though there's too much talk of agents and backstage negotiations, Nimoy's
intelligence shines through. So does his awareness of the ethical and
humanistic imperatives, which - as well as flights of imagination - have made
Star Trek such an admirable entertainment for the age. (I Am Spock, four
cassettes, Random House, #13.80).
Patrick Moore fires people's curiosity about the real universe through his TV
programme The Sky at Night. Now he offers, in his own inimitable, idiosyncratic
style, an audio introduction to sky-gazing (Patrick Moore's Astronomy, two
tapes, Bespoke Audio, #7.99).
The Naxos Classic Fiction series offers literature to musical accompaniment.
Juliet Stevenson's reading of Mansfield Park by Jane Austen is a winner, though
even this most intelligent of actresses can't make the mouselike Fanny Price a
second Elizabeth Bennett. The author's wisdom, not to mention her D-Parkerish
wit, are to the fore - ``Such a superfluity of children and want of almost
everything else ..... Selfishness must always be forgiven for there's no hope
of a cure ..... I must move; resting fatigues me''.
Austen often seems to espouse worldly standards while mocking them, but here
the worldly folk are chastened and the most douce of lovers end up happily in a
mere vicarage. Beethoven, Weber, and Mendelssohn add their counterpoint. (#7.99
for three cassettes.)
By contrast, Naxos has come unstuck with Alexandre Dumas's The Man in the Iron
Mask. The last in a series of adventures set at the seventeenth-century French
court, the novel relies heavily on background knowledge - not just about the
four Musketeers (patrician Athos, genial giant Portos, intriguer Aramis, and
captain of the King's Guard, d'Artagnan) but such historic personages as the
Chancellor Fouquet, his plebeian supplanter Colbert, and the Sun King and his
mother.
This Naxos abridgement has been so ruthless as to leave little character and no
suspense about the most compelling of plots. The rumour that Louis XIV had a
twin brother confined in the Bastille continues to fascinate but in the Naxos
version poor Prince Philippe has only the most perfunctory taste of freedom
before incarceration in the fearsome headgear of the title. (Two tapes, #6.49.)
Shades of the prison walls, too, about John Mortimer's Rumpole and the Angel of
Death (Penguin Audiobooks, two tapes, #7.99). The battered old advocate of the
underdog is in vintage form via the familiar voice of Leo McKern. Much fun is
had at the expense of the Sisterhood of Radical Lawyers, who mount a vendetta
against Rumpole's dim-witted colleague Claude Erskine-Brown. He has committed
the unforgivable offence of calling his woman pupil a fatty. The fact that she
doesn't mind in the least is neither here nor there.
self as a black cab waiting to lift any client, however hopeless or
disreputable - and makes this statement (presumably mirroring Mortimer's own
philosophy) into a kind of battered idealism.
There's lots of idealism - the brotherhood of man, the dignity of the poor and
lowly, etc - about Robert Burns. John Cairney, the actor who got under the skin
of the poet to an almost uncanny degree, reads some of his best verse in a tape
issued by HarperCollins as the bicentenary year hovers in sight.
Those old staples Tam o' Shanter and the Address to a Haggis get an inevitable
airing. Far more telling is The Cotter's Saturday Night - a testament to the
dignity of family life, however humble. The poem offers moments of great
lyricism (the lovers under the whitethorn) as well as a tirade against the
corruption of innocence (in which Burns reveals that typical Scottish capacity
for hypocrisy).
It's rather a waste to have such lovely songs as Mary Morrison, Sweet Afton, or
Ae Fond Kiss simply read - though the lyrics are strong enough to stand by
themselves. Little musical interludes with guitar and violin offer the briefest
taste of the missing melodies. (The Poems and Songs of Robert Burns, #5.95.)
Gillian Riley tells you How to Stop Smoking and Stay Stopped for Good in a
single cassette (Random House, #5.99). It seems an elaborate alternative to
deciding simply not to light up again.
LESLEY DUNCAN
</TEXT>
