<HEADLINE>Scots who stand on their own</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Benedict Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Benedict Brogan ventures to a land on the edge of America where the descendants
of our emigrants
have carved out a distinct version of an old culture
THE words ``New Glasgow'' jumped out at me from the map stretched out on my
hotel-room floor. I had been searching for a destination for the next day's
expedition from Halifax, and there, clinging to the north shore of Nova Scotia,
was exactly what I wanted: a small town with a likely name and a promise of the
sort of Scottishness this corner of Canada has turned into an industry.
My hire car was booked for 8am, my map showed New Glasgow to be about two
hours' drive away, and a few quick calls gave me a contact in the town hall and
a promise of lunch with the mayor. Even better, the guidebook told me mining,
steel, and shipbuilding were the area's main industries. I could see it
already: a host of ready-made contrasts between old and New Glasgow,
interspersed with happy coincidences and meaningful comparisons.
A closer look at the map showed the whole north coast of Nova Scotia to be ripe
for an exercise in Scots tracking. New Glasgow, north of Glencoe, west of
Knoydart, and east of Scotsburn, is the main town in an area first settled by
Scots in the eighteenth century.
But when I mentioned my brilliant plan to Sandy Ferguson, the man behind the
desk in the hotel lobby, who met his Canadian wife Jennifer at university in
Scotland and followed her to Halifax, he was dubious. ``It's nothing like
Scotland out there, it's the worst sort of teuchterfied Scots sentimentality.
It's a falsified, atrophied Scottish culture that defends its traditions so
much, all Scottishness is being squeezed out of it.''
Eight hours later, undaunted, I was on my way. Despite the farms, the
motorways, and the motels, the drive across Nova Scotia does little to dispel
the sense of a wild place on the edge of a vast continent, where civilisation
is only as permanent as nature and the elements allow. The forest crowds the
road, except where it has been hacked back to make room for a house or a garage
or a billboard advertising motor oil. Shortly after 11 o'clock I pulled into
New Glasgow. It straddles not the New Clyde, as coincidence might have wished,
but the slow-moving East River. The steel bridge says ``Welcome to New
Glasgow''; the parking meters on every street say otherwise. Later I discover
they are made locally and exported all over the place.
Meetings had been arranged for me. Out past the rows of detached clapboard
houses, with their screen doors and mowed lawns, past the mall and Aberdeen
Hospital, I called on the local development office, where three slightly
bemused men with Scottish names offered me coffee and answered my questions
about the local economy.
I picked up some facts: the first steel to be cast in North America was poured
here; the last shipyard in the area has just closed; mining is more or less
gone; the steel industry remains, but only thanks to the demand for boxcars
from the North American rail-freight market.
This sounded familiar. Once-proud industries broken by the modern world;
rampant unemployment; the perfidy of a Conservative government; just like home.
The men now looked puzzled. Then Rob Roy, the youngest, proceeded to demolish
what I had begun to imagine were the makings of transatlantic solidarity.
Decline has been managed so as to hardly be felt, he said. New industries have
replaced the old. New hi-tech jobs are helping to halt the exodus of the young.
Entrepreneurs have sprung up, creating businesses and jobs through hard work
and tenacity. ``We may be Scottish, but we stand on our own,'' he said. Ouch.
On to lunch with Anne MacLean, New Glasgow's formidable mayor. She is only the
second woman councillor, and the first woman mayor, in New Glasgow's 120-year
history. In a town this size, with only six councillors and the mayor to run
the town, government is a small, grassroots concern. When MacLean isn't being
mayor she is an addiction rehabilitation supervisor for the health department.
She is big on the burgeoning connections with the old Glasgow and speaks warmly
of Susan Baird, Robert Innes, and the other Glasgow notables who have visited
and who received her on her visit to Scotland. In between mouthfuls of lobster
roll - lobster is the province's mascot and most noteworthy industry; as a
result it's unavoidable - I quiz her on cultural similarities.
New Glasgow has a population of 10,000, and 90% of its citizens are of Scottish
extraction. Its first settlers - Frasers and McKays - arrived in about 1784,
though there is no record of an obvious connection with Glasgow. The first
Scots in the area had landed a few miles away in 1773 in the Hector, the local
equivalent of the Mayflower, that brought 33 families and 25 bachelors from
Scotland in 1773. Nova Scotia had been ceded by the French to the British in
1707 under the Treaty of Utrecht, and with the new owners came Highlanders
expelled by the Clearances.
Two centuries have not diminished the area's pride in its origins. Distance, if
anything, has intensified it. New Glasgow wants the world to know it is
Scottish, even if its definition of Scottish resembles more a tin of Walker's
shortbread than a Saturday at Ibrox. Its coat of arms is identical to
Glasgow's; its motto is ``Let New Glasgow flourish''. The war memorial is a
Highland piper, the plinth inscribed with the very Scottish names of those who,
on two occasions, crossed the Atlantic to die in wars that had little to do
with this remote corner of North America. Every year the town celebrates the
Festival of the Tartans with children in kilts and massed pipe bands. ``We
haven't got our own tartan yet, but that's the next thing on the list,'' the
mayor says.
And it's the same throughout Scottish Nova Scotia. St Francis Xavier University
up the road in Antigonish boasts a centre for Gaelic studies; St Ann's in Cape
Breton has North America's only Gaelic college, complete with a Great Hall of
the Clans and an annual Mod; in Lismore a cairn commemorates the slaughter of
Bonnie Prince Charlie's Highlanders at Culloden; a replica of the Hector is
under construction in Pictou.
The tourist brochures proclaim it as heritage, euphemism for a tightly defined
nostalgia for something that no longer exists - if ever it did. No surprise,
really, that this celebration of Brigadoon bears no resemblance to the Scotland
of today. There is no New Old Firm in New Glasgow. The area may be
traditionally Protestant - the Catholics settled further along the coast - but
Catholic and Protestant children attend the same schools.
Next stop - the offices of the Evening News, circulation 10,000, the local
paper. An attempted robbery at the credit union has disturbed the town's peace:
the police chase is given prominence on page one; on page three it's business
as usual, with details of the annual draw for 200 moose-hunting licences.
Managing editor Doug MacNeil admits the loss of traditional industries has
caused some pain, but no social dislocation on a Scottish scale.
Still, he claims the area is more Scottish than Scotland itself. The people of
Pictou County - Picts? - identify themselves closely with their origins, with
names and clans and a connection to the Old World. ``It's important that people
in Scotland realise that the people here are proud of their Scottish
heritage.'' MacNeil says.
There is a last visit to be made, on the outskirts of town, to a small house
overlooking a large parking lot. Dr Carrie Best is in her mid-nineties, wears
killer shades, and is black. Her colour matters only in that she is one of
Canada's most celebrated campaigning journalists, who founded Nova Scotia's
first newspaper for black people, the Clarion, in 1947. Her motto should sit
above every reporter's desk: ``Do a mile of research before writing an inch of
copy''. Her living-room walls are crowded with photos, awards, and citations,
the most prominent being the Order of Canada, awarded in 1974.
She reminds me that Nova Scotia, and New Glasgow, are not just about displaced
Scots with a tartan fixation. The black community here, one of the oldest in
North America, was granted a tract of land in 1787 by the then governor. ``We
weren't just dropped here. We were here before the Scots. This land was given
to us,'' she says, jabbing my kneecap for emphasis. This essential historical
detail is all too easily swamped by heritage.
Dr Best remembers the days when New Glasgow was a place where life was
distinctly easier if you were white. Now, with her sharp eye, she spots a town
that has progressed enormously. The New Glasgow she knows has nothing to do
with kilts and pipes. It is a small town in Canada that has overcome its
experiences of racism, prejudice, and narrow-mindedness to elect a woman mayor,
as well as one black and one Asian councillor. ``I'm passionate in my loyalty
now to New Glasgow because I have proved to myself that you can make the town
what you want it to be if you have got the guts to stand up for what is right.''
Late that night, as I drove back to Halifax in the blinding rain, following the
road by the glimmer of the lorry ahead of me, a local station played a
schmaltzy local version of the Skye Boat Song. Nova Scotia's understanding of
Scotland may be sentimental, but it is also clear, and happily oblivious of the
identity crisis that grips the mother country.
</TEXT>
