<HEADLINE>Parting the swirl of mist around the legend king</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alison Kerr</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra meet the author </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Alison Kerr enters the realm of fantasy
with a writer whose imagination ranges
from Middle Earth to Camelot
DAVID Day's multi-faceted career and varied interests have taken him all over
the world with a passport that has described him as both a lumberjack and a
writer - depending on the decade.
Now resident in London, he has written more than 30 books; an expert on
mythology he consequently, counts among his friends at least three of the Monty
Python team.
Day started his working life as a lumberjack in British Columbia - a job which
endeared him no end to his new Python pals after he first met Terry Jones in
1981. ``Terry kept inviting me round to dinner because it gave him and Michael
(Palin) the chance to sing the Lumberjack Song,'' he says in an Irish-sounding
drawl.
The son of a firechief, Day grew up next to an Indian reservation, in an area
steeped in folklore. Spare time was spent reading: his interest in Greek
mythology was, however, a closet activity since it was not in keeping with the
macho lifestyle of a young lumberjack. His other love was writing poetry, which
- along with storytelling - has always been part of Canadian culture,
especially among men in rural areas.
Over the course of the decade from the mid-1960s, Day spent blocks of time
either working in logging camps or studying for his two university degrees.
In 1977, after working for a Canadian publishing company for a year, Day moved
to England and looked for a similar job in London. There wasn't one, so he
helped his friend Alan Thornton set up Greenpeace in Britain. At that stage
Greenpeace's international status was unimaginable: it was a case of ``14
hippies and a dog,'' says the sardonic writer.
Day also began to work on ideas for books. His first was The Tolkien Bestiary -
an guide to the world of the author of The Hobbit series. Its success led to
two more Tolkien tomes, the more recent of which (Tolkien's Ring) has just
appeared in paperback. In between times Day has written everything from books
of poetry to works of natural history, with collections of children's stories
thrown in for good measure.
Another, less self-effacing but more likely, reason for his genre-spanning
tendencies is that all his writings have been outlets for, and have their roots
in, his interest in folklore and mythology. Day's natural history work (The
Doomsday Book of Animals and a series of films for American and Japanese
television on animals which have become extinct this century) stemmed from his
fascination with the Red Indian stories he heard as a youngster; He has also
written children's stories based on legends he has picked up on his travels.
Day's latest publication is an epic one: The Quest for King Arthur is
beautifully illustrated and takes a different approach from every other work on
the legend. ``Usually people write a generic book: they make Arthur all one
story. In fact, it's lots of different stories.''
Day's theory is that Arthur was a different person every century, depending on
who paid the storytellers. ``The Arthur we know - with the court at Camelot,
the magician Merlin, the sword Excalibur and the Knights of the Round Table -
was based on the Tudor version of the legend as written by Malory in his Morte
d'Arthur in 1485.''
This is certainly the version that Hollywood has decided to stick to; most
recently with the movie First Knight, in which Richard Gere hammed up Lancelot
and Sean Connery starred as Arthur - an appropriate choice since Arthur may
well have had some Scots in his accent. Day found First Knight ``painful to
watch. I kept on thinking: `What century is this?'. ''
Before the popular imagination settled on this version, however, the characters
had been through various changes: Henry II's wife, Eleanor, didn't like the
fact that kings got all the attention, so she ordered the storytellers to make
King Arthur's wife Guinevere the real star of the legend.
In the twelfth century, an order of monks rewrote the story to portray Arthur's
half-sister, Morgan le Fay, as a baddie because they wanted to promote the idea
that women had no souls. As Day points out, ``these were complex figures
originally used for propaganda, but people have forgotten that they had been
shaped by propaganda.''
``What my book does is peel back the layers surrounding the legend of Arthur.
He's like a whirlwind: we only know him by what whirls around him - all the
separate myths that have gathered around him.''
The first sighting of Arthur in the pages of history was in 480 AD. At that
time Arthur, or Arthurius, was not a name but a title. The original Arthur was
a Romanised Celt who commanded the British cavalry from Strathclyde - the last
stronghold of the Welsh-speaking Celts. Since his first appearance in history,
stories of the life of ``Arthur'' have, according to Day, been twisted and used
by almost every British monarch in order to prove their right to rule.
It may seem a long way from the logging camps of British Columbia, but David
Day asserts that ``the patterns are the same in both Red Indian and British
mythology''.
So what next, now that Day has grappled with the knights of the Round Table?
He's currently working on a volume of poetry to be entitled Just Say No to
Family Values, as well as juggling three children's books.
He has also been paving the way for his chum Michael Palin to meet some of his
old totem pole-carving friends as Palin is in the middle of another Around the
World-type exercise. And he's also keen to visit Scotland, to begin the next
stage of his Arthurian quest: an investigation into all the fraudulent
documents made through the centuries as part of what he cryptically calls ``The
King Arthur conspiracy''.
n The Quest for King Arthur, David Day, De Agostini Editions, #14.99.
