<HEADLINE>In darkest night, the brass handles rattled</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain White</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Iain White goes in
search of Scotland's
supernatural hotel
guests and has a few
disturbing moments
WHEN I hatched the idea of visiting a number of haunted hotels I was
enthusiastic and confident, almost blase about it all. However, as I was
approaching the Meldrum House Hotel, my early courage for the project was
waning. I had agreed to stay in a bedroom reputedly haunted by the ghost of The
White Lady, and as I entered this dark, old rambling place I had a sense of
foreboding. I half-expected an octogenarian butler to greet me with
ingratiating servility and a knowing smile.
It was, however, the lady proprietor who welcomed me cheerily from within the
sombre entrance hall. ``So you're the ghost-hunter,'' she enthused. I insisted
that I was keen to meet the owners of the ghost rather than the real thing and
further emphasised that curiosity was my only motive for the benefit of any
would-be eavesdropper.
``That's her behind you,'' my host added casually. I froze in horror and
turning slowly I met the piercing gaze of . . . an oil painting. My host led me
up a creaking staircase, through an enormous oak-panelled doorway and along a
gloomy portrait-lined passageway all the way along to the possessed room . . .
Scotland has always had a tradition of ghosts and ghouls and the Scottish
Tourist Board has published a list of 30 hotels which claim to have
supernatural occurrences or unexplained visitors. Many of the tales of these
permanent, non-paying guests centre on the North-east. The city of Aberdeen
boasts a hotel with two ghosts, while at Strathdon a hotel is haunted by a
phantom who plays the bagpipes. In Methlick, the hotel, which was originally
the manse, is troubled by the spirit of a previous Free Kirk pastor who, rather
surprisingly, appears only in the bar.
I had begun my investigation at the Thainstone House Hotel, near Inverurie,
which is reputedly haunted by a Green Lady. Believed to be the daughter of a
previous owner of the house, she was killed in a riding accident while wearing
her favourite green cloak. The hotel has been modernised inside and with the
addition of its well-appointed country club, and carried little initial
atmosphere of the wraithly lady's ethereal exploits. However, there is a
bedroom where things have been known to move around independently and into
which pets will not enter.
The ghost seems often to be irritated by other women and a recent resident
returned to her room after dinner to find the dressing-table glass smashed and
the contents of her make-up bag scattered around the room. I settled down for
the evening awaiting the unexpected.
At one o'clock in the morning I was awakened by the persistent and violent
rattling of the brass handles of the dressing-table. I switched on the light
and watched in disbelief as the activity blatantly continued. A closer
examination of the situation, however, evidenced the truth, for whenever my
next-door, all-too-earthly neighbour moved about his room, the vibrations
spread through some very flimsy floorboards to my room. At breakfast next
morning I was thus able to report that my sleep had passed untroubled.
In the Borders, there are a number of establishments which have reported the
activities of unaccountable apparitions. One hotel near Biggar has a spectre
who appears on the patio and the roof, and who seems to indulge in such pranks
as moving furniture and changing television channels. Another report is a ghost
called Gladys who makes regular appearances to the local patrons of an inn near
Castle Douglas. Angered by anyone who sits in her chair, she makes her presence
felt so vividly that Border Television believe the shadowy figure that they
once captured on film was her.
I next stayed at the Dryburgh Abbey Hotel, near St Boswells, where there have
been a number of separate reports of supernatural occurrences by yet another
colour of damsel, a Grey Lady. She is believed to have had an affair with one
of the monks from the abbey who was subsequently put to death for his
infidelity. On hearing this tragic news, the distraught lover drowned herself
in the nearby River Tweed.
Her ghost has been seen in the grounds and walking across the chain bridge, but
during 1993 she began to make her presence felt more often within the hotel
during major renovations to the building. Workmen reported that tools had been
mysteriously moved and equipment was being tampered with. The manager told me
that he is convinced that he felt the presence of someone behind him one
evening despite the fact that he was alone in the hotel. A complete search of
the building revealed no intruders while the locks on all the windows and doors
remained untampered with.
My own visit, however, was again uneventful and, despite close inspection of
the hotel and grounds during the early hours of the morning, I was unable to
locate any ghostly roommates.
When I arrived at Meldrum House Hotel, any scepticism was rapidly replaced by
an uneasy sense of foreboding. A previous visitor had received an icy kiss
during a violent thunderstorm in my room and in another incident a guest had
found himself compressed to the bed by an unknown force for several minutes.
The husband of the owner admitted with some degree of reluctance that he
believed he had seen the ghost working in the hallway upstairs.
Of course, I had heard similar stories elsewhere, but as I passed beneath the
stern gaze of those eerie portraits, I felt the presence of something extremely
unsettling. This wing of the house was as quiet as the grave, and my room
remained icy cold all night in spite of the central heating. I must admit that
for the first time in over 30 years, I went to bed with the light on, I even
left the radio on, offering a reassuring babble in the corner. I did not sleep
a wink.
When the first light of dawn arrived I immediately packed my bags to leave.
Shivering, I quickly dressed with hat, scarf, gloves and an extra jumper for
the winter weather. As I walked down the long driveway I did not look back. I
was remarkably hot, sweating in fact, Later I discovered from weather reports
that it had been one of the mildest weekends recorded for November.
</TEXT>
