<HEADLINE>A great leap into the unknown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH a bank account number which begins 007, I may have a head start on others
when it comes to daredevil exploits.
But an adventure break in the spectacular surroundings of the Swiss Alps
certainly - though perhaps only temporarily - sated my taste for danger.
Only a couple of miles from genuine James Bond territory in the shape of the
famous revolving restaurant at the top of the Schilthorn peak, used as a
location for the slightly less memorable On Her Majesty's Secret Service, I
found myself in a cable car, 100 metres above the ground, preparing for the
highest bungee jump in Europe.
It seemed a fitting end to a day which had begun with a 15km bike ride through
the Lauterbrunnen Valley, overlooked by two of the world's most famous peaks,
the Eiger and the Jungfrau and their slightly lesser-known friend, the Munch.
After lunch, we hit the water, literally, with a spot of whitewater river
rafting along the crystal-clear rapids of the Lutschine.
Safety is of paramount importance, with rafters kitted out not only with wet
suits, but also lifejackets and protective helmets.
The white water calmed as the river ran into one of the stunning lakes next to
the famous Swiss resort of Interlaken. Envious passengers on steamboats
cruising the lake waved as we drifted into Interlaken.
Wet suit deposited, I headed for a refreshing and relaxing swim in slightly
warmer waters at the action centre pool. But the highlight adventure of the day
still awaited me.
While others refused the option of the jump - even after watching other
daredevils leap safely -- I was still determined to give it a go.
Six of us climbed on board the cable car for the two-minute trip to the jumping
point, only a few metres from the highest waterfall in Europe, a cascade of
tumbling, clear pale blue water.The distant crash of the water echoed gently
around the cable car as the bungeemaster explained the rules and introduced the
jump team.
One by one, we lined up, like lambs to the slaughter, to choose our harness -
jumpers can be strapped in around the waist and chest, or for the more daring
there is the option of diving tied by the ankles.
Being a first-time jumper, I had decided on the chest harness. I might be
brave, but I'm not that brave, I thought.
My moment finally arrived and my cool veneer of confidence evaporated. My knees
turned to jelly. My stomach churned. My palms began sweating uncontrollably.
Final safety checks completed, the bungee team started the countdown. ``Five,
four, three . . . '' I was out, plunging uncontrollably towards the fast water
and green fields I had admired only seconds before.
I suddenly found my stomach in my mouth, but decided it would be inappropriate
to be sick, given my circumstances. I found I had no time to worry. Suddenly, I
was enjoying the insane sense of freedom, the sensation of flying towards the
ground.
Just as my senses began to adjust to the idea of my new-found Peter Pan status,
the bungee rope provided a timely reminder that I was not the fictional
flight-assisted child. Bouncing upwards for what seemed like an eternity, I
found myself somersaulting 360 degrees, a manoeuvre not completed since
schooldays. Several violent bounces later, I really was beginning to quickly go
off the entire idea . . . and it was all over.
As I touched the ground and hit the landing mat, the enormity of what I had
done suddenly hit home. Boosted by a sudden rush of exhilaration, I punched the
air and ran to find the other jumpers, hugging and congratulating themselves.
Trembling, we shared descriptions of the sensations we had experienced, but the
number one question on all lips was: Would you do it all again? The popular
consensus was yes, but please not right away!
Venturing out to dinner later at one of the very excellent hotels in my Alpen
base - the popular winter ski resort of Murren - I was greeted by the dulcet
tones of a Scots accent, who had shared my exploits.
The voice belonged to 27-year-old Alan Ramsay, head waiter at the Hotel Eiger.
Originally from Peebles, he moved to Switzerland in December 1990. The Eiger is
closed for five months every year, but the excellent pay allows him the
opportunity to travel.
``I've bungee-jumped 350 metres from a helicopter in New Zealand. I've offered
to do the one you did in a kilt, if they let me do it for nothing,'' said Alan.
It would be something of a dawdle for him, I imagine.
The three-day adventure break to the Bernese Oberland is organised through the
Swiss Tourist Authority, with flights from Heathrow by Swissair and
accommodation at the four-star Palace Hotel in Murren. Adventure activity can
be arranged through Adventure World of Interlaken.
</TEXT>
