<HEADLINE>When it comes to love, who's counting?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jane Scott is taken aback when she starts to tot up the true costs involved in
a medieval romance
THERE is a charming children's book, now sadly out of print, called The
Thirteen Days of Christmas by Jenny Overton. It describes what would happen if
one of history's great love songs were a true story, and the answer, of course,
is total chaos.
One partridge in a pear tree is an enchanting idea, but you may not have taken
the song as literally as the lover in Overton's book, who hoped to win his
lady's hand in marriage and who duly turned up every morning for 12 days with a
new partridge and a new pear tree - and medieval market town houses, where the
novel is set, have little enough room as it is.
Then there were the ever-increasing numbers of turtle doves (two every day for
11 days), calling birds (four for nine days) and French hens (three for 10
days) with the attendant squawking and mess.
Medieval families, however, were quite used to keeping poultry out the back;
even the bad-tempered geese laying eggs everywhere and the swans lording it
over the street were as nothing to eight maids a-milking bringing along eight
cows and delivering eight buckets of fresh milk daily until the end of
Christmas.
By this time the town was turning up en masse every morning to see delivery
boys bringing cages and rings and food and bedding for all the animals, and by
the ninth day there was really something to see; with ladies dancing, lords
a-leaping and pipers piping - 11 of them, for two days, on the last day
accompanied by the 12 drummers giving the loved one, who by then had
accumulated a grand total of 40 gold rings to help sway her mind, the wake-up
call to end them all.
But that was then. How would a lover, minded to give the 12 days of Christmas,
fare today - and how much would                  it cost?
Pear trees are no problem, according to Dobbies of Helensburgh; only that the
branches are bare at this time of year. But you could choose fruiting trees -
Conference, Williams, or Comice - for #16.99 for this year's stock - or pay a
little more and get silver pear trees for #19.99, bearing no fruit but giving a
beautiful silvery weeping foliage come the spring. Let's choose the expensive
option: 12 trees will set the cause of love back #239.88.
Finding the birds, however, is enough to make you weep. After days phoning
round organisations ranging from Edinburgh Zoo to the magazine Poultry World
(``Oh, we get all sorts of strange requests on Poultry World,'' said one
reporter), to the British Chicken Information Service (``I'm afraid you're
going to have to ring France. We only deal with British chickens. Can the egg
information service help?'') a shopping list was drawn up.
You'll have to part with about #7 a bird for the French Red Leg partridge
(``They don't roost in trees. The Red Leg has been seen on gates, however,''
said Michael Roberts of the Domestic Fowl Trust). Turtle doves have been almost
driven out of the country by the imported Ring dove (#10 a bird) and there's a
choice of French hen, rejoicing in names ranging from Salmon Faverolle to La
Flehe. We'll go for the popular Maran, which costs #18 a bird, and lays
beautiful brown eggs.
We'll take calling birds as canaries, #12 each, and geese, if you're lucky, at
around #24 a bird (you would be lucky because the hot summer simply sent the
ganders to sleep and reduced their fertility; geese are in short supply this
year).
Wild swans are protected birds and capturing them could land you in jail over
Christmas, but you could adopt Whooper or Bewick's Swans from the Wildlife and
Wetlands Trust in Slimbridge, Sussex, for #25 a bird for a year. Alternatively,
you could ferry the loved one to a country park like Calderglen, East Kilbride,
to see the black swans in situ.
The total cost of your fowl will be #3286.
Handmade rings, said Tom Wallace, jeweller of Queen Street, Glasgow, could cost
anything from #25 to #25,000 each, if a four-carat diamond were required, that
is. A plain gold band costs around #15 for the finest 2mm strand, and up to
#250 for the chunky 12mm option; we'll plump for 40 rings somewhere between the
two, say for #4800.
Eight maids a-milking, says Roberta Dunbar, west area chairman of the Scottish
Young Farmers, is more likely nowadays to be ``one cow in an Isuzu jeep and a
portable milking can. It's just not the same, is it?'' In her grandfather's day
they'd have eight or 10 milking the cows, doing the job of just one farmer and
his electric milking equipment today. All dairy farmers can still milk by hand,
however, and it shouldn't be too hard to find eight girls to do it - ``but it
would be expensive. Under NFU salary guides it's about #200 a week, and a milk
cow costs #900 to #1000.''
She reckoned, however, that if you could get someone to lend you the cows (you
can't really hire them for the day), paid #30 each a day for haulage (the cost
of getting a cow to market), paid the milkmaids #4 an hour, and bought the milk
at 26.5p a litre (that's with premiums for butterfat, protein, and cell count)
you'd get away with #2052. But you'd then have to work out what to do with 1400
pints of milk.
Now for the dancers.
``I'm not sure we can manage real lords doing it,'' said William Crawford of
Highlander Music near Beauly, Inverness. ``But you can certainly get dancers to
do that.''
William organises dance troupes and tours across the globe. In the repertoire
of his dancers are Scottish Country, Highland (``very competitive, nowadays,''
said William), step dancing - re-imported from Canada, where the immigrants
arrived with dance forms which subsequently died out in Scotland - ballroom and
Latin American.
You could have your nine ladies doing any of the above, although the 10 lords
a-leaping sounds just like Highland dancing, he said - ``A good lord should be
able to manage a quick sword dance before breakfast!''
And the cost? Each dancer receives #70 a day, plus travelling, accommodation,
and food - add another #40 a day. Then there are the costumes; lords and ladies
don't come cheap (all that brocade and lace); better count on #30 each. Grand
total: #7830.
Back to Glasgow for our pipes and drums, where Liz Spy, secretary of the
Kinning Park Pipe Band burst out laughing at our request.
``But it's not so daft,'' she said, wiping her eyes. ``For a start, I would
probably be able to get you 11 pipers, but we would need to filch some drummers
from another band because we've only got eight. I suppose it doesn't matter if
they are in another colour of kilt?''
Kinning Park turns out in the handsome blue-green Ancient Hunting McIntyre
tartan - ``and that doesn't come cheap, believe me,'' said Liz, who is keen to
get sponsorship for the band.
The main problem would be to get the band members, all working men, together on
a weekday; that costs money, and they need proper notice.
``Pipe bands have come to the conclusion that we have been selling ourselves
too cheap, because lots of people want an entire band of 30 people out for two
or three hours, for the whole parade, for #150, and that's not on.''
She thought, however, that with a bit of negotiation she could get the
requisite pipers and drummers together for #900 for the two days, taking us up
to the twelfth day of Christmas.
The lover in Jenny Overton's book won his lady's heart on the thirteenth day,
when she realised she wanted nothing so simple as to marry him. By this time,
of course, he had bought the most expensive Christmas presents anyone in the
town had ever seen, and perhaps a life of simplicity was the one that beckons,
although as a trader he may have had deep pockets. Our modern day lover, on the
thirteenth day, will be #19,107.88 in the red; although if the answer is the
right one it will no doubt be worth it.
n Twelve pear trees will set you back #239.88 and the twelve
partridges #84, making a total of #323.88.
n With Turtle Doves almost driven out of the country, their
replacement Ring Doves will cost in the region of #220.
n Three French hens, with              attendant Gallic squawking, will
all add up to #540 for ten days.
n Hark! Four calling birds, in the form of singing canaries of course, at #12
each, will hit you to the tune of #432.
n Five decent sized gold rings - let's not be stingy about this - for eight
days come to a staggering #4800.
n Six geese a laying will cost #168, but at least you'll have a decent sized
omelette every morning.
n Seven swans a swimming, being a protected species, should be seen only; the
adoption papers will set you back #150.
n If you can manage to organise a deal with the NFU for eight maids a milking,
the exercise would cost #2052. Have a word with the milkman, instead.
n To acquire nine ladies dancing for four days you have to worry about
travelling expenses, accomodation, and the cost of costumes: the total is #4230.
n If you hire the ten lords a           leaping from the same dance school as
your ladies, the cost is the right royal sum of #3600.
n In order to get a good deal on the eleven pipers piping, it is
better to ask them to bring some drummer friends for the whole musical package.
n With their piper chums          chanting, the twelve drummers drumming will
hit you in the            wallet for #900.
</TEXT>
