<HEADLINE>Complexities of truths</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Deirdre Chapman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974749900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PATRIOT IN BERLIN
Piers Paul Read
Weidenfeld and Nicolson, #15.99
I DIDN'T want to finish this book. It has seen me through three disturbed weeks
and four plane journeys - too much of a crutch to swap for a paperback. This is
a thriller, tightly controlled but with an ambitious overview that pits the
narcissistic elements of the fashionable free-world personality against the
impersonal, driven ideology of the former communist East.
Post cold-war Russia and Berlin are the settings. Nicolai Gerasimov, in an
office in the Lubyanka, being briefed on a secret mission to the West, has
career worries - will they abolish the KGB? - and a wife who won't go out and
stand in food queues. That his search for a missing top-rank unreconstructed
intelligence officer will take him to Berlin is as good as a holiday.
American art historian Francesca McDermott, invited to Berlin to organise a
major retrospective exhibition of those twentieth-century Russian paintings
dismissed under communism as ``decadent'', revels in the career boost and the
chance to renew acquaintances with the friends of her postgraduate years in the
city. However, she is too much of a skinny, gym-frequenting power-dresser to
empathise with the mind-set of her colleagues, emerging awkwardly from the
socialist system.
Kessler and Dorn, Berlin detectives investigating the torture and murder of a
pair of Russian icon smugglers in the Dubrowstrasse, have the weary wised-up
outlook of men whose crime-fighting is complicated by Ostpolitik. When they
request help from Moscow they fully expect to be sent a professional lummox, a
man who, behind a screen of lumpen camaraderie, will smoothly block all avenues
of inquiry.
When Gerasimov arrives and mistakes a prostitute for a pick-up their belief is
amply confirmed.
Francesca, meanwhile, early morning jogging in the park, is attacked by three
men of Turkish appearance, and saved from rape only by the timely arrival of
her enigmatic Russian colleague on the exhibition committee, Andrei Serotkin.
These two are cool, competent, and self-sufficient beyond the range of their
fellow committee members. An attraction begins to build that is fuelled as much
by their isolated arrogance, as the attraction of their opposing and mysterious
ideologies.
And then the paintings, Chagalls and Kandinskys from the finest collections of
the free world, vanish from their secure store. And nothing was as simple as it
seemed. As the pieces of the plot begin to fly into place, a contemporary love
story emerges, fashioned with immense restraint out of opposing and unyielding
personalities uncluttered by detail.
The complexities of the plot stem entirely from the complexity of truth,
belief, and identity. There are no ornamental red herrings to deflect its calm
unfolding, nor red-hot bedroom scenes to undermine the central purity of the
characters, and the writing entirely matches the controlled intensity of the
whole. Meryl Streep and Mel Gibson for the film. Read it.
</TEXT>
