<HEADLINE>Good art obscured by the penny dreadfuls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749901</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EGON SCHIELE: Eros
and Passsion
Klaus Albrecht Schroder
Prestel, #14.95
THERE are all sorts of ways of hooking an audience. Here Egon Schiele's
startling, superb, and innovative draughtsmanship could be one; his
asymmetrical compositions another. Schroder has chosen the soft option: sex.
Egon Schiele is a superb yet strangely unsung artist, so this book, with its
many excellent illustrations, should be very welcome. Unfortunately the
high-flown text - obviously someone's extended thesis - merely cobbles together
chunks of writing by others with a misleading, muddled appraisal of Schiele's
``allegedly pornographic imagery'', leaving us with a volume which raises more
questions than it answers.
As the short biographical introduction tells us, Schiele was born in Austria in
1890 and died, all too young, in 1918, just months after his famous countryman
Gustave Klimt. Bearing in mind Klimt's huge success (his pictures currently on
millions of birthday cards, postcards, and calendars), I have never been able
to understand Schiele's neglect - especially given his preoccupation with the
nude.
Yet when a major Schiele exhibition was held at London's Royal Academy a few
years ago, the Academy was unable to find any sponsorship till the very last
minute when a minor - but enterprising - spectacle-frame manufacturer stepped
in. The exhibition was memorable for paintings like Self Portait with Chinese
Lantern Plant 1912 and Seated Male Nude, which in the flesh, with their
beautifully textured paint surfaces and nuances of exquisite chalk-drawn line,
are somehow less shocking than on a glossy printed page.
The RA's difficulty with sponsorship is symptomatic of the general fear
surrounding Schiele's so-called soft porn which, as here, clouds the vision of
his genius.
True, Schiele depicted the body with a radical candour that was unheard of in
the early years of the twentieth century. True, a preoccupation with the human
body pervades his work. But this book leans on sex; uses sex as its main hook.
It details ``obscene nakedness and indecency'' with a Victorian relish,
introducing nineteenth-century photographs of mental patients without any
explanation as to their connection - or lack of it - with Schiele. Did Schiele
know of, or use, these photographs? We are not told.
So what is the dividing line between titillation and truth; obscenity and
aesthetics; prurience and painting? ``Schiele was an erotic artist. He was
extremely liberal in sexual matters.'' The analysis is simplistic in the
extreme, a fact underlined by the banal chapter headings. Sex Crime as Artifact
leads into an account of the Neulengbach affair when Schiele was charged with
abduction of a minor, sexual abuse, and ``open outrage of public morals or
decency''. (He was in fact totally innocent and aquitted.)
Other chapters are titled The Iconography of Mangled Flesh; Shamelessness as an
Aesthetic Principle, and even From Art to Pathology. It's all page-three,
penny-dreadful stuff dressed up as academic research. The amateur
psychoanalysis is perhaps the         most objectionable aspect,
where Schroder often gets his           facts wrong.
So leave your Victorian values at home; study the breathtaking images, and
don't take the text too seriously.
Schiele's lean bodies, bony, angular in the extreme, are ideal for structural
exaggeration; perfect for the turn-of-the-century Vienna Secessionist
androgynous aesthetic, creating an art nouveau aspect with bite; a graphic
hard-edged style that makes Charles Rennie Mackintosh look soft.
If not so sad and tormented, they could almost be said to be a caricature of
the artist as sufferer; artist as victim. Schiele is as cruel on himself as on
his women. His models included his beloved sister, his girlfriends, and
latterly his wife Edith. As is obvious from the helpful documentary
photos of Schiele and pals, he                                        was
a handsome, well-fed chap completely unlike his anguished self-portrait.
By the age of 28 Egon Schiele was a rave success, regarded as Austria's leading
artist and exhibiting all over Europe. His death, three days after that of his
pregnant wife, both of the deadly Spanish influenza, ended his life in the sort
of Hollywood-style melodrama of which, one feels, Schiele would have approved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
