<HEADLINE>Shy away from that crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Victoria Freedman</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>weekend extra </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Parties, far from being the heart of the
season, can be absolutely excruciating for more timid souls. Victoria Freedman
searches for a solution
BY now there will be people worrying themselves silly because they have
received an invitation to a Christmas party. For those who are shy, the season
to be social can be excruciating.
The simple advice to stay at home will not do. First, there are work parties
that have to be attended. Then there are partners to accompany. In any case, if
you are shy there is no choice in the matter, according to Dr Robert Edelmann,
senior lecturer in clinical psychology at Surrey University, who has studied
the problem for 15 years since he began to investigate why social encounters go
wrong.
``Shy people feel they have to go to parties. What will people think if they
don't? Therefore they put themselves into situations that others wouldn't
bother about. Non-shy people are quite happy to pick and choose. They would
just think, `I don't want to go'. But once a shy person is invited to a party,
the immediate thought is that they have to go even if they don't want to, even
if they won't know many people there. So the pressure they build on themselves
starts with the invitation.''
The worries mount - what will they wear, who will they know, what if they don't
know anyone, what will they say, what if they find nothing to say, what if
nobody wants to talk to them, what if people notice them.......?
``It's almost as if they're talking themselves into a state of anxiety,'' says
Edelmann.
``But the one thing that shy people clearly do is keep practising. They want to
be in contact with others, they don't want to be lonely, so they do put
themselves into disturbing contexts. And that is why they suffer. Life is a
constant round of discomfort. You want to be confident, outgoing, sociable, and
you're not.''
It is a scenario that Abigail Thompson recognises very well. ``I think a lot of
people who loathe parties go to them because it's expected, and to a certain
extent I've done that a lot. I've often had to go to parties or dances with my
husband and dreaded them beforehand and hated them while I was there. If I
found people I felt comfortable with, I could talk, but put me with another set
of people and I'd hardly open my mouth. I remember spending so many evenings
going back and forwards to the toilet, not because I needed to, but to pass
time.''
Shyness is not to be confused with social phobia, a condition that affects
around 2% of the population, where anxiety reaches such a level that people
avoid all social encounters. Nor does it mean that those   suffering are
socially unskilled. ``Shyness has an engrained self-consciousness, an
over-awareness of oneself, an over-focusing on oneself. That can feed into
being so concerned that it disrupts your performance and you look unskilled,
but you're not in reality,'' explains Edelmann. However, the more
people stammer and blush in conversation, the more they feel inadequate as they
focus on what others are thinking.
What can be done depends on how shyness is perceived. Edelmann says there are
three explanations of why people are shy - it's a personality trait, a learned
behaviour, and a pattern of thinking. ``There's not much you can do about a
personality trait as it is inherent. Learned behaviour can be changed to a
certain extent, by unlearning a pattern of reacting and learning new practices.
But you can probably do most about the way you think.'' Treatment involves
gradually replacing negative thoughts with positive ones.
``Most shy people tend to be fairly irrational in their thinking, not in
general but in how they think of themselves in social situations. They tend to
think `nobody else is shy, it's only me'. So they learn to think more
realistically and more positively.
``Another pattern of thinking that can be changed is absolutist, that
everything must go right. There are occasions when everybody will suffer in a
social situation and most of the time it's laughed off. But if you're shy, it's
a disaster.''
Self-consciousness can also be worked on by reflecting thoughts away from
oneself - ``this person finds me boring'' - and on to what the other person
looks like in terms of hairstyle and clothes.
Abigail Thompson, now 50, coped better with her shyness after becoming a
counsellor. ``I found that I wasn't shy on a one-to-one basis and it also gave
me confidence. And I don't really worry about what others are thinking any
more. I'm too old.''
Although extremely shy people are often regarded rather unfairly as aloof and
arrogant, those who cope with their shyness will simply be seen as quiet and
reserved. Which is not a bad thing. ``A certain amount of shyness in social
situations is actually seen in a quite positive way, particularly in women,''
says Edelmann. ``Even in this liberated age men still have this notion they
have to be the dominant males.
``But very few people are raving extroverts and they're not really liked that
much anyway. They're too brash, too loud, and they obviously don't understand
others. Whereas if you come across as just slightly demure, slightly reserved,
slightly hesitant, and if it's used appropriately, it's seen as quite empathic.
I can think of one young lady on Panorama recently who did just that.''
n.Abigail Thompson's name has been changed.
</TEXT>
