<HEADLINE>Chatter of the Christmas Parrot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Hugh Ouston</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>birdwatch</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974749903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hugh Ouston keeps his fingers crossed for an appearance of waxwings to weigh
down Scotland's berry bushes this winter and cap off a perfect festive season
YEARS may go by with just a handful of waxwings wintering here; then comes an
irruption and reports of parrots on the cotoneasters from all over suburban
Scotland. Even if you've seen them before, waxwings are a really special winter
bird. At first glance they might be starlings, but look closely and a more
exotic picture unfolds: a plump peachy body with a yellow-tipped tail, a mobile
crest, a black bib and eyestrip, secondary feathers give them the appearance of
having been dipped in sealing wax. These beautiful details combine with exotic
manners and photogenic poses, and above all with tameness and a weakness for
the berry bushes outside our windows, to make waxwings a Christmas favourite.
There are very good reasons why waxwings only visit us every few years and
equally good reasons why they are found in suburban gardens when they do. They
breed in the endless forests of the remote taiga, scattered and hard to find.
During the summer they eat insects, of which the northlands provide an
unlimited supply. I have seen them in the early winter flycatching from the
wires over the electrified Edinburgh-London rail line. They whirred up steeply
then planed around and down to the wires again. When a 125 came by, the party
of a dozen or so took refuge in an ash nearby, but only for a couple of
minutes. There aren't many trains - or people - in the boreal woods. However,
to survive right through the winter they depend on berries.
Specifically, they depend on our own familiar rowan. A hot summer in the far
north means more young waxwings grow up and it means - as 1995 has taught all
gardeners - more berries on the trees. This is fine for one winter, but the
increased numbers surviving face a problem if the berry crop fails the
following year, as it is likely to do.
By October, psychological stress, an important tool of evolution, encourages
the flocks to move on south before their food runs out. The prevailing autumn
winds and the shape of Scandinavia send them straight over to us.
In most years the few waxwings which arrive will find enough to eat on the east
coast. However, when the irruption is huge - and in November 1965 there were
11,000 in Britain - they will tour through to the west, down to England and
even on to the Continent, perhaps returning through Germany to their lonely
breeding forests.
But why cotoneasters? When the waxwings arrive, the berries in the countryside
will already have been stripped by the regular migrants, redwings and
fieldfares in particular. Thrushes are not so fond of cotoneasters, so there
may well be full bushes for the waxwings. A single bird can eat 170 berries an
hour, which means it would take two days for a party of seven to clear 100
square feet. In fact they will eat all kinds of berries: pyracantha and
viburnum, bramble, and dog rose, hawthorn and juniper . . .  and of course
mistletoe and holly, as we know from Auntie Morag's annual card.
Since I don't know the meteorological reports from the northern palearctic for
1994, I couldn't hazard a guess whether this will be a ``waxwing winter''.
There have been two fine irruptions in the last decade: 1988-89, and 1991-92.
On a glorious day in the spring of '89 I spent a happy hour photographing 30 or
so as they drank from the gutters of suburban Rosyth and posed in the saplings
along the M90. All the while they kept up a soft trill quite different from any
of our native birds. It ``at once strikes on the ear of the ornithologist as
the cry of a strange bird'', wrote Charles St John in 1847. Such social
sibilant conversations are almost continuous. Their Latin specific name is,
after all, garrulus.
These were the first waxwings I'd seen since I was a teenage postman in St
Andrews. Vanity forbids me from naming that year. However, the earliest
recorded invasion was in 1679-80. From the end of November to late February
that waxwing winter, the future King James II lived in Edinburgh to keep out of
the way of the anti-Catholic mob in London. Were his cold walks in the gardens
at Holyrood, or his golf or his horseracing down at Leith, enlivened by the
antics of the ``Bohemian chatterers'' as they used to be called?
The most reliable place to see waxwings recently has been the city centre of
Aberdeen, notably the trees by the art gallery, though the birds in 1991 used
to fly 20km to the Hill o' Fare to roost in an environment more like home. But
don't get the next train north; if they're in Scotland they could be anywhere.
They do like to stick around for a wee while at least, so it would be worth
ringing Birdline Scotland (0891 700 234) to find out where they are. Or you
could just plant some cotoneasters and wait a decade or two.
In a waxwing year they will be with us till mid-April. A big flock seems out of
place in a warm garden full of tulips but they know there is not much point in
turning up at the Arctic Circle when the conifer branches are still bent with
snow and not an insect has hatched. Enjoy them then, because you may not see
them again until you are a lot older. And enjoy them now, with a final festive
thought: waxwings have a rare ability to metabolise the alcohol in the
fermenting fruit they eat. A good excuse, if one were needed, to reach for the
Speyside malt and toast the compliments of the season of berries to them - and
many happy returns.
